Data Engineer|Junior \\n- 0 to 2 years experience / fresh grad\\n- Knows fundamentals of data pipelines and databases\\n- Has done projects or internships\\n- Not expected to design large-scale systems end-to-end\" |A|2|Behavioral ​|I once had a teammate who didn't know what they were doing and kept suggesting wrong ideas. I just ignored their suggestions and did the whole project myself to make sure it was done correctly. It was more work for me, but it was better than arguing with someone who didn't understand the task as well as I did.|During a group project, a teammate wanted to skip the testing phase to meet a deadline, but I felt it was too risky. I suggested we sit down and list the three most critical components that needed validation so we could compromise on time without sacrificing quality. We agreed on a shortened testing plan that covered the essentials, and we successfully submitted the project on time with no major bugs.|I was working on a task where my partner wanted to use one method, and I wanted to use another. We talked about it for a while and couldn't agree, so we eventually just asked our supervisor to pick one for us. We followed the supervisor's advice and finished the work, though it was a bit awkward for a few days afterward.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a collaborative mindset and an ability to find compromises. They focus on the project's success rather than winning the argument. Mid: The candidate is willing to resolve conflict but lacks the initiative to solve it themselves. They rely on authority figures to settle minor disputes. Bad: The candidate shows a total lack of teamwork and conflict resolution skills. They are dismissive of others and prefer to work in isolation. Structure check: Good: The answer uses the STAR method effectively to describe the conflict, the action taken, and the resolution. It highlights interpersonal maturity. Mid: The story has a clear conflict but the resolution feels flat. It does not clearly articulate the logic behind the chosen solution. Bad: The response lacks a resolution phase where both parties move forward. It focuses only on the disagreement itself. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about the nature of the disagreement and the logic used to find a middle ground. They show reflection on the process. Mid: The candidate gives a very brief overview of the disagreement. It is hard to tell how significant the conflict really was. Bad: The response is superficial and avoids discussing the actual dynamics of the situation. It provides no insight into the candidate's interpersonal style. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains the situation clearly without using inflammatory language about their teammate. The communication is professional and balanced. Mid: The candidate’s explanation is slightly biased toward their own perspective. The narrative is clear but lacks objective balance. Bad: The language used is defensive or critical of others. It makes the candidate seem difficult to work with. Relevance to role: Good: This demonstrates the exact kind of professional maturity needed in a collaborative team environment. It shows they can handle the pressure of deadlines without losing their temper. Mid: The response shows they can function in a team but may need management intervention for minor issues. It is an average junior response. Bad: The response is problematic because it suggests the candidate cannot collaborate. It indicates a high risk for team toxicity.|2|Describe a situation where you had a disagreement with a teammate about how to approach a task?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect schema compliance and question ID mapping.\", \"Excellent adherence to internal rubric labeling (Good/Mid/Bad) across all sections.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers representing the junior level.\", \"Diverse dimensions covered across behavioral, situational, and specific types.\"]|a68bbf7d5ad36e808d24c6374acd6c7e66860a42|52b717ae