Data Engineer|Junior \\n- 0 to 2 years experience / fresh grad\\n- Knows fundamentals of data pipelines and databases\\n- Has done projects or internships\\n- Not expected to design large-scale systems end-to-end\" |A|3|Specific|I trust that the tools I am using are built to move data correctly, so I don't usually do manual checks. If there is a problem, the person receiving the data will usually let me know that something is wrong. Checking every transfer manually takes too much time and isn't really necessary if the code runs.|I always start by performing a row count on both the source and the destination to ensure no records were lost during the transfer. After that, I check for null values in critical columns and perform sum validations on numeric fields to ensure the data wasn't corrupted. Finally, I sample a few random records to verify that the formatting and content match the original source exactly.|I usually just check the logs after the transfer is finished to see if there were any error messages reported. If the logs are clean and the total number of records looks about right, I assume that the data moved correctly. Sometimes I will open the file at the end just to make sure it looks like it has data in it.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a rigorous approach to data integrity and understands various validation techniques. They take personal responsibility for the quality of their output. Mid: The candidate understands the need for validation but relies on passive methods like log checking. Their approach is not exhaustive. Bad: The candidate lacks a quality-control mindset. They assume the technology is infallible and defer responsibility to others. Structure check: Good: The candidate provides a step-by-step process starting with high-level checks and moving to granular verification. The logic is easy to follow. Mid: The answer is a bit disorganized and lists checks as they come to mind. It lacks a formal methodology. Bad: The response is a single statement of non-action. It does not describe a process at all. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific types of checks like null validation, row counts, and checksums. They show an understanding of different failure modes. Mid: The candidate only mentions one or two basic checks. They do not seem to consider data corruption or schema issues. Bad: No depth is provided regarding technical validation. The answer is purely conceptual and lacks practical application. Clarity check: Good: The technical steps are explained clearly and would be easy for a teammate to follow. The candidate uses appropriate terminology correctly. Mid: The explanation is a bit vague and uses non-specific language. It is clear enough to understand but lacks precision. Bad: The answer is confusing or suggests a lack of understanding of the data transfer process. Relevance to role: Good: This is a critical skill for the job, and the candidate shows they are reliable. They prioritize accuracy over speed. Mid: The candidate has the basic idea but needs more training on rigorous validation. They are at an acceptable junior level. Bad: The candidate is not suitable for a role involving data accuracy. Their lack of diligence could lead to significant downstream errors.|3|How do you ensure that the data being moved from a source to a destination is accurate and complete?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect schema compliance and question ID mapping.\", \"Excellent adherence to internal rubric labeling (Good/Mid/Bad) across all sections.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers representing the junior level.\", \"Diverse dimensions covered across behavioral, situational, and specific types.\"]|a68bbf7d5ad36e808d24c6374acd6c7e66860a42|52b717ae2008be0897adef3eb032bcc0c96bcf2e|Data Engineer|12|6c6baefb2d9bafe6a9f14fb2081775e6d0bb8578|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262493Z
Data Engineer|Junior \\n- 0 to 2 years experience / fresh grad\\n- Knows fundamentals of data pipelines and databases\\n- Has done projects or internships\\n- Not expected to design large-scale systems end-to-end\" |A|4|Specific|If a query is slow, I usually just try running it a few more times to see if it gets faster. If that doesn't work, I might try rewriting the whole thing from scratch in a different way, but I don't really have a specific method for finding the problem. Sometimes the database is just slow and there's nothing you can do.|I begin by using the EXPLAIN command to see the execution plan and look for things like full table scans or inefficient joins. Once I identify the bottleneck, I check if the relevant columns are indexed properly or if I can rewrite the query to use a more efficient filter. After making changes, I run the query again to compare the execution time and ensure the performance has actually improved.|I look at the query to see if it's joining too many tables or if the filters are too broad. I might try adding an index to the columns in the WHERE clause to see if that helps speed things up. If it's still slow, I might ask a more senior person to look at it for me.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a structured approach to performance tuning and knows how to use diagnostic tools. They demonstrate a logical troubleshooting mindset. Mid: The candidate knows a few common fixes like indexing but doesn't show a deep understanding of the 'why'. Their approach is more trial-and-error. Bad: The candidate has no methodical approach to optimization. They rely on luck or hope rather than technical analysis. Structure check: Good: The response follows a logical progression from diagnosis to implementation to verification. It shows a disciplined workflow. Mid: The response mentions several things to check but doesn't present them in a clear order. It feels like a list of random tips. Bad: The response is disorganized and suggests a lack of understanding of how databases execute queries. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific tools like execution plans and concepts like table scans. They understand the importance of baseline comparison. Mid: The candidate mentions indexes but fails to discuss execution plans or other diagnostic steps. The depth is limited to surface-level fixes. Bad: The answer is very shallow and doesn't mention any specific technical concepts. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains technical concepts in a way that is easy to understand. They communicate their thought process effectively. Mid: The language is somewhat informal and could be more precise. It gets the point across but isn't very professional. Bad: The answer is confusing or uses terms incorrectly. Relevance to role: Good: Performance is key to the job, and the candidate shows they can handle basic optimization tasks. They are ready to work with production databases. Mid: The candidate is at a standard junior level but will need guidance on complex queries. They show enough promise to be trained. Bad: The candidate lacks fundamental knowledge of how to manage query efficiency. This could lead to resource issues in a live environment.|4|Can you explain the steps you take to identify and fix a slow-running SQL query in a database?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect schema compliance and question ID mapping.\", \"Excellent adherence to internal rubric labeling (Good/Mid/Bad) across all sections.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers representing the junior level.\", \"Diverse dimensions covered across behavioral, situational, and specific types.\"]|a68bbf7d5ad36e808d24c6374acd6c7e66860a42|52b717ae2008be0897adef3eb032bcc0c96bcf2e|Data Engineer|13|6c6baefb2d9bafe6a9f14fb2081775e6d0bb8578|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262493Z
Data Engineer|Junior \\n- 0 to 2 years experience / fresh grad\\n- Knows fundamentals of data pipelines and databases\\n- Has done projects or internships\\n- Not expected to design large-scale systems end-to-end\" |A|5|Situational​|I wouldn't start the task because it is impossible to do a good job without clear instructions. I would wait until the stakeholder is available again to get more details, even if that means missing the deadline. It's better to do nothing than to do the wrong thing and waste time.|I would first document my best interpretation of the requirements and identify the areas where I have the most uncertainty. I would then check if there is a similar existing project I can use as a reference to fill in the gaps. Finally, I would send a summary of my assumptions and a draft of my plan to the stakeholder so they can see it as soon as they are back, while I work on the parts I am sure about.|I would try to find a teammate who has worked with that stakeholder before to see if they can explain what is usually expected. If nobody knows, I would just do the task based on what I think they want. I would try to finish it quickly so I have time to change it later if I got it wrong.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows initiative and the ability to make progress in ambiguous situations. They balance the need for clarity with the need to meet deadlines. Mid: The candidate is willing to move forward but relies on others to interpret the requirements. They don't take full ownership of the documentation process. Bad: The candidate is paralyzed by ambiguity. They use a lack of clear instructions as an excuse to stop working. Structure check: Good: The response outlines a clear three-step plan: document, research, and communicate. It is a very professional approach to problem-solving. Mid: The response is a bit reactive and focuses on asking others for help. It lacks a structured internal process for handling the work. Bad: The response is a simple 'refusal to act' statement. It lacks any structure or constructive strategy. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific actions like creating an assumptions list and checking historical projects. They show maturity in their project management style. Mid: The candidate suggests a few basic ideas but doesn't go into detail about how they would manage the uncertainty. The level of detail is minimal. Bad: The answer is superficial and doesn't address the complexities of managing stakeholder expectations. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's plan is easy to understand and logically sound. They articulate their reasoning clearly. Mid: The candidate's explanation is a bit scattered but the main points are understandable. It lacks the crispness of a top-tier answer. Bad: The explanation is unclear and shows a lack of professional judgment. Relevance to role: Good: Ambiguity is common in the job, and this candidate shows they can handle it without getting stuck. They are proactive and communicative. Mid: The candidate is a safe hire who will try their best but might need help navigating complex office dynamics. Bad: The candidate would likely be a bottleneck in the project. Their inability to handle vague requirements is a major weakness.|5|What would you do if a stakeholder gave you a task with vague requirements and then became unavailable for questions?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect schema compliance and question ID mapping.\", \"Excellent adherence to internal rubric labeling (Good/Mid/Bad) across all sections.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers representing the junior level.\", \"Diverse dimensions covered across behavioral, situational, and specific types.\"]|a68bbf7d5ad36e808d24c6374acd6c7e66860a42|52b717ae2008be0897adef3eb032bcc0c96bcf2e|Data Engineer|14|6c6baefb2d9bafe6a9f14fb2081775e6d0bb8578|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262493Z
Data Engineer|Junior \\n- 0 to 2 years experience / fresh grad\\n- Knows fundamentals of data pipelines and databases\\n- Has done projects or internships\\n- Not expected to design large-scale systems end-to-end\" |B|6|Behavioral ​|I haven't really made any big mistakes because I am very careful with my work. One time a teammate said I did something wrong, but it turned out the instructions were just confusing, so it wasn't really my fault. We just fixed it and moved on to the next task.|I once accidentally deleted a small configuration file because I was working too fast in the command line. As soon as I realized it, I notified my team leader and checked the version control history to restore the file. I then created a personal checklist for that specific task to ensure I double-check my commands before hitting enter in the future.|I made a mistake in a report where I used the wrong date range, and the numbers didn't match. When my manager pointed it out, I apologized and spent the afternoon redoing the entire report with the correct dates. I made sure to check the numbers twice before I sent the new version back.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows honesty, accountability, and a focus on long-term prevention. They treat mistakes as a learning opportunity. Mid: The candidate admits to the mistake and fixes it but doesn't show a strong focus on preventing it from happening again. They are reactive. Bad: The candidate is defensive and avoids taking responsibility. They blame external factors instead of reflecting on their own actions. Structure check: Good: The response follows the classic 'admit, fix, prevent' structure. It is very effective for demonstrating professional growth. Mid: The response focuses mostly on the fix itself. It lacks a clear 'lesson learned' component. Bad: The response is evasive and does not provide a clear narrative of the error or the resolution. Depth check: Good: The candidate describes a specific technical error and a specific prevention strategy. They show awareness of team communication. Mid: The error described is very simple and the resolution is basic. It doesn't show much depth of thought. Bad: No detail is provided about the mistake or the recovery process. The answer is dismissive of the question's premise. Clarity check: Good: The candidate speaks clearly and professionally about a difficult topic. They remain calm and objective throughout the story. Mid: The language is fine but the story is a bit generic. It sounds like a rehearsed answer rather than a genuine reflection. Bad: The language is defensive or vague. It is hard to get a clear picture of what actually happened. Relevance to role: Good: In the job, small mistakes can have big impacts, so this level of honesty and prevention is vital. This candidate is highly trustworthy. Mid: The candidate is typical for a junior role. They will fix their errors but might need help establishing better systems of self-check. Bad: This candidate is a liability. Their refusal to admit mistakes means they won't learn from them and might hide them in the future.|6|Describe a time you made a mistake on a project and the steps you took to correct it?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect schema compliance and question ID mapping.\", \"Excellent adherence to internal rubric labeling (Good/Mid/Bad) across all sections.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers representing the junior level.\", \"Diverse dimensions covered across behavioral, situational, and specific types.\"]|a68bbf7d5ad36e808d24c6374acd6c7e66860a42|52b717ae2008be0897adef3eb032bcc0c96bcf2e|Data Engineer|15|6c6baefb2d9bafe6a9f14fb2081775e6d0bb8578|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262493Z
Data Engineer|Junior \\n- 0 to 2 years experience / fresh grad\\n- Knows fundamentals of data pipelines and databases\\n- Has done projects or internships\\n- Not expected to design large-scale systems end-to-end\" |B|7|Behavioral ​|I usually just focus on my own work to make sure it's perfect, as I don't want to get distracted by other people's problems. If a teammate is struggling, I assume they will ask the manager for help because that's what the manager is there for. I don't want to overstep my bounds or make them feel bad.|A teammate was having trouble with a specific coding logic that I had used in a previous project. I finished my own tasks an hour early and offered to sit with them to walk through the logic step-by-step. Instead of doing it for them, I asked questions to lead them to the solution, which helped them understand the concept better and finish their work on time.|My coworker was falling behind on their documentation because they had too many other meetings. I noticed they were stressed, so I offered to take over a few of their easier pages to help them catch up. We finished the whole project by the deadline because I helped out.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a high level of team spirit and an effective 'teaching' approach to mentorship. They understand that helping others improves the whole team. Mid: The candidate is helpful and kind but their approach is more about doing the work for others rather than helping them grow. It is a helpful but less impactful approach. Bad: The candidate is individualistic and lacks empathy for their teammates. They don't see the value in supporting others for the good of the project. Structure check: Good: The response clearly identifies the need, the specific action taken, and the positive outcome for the team. It is a well-rounded story. Mid: The story is simple and lacks detail about the interaction. It is clear but not particularly compelling. Bad: The response does not describe an act of helping. It is a statement of personal policy rather than a story. Depth check: Good: The candidate describes a specific mentoring technique (asking leading questions). They show they understand how to help effectively without creating dependency. Mid: The candidate provides basic details about the task they took over. It is a surface-level description of a simple favor. Bad: There is no depth because there is no story. The candidate avoids the core of the question. Clarity check: Good: The language is warm and professional. It reflects a person who is easy to work with and articulate in their support. Mid: The language is clear and straightforward. It is a standard professional response. Bad: The language is somewhat cold and dismissive. It makes the candidate seem unapproachable. Relevance to role: Good: This person would be a great addition to any team culture. They help build a supportive and efficient environment. Mid: They are a good team player who will help out when they can. They are a solid junior hire. Bad: They might be technically skilled but could hurt the overall team dynamic. Their lack of support for others is a concern.|7|Tell me about a time you helped a teammate who was struggling with their portion of a shared assignment?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect schema compliance and question ID mapping.\", \"Excellent adherence to internal rubric labeling (Good/Mid/Bad) across all sections.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers representing the junior level.\", \"Diverse dimensions covered across behavioral, situational, and specific types.\"]|a68bbf7d5ad36e808d24c6374acd6c7e66860a42|52b717ae2008be0897adef3eb032bcc0c96bcf2e|Data Engineer|16|6c6baefb2d9bafe6a9f14fb2081775e6d0bb8578|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262493Z
Data Engineer|Junior \\n- 0 to 2 years experience / fresh grad\\n- Knows fundamentals of data pipelines and databases\\n- Has done projects or internships\\n- Not expected to design large-scale systems end-to-end\" |B|8|Specific|I usually just try to run the process again several times to see if it was just a temporary glitch. If it keeps failing, I would tell my supervisor that the pipeline is broken and wait for them to give me instructions on how to fix it. I don't want to touch the code and make the problem even worse.|I start by checking the logs for the most recent run to see where exactly the execution failed. If the error isn't clear, I try to run the pipeline with a very small sample of data to see if it's a data-quality issue or a logic error in the code. I also check the connections to the source database to make sure it's not a simple network or permission problem.|I would look at the last few changes that were made to the code to see if something new caused the break. I would also try restarting the system to see if that fixes the issue automatically. If I can't find it in ten minutes, I would search for the error message on the internet to see if someone else has solved it.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a logical and systematic approach to technical troubleshooting. They know how to isolate variables and use diagnostic data. Mid: The candidate has a few basic troubleshooting ideas but relies heavily on external help or trial and error. Their approach is less disciplined. Bad: The candidate is afraid to troubleshoot and lacks the basic logic needed to identify a root cause. They are too dependent on supervision. Structure check: Good: The response is organized as a step-by-step diagnostic tree. It shows how the candidate moves from high-level checks to detailed analysis. Mid: The response is a bit scattered and suggests a few random things to try. It doesn't feel like a cohesive process. Bad: The response is a single-step 'report and wait' strategy. It lacks any diagnostic structure. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific technical actions like log analysis, data sampling, and connection checks. They understand the layers of a data system. Mid: The candidate mentions checking code changes or searching online. These are valid but less sophisticated than a true diagnostic process. Bad: No technical depth is provided. The candidate doesn't seem to know what parts of a system could fail. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's technical explanation is clear and easy to follow. They communicate their logic in a professional manner. Mid: The language is a bit informal and the explanation is somewhat vague. It is understandable but not precise. Bad: The answer is confusing or indicates a lack of technical understanding. Relevance to role: Good: Debugging is a daily part of the job, and this candidate shows they can handle it independently. They are a strong technical fit for a junior role. Mid: The candidate can do basic troubleshooting but will need a lot of guidance for complex issues. They are at an entry-level stage. Bad: The candidate is not ready for the technical responsibilities of the job. Their lack of troubleshooting skills would be a major hurdle.|8|Walk me through your process for finding the root cause of a broken pipeline that stopped producing output?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect schema compliance and question ID mapping.\", \"Excellent adherence to internal rubric labeling (Good/Mid/Bad) across all sections.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers representing the junior level.\", \"Diverse dimensions covered across behavioral, situational, and specific types.\"]|a68bbf7d5ad36e808d24c6374acd6c7e66860a42|52b717ae2008be0897adef3eb032bcc0c96bcf2e|Data Engineer|17|6c6baefb2d9bafe6a9f14fb2081775e6d0bb8578|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262493Z
Data Engineer|Junior \\n- 0 to 2 years experience / fresh grad\\n- Knows fundamentals of data pipelines and databases\\n- Has done projects or internships\\n- Not expected to design large-scale systems end-to-end\" |B|9|Specific|I usually just try to load the data as it is and see if the database gives me any errors. If it fails, I look at the error message and try to fix that one thing and then try again. I don't think you need to clean data unless the system actually breaks because it's too much work.|I would first perform a schema check to make sure the incoming data matches the expected format and types. Next, I would apply cleaning rules like handling nulls, trimming whitespace, and deduplicating records based on a unique ID. Finally, I would apply any necessary business logic transformations, like converting currency or date formats, before doing a final count check and loading the data.|I would start by looking at the data to see what looks messy and then write some code to fix those specific things. I would make sure the column names match the destination table and then just run the load command. I try to keep it simple so I don't overcomplicate the process.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate understands the fundamental steps of data processing and the importance of quality. They show a disciplined approach to building workflows. Mid: The candidate understands that data needs to be 'fixed' but lacks a formal structure for doing so. Their approach is reactive to the specific data they see. Bad: The candidate lacks a basic understanding of data hygiene. They view cleaning as an optional step rather than a core requirement. Structure check: Good: The response follows a logical sequence: validation, cleaning, transformation, and final check. This is a very professional workflow. Mid: The response is a bit loose and doesn't clearly separate the different stages of the process. It feels like a single big task. Bad: The response is disorganized and suggests a 'trial by fire' approach to loading data. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific cleaning actions like deduplication, null handling, and date formatting. They understand the common pitfalls of raw data. Mid: The candidate mentions 'fixing messy things' but doesn't specify what those things are. The level of detail is low. Bad: No technical depth is provided. The answer shows a lack of experience with data manipulation. Clarity check: Good: The technical steps are explained clearly and the candidate uses industry-standard terms correctly. They are easy to understand. Mid: The explanation is a bit vague and uses non-technical language. It's okay but could be much sharper. Bad: The explanation is confusing and reflects a lack of technical knowledge. Relevance to role: Good: This is a core part of the job's workflow. This candidate has a strong grasp of the fundamentals and can be trusted with data tasks. Mid: The candidate has a basic understanding but will need training on best practices and standardization. They are a typical junior. Bad: The candidate's approach would lead to poor data quality in the warehouse. They are not currently prepared for this role.|9|Explain how you would structure a basic task to clean and transform raw data before loading it into a table?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect schema compliance and question ID mapping.\", \"Excellent adherence to internal rubric labeling (Good/Mid/Bad) across all sections.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers representing the junior level.\", \"Diverse dimensions covered across behavioral, situational, and specific types.\"]|a68bbf7d5ad36e808d24c6374acd6c7e66860a42|52b717ae2008be0897adef3eb032bcc0c96bcf2e|Data Engineer|18|6c6baefb2d9bafe6a9f14fb2081775e6d0bb8578|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262493Z
Data Engineer|Junior \\n- 0 to 2 years experience / fresh grad\\n- Knows fundamentals of data pipelines and databases\\n- Has done projects or internships\\n- Not expected to design large-scale systems end-to-end\" |B|10|Situational​|I would just pick the task that I find more interesting or the one that is easier to do first. I wouldn't say anything to the other person because I don't want to start an argument or make them think I'm lazy. If they ask where their work is later, I'll just say I was too busy with the other thing.|I would start by clarifying the true deadline and the estimated time required for each task to see if there is any natural overlap. I would then explain the situation to both team members and ask for their help in prioritizing based on which task has a bigger impact on the overall project goal. If we still couldn't agree, I would take the information to my direct manager to make the final decision.|I would try my best to work faster and stay late so I could finish both tasks by the deadline without bothering anyone. If I realized I definitely couldn't finish both, I would tell the person who gave me the second task that I might be a little bit late. I usually try to keep everyone happy by saying yes.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates strong communication skills and an ability to prioritize based on business value. They know when to escalate a problem. Mid: The candidate is hardworking but takes on too much pressure themselves rather than communicating. They are at risk of burnout or low-quality work. Bad: The candidate is passive-aggressive and lacks transparency. They don't know how to manage their time or communicate expectations. Structure check: Good: The response shows a clear progression: analyze, communicate, and escalate if necessary. It is a very mature approach to time management. Mid: The response focuses only on 'working harder' and doesn't show a clear plan for managing the conflict. It is a bit one-dimensional. Bad: The response lacks any constructive structure. It is a description of how to avoid the problem rather than solve it. Depth check: Good: The candidate considers factors like business impact and time estimation. They show a realistic understanding of workplace dynamics. Mid: The candidate only considers 'working faster' as a solution. They don't show much depth in terms of organizational awareness. Bad: The answer is superficial and suggests a lack of professional responsibility. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their reasoning clearly and professionally. Their strategy for communication is well-articulated. Mid: The explanation is clear enough but the logic is a bit flawed. It's understandable but not ideal. Bad: The explanation is vague and shows a lack of integrity in how they manage their work. Relevance to role: Good: Prioritization is key in a project-based environment, and this candidate handles it perfectly. They would be a reliable and communicative team member. Mid: They are a standard junior who might struggle with boundaries. They will need a manager who checks in on their workload frequently. Bad: This candidate would likely miss deadlines and fail to communicate, which is a major risk for the team.|10|How would you handle a situation where two different team members assigned you urgent tasks due at the same time?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect schema compliance and question ID mapping.\", \"Excellent adherence to internal rubric labeling (Good/Mid/Bad) across all sections.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers representing the junior level.\", \"Diverse dimensions covered across behavioral, situational, and specific types.\"]|a68bbf7d5ad36e808d24c6374acd6c7e66860a42|52b717ae2008be0897adef3eb032bcc0c96bcf2e|Data Engineer|19|6c6baefb2d9bafe6a9f14fb2081775e6d0bb8578|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262493Z
