es, and tracers. They provide a high level of detail for each step. Mid: The candidate provides very general steps without explaining how they are performed. The answer feels a bit 'textbook' and lacks personal experience. Bad: The response is very brief and shows no depth of thought. It indicates that the candidate has not spent much time debugging their own work. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their thought process clearly and concisely. The interviewer can easily visualize the candidate working through the problem. Mid: The candidate's explanation is a bit repetitive or uses vague terms. The communication is adequate but could be more professional. Bad: The candidate's description is confusing and suggests they don't really know what they are doing. The lack of clarity is a reflection of their disorganized approach. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate possesses the critical thinking skills essential for this job. They are capable of handling the daily challenges of the project. Mid: The candidate shows potential but will likely take longer to solve problems than a more organized peer. They would benefit from mentorship on the team. Bad: The candidate's current problem-solving habits would likely slow down the project. They do not yet demonstrate the fundamental logic required for the role.|4|Walk me through the logical steps you take when you encounter an unexpected error in your code that you cannot immediately identify?|PASS|98|[\"Strict adherence to rubric structure with per-section Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single-sentence interrogatives.\", \"Excellent differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"High level of detail and relevance across all competencies.\"]|587130c33cd5bb6372e4988375795256f0f22138|d06650cf7f058a41ecd0b8dc33cf0c4886e8f503|Software Developer|23|1db4a2612ce41bf150139064e08c85a4ff5a6035|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255482Z
