 Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details on how they would communicate (e.g., listing assumptions). They show they understand the importance of being efficient. Mid: The candidate gives a general answer about trying hard and eventually asking for help. It lacks the detail needed to show they can handle ambiguity. Bad: The response is very shallow and suggests the candidate has not encountered this common workplace situation before. They offer no real solution. Clarity check: Good: The candidate’s communication is direct and professional. Their plan is easy to understand and sounds like a realistic approach for the job. Mid: The candidate uses some vague language that makes their plan sound a bit uncertain. The communication is clear enough to understand the intent but lacks confidence. Bad: The candidate is unable to articulate a clear plan of action. Their response is confusing and doesn't directly answer how they would meet the deadline. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can navigate the typical ambiguities of a junior-level project. They demonstrate the proactive attitude needed to succeed. Mid: The candidate shows they are willing to work but might need a lot of hand-holding. They are an acceptable fit but will require close supervision. Bad: The candidate’s passive approach is not suitable for a fast-paced environment. They would likely struggle in a role that requires any level of independence.|5|How would you handle a situation where you are given a task with a tight deadline but the instructions are unclear?|PASS|98|[\"Strict adherence to rubric structure with per-section Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single-sentence interrogatives.\", \"Excellent differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"High level of detail and relevance across all competencies.\"]|587130c33cd5bb6372e4988375795256f0f22138|d06650cf7f058a41ecd0b8dc33cf0c4886e8f503|Software Developer|24|1db4a2612ce41bf150139064e08c85a4ff5a6035|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255482Z
Software Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nKnows fundamentals of programming, data structures, and basic software development practices\\nHas done projects or internships\\nNot expected to design complex systems end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I usually don't like it when requirements change because it makes my previous work feel like a waste of time. I usually just keep working on what I was doing until someone tells me I absolutely have to stop and switch.|In a recent project, our goal shifted from building a full-featured prototype to creating a simple demonstration for a stakeholder. I immediately re-prioritized my tasks to focus only on the core functionality that was needed for the demo. By adjusting my timeline and simplifying the design, I was able to deliver the work on time despite the late change.|We once had to change the way we were doing a task halfway through because the client wanted something else. I just stopped what I was doing and started the new task, but it was a bit frustrating because I had already done a lot of work.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates adaptability and a focus on the final goal of the project. They show they can handle shifting priorities without losing productivity. Mid: The candidate shows they can follow new directions but lacks a positive or proactive mindset. They focus more on the inconvenience than the solution. Bad: The candidate is resistant to change and demonstrates a lack of flexibility. This attitude can be detrimental to a team that needs to be agile and responsive. Structure check: Good: The candidate uses the STAR method to show how they identified the change and adjusted their workflow. The narrative is cohesive and focuses on results. Mid: The response is a bit brief and doesn't clearly show the steps taken to adjust. It describes the situation but skips over the 'action' part of the structure. Bad: The response is unstructured and focuses on the candidate's personal feelings rather than the project. It doesn't provide a clear example of adaptation. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the specific trade-offs they made to meet the new deadline. They demonstrate a high level of professional judgment. Mid: The candidate provides only a surface-level description of the change. They do not show much insight into how they managed their time or resources during the transition. Bad: The response is very shallow and lacks any specific details. It does not provide any evidence that the candidate actually changed their behavior. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains the situation and their response in a clear, professional manner. Their language is well-chosen and the story is easy to follow. Mid: The candidate’s language is a bit informal and the story is somewhat vague. The main points are conveyed but the communication lacks precision. Bad: The candidate is unable to clearly describe the situation or their reaction. The lack of clarity makes it hard to judge their actual performance in the scenario. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they have the resilience and flexibility needed for the job. They are a great fit for a team that experiences frequent updates. Mid: The candidate is capable of following orders but might struggle with morale during changes. They meet the basic requirements but may need encouragement. Bad: The candidate’s resistance to change would make them a difficult fit for the project. They do not show the adaptability expected of a junior professional.|6|Can you describe a time when a project requirement changed suddenly and how you adjusted your approach to meet the new goal?|PASS|98|[\"Strict adherence to rubric structure with per-section Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single-sentence interrogatives.\", \"Excellent differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"High level of detail and relevance across all competencies.\"]|587130c33cd5bb6372e4988375795256f0f22138|d06650cf7f058a41ecd0b8dc33cf0c4886e8f503|Software Developer|25|1db4a2612ce41bf150139064e08c85a4ff5a6035|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255482Z
Software Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nKnows fundamentals of programming, data structures, and basic software development practices\\nHas done projects or internships\\nNot expected to design complex systems end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I usually just follow the processes that are already there because I am new and don't want to overstep. I figure the seniors know the best way to do things, so I just do my own work and don't worry about the team's process.|During a project, I noticed that we were spending too much time searching for project files in different folders. I suggested a standardized naming convention and a central directory structure to the team, which everyone agreed to. I then spent an hour organizing the existing files, which saved us a lot of time during the final weeks of the project.|I thought our team meetings were a bit too long, so I mentioned it to my lead once. They started using a timer after that, and the meetings got a little bit faster, which was better for everyone's schedule.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates initiative and a desire to contribute to the overall success of the team. They show they can identify inefficiencies and propose solutions. Mid: The candidate shows they can identify problems but takes a more passive role in fixing them. They rely on others to do the actual implementation of the change. Bad: The candidate lacks initiative and does not see it as their role to improve things. This shows a lack of engagement with the project and the team. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear path from observation to proposal and then implementation and results. It is a very well-structured behavioral answer. Mid: The response is a bit short and misses the 'implementation' part of the candidate's own actions. It attributes the success more to the leader than the candidate. Bad: The response is unstructured and doesn't provide a real example of the candidate doing anything proactive. It is a statement of philosophy rather than a story. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about the problem and the time saved. They show they took ownership of the task to make it happen. Mid: The candidate gives a general idea of a problem but doesn't go into detail about how they identified it. The result is also described in vague terms. Bad: The response is very shallow and lacks any substance. It shows a lack of critical thinking about how work is performed on a team. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their idea and the process clearly. The communication is professional and demonstrates a high level of confidence. Mid: The candidate’s explanation is a bit vague and doesn't quite show the 'spark' of initiative. The message is clear but not particularly compelling. Bad: The candidate struggles to explain their thoughts and the response is very brief. The lack of clarity reflects a lack of experience in thinking about process improvement. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows the proactive mindset that adds value to any project. They are a strong choice for a team that wants to grow and improve. Mid: The candidate is a solid team player but might not be the one to drive change. They are a safe but somewhat uninspiring choice for the role. Bad: The candidate’s passive attitude is not ideal for a project that requires active participation. They do not show the engagement needed to be a high performer.|7|Tell me about a time you identified a way to improve a process within your team and how you implemented that change?|PASS|98|[\"Strict adherence to rubric structure with per-section Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single-sentence interrogatives.\", \"Excellent differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"High level of detail and relevance across all competencies.\"]|587130c33cd5bb6372e4988375795256f0f22138|d06650cf7f058a41ecd0b8dc33cf0c4886e8f503|Software Developer|26|1db4a2612ce41bf150139064e08c85a4ff5a6035|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255482Z
Software Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nKnows fundamentals of programming, data structures, and basic software development practices\\nHas done projects or internships\\nNot expected to design complex systems end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I usually just finish the work and send it over immediately because I want to move on to the next task. I figure the reviewer will find any problems anyway, so I don't need to spend extra time checking it myself.|I start by running all existing automated tests to make sure I haven't caused any regressions. Then, I manually walk through each requirement in the task description to verify that the feature behaves as expected. Finally, I do a self-review of the code to check for edge cases and ensure the logic is clean and easy to read.|I usually just run the code on my machine to see if it works for the specific case I was working on. If it looks good and doesn't crash, I assume it is ready and send it over to the reviewer to check for any mistakes I might have missed.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a strong commitment to quality and a disciplined approach to their work. They take pride in delivering work that is as error-free as possible. Mid: The candidate has a basic check process but relies too heavily on the reviewer to catch errors. They show some care but lack a thorough methodology. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of responsibility for their own work. Their approach is inefficient and places an unfair burden on the rest of the team. Structure check: Good: The response is a logical list of quality control steps that progress from automated to manual and then to self-review. It shows a very professional mindset. Mid: The response mentions a couple of things they do but doesn't feel like a comprehensive process. It is a bit disorganized and focuses only on the easiest checks. Bad: The response is unstructured and reflects a chaotic way of working. It shows no evidence of a planned approach to quality assurance. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific types of checks like regression testing and edge case analysis. They show they understand the different ways code can fail. Mid: The candidate provides surface-level details about running the code. They don't mention any specific techniques or tools they use to ensure quality. Bad: The response is very shallow and shows a lack of understanding of professional standards. It indicates that the candidate is not very detail-oriented. Clarity check: Good: The candidate’s explanation is clear and uses professional terminology correctly. It is easy for the interviewer to understand exactly what the candidate does. Mid: The candidate uses informal language that is a bit vague. While the intent is clear, the communication lacks the precision of a professional. Bad: The candidate is unable to describe their process in a way that makes sense. The lack of clarity is a reflection of their lack of process. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate is a highly reliable individual who will produce high-quality work for the project. They are an excellent fit for the technical requirements of the job. Mid: The candidate is capable but will need to be taught more rigorous self-review habits. They are an acceptable fit but will require more feedback from seniors. Bad: The candidate’s current habits would likely lead to a high rate of errors in the codebase. They do not show the technical discipline required for the role.|8|Describe the specific methods or checks you use to ensure your code is functional and meets requirements before you hand it over for review?|PASS|98|[\"Strict adherence to rubric structure with per-section Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single-sentence interrogatives.\", \"Excellent differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"High level of detail and relevance across all competencies.\"]|587130c33cd5bb6372e4988375795256f0f22138|d06650cf7f058a41ecd0b8dc33cf0c4886e8f503|Software Developer|27|1db4a2612ce41bf150139064e08c85a4ff5a6035|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255482Z
Software Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nKnows fundamentals of programming, data structures, and basic software development practices\\nHas done projects or internships\\nNot expected to design complex systems end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I don't think documentation is very important if the code is written clearly. I usually just add a few comments in the file itself and assume that whoever reads it will be able to figure out how it works.|I believe good documentation should include a clear summary of what the feature does and why it was created. It is also essential to list any dependencies, provide a brief guide on how to use it, and include notes on any specific edge cases or limitations that I encountered during development.|I usually just write a short description of what the code does and maybe include an example of how to run it. I try to keep it brief so that people can read it quickly and get back to their own work.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate understands the importance of documentation for team collaboration and long-term project maintenance. They show they think about the needs of others. Mid: The candidate sees documentation as a chore to be finished quickly. They provide the bare minimum and don't consider the perspective of a future reader. Bad: The candidate does not value documentation at all and believes their code should speak for itself. This is a common but dangerous mindset for a team-based project. Structure check: Good: The response is a well-categorized list of information types (purpose, usage, limits). It shows an organized mind that can communicate complex ideas. Mid: The response lists a few items but doesn't have a clear framework for what makes documentation effective. It feels a bit like an afterthought. Bad: The response is unstructured and dismissive. It does not provide any useful information about how to document a project effectively. Depth check: Good: The candidate includes details like dependencies and edge cases, which shows they have a deep understanding of the project lifecycle. They think beyond the immediate task. Mid: The candidate provides only the most basic components of documentation. They miss out on the context and the technical details that make documentation truly useful. Bad: The response is extremely shallow and shows a lack of professional experience. It indicates that the candidate does not understand how projects are managed over time. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their views on documentation clearly and professionally. Their language is precise and shows they value clear communication. Mid: The candidate’s explanation is a bit vague and they use informal language. The message is understandable but lacks professional weight. Bad: The candidate struggles to articulate why documentation matters or what it should contain. The lack of clarity reflects their lack of interest in the topic. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate will contribute to the long-term health of the project through their documentation. They are a strong fit for a team that values knowledge sharing. Mid: The candidate will need some guidance on the team's documentation standards. They are a solid choice but will need to be encouraged to be more thorough. Bad: The candidate’s attitude toward documentation would be a liability for the team. They do not show the collaborative mindset needed for the job.|9|What information do you believe is essential to include when writing documentation for a feature you have just finished developing?|PASS|98|[\"Strict adherence to rubric structure with per-section Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single-sentence interrogatives.\", \"Excellent differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"High level of detail and relevance across all competencies.\"]|587130c33cd5bb6372e4988375795256f0f22138|d06650cf7f058a41ecd0b8dc33cf0c4886e8f503|Software Developer|28|1db4a2612ce41bf150139064e08c85a4ff5a6035|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255482Z
Software Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nKnows fundamentals of programming, data structures, and basic software development practices\\nHas done projects or internships\\nNot expected to design complex systems end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would probably feel a bit hurt if I worked hard on it, so I might just stay quiet for the rest of the meeting. I would eventually fix the work but I wouldn't really talk to that person about it again for a while because it would be awkward.|I would first listen carefully to the feedback and thank them for taking the time to review my work. I would ask clarifying questions to make sure I fully understand their perspective and the improvements they are suggesting. Then, I would incorporate the feedback into my work as a learning opportunity to improve my skills.|I would be a little bit disappointed at first, but I would listen to what they have to say. I would fix the parts they mentioned, even if I still thought my original way was okay, just to keep the project moving.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a growth mindset and professional maturity. They show they can handle criticism without it affecting their productivity or relationships. Mid: The candidate accepts the feedback but does not show a clear plan to use it for personal growth. They are professional but somewhat defensive in their mindset. Bad: The candidate takes criticism personally and allows it to affect their morale and communication. This can create a toxic or unproductive dynamic on the team. Structure check: Good: The response is structured logically, starting with the immediate reaction and ending with the action taken. It flows naturally from one step to the next. Mid: The response is a bit fragmented and doesn't clearly show the progression from receiving feedback to changing behavior. It hits the main points but lacks a narrative. Bad: The response is unstructured and focuses mostly on the candidate's feelings. It is hard to follow what the candidate actually did with the information provided. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides a detailed explanation of why they value the feedback process. They reflect on the importance of the senior member's experience and mentorship. Mid: The candidate provides a brief summary of the feedback and says they followed it. There is not much detail about the specific value they see in getting critiques. Bad: The response is very superficial and does not address the impact of the feedback at all. It feels like a standard, unreflective answer that avoids the core issue. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses precise language to describe their internal thoughts and external actions. The explanation is easy to understand and well-articulated. Mid: The candidate's language is somewhat vague, making it harder to visualize the situation. Some sentences are a bit repetitive or slightly unclear in their meaning. Bad: The candidate struggles to explain their reaction clearly and uses confusing or unprofessional language. The interviewer is left with many unanswered questions about their attitude. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they are a strong fit for a collaborative team environment where peer review is common. They demonstrate the coachability necessary for a junior member. Mid: The candidate shows they can handle basic feedback but might struggle with more significant critiques. They are an acceptable fit but may need support in building resilience. Bad: The candidate’s reaction suggests they would be difficult to manage or train. They do not demonstrate the openness to learning required for the project.|10|Describe how you would respond if a senior team member gave you critical feedback on a piece of work you were proud of?|PASS|98|[\"Strict adherence to rubric structure with per-section Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single-sentence interrogatives.\", \"Excellent differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"High level of detail and relevance across all competencies.\"]|587130c33cd5bb6372e4988375795256f0f22138|d06650cf7f058a41ecd0b8dc33cf0c4886e8f503|Software Developer|29|1db4a2612ce41bf150139064e08c85a4ff5a6035|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255482Z
Consultant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic consulting concepts and problem-solving frameworks\\nHas done case studies, internships, or project-based work\\nNot expected to lead client engagements or design end-to-end strategies|A|1|Behavioral ​|I worked with someone who didn't agree with my way of doing things, so I just did my part of the project separately. We didn't really talk much after that, and I made sure my section was perfect so that I wouldn't be blamed for any issues. The project got finished, but the team didn't really work well together during the final week.|During a group project, a teammate and I disagreed on the best way to present our final findings to the client. I suggested we use a data-heavy approach, while they preferred a more narrative and visual style. I scheduled a quick meeting for us to review the initial project requirements together, and we eventually agreed to combine both methods by using clear charts supported by a strong narrative. This collaborative solution ensured all stakeholders were satisfied and the project was successfully delivered.|I once had a disagreement with a coworker about which tasks should be prioritized for our weekly deadline. We discussed our different viewpoints for a while, but eventually, I decided to just follow their lead to avoid further conflict. While the project was completed on time, I feel like we could have found a better balance if we had spent more time looking at the actual project goals together.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The candidate demonstrates a clear understanding of conflict resolution as a tool for team success. They focus on professional outcomes rather than personal feelings.\\nMid: The candidate identifies that conflict occurred but focuses more on compromise than on active problem-solving. They show basic awareness of the need for harmony but lack a strategic approach.\\nBad: The candidate ignores the professional implications of the conflict or avoids the issue entirely. They fail to see the importance of resolving issues for the project's sake.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The response follows a clear STAR method with a defined situation, task, action, and result. The actions taken are specific and lead directly to the positive outcome.\\nMid: The candidate provides a general overview of the event but misses either the specific action or the final result. The narrative is somewhat disjointed but the main point is understandable.\\nBad: The response is a collection of vague statements without a clear beginning, middle, or end. It is difficult to follow the sequence of events or what the candidate actually did.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate provides specific details about the nature of the disagreement and the logic used to resolve it. They reflect on the importance of meeting project requirements through collaboration.\\nMid: The candidate gives a surface-level account of a minor disagreement. They do not explore the underlying causes or provide significant detail on the resolution steps.\\nBad: The answer is extremely brief and lacks any detail regarding the candidate's personal contribution. It feels like a generic response not based on a real experience.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The language used is professional, clear, and easy to follow. The candidate avoids unnecessary filler and focuses on the most relevant information.\\nMid: The candidate uses some repetitive language or takes a long time to get to the point. The main message is present but requires effort from the listener to extract.\\nBad: The response is confusing or uses overly complex sentences that obscure the meaning. The interviewer is left unsure of what the candidate's actual role in the situation was.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The candidate shows the ability to work effectively in a team environment, which is crucial for the job. They demonstrate the maturity needed to handle professional friction.\\nMid: The candidate shows they can function in a team but might require guidance when high-pressure conflicts arise. Their approach is standard and does not show high initiative.\\nBad: The candidate's approach suggests they might be a source of friction or lack the communication skills for the team. Their behavior does not align with the collaborative nature of the project.|1|Describe a time when you had a significant disagreement with a teammate during a project and how you went about resolving it?|PASS|98|[\"Complete and accurate mapping of all question IDs and dimensions.\", \"Rubrics fully comply with the complex per-section label requirements.\", \"High-quality content with clear differentiation between answer levels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted and perfectly appropriate for the specified level.\"]|85238ba120005c77b7b432e62d1448be8f7b938b|16ad43a7dd3932f91e8d6795532811dedf4bec61|Consultant|30|9d27fba9b43c4bef720ca9a86fcdde02dbe6006d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.256118Z
Consultant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic consulting concepts and problem-solving frameworks\\nHas done case studies, internships, or project-based work\\nNot expected to lead client engagements or design end-to-end strategies|A|2|Behavioral ​|I made a mistake once on a task, but it wasn't a very big deal so I didn't say anything about it at the time. I just fixed it quietly later on so that no one would notice that I had messed up in the first place. Eventually, the project turned out fine and my manager never found out that there had been an issue with my initial work.|In my previous internship, I accidentally sent an internal draft of a report to a stakeholder before it was finalized. As soon as I realized the error, I contacted my manager to inform them and then sent a follow-up email to the stakeholder apologizing and providing the correct version. I also created a new checklist for myself to ensure that I double-check recipient lists and document versions before hitting send in the future.|I once made a mistake on a calculation for a project, which led to some incorrect results in our final presentation. Once I found the error, I told my team leader about it and they helped me fix the numbers before we had to present to the class. It was an embarrassing moment, but I made sure to be more careful with my spreadsheets after that happened.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The candidate takes full ownership of the mistake and focuses on the corrective actions and the lesson learned. They demonstrate accountability and a proactive mindset.\\nMid: The candidate admits to the mistake but relies heavily on others to help fix the problem. They show some accountability but lack a self-driven approach to prevention.\\nBad: The candidate minimizes the mistake or attempts to hide it from their supervisor. They fail to demonstrate the transparency and integrity required for the project.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The response clearly identifies the mistake, the immediate reaction, the solution, and the long-term preventative measure. The flow is logical and emphasizes the candidate's growth.\\nMid: The candidate describes the mistake and the fix but skips the part about how they will prevent it from happening again. The structure is adequate but incomplete.\\nBad: The response is disorganized and does not clearly explain what the mistake was or how it was eventually resolved. It focuses more on the feeling of making a mistake than the actions taken.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate provides specific details about the context of the mistake and the exact steps taken to remedy the situation. They show a high level of self-reflection.\\nMid: The candidate provides a vague description of the mistake. The details about the resolution are thin and do not show a deep understanding of why the mistake occurred.\\nBad: The answer is very short and lacks any meaningful detail. It does not provide the listener with enough information to judge the candidate's problem-solving skills.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate explains the situation using clear and concise language. They remain professional and objective throughout the entire explanation.\\nMid: The candidate uses some informal language or tangents that distract from the main story. The core message is clear but the delivery could be more polished.\\nBad: The candidate rambles or uses confusing terminology that makes it hard to understand what went wrong. The response lacks the professional tone expected for the job.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The candidate demonstrates the high level of responsibility and attention to detail needed for a junior position. They show they can handle errors professionally without panicking.\\nMid: The candidate shows they are capable of acknowledging faults but might need more supervision to ensure mistakes are caught and corrected early. They are an acceptable but not strong fit.\\nBad: The candidate's lack of transparency is a significant red flag for the team. Their approach to error management does not align with professional standards.|2|Tell me about a time you made a mistake at work or school and explain the steps you took to correct the situation?|PASS|98|[\"Complete and accurate mapping of all question IDs and dimensions.\", \"Rubrics fully comply with the complex per-section label requirements.\", \"High-quality content with clear differentiation between answer levels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted and perfectly appropriate for the specified level.\"]|85238ba120005c77b7b432e62d1448be8f7b938b|16ad43a7dd3932f91e8d6795532811dedf4bec61|Consultant|31|9d27fba9b43c4bef720ca9a86fcdde02dbe6006d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.256118Z
Consultant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic consulting concepts and problem-solving frameworks\\nHas done case studies, internships, or project-based work\\nNot expected to lead client engagements or design end-to-end strategies|A|3|Specific|I just use a search engine to find the information I need and I usually go with the first few results because they are the most popular. I don't really have a formal process for checking the sources, but I assume that if it's on a major website, the data must be accurate enough for our purposes.|When I start a new project, I first identify primary sources such as official reports and reputable industry databases. I always cross-reference any data I find with at least one other independent source to ensure consistency and check for any potential biases. Finally, I document the date and origin of every data point to ensure that the information is current and can be easily verified by other members of the team.|I usually search for data on well-known websites and pick the most recent articles I can find. I try to make sure the data looks reasonable compared to other things I have read, and I save the links to the websites in case my manager wants to see where I got the information from for the project.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The candidate understands the importance of data integrity and has a structured process for validation. They show they are thorough and recognize the risks of using poor data.\\nMid: The candidate has a basic understanding of data reliability but lacks a rigorous or repeatable process. They rely more on intuition than on structured verification methods.\\nBad: The candidate shows a lack of concern for data accuracy and source credibility. They prioritize speed over quality, which is a major risk for the project.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate provides a logical, step-by-step workflow that moves from identification to verification and documentation. The process is easy to follow and replicate.\\nMid: The candidate mentions a few different actions they take but does not present them as a cohesive or organized process. The steps feel a bit haphazard.\\nBad: The response lacks any clear structure or methodology. The candidate seems to approach the task in an ad-hoc manner without any planning.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate mentions specific techniques like cross-referencing and checking for bias. They demonstrate a sophisticated understanding of what makes data reliable for a professional project.\\nMid: The candidate provides general statements about looking for good websites. They do not go into detail about how they actually evaluate the information they find.\\nBad: The answer is superficial and suggests the candidate does not understand the complexities of professional research. It lacks any specific details on validation techniques.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate uses precise language to describe their research process. They communicate their methodology in a way that is easy for a senior team member to understand.\\nMid: The candidate uses vague terms like 'reasonable' or 'popular' without explaining what those mean in a professional context. The clarity is moderate but needs more precision.\\nBad: The response is poorly articulated and does not clearly convey how the candidate handles data. It is difficult to determine if they actually have a process at all.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The candidate's thorough approach to research and documentation is exactly what is expected from a high-performing junior team member. They show they can be trusted with data tasks.\\nMid: The candidate's approach is acceptable for very simple tasks but might lead to errors on more complex assignments. They would require significant oversight from the team.\\nBad: The candidate's disregard for source verification makes them unsuitable for tasks involving data analysis. Their current habits could compromise the quality of the team's output.|3|Walk me through the steps you take to ensure the data you collect for a new project is accurate and comes from reliable sources?|PASS|98|[\"Complete and accurate mapping of all question IDs and dimensions.\", \"Rubrics fully comply with the complex per-section label requirements.\", \"High-quality content with clear differentiation between answer levels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted and perfectly appropriate for the specified level.\"]|85238ba120005c77b7b432e62d1448be8f7b938b|16ad43a7dd3932f91e8d6795532811dedf4bec61|Consultant|32|9d27fba9b43c4bef720ca9a86fcdde02dbe6006d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.256118Z
Consultant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic consulting concepts and problem-solving frameworks\\nHas done case studies, internships, or project-based work\\nNot expected to lead client engagements or design end-to-end strategies|A|4|Specific|I try to work as carefully as possible while I am doing the task so that I don't have to spend a lot of time reviewing it later. Once I am finished, I usually just do a very quick scan of the final page to make sure everything looks okay and then I send it over so I can move on to the next task.|Before I submit any work, I always step away from the task for a short period to clear my mind so I can review it with fresh eyes. I then perform a three-step check: first, I verify that all numbers and data points match the source material; second, I check for formatting and grammatical consistency; and third, I read the entire document aloud to ensure the logic and flow make sense to an outside reader.|I usually read through my work once or twice after I finish it to make sure there are no typos or obvious mistakes. I also use a spell-checker and look at the main headers to make sure I followed the template that was given to me by my manager at the start of the project.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The candidate shows a high level of diligence and a structured approach to quality control. They understand that their work reflects on the whole team and take steps to ensure high standards.\\nMid: The candidate performs basic checks but lacks a deep or rigorous process for ensuring quality. They depend heavily on automated tools like spell-checkers rather than logical review.\\nBad: The candidate does not see the value in a formal review process and prioritizes speed over accuracy. They expect the senior team member to catch any errors they might have missed.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate describes a clear, multi-stage process for self-review. The transition between different types of checks (data, formatting, logic) is well-defined and logical.\\nMid: The candidate lists a few things they check for but the process is not very organized. It feels more like a casual read-through than a systematic review.\\nBad: The response lacks any clear structure or logical flow. It suggests the candidate does not have a plan for how to catch their own mistakes before submission.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate explains the specific 'why' behind their actions, such as stepping away to gain a fresh perspective. They provide concrete examples of the types of errors they look for.\\nMid: The candidate gives a very basic description of looking for typos. They do not mention checking for logic, consistency, or data accuracy in any detail.\\nBad: The answer is extremely shallow and does not demonstrate any effort to improve the quality of the work. It shows a lack of professional pride in the final output.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate's explanation is highly professional and easy to follow. They present their process in a way that builds confidence in their ability to work independently.\\nMid: The candidate's language is somewhat informal, and the explanation of their process is a bit vague. The message is clear but the presentation could be stronger.\\nBad: The response is disorganized and the candidate's attitude toward quality comes across as dismissive. It is difficult to understand what, if any, checks are actually performed.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: This level of attention to detail is a critical skill for the job. The candidate demonstrates that they can produce reliable work that requires minimal correction from seniors.\\nMid: The candidate's habits are average and would likely lead to occasional errors being passed up the chain. They would need reminders to be more thorough in their reviews.\\nBad: The candidate's current approach to quality control is a liability for the team. Their lack of a review process indicates they may not be ready for the responsibilities of the job.|4|Can you explain the process you use to check your own work for errors before submitting it to a senior team member?|PASS|98|[\"Complete and accurate mapping of all question IDs and dimensions.\", \"Rubrics fully comply with the complex per-section label requirements.\", \"High-quality content with clear differentiation between answer levels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted and perfectly appropriate for the specified level.\"]|85238ba120005c77b7b432e62d1448be8f7b938b|16ad43a7dd3932f91e8d6795532811dedf4bec61|Consultant|33|9d27fba9b43c4bef720ca9a86fcdde02dbe6006d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.256118Z
Consultant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic consulting concepts and problem-solving frameworks\\nHas done case studies, internships, or project-based work\\nNot expected to lead client engagements or design end-to-end strategies|A|5|Situational​|I would just start working on whichever task I received first because that seems like the fairest way to handle it. If I can't finish the second one, I'll just apologize at the end of the day and hope that they understand I was busy with another important assignment from a different stakeholder.|I would first estimate the time required for each task and assess their relative importance to the project's overall goals. Then, I would speak with both stakeholders to explain the situation transparently and see if one of the deadlines could be adjusted. If both remain urgent, I would consult my direct supervisor to help me prioritize based on the team's current needs and resource availability.|I would try my best to finish both tasks by working through my lunch break and staying late if necessary. If it becomes clear that I cannot finish both, I would pick the one that seems more difficult and finish that first, and then I would tell the other stakeholder that I will have their task done by tomorrow morning.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The candidate demonstrates the ability to prioritize based on objective criteria and communicate proactively. They understand the importance of managing expectations rather than just working harder.\\nMid: The candidate's primary strategy is to work harder, which is not sustainable or always effective. They show a willingness to work but lack the communication skills to manage stakeholder expectations.\\nBad: The candidate uses a 'first-come, first-served' approach which ignores the actual importance of the tasks. They fail to communicate until it is too late, which could damage relationships.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The response follows a logical progression: assessment, communication, negotiation, and escalation. Each step is clearly explained and justified based on the scenario.\\nMid: The candidate focuses mostly on the action of doing the work, with communication as an afterthought. The structure is simple but does not cover all the necessary professional steps.\\nBad: The response is very brief and doesn't show a clear plan for managing the situation. It lacks any formal approach to prioritization or professional communication.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate considers multiple factors such as time estimation, project goals, and resource availability. They show they can think about the big picture even when under pressure.\\nMid: The candidate's approach is very tactical and short-term. They do not consider how their choices might affect the project or the stakeholders' overall needs.\\nBad: The answer is superficial and suggests the candidate has not faced this common workplace challenge before. It shows a lack of maturity in handling professional constraints.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate explains their reasoning clearly and uses professional terminology appropriate for the project environment. Their plan is easy to understand and execute.\\nMid: The candidate's explanation is a bit repetitive and focuses too much on the effort of working late. The main strategy for handling the conflict is present but not well-articulated.\\nBad: The response is vague and the candidate sounds unsure of how they would actually solve the problem. The clarity is low and the solution provided is not professional.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The ability to manage competing priorities is essential for success in the job. The candidate shows they have the communication and analytical skills to handle these situations.\\nMid: The candidate has a good work ethic but needs to develop better professional communication and prioritization frameworks. They would require significant guidance from a supervisor.\\nBad: The candidate's approach to prioritization is poorly suited for a professional environment. Their lack of communication would create unnecessary stress for the team and stakeholders.|5|How would you handle a situation where two different stakeholders give you urgent tasks that are both due at the end of the day?|PASS|98|[\"Complete and accurate mapping of all question IDs and dimensions.\", \"Rubrics fully comply with the complex per-section label requirements.\", \"High-quality content with clear differentiation between answer levels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted and perfectly appropriate for the specified level.\"]|85238ba120005c77b7b432e62d1448be8f7b938b|16ad43a7dd3932f91e8d6795532811dedf4bec61|Consultant|34|9d27fba9b43c4bef720ca9a86fcdde02dbe6006d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.256118Z
Consultant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic consulting concepts and problem-solving frameworks\\nHas done case studies, internships, or project-based work\\nNot expected to lead client engagements or design end-to-end strategies|B|6|Behavioral ​|A project I was on changed its goals halfway through, and I found it very frustrating because I had already done a lot of work on the original plan. I kept trying to use some of my old research even though it didn't really fit the new goals anymore, just so my earlier effort wouldn't be wasted. In the end, my section of the project didn't align very well with what the rest of the team did.|During a research project in my final year, the focus shifted from a broad market analysis to a specific study of one competitor due to a change in the sponsor's needs. I immediately stopped my current data collection, reorganized my research outline to fit the new scope, and reallocated my time to deep-dive into the new topic. By pivoting quickly and focusing on the new goal, I was able to deliver a highly relevant report by the original deadline.|I was working on a group presentation when the professor told us we had to cut five minutes from our speaking time just two days before the due date. I went through my slides and removed some of the extra details that weren't strictly necessary for the main point. It was stressful to change it so late, but we managed to get it done and stay within the time limit.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The candidate shows flexibility and a positive attitude toward change. They prioritize the project's success over their own personal preferences or previous work.\\nMid: The candidate can adapt when forced to, but they focus more on the stress of the change than on the strategic adjustment. They show functional adaptability but limited resilience.\\nBad: The candidate is resistant to change and clings to obsolete work. They demonstrate a lack of flexibility that could hinder the team's ability to respond to stakeholder needs.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The response clearly describes the change, the candidate's immediate reaction, the specific adjustments made, and the successful outcome. It is a well-structured narrative.\\nMid: The candidate describes the change and the final result but doesn't give much detail about the specific process of adjusting their work. The structure is basic but provides the necessary info.\\nBad: The response is disorganized and focuses more on the candidate's feelings than on the actions they took. It is difficult to see a clear plan in their response.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate provides specific details about how they reorganized their work and reallocated their time. They show they understand how to transition between different project scopes efficiently.\\nMid: The candidate gives a surface-level account of removing some work. They do not explain the logic behind what they kept or how they ensured the new requirements were fully met.\\nBad: The answer is very brief and does not show any real effort to adapt. It suggests the candidate has difficulty moving on from previous plans even when they are no longer relevant.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate uses clear, professional language to explain their pivot. They communicate their ability to stay calm and productive during transitions very effectively.\\nMid: The candidate's language is a bit informal and they sound a bit overwhelmed by the situation they are describing. The main points are clear but the tone could be more professional.\\nBad: The response is confusing and it's hard to tell exactly what the new goals were or how the candidate tried to meet them. The lack of clarity reflects a lack of organized thinking.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: Adaptability is a key requirement for the job, as project scopes often change. The candidate demonstrates the mindset and skills needed to thrive in a dynamic environment.\\nMid: The candidate can handle minor changes but might struggle with more significant shifts in direction. They would likely need a lot of support and reassurance during project pivots.\\nBad: The candidate's resistance to change is a significant drawback for this job. They are likely to struggle in any environment where priorities shift frequently.|6|Tell me about a time when a project's goals suddenly changed and how you adjusted your work to meet the new requirements?|PASS|98|[\"Complete and accurate mapping of all question IDs and dimensions.\", \"Rubrics fully comply with the complex per-section label requirements.\", \"High-quality content with clear differentiation between answer levels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted and perfectly appropriate for the specified level.\"]|85238ba120005c77b7b432e62d1448be8f7b938b|16ad43a7dd3932f91e8d6795532811dedf4bec61|Consultant|35|9d27fba9b43c4bef720ca9a86fcdde02dbe6006d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.256118Z
Consultant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic consulting concepts and problem-solving frameworks\\nHas done case studies, internships, or project-based work\\nNot expected to lead client engagements or design end-to-end strategies|B|7|Behavioral ​|I had a great idea for our team project, but one of my teammates thought their idea was better. I ended up going to our project supervisor and explaining why my idea was the right one, and the supervisor told the teammate they had to do it my way. It made things a bit awkward for a while, but we ended up using my idea in the end.|In a recent project, a teammate wanted to use a complex software tool that I felt was unnecessary for our simple task. Instead of just saying no, I prepared a small demonstration showing how a simpler tool could achieve the same results in half the time. By focusing on the benefit to the team's schedule and the lower risk of errors, I was able to convince them to try my approach, which we ultimately used successfully.|I had an idea for a project layout that my partner didn't like at first because they wanted something more traditional. I kept explaining my reasons over and over until they finally agreed to try it my way for one part of the project. Once they saw it worked, they were okay with using it for the rest of the assignment too.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The candidate uses logic, evidence, and a focus on team benefits to persuade others. They show they can influence colleagues without creating conflict or relying on authority.\\nMid: The candidate's method of persuasion is persistence rather than evidence-based reasoning. They are successful but their approach is less professional and could be annoying to teammates.\\nBad: The candidate bypasses their teammate and uses external authority to force their idea. This demonstrates a lack of interpersonal skill and could damage team morale.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate clearly outlines the disagreement, the preparation they did to persuade the teammate, the conversation itself, and the final positive outcome.\\nMid: The candidate describes the conflict and the result but the 'action' part of the story (how they persuaded the person) is a bit vague and lacks detail.\\nBad: The response is a short narrative that focuses on the conflict and the outcome but misses the professional 'persuasion' aspect entirely. It lacks a clear logical flow.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate mentions specific factors like time-saving and risk reduction. They show an understanding of what motivates others to change their minds in a professional setting.\\nMid: The candidate provides very little detail about why their idea was better or how they actually changed the other person's mind. The reflection on the process is minimal.\\nBad: The answer is extremely shallow and does not show any insight into professional communication or influence. It feels like a very immature approach to a common team dynamic.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate explains the situation and their thought process in a very clear and professional manner. They present themselves as a reasonable and collaborative colleague.\\nMid: The candidate's explanation is a bit repetitive and the tone is slightly less professional. The main message is understandable but could be conveyed more effectively.\\nBad: The response is confusing and it's hard to see how the candidate actually convinced anyone. The lack of clarity makes it difficult to evaluate their communication skills.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: Influence and communication are vital for the job, especially when working in teams or with stakeholders. The candidate shows they have the right instincts for these interactions.\\nMid: The candidate has basic communication skills but needs to learn more professional ways to influence others. They are a decent fit but will need some coaching on teamwork.\\nBad: The candidate's approach to persuasion is likely to cause team friction and indicates a lack of maturity. They do not demonstrate the interpersonal skills required for the job.|7|Describe a situation where you had to persuade a team member to accept your idea when they initially disagreed with you?|PASS|98|[\"Complete and accurate mapping of all question IDs and dimensions.\", \"Rubrics fully comply with the complex per-section label requirements.\", \"High-quality content with clear differentiation between answer levels.\", \"Questions are well-formatted and perfectly appropriate for the specified level.\"]|85238ba120005c77b7b432e62d1448be8f7b938b|16ad43a7dd3932f91e8d6795532811dedf4bec61|Consultant|36|9d27fba9b43c4bef720ca9a86fcdde02dbe6006d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.256118Z
Consultant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic consulting concepts and problem-solving frameworks\\nHas done case studies, internships, or project-based work\\nNot expected to lead client engagements or design end-to-end strategies|B|8|Specific|I don't really use a formal framework for that because I think it's better to just jump in and start working on the parts of the problem that seem the most important. If I hit a wall, I'll stop and look for a different part of the problem to work on instead until the whole thing eventually gets finished.|I would use a top-down approach by first identifying the main objective and then breaking it into three or four high-level categories that cover the entire scope. I would make sure these categories are mutually exclusive so there is no overlap in my research, and then I would continue breaking those down into specific questions or data points until each part is small enough to be solved individually.|I try to look at the big problem and then list all the different things that might be causing it on a whiteboard. I then group those things into different buckets like 'internal' and 'external' factors so I can start tackling them one by one without getting too overwhelmed by the whole thing at once.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The candidate understands the concept of structured problem-solving and can explain a clear methodology. They recognize the value of organization in tackling complex tasks.\\nMid: The candidate has a basic idea of how to group problems but lacks a rigorous or formal framework. Their approach is more intuitive and less systematic than what is required.\\nBad: The candidate lacks any formal approach to problem-solving and relies on a disorganized 'trial and error' method. This approach is highly inefficient for professional project work.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate provides a clear, step-by-step description of a top-down analysis process. The explanation is 