Product Owner|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic product concepts such as user needs, requirements, and prioritization\\nHas done projects, internships, or worked closely with developers or stakeholders\\nNot expected to own product strategy or roadmap end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I usually don't have disagreements with my teammates because I tend to work alone on my specific tasks to avoid any drama. If someone does have a different opinion, I usually just ignore it and keep working on my part of the project until the manager tells us which way is correct.|During a group project last semester, a teammate and I disagreed on the best way to present our findings to the project lead. I suggested using a visual dashboard, while they wanted a text-heavy report. I organized a brief meeting where we both listed the pros and cons of each approach, and we eventually agreed to create a hybrid presentation that used visuals for the data but included a detailed appendix for the text. This allowed us to meet the deadline while ensuring all critical information was captured accurately.|I once worked on a project where my partner wanted to use a different tool than I did for our work. We talked about it for a bit, but we could not really agree on which one was better for the team. Eventually, I just decided to let them have their way because I did not want to cause a fight and I wanted to make sure we finished the task on time.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a proactive approach to resolving conflict through clear communication and mutual compromise. They show they can handle interpersonal friction without escalating the situation or shutting down. Mid: The candidate acknowledges the conflict but avoids a constructive resolution by simply giving in to the other person. This shows an ability to maintain peace but lacks the initiative to advocate for the best project outcome. Bad: The candidate displays a passive or avoidant attitude and a total lack of conflict resolution skills. They rely entirely on external authority or isolation to manage their professional relationships. Structure check: Good: The response follows a logical flow including the situation, the specific action taken, and a positive result. It clearly outlines the steps taken to reach a conclusion and reflects on the success of the compromise. Mid: The response provides a simple narrative but lacks a clear description of the reasoning or the final impact of the decision. It feels somewhat incomplete as a professional story and lacks detail. Bad: The response is very short and provides no specific details about the event or the resolution. There is no clear structure or sequence of events described by the candidate. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about the nature of the disagreement and the logic behind their solution. They explain why the hybrid approach was beneficial for the project and the team. Mid: The candidate mentions the disagreement but does not explain the underlying reasons for their perspective or the other person's view. The depth of reflection is minimal. Bad: The candidate offers a generic statement about avoiding conflict rather than describing a real experience. This suggests a lack of experience or an unwillingness to engage with the question. Clarity check: Good: The candidate communicates their thoughts clearly and uses professional language throughout the answer. They explain their logic in a way that is very easy for the interviewer to follow. Mid: The candidate's explanation is understandable but includes some vague phrasing or jumps between points. They may need to be prompted to clarify certain parts of their answer for better understanding. Bad: The candidate's response is disorganized and difficult to follow. They fail to convey a coherent message or use appropriate terminology for a professional setting. Relevance to role: Good: The answer shows qualities essential for the job, such as collaboration and professional maturity. This aligns perfectly with what is expected from an entry-level professional in a team environment. Mid: The answer shows some relevant traits but lacks the full depth of leadership and negotiation required for the job. It demonstrates a basic understanding of professional expectations without showing excellence. Bad: The answer does not demonstrate any qualities that would make the candidate successful in the job. It indicates a lack of preparation or understanding of how to work effectively within a project team.|1|Tell me about a time when you had a disagreement with a teammate about how to finish a task and how you resolved it.|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric structure including all section labels and performance tokens.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single sentences, and interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and perfectly aligned with the junior level.\", \"Complete response containing all requested IDs with no schema violations.\"]|85c0875d9df8d18b7ca2883b6648f54679a59626|eb1cc4d7c75d460c95b520171f5537db2b393539|Product Owner|40|8bd52393c3d8e18a8427095a5f26aec2ca39a288|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.251358Z
Product Owner|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic product concepts such as user needs, requirements, and prioritization\\nHas done projects, internships, or worked closely with developers or stakeholders\\nNot expected to own product strategy or roadmap end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I don't really miss deadlines because I am very organized, but if I did, it would probably be because the instructions were not clear enough. Usually, if a project is late, it is because the whole team was waiting for someone else to finish their part first.|In my first internship, I misunderstood the instructions for a weekly report and missed the submission deadline by several hours. As soon as I realized my mistake, I notified my supervisor, explained where the confusion happened, and provided a realistic timeline for when the work would be finished. I then created a personal checklist to ensure I verified all future deadlines and requirement details at the start of every week.|I once forgot to finish a part of a task that was due on a Friday afternoon. I realized it over the weekend and sent it in first thing on Monday morning with an apology to the team. My manager was a little frustrated, but I made sure to be more careful with my calendar for the rest of the month.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate takes full ownership of the mistake and describes a concrete plan to prevent it from happening again. They show high accountability and the ability to communicate transparently under pressure. Mid: The candidate admits to the mistake but their response is reactive rather than proactive. They apologized, but they did not show a strong system for ensuring the error would not be repeated in the future. Bad: The candidate avoids taking responsibility or blames external factors like unclear instructions or other team members. This indicates a lack of self-awareness and poor accountability. Structure check: Good: The response clearly follows the STAR method by explaining the situation, the error, the immediate fix, and the long-term learning. It is easy to follow the candidate's growth through the story. Mid: The response is structured chronologically but lacks a strong emphasis on the resolution or the learning phase. It focuses more on the mistake itself than on the professional recovery. Bad: The response is disjointed or defensive, making it difficult to understand what actually happened. The lack of a clear beginning, middle, and end suggests poor communication skills. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about how they notified their supervisor and what specific tools they used to improve. This level of detail makes the experience feel authentic and reflective. Mid: The candidate gives a general overview of the mistake but does not go into detail about the conversation with the team. The reflection on personal improvement is fairly surface-level. Bad: The candidate provides almost no detail and dismisses the premise of the question. This shows a lack of depth and a failure to engage with the reality of professional challenges. Clarity check: Good: The language is professional and the explanation of the misunderstanding is articulated very clearly. The candidate does not sound defensive or overly emotional about the mistake. Mid: The candidate is clear enough to be understood, but the tone is a bit informal. They use simple sentences that do not fully convey the weight of the situation. Bad: The candidate's response is vague and lacks clarity on what the actual mistake was. This makes it hard for the interviewer to assess their judgment or learning. Relevance to role: Good: Accountability and learning from failure are critical for this job. The candidate demonstrates that they can be trusted to manage their own tasks and improve over time. Mid: The candidate shows a basic level of competence by fixing their mistake. However, they do not show the high level of reliability needed for a fast-paced project environment. Bad: The response is a red flag for the job because it suggests the candidate cannot handle feedback or take responsibility. This would make them a difficult teammate to work with on a project.|2|Describe a situation where you missed a deadline or made a mistake on a project and how you handled the outcome.|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric structure including all section labels and performance tokens.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single sentences, and interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and perfectly aligned with the junior level.\", \"Complete response containing all requested IDs with no schema violations.\"]|85c0875d9df8d18b7ca2883b6648f54679a59626|eb1cc4d7c75d460c95b520171f5537db2b393539|Product Owner|41|8bd52393c3d8e18a8427095a5f26aec2ca39a288|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.251358Z
Product Owner|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic product concepts such as user needs, requirements, and prioritization\\nHas done projects, internships, or worked closely with developers or stakeholders\\nNot expected to own product strategy or roadmap end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I don't really have a specific method for deciding what to do first, so I just pick the tasks that I enjoy doing the most. I figure that as long as I am working on something related to the project, the order doesn't matter that much in the long run.|I prioritize my work by first identifying which tasks have the closest deadlines and which ones have the biggest impact on the project's success. I use a simple matrix to categorize tasks as urgent or important, and if I am ever unsure, I ask my lead for clarification. This ensures that I am always working on the items that provide the most value to the team and keep the project moving forward.|I usually just try to do the tasks in the order that they were given to me by the stakeholder. If something sounds very urgent, I will put it at the top of my list for that day. I try to get through as many small tasks as possible so my to-do list looks shorter by the end of the afternoon.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a structured approach to prioritization using logic and impact assessment. They show they understand how their individual work contributes to the broader project goals. Mid: The candidate uses a basic 'first-come, first-served' approach which is acceptable but lacks strategic thinking. They focus on output volume rather than prioritizing the most critical project needs. Bad: The candidate lacks any formal system for organization and prioritizes based on personal preference. This is a high-risk approach that often leads to missing critical deadlines or wasting time on low-value tasks. Structure check: Good: The answer is organized logically, starting with the criteria for evaluation and ending with the action of seeking feedback. It shows a clear step-by-step process for managing a workload. Mid: The answer is a bit rambling but covers the basic idea of making a list. It lacks a clear transition between identifying tasks and actually executing the plan. Bad: The response is a single sentence or a few disconnected thoughts. There is no evidence of a systematic way of thinking about professional responsibilities. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific tools like a prioritization matrix and the importance of stakeholder impact. They show a level of professional maturity by admitting they would seek guidance when priorities are unclear. Mid: The candidate explains a simple method but does not justify why they chose it. They do not seem to consider the long-term consequences of how they order their work. Bad: The candidate provides no depth or reasoning for their actions. They seem to view task management as a random process rather than a professional skill. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's explanation is concise and easy to understand. They use professional terminology correctly and explain their reasoning in a way that makes sense for the job. Mid: The candidate is clear but uses very casual language that might not be appropriate for a formal setting. The explanation of their process is a bit simplistic. Bad: The candidate is unclear about how they spend their time. Their lack of clarity suggests they might struggle with organization in a real office environment. Relevance to role: Good: This response is highly relevant because the job requires constant balancing of different requests. The candidate shows they have the foundational skills to manage a busy project schedule. Mid: The response shows they can handle a basic workload but may need significant supervision to ensure they are focusing on the right things. They are at an entry-level stage of development. Bad: The response shows a lack of professional discipline that is required for the job. Choosing tasks based on preference rather than project need is not acceptable in this role.|3|How do you decide which tasks are the most important to complete first when you have several different requests from a stakeholder?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric structure including all section labels and performance tokens.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single sentences, and interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and perfectly aligned with the junior level.\", \"Complete response containing all requested IDs with no schema violations.\"]|85c0875d9df8d18b7ca2883b6648f54679a59626|eb1cc4d7c75d460c95b520171f5537db2b393539|Product Owner|42|8bd52393c3d8e18a8427095a5f26aec2ca39a288|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.251358Z
Product Owner|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic product concepts such as user needs, requirements, and prioritization\\nHas done projects, internships, or worked closely with developers or stakeholders\\nNot expected to own product strategy or roadmap end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I don't usually talk to the client directly because I prefer to just get the instructions from my manager. I think it is faster to just start working and then show them the results later so they can tell me if they like it or if I need to change anything.|I begin by reviewing any existing documentation to understand the project's context, then I prepare a list of specific questions for the client. During the meeting, I listen carefully and take detailed notes, and I always finish by summarizing my understanding back to them to confirm we are aligned. Finally, I document these requirements and share them with the team to make sure everyone is on the same page before work starts.|I usually just set up a meeting with the client and ask them to explain what they want me to build or do. I take some notes during the call and then I go back to my desk to start working on it right away. If I have questions later, I will just send them an email to ask for more details.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a thorough and disciplined approach to gathering information and validating requirements. They understand that preventing misunderstandings early saves time and resources for the project. Mid: The candidate has a basic understanding of communication but lacks a formal validation step. They are at risk of starting work based on a partial understanding of the client's needs. Bad: The candidate avoids direct communication and relies on trial and error. This is an inefficient way to work that leads to high amounts of rework and client dissatisfaction. Structure check: Good: The response is a clear walkthrough that follows a logical timeline from preparation to final team sharing. Each step builds on the previous one to ensure a high-quality outcome. Mid: The response is a bit fragmented and focuses only on the meeting itself. It misses the preparation and follow-up phases that are necessary for professional success. Bad: The response is disorganized and does not provide a clear sequence of actions. It feels like the candidate is guessing what they should do rather than describing a process. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains 'why' they take each step, such as summarizing back to the client to ensure alignment. This shows they understand the psychology of effective communication. Mid: The candidate describes 'what' they do but not 'why' it is important. The answer lacks the professional insight that distinguishes a strong junior candidate. Bad: The candidate gives a very superficial answer with no details. They do not seem to appreciate the complexity involved in understanding professional requirements. Clarity check: Good: The language is precise and professional. The candidate uses terms like 'documentation,' 'alignment,' and 'requirements' correctly and in context. Mid: The candidate is easy to understand but uses very informal language. They describe the process as a casual conversation rather than a professional work step. Bad: The candidate is vague and their answer is too brief to provide any real insight. They fail to communicate a clear plan or philosophy for their work. Relevance to role: Good: Understanding needs is a core part of the job. The candidate demonstrates they have the patience and the methodology to handle this responsibility effectively. Mid: The candidate shows they can participate in the process but will need guidance on how to be more thorough. They demonstrate a baseline level of competence. Bad: The candidate does not show the necessary communication skills for the job. Their approach would likely lead to errors and project delays.|4|Walk me through the steps you take to understand what a client needs before you start working on a specific project requirement.|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric structure including all section labels and performance tokens.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single sentences, and interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and perfectly aligned with the junior level.\", \"Complete response containing all requested IDs with no schema violations.\"]|85c0875d9df8d18b7ca2883b6648f54679a59626|eb1cc4d7c75d460c95b520171f5537db2b393539|Product Owner|43|8bd52393c3d8e18a8427095a5f26aec2ca39a288|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.251358Z
Product Owner|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic product concepts such as user needs, requirements, and prioritization\\nHas done projects, internships, or worked closely with developers or stakeholders\\nNot expected to own product strategy or roadmap end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would tell my project leader that it is unfair to change the goal so late and that I cannot finish it in time. I would probably just submit the original version of the task because that is what I spent all my time working on for the past week.|First, I would stay calm and ask for a quick meeting to understand the new goal and its priority relative to the original deadline. I would then assess what parts of my existing work can be reused and identify the minimum steps needed to meet the new requirement by the deadline. If the change is too large to complete in 24 hours, I would provide an honest update on what can be finished and ask for guidance on how to proceed.|I would be very stressed out, but I would try my best to stay late and finish the new task as quickly as possible. I would probably just stop working on the old version and start the new one from scratch to make sure I don't get the two goals mixed up. I would hope that my manager understands that the quality might not be perfect.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates resilience, adaptability, and professional communication in a high-pressure situation. They focus on finding a solution and managing expectations rather than complaining about the change. Mid: The candidate is willing to work hard but lacks a strategic approach to managing the change. They focus on effort rather than efficiency and communication, which could lead to burnout or poor quality. Bad: The candidate is inflexible and defensive. They prioritize their own feelings of fairness over the needs of the project and the team, which is a significant drawback. Structure check: Good: The response follows a logical sequence: clarify, assess, execute, and communicate. This shows a structured mindset that can handle unexpected shifts in a professional environment. Mid: The response is a bit chaotic and focuses mostly on the emotional reaction and the extra hours worked. It lacks a clear plan for how to handle the work itself. Bad: The response is brief and confrontational. There is no structure, only a refusal to adapt to the new project requirements. Depth check: Good: The candidate considers multiple factors like reusability of work and honest communication about feasibility. They show they can think critically under pressure. Mid: The candidate only considers the option of working harder. They do not think about how to reuse work or how to negotiate the scope of the new task. Bad: The candidate provides no depth of thought regarding the project's goals. They see the situation as a personal conflict rather than a business reality. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their thought process clearly and professionally. They use calm and logical language to describe how they would navigate the stress of the deadline. Mid: The candidate is clear enough but sounds a bit overwhelmed. Their answer reflects the stress of the situation rather than a professional approach to solving it. Bad: The candidate's response is blunt and lacks professional polish. It is clear they would be difficult to work with during a project pivot. Relevance to role: Good: In this job, priorities change frequently. The candidate's ability to pivot quickly while maintaining clear communication is a vital skill for success. Mid: The candidate's willingness to work hard is good, but they need to learn better ways to manage shifting priorities without just working more hours. Bad: The candidate is not a good fit for a dynamic project environment. Their refusal to adapt would create bottlenecks and conflict within the team.|5|What would you do if your project leader changed the main goal of your task one day before the final submission was due?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric structure including all section labels and performance tokens.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single sentences, and interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and perfectly aligned with the junior level.\", \"Complete response containing all requested IDs with no schema violations.\"]|85c0875d9df8d18b7ca2883b6648f54679a59626|eb1cc4d7c75d460c95b520171f5537db2b393539|Product Owner|44|8bd52393c3d8e18a8427095a5f26aec2ca39a288|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.251358Z
Product Owner|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic product concepts such as user needs, requirements, and prioritization\\nHas done projects, internships, or worked closely with developers or stakeholders\\nNot expected to own product strategy or roadmap end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I usually don't try to convince people of my ideas because I think everyone should just do what they think is best. If the group doesn't like my proposal right away, I just give up on it and go along with whatever the majority wants to do.|During a club project, I proposed that we switch from using email to a shared task management app to track our progress. Many members were hesitant because they were comfortable with email, so I did a small demo of the app to show how much time it would save us. By highlighting the benefits of transparency and reduced clutter, I was able to get everyone to agree to a one-week trial, which eventually became our permanent process.|I had an idea for a new way to organize our project files, but my teammates didn't think it was necessary at first. I kept telling them that it would be better and eventually I just started using the new system myself. After they saw me using it for a few days, they decided it was okay and they started using it too.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates effective persuasion skills by focusing on benefits and using a low-risk trial to overcome resistance. They show they can lead through influence rather than authority. Mid: The candidate uses persistence and leading by example, which is effective but less collaborative. They managed to change the group's mind but did not use a structured approach to gain buy-in. Bad: The candidate lacks the confidence or the skill to advocate for their ideas. This passivity means the team might miss out on valuable improvements or innovations. Structure check: Good: The response is well-structured using a clear 'Situation, Task, Action, Result' format. It identifies the problem, the specific strategy used for persuasion, and the successful outcome. Mid: The response is a bit more of a casual story and lacks a clear beginning and end. The 'Result' is clear, but the 'Action' is a bit passive. Bad: The response is very short and lacks any narrative structure. It describes a failure to act rather than a professional experience. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific pain points they addressed, such as 'email clutter' and 'transparency.' This shows they understand how to tailor their message to their audience. Mid: The candidate explains that they were persistent but doesn't detail the logic they used to convince others. The depth of the persuasion strategy is missing. Bad: The candidate provides no depth or detail. They seem to view the concept of persuasion as unnecessary or too difficult to attempt. Clarity check: Good: The candidate speaks clearly and uses professional terms like 'transparency' and 'buy-in.' Their explanation of the demo and trial period is very easy to follow. Mid: The candidate is clear, but the language is a bit repetitive. They explain what happened in a simple way that lacks professional nuance. Bad: The candidate is vague about what their idea was and how people reacted. Their lack of clarity makes it hard to judge their interpersonal skills. Relevance to role: Good: This job requires the ability to influence stakeholders and teammates without having direct authority over them. The candidate's approach is highly relevant and professional. Mid: The candidate shows some potential for influence but will need to develop more formal communication strategies. They are at an appropriate level for a junior role. Bad: The response is a concern for the job because it suggests the candidate will not speak up for good ideas. A person in this role must be able to advocate for the project's success.|6|Explain a time when you had to convince a group of people to support an idea or approach that you proposed for a project.|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric structure including all section labels and performance tokens.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single sentences, and interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and perfectly aligned with the junior level.\", \"Complete response containing all requested IDs with no schema violations.\"]|85c0875d9df8d18b7ca2883b6648f54679a59626|eb1cc4d7c75d460c95b520171f5537db2b393539|Product Owner|45|8bd52393c3d8e18a8427095a5f26aec2ca39a288|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.251358Z
Product Owner|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic product concepts such as user needs, requirements, and prioritization\\nHas done projects, internships, or worked closely with developers or stakeholders\\nNot expected to own product strategy or roadmap end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I prefer to stick to the tools I already know because learning new things during a project usually takes too much time and leads to mistakes. If a task requires a tool I don't know, I usually ask if someone else on the team can do that part instead of me.|Last summer, I was asked to use a specific data analysis tool that I had never seen before to finish a report by the end of the week. I spent the first few hours watching online tutorials and reading the basic documentation, then I practiced by recreating a small part of an old project. By the third day, I was comfortable enough to complete the new report, and I finished it one day ahead of the deadline.|I had to learn how to use a new project tracking software when I started my last internship. I didn't have much time, so I just asked my coworkers a lot of questions every time I got stuck. I eventually figured it out after a few weeks, although I was a bit slow at first while I was still learning the buttons.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a proactive and structured approach to self-directed learning. They demonstrate a high level of curiosity and the ability to take initiative to solve their own knowledge gaps. Mid: The candidate is willing to learn but relies heavily on others for help rather than trying to find information themselves. This shows a lack of independence but a willingness to adapt. Bad: The candidate is resistant to learning new things and tries to avoid tasks that are outside their comfort zone. This is a significant negative trait in a rapidly changing work environment. Structure check: Good: The response is structured around a clear timeline: the challenge, the learning phase, the practice phase, and the successful completion. It shows a disciplined mind. Mid: The response is a simple chronological account but lacks details on the specific steps taken to learn. It focuses more on the difficulty than the strategy for learning. Bad: The response is very brief and does not describe a learning process at all. It focuses on the candidate's preference for staying with familiar tools. Depth check: Good: The candidate describes specific actions like watching tutorials and practicing with old data. This level of detail makes the learning process feel realistic and repeatable. Mid: The candidate mentions asking questions but doesn't describe any personal effort to study or research. The depth of their self-sufficiency is quite low. Bad: The candidate provides no depth and seems to find the idea of learning new tools to be a burden rather than an opportunity. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's explanation of their learning schedule is very clear and easy to follow. They communicate their ability to manage their time effectively during the learning process. Mid: The candidate is understandable but a bit vague about how long it took and what was actually difficult. The language is very basic. Bad: The candidate is clear about their refusal to learn, which highlights a lack of adaptability. Their message is simple but not professionally appropriate. Relevance to role: Good: In a project-based role, learning new tools and domains is constant. The candidate's ability to quickly upskill is a major asset for the team. Mid: The candidate's ability to learn is acceptable for a junior role, but they will need more coaching to become self-sufficient. Bad: This response is a red flag for the job. The role requires someone who is eager to learn and adapt, not someone who avoids new challenges.|7|Can you tell me about a time when you had to learn a new tool or process quickly to finish a task on time?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric structure including all section labels and performance tokens.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single sentences, and interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and perfectly aligned with the junior level.\", \"Complete response containing all requested IDs with no schema violations.\"]|85c0875d9df8d18b7ca2883b6648f54679a59626|eb1cc4d7c75d460c95b520171f5537db2b393539|Product Owner|46|8bd52393c3d8e18a8427095a5f26aec2ca39a288|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.251358Z
Product Owner|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic product concepts such as user needs, requirements, and prioritization\\nHas done projects, internships, or worked closely with developers or stakeholders\\nNot expected to own product strategy or roadmap end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I don't really have a specific process for checking my work because I usually get it right the first time. I figure that if there are any big mistakes, my manager will see them and tell me to fix them anyway, so I don't spend much extra time on reviewing.|I always start by taking a short break after finishing a task so I can review it with fresh eyes. I then use a checklist of common errors and compare my final output against the original project requirements to make sure nothing was missed. Finally, I double-check all my formatting and data points one last time to ensure the work is professional and accurate before I hit send.|I usually just read through my work once or twice after I finish it to see if anything looks weird or if I made any obvious typos. If the project is very important, I might ask a friend to take a quick look at it for me too. I try to be careful, but sometimes I still miss small things when I am in a hurry.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a disciplined and systematic approach to quality assurance. They show a high level of professional pride and an understanding of the importance of accuracy. Mid: The candidate has a basic awareness of quality but their process is informal and inconsistent. They rely on their 'eyes' rather than a structured system like a checklist. Bad: The candidate lacks accountability for the quality of their work and expects others to find their mistakes. This attitude is unprofessional and creates more work for the rest of the team. Structure check: Good: The answer is structured as a clear step-by-step procedure: break, checklist, comparison, and final review. It shows a repeatable process that ensures consistency. Mid: The answer is a bit vague and describes a casual review rather than a professional process. It lacks a clear beginning and end. Bad: The response is very short and shows no evidence of a structured way of working. It highlights a lack of discipline and attention to detail. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific techniques like 'fresh eyes' and 'comparing against requirements.' This shows they have thought deeply about how to improve their own performance. Mid: The candidate mentions reading through the work but doesn't explain what specifically they are looking for. The depth of the review process is quite shallow. Bad: The candidate provides no depth and seems to think that checking work is a waste of time. Clarity check: Good: The language is professional and the steps are explained in a very logical order. The candidate's commitment to quality is clear in their tone. Mid: The candidate is clear enough, but their tone is a bit too casual. They sound like they are describing a school assignment rather than a professional project. Bad: The candidate is blunt and their lack of a process is clear. They fail to communicate any sense of professional responsibility. Relevance to role: Good: Attention to detail is a core requirement for this job. The candidate's structured approach makes them a reliable member of a project team. Mid: The candidate shows a baseline level of care, but they would need to be taught more rigorous quality control methods for this role. Bad: The candidate's approach is not suitable for the job. Mistakes in this role can have a large impact, so a lack of self-review is a major risk.|8|Describe the process you use to check your own work for errors before you hand it over to a teammate or a manager.|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric structure including all section labels and performance tokens.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single sentences, and interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and perfectly aligned with the junior level.\", \"Complete response containing all requested IDs with no schema violations.\"]|85c0875d9df8d18b7ca2883b6648f54679a59626|eb1cc4d7c75d460c95b520171f5537db2b393539|Product Owner|47|8bd52393c3d8e18a8427095a5f26aec2ca39a288|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.251358Z
Product Owner|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic product concepts such as user needs, requirements, and prioritization\\nHas done projects, internships, or worked closely with developers or stakeholders\\nNot expected to own product strategy or roadmap end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I would just assume the user is making a mistake or doesn't know how to use the feature correctly. I would send them the instruction manual and tell them to read it again before they report any more problems to the team.|I would start by asking the user for specific details about what they were doing when the issue occurred and what they expected the result to be. Then, I would try to reproduce the problem myself using the same steps they described. Once I understand the gap between the actual and expected behavior, I would check the project requirements to see if this is a technical bug or a misunderstanding of how the feature works.|I would probably just go and look at the feature myself to see if I can find anything wrong with it. If it seems to be working for me, I would tell the user that I couldn't find any problems. If it is broken, I would just tell the developers that they need to fix it right away.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a logical and empathetic approach to problem-solving. They understand the importance of gathering data and verifying the issue before jumping to conclusions. Mid: The candidate is willing to help but lacks a structured investigative process. They might miss subtle issues if they only rely on their own experience rather than the user's report. Bad: The candidate is dismissive of user feedback and lacks basic troubleshooting skills. This attitude would lead to poor relationships with stakeholders and unresolved project issues. Structure check: Good: The response is organized as a logical investigation: gather info, reproduce, and analyze. It shows the candidate can think like a researcher when faced with a problem. Mid: The response is a bit impulsive and lacks a clear sequence of events. It focuses on the immediate reaction rather than a comprehensive investigation. Bad: The response is very brief and shows no evidence of a professional troubleshooting mindset. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses clear language and correctly identifies the difference between a 'bug' and a 'misunderstanding.' Their explanation of the steps is easy to follow. Mid: The candidate is clear but a bit informal. They describe the process in very simple terms that lack professional depth. Bad: The candidate's response is blunt and dismissive. They fail to communicate how they would actually solve the problem. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions the importance of 'expected vs actual behavior' and checking 'project requirements.' This shows a sophisticated understanding of project fundamentals. Mid: The candidate provides a very surface-level answer about 'looking at the feature.' They do not consider the various reasons why a user might be unhappy. Bad: The candidate provides no depth of thought and shows no interest in investigating the root cause of the problem. Relevance to role: Good: Investigating issues and understanding user needs is a major part of the job. The candidate demonstrates they have the right mindset for this type of work. Mid: The candidate has the basic skills to help, but they would need training on how to handle more complex investigations. Bad: The candidate's dismissive approach is a major red flag. This job requires someone who takes user feedback seriously and works to improve the project.|9|How would you investigate a situation where a user reports that a specific feature of a project is not working as they expected?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric structure including all section labels and performance tokens.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single sentences, and interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and perfectly aligned with the junior level.\", \"Complete response containing all requested IDs with no schema violations.\"]|85c0875d9df8d18b7ca2883b6648f54679a59626|eb1cc4d7c75d460c95b520171f5537db2b393539|Product Owner|48|8bd52393c3d8e18a8427095a5f26aec2ca39a288|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.251358Z
Product Owner|Junior\\n0 to 2 years experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands basic product concepts such as user needs, requirements, and prioritization\\nHas done projects, internships, or worked closely with developers or stakeholders\\nNot expected to own product strategy or roadmap end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would probably just start doing what I think they want, even if I am not sure. I figure that it is better to be busy and doing something than to look like I don't know what I am doing. If they don't like it later, I can always change it then.|If I received a vague task, I would first spend some time researching the topic to see if I can find any obvious starting points or previous examples. Then, I would draft a brief outline of how I plan to approach the work and send it to the stakeholder for feedback. This allows me to show initiative while also ensuring that I don't waste time going in the wrong direction.|I would just go and ask the stakeholder for more instructions as soon as I get the task. I would tell them that I don't understand what they want and ask them to give me a step-by-step list of what I should do. I would wait until they reply before I start working on anything.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a balance of initiative and collaboration. They try to find their own answers first but also know when to check in for alignment, which saves time and prevents errors. Mid: The candidate is too dependent on the stakeholder and lacks the initiative to try to solve the problem themselves. This could be seen as a lack of confidence or resourcefulness. Bad: The candidate is reckless and would rather waste time working on the wrong thing than ask for clarity. This approach leads to significant rework and project inefficiency. Structure check: Good: The response is a clear three-step process: research, propose, and validate. It shows a professional way to manage ambiguity. Mid: The response is a simple one-step process of asking for help. It lacks the professional depth of the stronger answer. Bad: The response is disorganized and shows a lack of professional judgment. It describes a 'shoot first, ask questions later' mentality. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains 'why' they draft an outline—to show initiative and ensure alignment. This shows they understand the dynamics of stakeholder management. Mid: The candidate provides a simple answer with no reflection on why they would take that approach. They don't seem to consider how their actions affect the stakeholder's time. Bad: The candidate provides no depth and seems to value 'looking busy' over actually being productive. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's explanation is very clear and professional. They use appropriate language to describe their strategy for managing ambiguity. Mid: The candidate is understandable but sounds a bit like they are complaining about the vague instructions. The tone is slightly less professional. Bad: The candidate's response is clear but reveals a problematic mindset. Their lack of professional maturity is evident in their answer. Relevance to role: Good: Handling ambiguity is a frequent challenge in this job. The candidate's ability to create a plan out of a vague request is a highly valuable skill. Mid: The candidate can handle the task but will require a lot of 'hand-holding' from their manager or stakeholders. They are at a basic entry-level. Bad: The candidate's approach is a risk for the job. A person in this role must be able to navigate uncertainty without wasting resources or making wild guesses.|10|Could you describe how you would handle a situation where a stakeholder gives you a very vague task with no clear instructions on how to start?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric structure including all section labels and performance tokens.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Questions are well-formatted, single sentences, and interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and perfectly aligned with the junior level.\", \"Complete response containing all requested IDs with no schema violations.\"]|85c0875d9df8d18b7ca2883b6648f54679a59626|eb1cc4d7c75d460c95b520171f5537db2b393539|Product Owner|49|8bd52393c3d8e18a8427095a5f26aec2ca39a288|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.251358Z
Mobile Application Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I had a teammate who didn't understand the right way to do things, so I just did the task myself to make sure it was correct. I didn't really talk to them about it because I knew I had more experience with that specific part of the project. They were a bit annoyed later, but the project got a good grade, so I don't think it was a big deal. I prefer working alone when people have different opinions.|During a group project, a teammate and I disagreed on the best way to structure our shared data files. I listened to their concerns about accessibility, and then I shared my perspective on performance. We decided to create a small prototype of both methods to see which worked better for the specific requirements of the project. Ultimately, we chose a hybrid approach that satisfied both needs, which helped us finish the task ahead of schedule and improved our working relationship.|I once worked with someone who wanted to use a different tool than the one I preferred for our project. We talked about it for a while and both felt our ways were better. Eventually, I just decided to go with their idea because I didn't want to cause more tension in the team. It worked out okay, and we finished the project on time, but I still think my way might have been slightly faster to implement.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The response demonstrates active listening, objective evaluation of ideas, and a focus on project goals. It shows the candidate can navigate social friction to reach a productive outcome.\\nMid: The response shows a willingness to avoid conflict but lacks proactive problem-solving or collaboration. The candidate compromises just to end the discussion rather than find the best solution.\\nBad: The response shows a lack of teamwork and poor communication. It indicates a preference for working in isolation rather than resolving differences professionally.\\n\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate uses a clear narrative structure that outlines the situation, the specific action taken, and the positive result. It is easy to follow the logic of their decision-making process.\\nMid: The structure is somewhat loose and focuses more on the feeling of the disagreement than the steps taken to fix it. The outcome is mentioned but not detailed.\\nBad: The response is disorganized and fails to provide a clear sequence of events. It lacks a professional resolution or a clear learning point.\\n\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate provides specific details about the nature of the disagreement and the reasoning behind their hybrid solution. This shows a high level of reflection and maturity for a junior role.\\nMid: The candidate provides only a surface-level description of the disagreement and the resolution. There is little explanation of why they chose to give in or how it affected the work.\\nBad: The response is very brief and avoids explaining any of the underlying logic or interpersonal dynamics. It provides no evidence of critical thinking.\\n\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The language is professional, clear, and avoids blaming others. The candidate speaks clearly about their own actions and the team's collaborative effort.\\nMid: The language is a bit informal and includes some vague descriptions of the conflict. It is mostly understandable but lacks professional polish.\\nBad: The response is confusing or uses biased language that reflects poorly on the candidate's attitude. It is difficult to see how the candidate contributed to a solution.\\n\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The answer is highly relevant as it shows the candidate can work within a team environment which is essential for the job. It reflects a professional mindset regarding peer collaboration.\\nMid: The answer is relevant but suggests the candidate might be a passive team member. It meets the basic requirement of having worked in a team but doesn't show leadership or initiative.\\nBad: The answer is irrelevant to professional collaboration because it highlights a refusal to work with others. It suggests the candidate might be a liability in a team-based project.|1|Tell me about a time when you had a disagreement with a teammate about how to complete a specific task and how you reached a resolution?|PASS|85|[\"Rubric includes specific role title in Relevance to role section across all questions, violating the instruction to avoid it.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers and grading rubrics.\", \"Perfect adherence to complex rubric sub-section labeling requirements for all questions.\"]|8ce2cc979729e667074df93f7b3ae626458e34e9|b328f927e652dc76c6f0a396097b12aa27b2e72f|Mobile Application Developer|50|73424df2f80404b2cf959bc80f225a49ccc4782a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262223Z
Mobile Application Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I was told to use a new tool for a project, but I found it really confusing, so I just used the old tool I already knew. I figured as long as the work got done, it didn't really matter which tool I used. My manager wasn't happy that my work wasn't compatible with the rest of the team's files, but I told them the new tool was too hard to learn quickly.|In my last internship, I was asked to use a specific version control workflow that I hadn't used before. I spent my first weekend reading the documentation and watching several tutorial videos to understand the commands. I then set up a private practice area to test the workflow before applying it to the main project files. This allowed me to contribute to the team's codebase on Monday without needing constant supervision or making mistakes that affected others.|I had to learn a new project management software during a school assignment because our lead wanted everyone to use it. I mostly just clicked around and figured it out as I went along. Whenever I got stuck, I would ask a teammate to show me what to do. I eventually learned the basics, but it took me a few weeks to feel comfortable using all the features of the software.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The response shows a proactive and self-driven approach to skill acquisition. It demonstrates that the candidate can take ownership of their own professional development and apply new knowledge quickly.\\nMid: The response shows a reactive approach to learning where the candidate only learns what is necessary. It relies heavily on others for guidance rather than independent research.\\nBad: The response shows a resistance to learning and a lack of adaptability. The candidate prioritizes their own comfort over the project's requirements and team standards.\\n\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate clearly outlines the challenge, the specific resources used for learning, and the successful application of the skill. The flow is logical and emphasizes self-reliance.\\nMid: The structure is a bit disorganized and focuses more on the difficulty of the task than the learning process. The outcome is vague and lacks a sense of accomplishment.\\nBad: The response lacks a clear beginning, middle, or end. It focuses on failure or avoidance rather than the process of learning.\\n\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate mentions specific actions like reading documentation and setting up a practice environment. This shows a disciplined approach to learning that is very valuable in the job.\\nMid: The candidate provides very little detail about how they actually learned the tool. They describe 'clicking around' which suggests a lack of systematic effort.\\nBad: The response is shallow and does not describe any learning process at all. It indicates a lack of effort and a low level of curiosity.\\n\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate uses clear and professional language to describe their learning journey. They articulate the value of their self-study to the wider team.\\nMid: The response is clear enough to understand but lacks professional terminology or a strong conclusion. It feels more like a casual conversation than an interview answer.\\nBad: The response is poorly articulated and may come across as defensive or dismissive of the task. It does not clearly communicate a successful outcome.\\n\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The answer is very relevant because the project environment often requires learning new technologies. It shows the candidate is prepared for the fast-paced nature of the job.\\nMid: The answer is somewhat relevant but suggests the candidate might require significant hand-holding. This is a concern for a junior role that requires some independence.\\nBad: The answer is not relevant to a growth-oriented role because it shows a refusal to adapt. It suggests the candidate will struggle to keep up with changing project needs.|2|Describe a situation where you had to learn a new tool or process on your own to complete a task within the project?|PASS|85|[\"Rubric includes specific role title in Relevance to role section across all questions, violating the instruction to avoid it.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers and grading rubrics.\", \"Perfect adherence to complex rubric sub-section labeling requirements for all questions.\"]|8ce2cc979729e667074df93f7b3ae626458e34e9|b328f927e652dc76c6f0a396097b12aa27b2e72f|Mobile Application Developer|51|73424df2f80404b2cf959bc80f225a49ccc4782a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262223Z
Mobile Application Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I don't really worry about the design details too much because I think the functionality is more important. As long as the buttons work and the text is readable, I feel like the job is done. If the stakeholder wants it to look different, they can tell me later and I'll try to change it. I find measuring pixels to be a waste of time during the early stages of a project.|I start by carefully reviewing the design files and extracting specific values like hex codes for colors, font sizes, and padding measurements in pixels. After I build the initial layout, I use an overlay tool or a screen ruler to compare my work directly against the original mockup. I also check the screen on different device sizes to ensure that the proportions remain consistent. Finally, I ask a peer to give it a quick look to catch any small visual details I might have missed during development.|I usually just look at the design and try to make my screen look as close as possible to the picture. I pick colors that seem right and guess the spacing based on how it looks on my monitor. If it looks okay to me, I assume it's correct. I might check it once more before I finish, but I don't usually use any special tools to measure things exactly.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The response demonstrates a high level of detail-orientation and a systematic approach to quality control. It shows the candidate understands the importance of visual fidelity in the project.\\nMid: The response shows a casual approach to design implementation. While the candidate tries to match the design, they lack the rigor needed for professional-grade work.\\nBad: The response shows a disregard for design specifications and a lack of understanding of the user experience. It indicates the candidate may produce inconsistent or low-quality work.\\n\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate provides a clear, step-by-step process that moves from preparation to execution to final verification. This shows they have a repeatable workflow.\\nMid: The response is a bit fragmented and doesn't follow a logical sequence. It describes general habits rather than a structured professional process.\\nBad: The response is very brief and lacks any sense of a structured approach. It sounds like the candidate is making it up as they go along.\\n\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The mention of specific technical details like hex codes, padding, and device scaling shows the candidate has practical experience. They understand the nuances of the task.\\nMid: The candidate provides only general statements about 'looking' at the design. There is no mention of specific techniques or tools used to ensure accuracy.\\nBad: The response has no depth and dismisses the core requirements of the task. It shows a lack of technical maturity and professional standards.\\n\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The explanation is easy to follow and uses appropriate terminology for the job. The candidate clearly communicates their dedication to high-quality output.\\nMid: The response is clear but sounds a bit amateurish. The language used doesn't convey a sense of professional expertise or attention to detail.\\nBad: The response is unclear and may even be contradictory. It fails to explain how the candidate would achieve the goal mentioned in the question.\\n\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: This is a fundamental skill for the job, and the candidate's thorough answer proves they are ready for the execution-focused tasks of a junior role.\\nMid: The answer is relevant but indicates the candidate may need more training on professional standards and tools. They are at a basic level of proficiency.\\nBad: The answer is not relevant to a professional role because it ignores the necessity of following specifications. It suggests the candidate is not yet ready for professional project work.|3|Walk me through the steps you take to ensure that a user interface screen matches the design specifications provided by a stakeholder?|PASS|85|[\"Rubric includes specific role title in Relevance to role section across all questions, violating the instruction to avoid it.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers and grading rubrics.\", \"Perfect adherence to complex rubric sub-section labeling requirements for all questions.\"]|8ce2cc979729e667074df93f7b3ae626458e34e9|b328f927e652dc76c6f0a396097b12aa27b2e72f|Mobile Application Developer|52|73424df2f80404b2cf959bc80f225a49ccc4782a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262223Z
Mobile Application Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I don't really know how to fix performance issues yet, so I usually just ignore them unless they make the application crash. I figure that as long as the application works on my fast computer, it should be fine for most users. If someone complains, I might try deleting some parts of the screen to make it load faster, but I don't have a specific process for it.|First, I try to reproduce the lag consistently so I can measure it accurately. I then use debugging tools to look for heavy assets like uncompressed images or inefficient loops that might be blocking the main thread. If I find a large image, I resize it; if I find complex logic, I try to simplify it or run it in the background. After making a change, I re-test the interaction to confirm that the performance has actually improved without breaking other features.|If a screen is slow, I usually look through my code to see if I left any unnecessary lines or comments that might be slowing it down. I might also try restarting the application to see if that fixes the problem. If it's still slow, I ask a senior teammate to help me find the bug because they usually know exactly where to look for performance issues.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The response shows a logical, evidence-based approach to troubleshooting and optimization. It demonstrates that the candidate understands common causes of performance issues at a junior level.\\nMid: The response shows a basic understanding of debugging but lacks a technical strategy. The candidate relies on trial-and-error or external help rather than systematic analysis.\\nBad: The response shows a lack of technical knowledge and an unprofessional attitude toward software quality. The candidate does not take responsibility for the performance of their work.\\n\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate follows a clear 'identify, analyze, fix, verify' cycle. This structure is essential for efficient problem-solving in a technical role.\\nMid: The response is a bit scattered and doesn't follow a clear path. It jumps from one idea to another without explaining how they are connected.\\nBad: The structure is non-existent. The candidate just lists a few things they might do without any logical order or professional reasoning.\\n\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate identifies specific potential issues like uncompressed images and main thread blocking. This shows they have a practical understanding of how project resources work.\\nMid: The candidate's suggestions are very basic and show a limited understanding of how performance works. Mentioning 'comments' as a cause of lag shows a lack of technical depth.\\nBad: The response is extremely shallow and shows no understanding of the tools or concepts involved in performance optimization.\\n\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The explanation is clear, concise, and uses professional terminology appropriately. It gives confidence that the candidate can handle basic technical challenges.\\nMid: The language is simple and easy to understand but lacks professional precision. It sounds like a student who is still learning the basics of the job.\\nBad: The response is confusing and demonstrates a lack of professional communication skills. It doesn't provide a clear answer to the question asked.\\n\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: Performance is a key part of the job, and this answer shows the candidate has the right mindset for technical execution and quality assurance.\\nMid: The answer is relevant at a very basic level but suggests the candidate will need a lot of guidance to handle real-world performance tasks.\\nBad: The answer is not relevant for a technical role because it shows a lack of basic troubleshooting skills and a disregard for technical standards.|4|Explain the process you use to identify and resolve a slow-loading screen or a laggy user interaction within a project?|PASS|85|[\"Rubric includes specific role title in Relevance to role section across all questions, violating the instruction to avoid it.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers and grading rubrics.\", \"Perfect adherence to complex rubric sub-section labeling requirements for all questions.\"]|8ce2cc979729e667074df93f7b3ae626458e34e9|b328f927e652dc76c6f0a396097b12aa27b2e72f|Mobile Application Developer|53|73424df2f80404b2cf959bc80f225a49ccc4782a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262223Z
Mobile Application Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would tell the stakeholder that I'm too busy and they need to wait until I finish my current task. I don't think it's fair for people to add work at the last minute when I've already planned my schedule. If they keep insisting, I might just start the new task and stop working on the old one, but I wouldn't tell anyone because I don't want to get in trouble for missing a deadline.|If a stakeholder approached me with an urgent request, I would first document the requirements of the new task to understand its scope. Then, I would speak with my immediate supervisor to explain my current progress on the existing deadline and ask for guidance on which task should take priority. I would also provide an estimate of how the new request might delay my current work so that the supervisor can manage the stakeholder's expectations. This ensures that the most important work gets done without me making unauthorized decisions about project priorities.|I would probably try to work faster or stay late to get both things done at the same time. I don't want to tell the stakeholder no because I want to be helpful. If I realize I can't finish everything, I would tell my teammate and see if they can help me with the new feature. I usually just try to handle everything myself until it becomes too much to manage.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The response shows a professional understanding of hierarchy and prioritization. It demonstrates that the candidate knows how to communicate trade-offs rather than just saying yes to everything.\\nMid: The response shows a willingness to work hard but a lack of professional boundaries or communication. The candidate risks burnout or poor quality by trying to do too much without coordination.\\nBad: The response shows poor communication skills and a lack of professionalism. The candidate is either too blunt or hides their progress, which can cause significant issues for the team.\\n\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate provides a clear step-by-step plan: document, communicate with a supervisor, and provide impact estimates. This is a very mature approach for a junior candidate.\\nMid: The response is a bit impulsive and lacks a clear plan. It focuses on the candidate's personal effort rather than a team-oriented process for managing workload.\\nBad: The response is reactive and disorganized. It doesn't show any understanding of how to manage professional responsibilities under pressure.\\n\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate explains the reasoning behind their actions, such as the need to manage expectations and ensure authorized prioritization. This shows a deep understanding of workplace dynamics.\\nMid: The candidate provides only a surface-level response focused on working harder. They don't seem to consider the long-term impact on the project or the team.\\nBad: The response is very shallow and shows a lack of professional maturity. The candidate doesn't seem to understand the importance of collaboration or transparency.\\n\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The language is professional and the logic is easy to follow. The candidate sounds reliable and capable of handling workplace stress.\\nMid: The language is a bit informal and the reasoning is somewhat shaky. It's clear what the candidate would do, but it doesn't sound like a well-thought-out professional strategy.\\nBad: The response is poorly articulated and reflects a negative attitude. It doesn't clearly show how the candidate would resolve the conflict in a productive way.\\n\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: This scenario is very common in the job, and the candidate's answer shows they are ready to handle the practical realities of project work.\\nMid: The answer is relevant but shows a lack of experience in managing stakeholders. The candidate would need coaching on how to communicate effectively with leadership.\\nBad: The answer is not relevant for a professional role because it shows a lack of basic teamwork and communication skills. It suggests the candidate would be difficult to manage in a high-pressure environment.|5|How would you handle a situation where a stakeholder asks for an urgent feature update while you are already working on a tight deadline?|PASS|85|[\"Rubric includes specific role title in Relevance to role section across all questions, violating the instruction to avoid it.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers and grading rubrics.\", \"Perfect adherence to complex rubric sub-section labeling requirements for all questions.\"]|8ce2cc979729e667074df93f7b3ae626458e34e9|b328f927e652dc76c6f0a396097b12aa27b2e72f|Mobile Application Developer|54|73424df2f80404b2cf959bc80f225a49ccc4782a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262223Z
Mobile Application Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I don't really like talking to non-technical people because they never understand what I'm talking about anyway. Usually, I just send them a long email with all the technical details and hope they can figure it out themselves. If they have questions, I tell them to talk to my manager because I'd rather spend my time working on the project than explaining it to people who don't code.|During a project presentation, I had to explain why a certain feature was taking longer than expected. Instead of talking about the specific lines of code, I used an analogy about building a house to explain why the foundation needed more time to set. I focused on the benefits to the final user, such as better stability and fewer crashes later on. This helped the stakeholder understand the delay without getting confused by the technical details, and they were much more supportive of our timeline.|I once had to tell a client that their request wasn't possible with the tools we were using. I tried to explain the technical limitations, but they seemed a bit confused by the jargon I used. Eventually, I just told them that it would cost more money and take more time, which they understood better. It wasn't the best explanation, but we managed to reach an agreement about what to do next.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The response shows the candidate can bridge the gap between technical work and business needs. It demonstrates empathy for the audience and an ability to simplify complex ideas.\\nMid: The response shows a basic attempt to communicate but lacks the skill to do so effectively without falling back on jargon or simple metrics like cost. The candidate struggles to find the right level of detail.\\nBad: The response shows a lack of communication skills and a dismissive attitude toward others. It indicates the candidate is unwilling or unable to collaborate with people outside their technical bubble.\\n\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate describes the context, the specific technique used (analogy), and the positive outcome. It is a well-rounded and professional narrative.\\nMid: The structure is a bit weak and focuses more on the difficulty of the task than the candidate's specific actions to improve the situation. The resolution is functional but not impressive.\\nBad: The response is brief and focuses on the candidate's personal preference for avoiding communication rather than a professional process.\\n\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The use of an analogy and the focus on user benefits shows the candidate has put thought into how to be a better communicator. This is a sign of high potential in a junior role.\\nMid: The candidate provides very little detail about how they tried to explain the concept. They seem to have given up on the technical explanation very quickly.\\nBad: The response has no depth and shows a complete lack of interest in developing communication skills. It is highly unprofessional.\\n\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate's explanation of their own communication style is clear and professional. They articulate their thoughts well and show a positive attitude.\\nMid: The language is a bit informal and the candidate sounds a little frustrated by the experience. The response is clear but doesn't inspire much confidence.\\nBad: The response is blunt and negative. It clearly communicates a lack of suitability for a role that requires stakeholder interaction.\\n\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: This is an essential skill for the job as teams often interact with product owners and clients. The candidate's proactive approach is a major asset.\\nMid: The answer is relevant but shows a need for significant development in communication skills. The candidate might struggle in a client-facing or collaborative environment.\\nBad: The answer is not relevant for a professional role because it highlights a major weakness in a core competency required for project success.|6|Tell me about a time when you had to explain a technical concept or a project update to a non-technical stakeholder?|PASS|85|[\"Rubric includes specific role title in Relevance to role section across all questions, violating the instruction to avoid it.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers and grading rubrics.\", \"Perfect adherence to complex rubric sub-section labeling requirements for all questions.\"]|8ce2cc979729e667074df93f7b3ae626458e34e9|b328f927e652dc76c6f0a396097b12aa27b2e72f|Mobile Application Developer|55|73424df2f80404b2cf959bc80f225a49ccc4782a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262223Z
Mobile Application Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I don't really make many mistakes, but if I do, I usually just try to fix them quietly so no one notices. I think it's better to just get it done than to draw attention to a small error. If someone else notices, I just say it must have been a glitch in the software. I don't think it's necessary to tell the team every time something goes wrong as long as the project ends up working in the end.|Once, I accidentally deleted some important configuration files while trying to clean up my workspace. As soon as I realized what happened, I stopped what I was doing and checked if I had a recent backup. I then informed my team lead immediately so they were aware of the potential delay. I spent the next hour restoring the files from our version control system and verified that everything was working correctly before continuing. I also wrote a small note to myself to double-check my commands in the future to prevent it from happening again.|I made a mistake in a school project where I used the wrong version of a library. The project wouldn't run on my teammate's computer, and they were pretty annoyed. I spent all night trying to fix it and eventually found the problem. I told them about it the next day after I had already fixed it. They were happy it was working again, but it did cause some stress for the team for a few hours.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The response demonstrates integrity, accountability, and a proactive approach to problem-solving. It shows the candidate values transparency and learns from their failures.\\nMid: The response shows accountability but a lack of transparency. The candidate fixes the problem but doesn't communicate with the team in a timely manner, which is a risk for the project.\\nBad: The response shows a lack of integrity and a tendency to hide mistakes. It indicates the candidate may be untrustworthy or unable to learn from their errors.\\n\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate follows a clear sequence: identification, immediate action, communication, resolution, and future prevention. This is an ideal response for a behavioral question.\\nMid: The structure is a bit linear and focuses mostly on the technical fix rather than the interpersonal and professional aspects of the mistake. The outcome is positive but the process is flawed.\\nBad: The response is defensive and lacks a clear structure. It focuses on avoiding blame rather than resolving an issue or learning from it.\\n\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate mentions specific actions like checking backups and using version control. This shows they understand the professional tools available to them and how to use them under pressure.\\nMid: The candidate provides some detail about the technical error but very little about the team dynamic or the professional consequences. It feels like a student-level response.\\nBad: The response is very shallow and dismissive. It shows a lack of reflection and a poor understanding of the importance of quality and transparency.\\n\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The explanation is clear, honest, and professional. The candidate's language shows they take their work seriously and care about the team's success.\\nMid: The response is clear but the candidate sounds a bit embarrassed or defensive. The language is informal and lacks the polish of a professional answer.\\nBad: The response is confusing and reflects a negative attitude. It is difficult to see how the candidate would contribute positively to a team environment.\\n\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: Making mistakes is part of learning in a junior role, and this answer shows the candidate is prepared to handle those situations professionally. This is highly relevant for the job.\\nMid: The answer is relevant but shows a need for coaching on professional communication and teamwork. The candidate has the technical skill but lacks the professional mindset.\\nBad: The answer is not relevant for a professional role because it indicates the candidate would be a risk to project quality and team trust.|7|Describe a time you made a mistake on a project and the specific steps you took to correct the error and inform your team?|PASS|85|[\"Rubric includes specific role title in Relevance to role section across all questions, violating the instruction to avoid it.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers and grading rubrics.\", \"Perfect adherence to complex rubric sub-section labeling requirements for all questions.\"]|8ce2cc979729e667074df93f7b3ae626458e34e9|b328f927e652dc76c6f0a396097b12aa27b2e72f|Mobile Application Developer|56|73424df2f80404b2cf959bc80f225a49ccc4782a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262223Z
Mobile Application Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I don't really do any checks before I submit my work because I trust that I did it right the first time. I think it's the reviewer's job to find any mistakes or problems. I like to finish my tasks as quickly as possible so I can move on to the next thing. Checking my own work feels like I'm doing the same task twice, which I think is a waste of time.|Before I submit my work, I always run the application one last time to ensure that my changes haven't introduced any obvious bugs. I then go through a checklist where I verify that I've followed the team's naming conventions and that my code is properly commented for clarity. I also double-check that I've removed any temporary print statements or test data that shouldn't be in the final version. Finally, I do a quick manual test of the specific feature I was working on to make sure it meets all the requirements we discussed.|I usually just check to see if my code runs without any errors. If it works on my machine, I assume it's good to go. I might look over the code once to see if I made any obvious typos, but I don't really have a formal checklist. If there's something wrong, I figure the person doing the review will tell me and then I can fix it later.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The response shows a high level of personal responsibility and a commitment to producing high-quality work. It demonstrates that the candidate values the time of their teammates and the quality of the project.\\nMid: The response shows a basic level of care but relies too heavily on the review process to catch errors. The candidate lacks a systematic approach to self-review.\\nBad: The response shows a lack of professional standards and a disregard for the quality of their output. It indicates the candidate is likely to submit work that contains preventable errors.\\n\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate provides a clear, categorized list of checks: functionality, style, documentation, and clean-up. This shows a very professional and organized mindset.\\nMid: The response is a bit vague and doesn't follow a clear structure. It sounds like the candidate does a quick, superficial check rather than a thorough review.\\nBad: The response is brief and focuses on the candidate's desire to work quickly rather than accurately. It lacks any sense of a professional process.\\n\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The mention of naming conventions, comments, and removing temporary test data shows the candidate has been taught professional standards and takes them seriously. This is very good for a junior level.\\nMid: The candidate provides very little detail about what they actually look for during a check. 'Looking for typos' is a very basic level of quality control.\\nBad: The response has no depth and dismisses the value of the task entirely. It shows a lack of technical maturity and professional discipline.\\n\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The explanation is clear, logical, and uses professional terminology. The candidate sounds like someone who takes pride in their work.\\nMid: The language is informal and the candidate sounds a bit lazy about their quality control process. The response is clear but doesn't leave a strong impression.\\nBad: The response is blunt and unprofessional. It clearly communicates a lack of suitability for a role that requires attention to detail and collaboration.\\n\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: This is a critical skill for the job, as high-quality work reduces technical debt and improves team efficiency. The candidate's answer is highly relevant.\\nMid: The answer is relevant but shows the candidate needs to develop a more rigorous professional workflow. They are currently at a student level of quality control.\\nBad: The answer is not relevant for a professional role because it highlights a complete lack of interest in quality or teamwork.|8|Could you describe the specific checks you perform on your work before you submit it for a code review or a final quality check?|PASS|85|[\"Rubric includes specific role title in Relevance to role section across all questions, violating the instruction to avoid it.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers and grading rubrics.\", \"Perfect adherence to complex rubric sub-section labeling requirements for all questions.\"]|8ce2cc979729e667074df93f7b3ae626458e34e9|b328f927e652dc76c6f0a396097b12aa27b2e72f|Mobile Application Developer|57|73424df2f80404b2cf959bc80f225a49ccc4782a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262223Z
Mobile Application Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I don't think it's possible to save data if the application closes unexpectedly. If the user doesn't save their work, then it's their responsibility if they lose it. I just focus on making sure the save button works when everything is running normally. Dealing with lost connections is too complicated for the projects I've worked on so far, so I usually just ignore those scenarios.|My approach is to use local storage to save the user's progress incrementally as they work, rather than waiting until the end. I implement a process that checks for a network connection before trying to sync with a server; if the connection is lost, the data remains safely in the local storage until the application is opened again with a stable connection. I also test this by manually turning off my internet while using the application to make sure the data recovery process works as expected for the user.|I try to save the data whenever the user clicks a save button, but I haven't really thought about what happens if the application closes unexpectedly. I guess I could try to add a feature that saves automatically every few minutes. If the connection is lost, the application usually just shows an error message, and the user has to try again later. It's not perfect, but it works most of the time.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The response shows an understanding of data persistence and the importance of user experience in edge-case scenarios. It demonstrates that the candidate can think beyond the 'happy path' of application use.\\nMid: The response shows a basic understanding of data saving but lacks a robust strategy for handling interruptions. The candidate relies on the user to manage their own data safety.\\nBad: The response shows a lack of technical knowledge and a disregard for the user's needs. It indicates the candidate is unable to handle basic data management challenges.\\n\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate explains a clear technical strategy: incremental local saving, connection checking, and manual testing. The logic is sound and easy to follow.\\nMid: The response is a bit fragmented and focuses more on the problem than the solution. The candidate suggests a few ideas but doesn't have a coherent plan.\\nBad: The structure is non-existent. The candidate just dismisses the problem and doesn't provide any useful technical information.\\n\\nDepth check:\\nGood: Mentioning 'local storage' and 'synchronization logic' shows the candidate has a practical understanding of how data works in the project. Their testing method shows a hands-on approach.\\nMid: The candidate's suggestions are very surface-level and show a limited understanding of technical options like background syncing or persistent storage. They seem unsure of how to proceed.\\nBad: The response is extremely shallow and shows no understanding of the tools or concepts involved in data persistence.\\n\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The explanation is clear, professional, and demonstrates a user-centric mindset. The candidate articulates their technical choices well.\\nMid: The language is simple and the candidate sounds a bit uncertain about their approach. The response is clear but lacks technical authority.\\nBad: The response is confusing and demonstrates a lack of professional communication skills. It doesn't provide a clear answer to the technical question.\\n\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: Data integrity is a key part of the job, and this answer shows the candidate has the right technical foundation for a junior role. It's highly relevant to the project environment.\\nMid: The answer is relevant at a very basic level but suggests the candidate will need a lot of guidance to handle real-world data tasks. They are still learning the fundamentals.\\nBad: The answer is not relevant for a technical role because it shows a lack of basic data management skills and a disregard for professional standards.|9|What is your approach for ensuring that data is saved correctly when a user closes a project application unexpectedly or loses their connection?|PASS|85|[\"Rubric includes specific role title in Relevance to role section across all questions, violating the instruction to avoid it.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers and grading rubrics.\", \"Perfect adherence to complex rubric sub-section labeling requirements for all questions.\"]|8ce2cc979729e667074df93f7b3ae626458e34e9|b328f927e652dc76c6f0a396097b12aa27b2e72f|Mobile Application Developer|58|73424df2f80404b2cf959bc80f225a49ccc4782a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262223Z
Mobile Application Developer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would just stop working on the task until the person who assigned it came back to explain it to me. I don't think it's a good idea to guess what they want because I'll probably get it wrong. I would just use the time to catch up on other things or wait for someone to give me a new task with better instructions. I think the person who assigned the task is responsible for making sure I know what to do.|If I received a vague task and couldn't reach the assigner, I would first look through the existing project files and documentation to see if there were similar tasks done in the past that I could use as a reference. I would then create a brief outline of my plan and share it with a teammate to see if it aligned with their understanding of the project. If no one was sure, I would work on a small, flexible prototype of the task so that I could easily make changes once the assigner returned. This way, I'm still making progress without risking a huge amount of wasted effort.|I would probably just start working on what I think they want me to do. I'd try to remember anything they said in previous meetings that might be related to the task. If I get stuck, I'll just wait until the person comes back and ask them for more details. I don't want to do too much work if it's going to be wrong, so I'd probably just do the easy parts first and leave the confusing parts for later.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The response shows initiative, problem-solving skills, and a professional ability to handle ambiguity. It demonstrates that the candidate can be productive even when instructions are not perfect.\\nMid: The response shows a willingness to try but a lack of a structured approach to resolving ambiguity. The candidate is likely to waste time or produce work that doesn't meet the requirements.\\nBad: The response shows a lack of initiative and a tendency to stop working when faced with a challenge. It indicates the candidate may be difficult to manage in a fast-paced environment.\\n\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate provides a clear, logical sequence of actions: research, peer consultation, and creating a flexible prototype. This is a very professional approach for a junior role.\\nMid: The response is a bit impulsive and lacks a clear plan. It focuses on the candidate's personal feelings about the task rather than a professional strategy.\\nBad: The response is reactive and disorganized. It doesn't show any understanding of how to manage professional responsibilities independently.\\n\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate explains the reasoning behind their actions, such as the need to avoid wasted effort while still moving the project forward. This shows a high level of professional maturity.\\nMid: The candidate provides only a surface-level response focused on guessing or waiting. They don't seem to consider how their delay might affect the rest of the team.\\nBad: The response is very shallow and shows a lack of professional responsibility. The candidate doesn't seem to understand the importance of making progress on their own.\\n\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The language is professional and the logic is easy to follow. The candidate sounds reliable and capable of handling workplace ambiguity.\\nMid: The language is a bit informal and the reasoning is somewhat shaky. It's clear what the candidate would do, but it doesn't sound like a well-thought-out professional strategy.\\nBad: The response is poorly articulated and reflects a negative attitude. It doesn't clearly show how the candidate would resolve the conflict in a productive way.\\n\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: Ambiguity is common in project work, and this answer shows the candidate is prepared to handle the practical realities of the job. This is highly relevant.\\nMid: The answer is relevant but shows a need for coaching on professional initiative and research skills. The candidate is at a basic level of professional independence.\\nBad: The answer is not relevant for a professional role because it shows a lack of basic initiative and problem-solving skills. It suggests the candidate would struggle in a real-world project environment.|10|Explain what you would do if you were assigned a task with very vague instructions and the person who assigned it was unavailable for questions?|PASS|85|[\"Rubric includes specific role title in Relevance to role section across all questions, violating the instruction to avoid it.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers and grading rubrics.\", \"Perfect adherence to complex rubric sub-section labeling requirements for all questions.\"]|8ce2cc979729e667074df93f7b3ae626458e34e9|b328f927e652dc76c6f0a396097b12aa27b2e72f|Mobile Application Developer|59|73424df2f80404b2cf959bc80f225a49ccc4782a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262223Z
Cloud Solutions Architect|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I don't really like to argue with people, so when a teammate disagreed with me, I just let them have their way. It is more important to keep the peace in the team than to be right about a technical choice. I usually just wait for the manager to decide if there is a real problem.|During a project, my teammate and I disagreed on whether to use a relational or non-relational database for our storage needs. I scheduled a brief meeting where we both listed the pros and cons relative to our specific requirements, and we eventually agreed to use a relational database because our data structure was highly consistent. This approach helped us move forward without any lingering tension because we based the decision on technical facts.|I once worked with someone who wanted to do things differently than the way I had planned. I sat down with them and explained why my way was better for the project timeline, and they eventually agreed to follow my lead so we could finish on time. It was a bit stressful, but we got the work done eventually.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a proactive and objective approach to conflict resolution. They show a focus on project goals rather than personal ego. Mid: The candidate resolves the conflict but focuses more on winning the argument than collaborative problem-solving. It shows limited interpersonal flexibility. Bad: The candidate avoids the conflict entirely or depends on external authority. This indicates a lack of ownership and communication skills. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear STAR format with a logical flow from conflict to resolution. The outcome is clearly defined and positive. Mid: The response is chronological but misses key details about the actions taken. The structure is somewhat loose. Bad: The response is disorganized and lacks a clear beginning or end. It is difficult to follow the sequence of events. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about the technical nature of the disagreement. They reflect on how this improved the project outcome. Mid: The candidate provides a general overview of a disagreement without much specific detail. The reflection is shallow. Bad: The response is very brief and lacks any meaningful detail. It fails to show the complexity of the situation. Clarity check: Good: The language is professional, clear, and easy to understand. The candidate avoids filler words and stays on topic. Mid: The language is mostly clear but contains some vague phrasing. The candidate occasionally drifts from the main point. Bad: The response is confusing or uses overly simplistic language. The candidate struggles to communicate their thoughts effectively. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows strong potential for team collaboration in a professional environment. This is vital for any project-based role. Mid: The candidate shows basic ability to work in a team but may need guidance on professional communication. They are competent but not exceptional. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of interest in team dynamics. This behavior is unsuitable for a collaborative workplace.|1|Tell me about a time you had a disagreement with a teammate on a project and how you went about resolving it?|PASS|92|[\"Strict compliance with schema and 5-section rubric structure including Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions 5 and 6 are grammatically imperatives rather than interrogative sentences.\", \"Excellent differentiation between answer levels with concrete, junior-appropriate examples.\", \"Clear alignment with dimensions and junior scope across the entire set.\"]|3607d84bb5233f90884e268812db171326f361b0|4345b14b803a834e892aaa23acd5f0757d625c8c|Cloud Solutions Architect|60|d43b381d7ed694accdacedd75823506cdf0f4e53|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.259476Z
Cloud Solutions Architect|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I don't usually make many mistakes because I am very careful with my work. One time a tool I was using crashed, but that wasn't really my fault, so I just waited for the IT department to fix the software so I could keep working.|In a recent project, I accidentally misconfigured a configuration file which caused a temporary service interruption in our testing environment. As soon as I realized the error, I notified the team, reverted to the previous version from our repository, and then documented the incident in our internal log. I later set up a validation check to ensure that similar errors would be caught automatically in the future.|I once made a typo in a report that went to a stakeholder, and they noticed it during the meeting. I felt bad about it, so I immediately sent out a corrected version of the document right after the call finished. I now double-check my work more carefully before I hit send.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate takes full ownership of a mistake and focuses on the remediation and future prevention. They demonstrate a high level of accountability. Mid: The candidate admits the mistake but focuses more on the embarrassment than the technical lesson. They show reactive rather than proactive learning. Bad: The candidate avoids responsibility or blames the environment. This indicates a lack of professional growth and self-awareness. Structure check: Good: The answer clearly identifies the mistake, the immediate action, and the long-term fix. It is very easy to follow. Mid: The answer mentions the mistake and a quick fix but lacks a clear explanation of the long-term outcome. The sequence is a bit jumpy. Bad: The response is unstructured and fails to address the 'learning' part of the question. It feels like an incomplete thought. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific technical context and mentions professional tools like repositories and validation checks. They show junior-level technical maturity. Mid: The candidate provides a very simple example that doesn't show much technical complexity. The depth of reflection is minimal. Bad: The response is shallow and fails to provide any specific context. It does not meet the requirements of a behavioral interview. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses precise language and communicates the incident with transparency. The narrative is concise. Mid: The response is understandable but lacks professional polish. Some parts are repetitive or vague. Bad: The candidate is unclear about what actually happened. The response requires significant prompting to understand. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can be trusted with responsibilities and will learn from failures. This mindset is essential for any technical project. Mid: The candidate shows they can handle basic tasks but might need supervision to avoid repeating errors. They are a safe but uninspired choice. Bad: The candidate shows a defensive attitude that could be toxic to a team. This is a significant red flag for a junior hire.|2|Can you describe a specific mistake you made during a task and what steps you took to correct it and learn from it?|PASS|92|[\"Strict compliance with schema and 5-section rubric structure including Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions 5 and 6 are grammatically imperatives rather than interrogative sentences.\", \"Excellent differentiation between answer levels with concrete, junior-appropriate examples.\", \"Clear alignment with dimensions and junior scope across the entire set.\"]|3607d84bb5233f90884e268812db171326f361b0|4345b14b803a834e892aaa23acd5f0757d625c8c|Cloud Solutions Architect|61|d43b381d7ed694accdacedd75823506cdf0f4e53|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.259476Z
Cloud Solutions Architect|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I just follow the standard instructions given in the manual and hope everything works. If the user has a problem later, they usually just open a ticket and then I can go back and fix whatever was missing. I don't really have a set list of checks.|First, I verify that the allocated resources like memory and storage match the user's requirements exactly. Second, I run a series of connectivity tests to ensure the network permissions are properly set for their specific access needs. Finally, I perform a clean startup to make sure there are no error logs and provide the user with a brief summary of the login credentials and resource limits.|I usually start by checking if the system is running and that the user can log in. I make sure I haven't left any of my own test files in the directory. Once it looks okay, I send an email to the user telling them that their project environment is ready for them to use.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a systematic approach to quality assurance and delivery. They understand the importance of validation before handover. Mid: The candidate has a basic process but it is informal and lacks thoroughness. They focus more on completion than on quality. Bad: The candidate lacks a process and relies on trial and error. This shows a lack of professionalism and attention to detail. Structure check: Good: The candidate uses a logical, step-by-step sequence that is easy for the interviewer to visualize. The flow is very structured. Mid: The candidate mentions a few things they do but without a clear order. It feels like a list of random tasks. Bad: The response is disorganized and does not follow a 'walk me through' format. It is hard to follow what happens first. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific technical checks like connectivity tests and log reviews. This shows practical, hands-on experience. Mid: The candidate uses general terms like 'checking if it is running' without explaining how. The level of detail is low. Bad: The response is too brief to evaluate the candidate's technical competence. It provides no insight into their workflow. Clarity check: Good: The candidate is articulate and uses appropriate terminology. They explain their process clearly and concisely. Mid: The candidate's explanation is mostly clear but uses some informal language. It is acceptable for a junior level. Bad: The explanation is muddled and confusing. The candidate seems unsure of their own process. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the type of organized workflow required for managing technical infrastructure. They show readiness for execution-focused tasks. Mid: The candidate can perform the work but may require checklists provided by others. They show a need for more structure. Bad: The candidate is not yet ready for independent tasks. Their lack of process would likely lead to frequent errors.|3|Walk me through the steps you take to ensure that a virtual environment is correctly configured before you hand it over to a user?|PASS|92|[\"Strict compliance with schema and 5-section rubric structure including Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions 5 and 6 are grammatically imperatives rather than interrogative sentences.\", \"Excellent differentiation between answer levels with concrete, junior-appropriate examples.\", \"Clear alignment with dimensions and junior scope across the entire set.\"]|3607d84bb5233f90884e268812db171326f361b0|4345b14b803a834e892aaa23acd5f0757d625c8c|Cloud Solutions Architect|62|d43b381d7ed694accdacedd75823506cdf0f4e53|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.259476Z
Cloud Solutions Architect|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I usually just pick the fastest and most powerful resources available so that the project doesn't have any performance issues. I don't really worry about the budget because that is usually handled by the finance department or the senior project manager.|I begin by reviewing the expected workload and selecting the smallest instance sizes that can handle the peak traffic. I also look for opportunities to use shared resources where possible and set up automated alerts to notify me if costs exceed a certain threshold. Finally, I schedule regular reviews to shut down any temporary resources that are no longer being used by the team.|I try to guess how many people will use the project and then I pick a medium-sized plan so we don't run out of space. I check the billing page once a month to make sure we aren't spending too much money. If it looks high, I ask my lead what I should delete.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates cost-consciousness and a logical approach to resource allocation. They understand the balance between performance and budget. Mid: The candidate has a vague understanding of cost but lacks a proactive strategy. Their approach is largely reactive. Bad: The candidate ignores the budget entirely in favor of over-provisioning. This shows a lack of business alignment. Structure check: Good: The candidate explains a clear sequence: analysis, selection, monitoring, and optimization. The logic is very easy to follow. Mid: The candidate mentions a few separate ideas but they don't form a cohesive strategy. The structure is weak. Bad: The response is a single statement that does not address the 'how' of the evaluation. It lacks any logical structure. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific techniques like using small instances and automated alerts. This shows practical knowledge of cost management. Mid: The candidate provides generic advice without mentioning specific tools or metrics. The depth is insufficient. Bad: The candidate provides no technical or logical depth. The answer is dismissive of the core constraint. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their reasoning clearly and uses professional terminology. The response is easy to follow and persuasive. Mid: The response is clear enough to get the point across but lacks professional polish. It feels like an informal chat. Bad: The candidate's response is confusing and demonstrates a lack of understanding of the question. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can be trusted with project resources. This is a key skill for any technical role involving infrastructure. Mid: The candidate is capable of following a budget but is unlikely to optimize it on their own. They require oversight. Bad: The candidate's approach could lead to significant financial waste for the company. This is a disqualifying trait for this level.|4|How do you evaluate which resources are necessary for a small project to ensure that the project stays within its budget?|PASS|92|[\"Strict compliance with schema and 5-section rubric structure including Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions 5 and 6 are grammatically imperatives rather than interrogative sentences.\", \"Excellent differentiation between answer levels with concrete, junior-appropriate examples.\", \"Clear alignment with dimensions and junior scope across the entire set.\"]|3607d84bb5233f90884e268812db171326f361b0|4345b14b803a834e892aaa23acd5f0757d625c8c|Cloud Solutions Architect|63|d43b381d7ed694accdacedd75823506cdf0f4e53|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.259476Z
Cloud Solutions Architect|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|If the instructions are too vague to understand, I would probably just stop working on the task until the stakeholder returns. I wouldn't want to waste time doing the wrong thing, so it's better to just wait for them to give me better directions.|First, I would search through any existing project documentation or previous emails to see if there is any relevant context I missed. If I am still unsure, I would ask a more senior teammate for their interpretation of the request based on their experience with that stakeholder. Finally, I would create a small prototype or a draft and present it as soon as the stakeholder is available to ensure I am on the right track.|I would try my best to guess what they wanted me to do based on the few words they gave me. I would start the task and work on the parts that seem the most obvious. When they come back, I would show them what I did and hope that it is what they were looking for.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows initiative and resourcefulness when faced with ambiguity. They focus on making progress rather than being blocked. Mid: The candidate shows a willingness to work but relies on guesswork rather than systematic research. Their approach is risky. Bad: The candidate is easily blocked and lacks the initiative to seek out information. This suggests a lack of productivity in a dynamic environment. Structure check: Good: The response follows a logical progression from research to collaboration to incremental action. It is very well-organized. Mid: The response lists a few actions but they are not prioritized. The structure is basic but functional. Bad: The response is a single, negative reaction. It lacks any helpful structure or plan. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific resources like documentation and team expertise. They demonstrate a sophisticated understanding of how to handle project gaps. Mid: The candidate provides a very simple 'trial and error' approach. There is little depth to their problem-solving strategy. Bad: The response is shallow and fails to show any critical thinking. It is an inadequate answer for a situational question. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's plan is expressed clearly and professionally. The interviewer can easily see the candidate's thought process. Mid: The explanation is simple and easy to understand but lacks professional nuance. It is an average response. Bad: The candidate sounds frustrated or unhelpful. The lack of clarity in their actions is a concern. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can function in a professional setting where instructions are not always perfect. This is a critical soft skill. Mid: The candidate is willing to work but might produce incorrect results due to poor communication habits. They need more training. Bad: The candidate is not suitable for a fast-paced team. Their tendency to stop work when faced with difficulty is a liability.|5|What would you do if a stakeholder gave you a task with very vague instructions and then became unavailable for questions?|PASS|92|[\"Strict compliance with schema and 5-section rubric structure including Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions 5 and 6 are grammatically imperatives rather than interrogative sentences.\", \"Excellent differentiation between answer levels with concrete, junior-appropriate examples.\", \"Clear alignment with dimensions and junior scope across the entire set.\"]|3607d84bb5233f90884e268812db171326f361b0|4345b14b803a834e892aaa23acd5f0757d625c8c|Cloud Solutions Architect|64|d43b381d7ed694accdacedd75823506cdf0f4e53|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.259476Z
Cloud Solutions Architect|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I usually find it very difficult to explain technical things to people who don't understand them. I usually just tell them that it is a complex process and that they should just trust that I am doing it correctly because I have the training to handle it.|During an internship, I had to explain why a certain data backup process was necessary for a client who was non-technical. I used the analogy of a spare tire for a car to explain that while we don't use it every day, it is essential to have it ready for emergencies. This helped them understand the value of the service without needing to know the specific underlying technology.|I had to explain to a classmate how a specific software tool worked so they could help me with a project. I showed them the buttons to click and explained what each one did in simple terms. They were able to use the tool, though they didn't really understand the logic behind it.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates empathy and communication flexibility. They use analogies effectively to bridge the knowledge gap. Mid: The candidate simplifies the task but focuses on the 'how' rather than the 'why'. They show basic communication skills. Bad: The candidate is dismissive and fails to communicate with non-technical stakeholders. This shows poor interpersonal skills and potential for friction. Structure check: Good: The response follows the STAR format and clearly describes the challenge, the method, and the result. It is very cohesive. Mid: The response is a simple narrative that gets the point across. The structure is linear but lacks a strong conclusion. Bad: The response is disorganized and does not provide a clear example. It feels like a generic opinion rather than a story. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides a specific analogy and explains the context of the interaction. They show reflection on the effectiveness of their method. Mid: The candidate provides a surface-level example of teaching someone a tool. The depth of the communication strategy is missing. Bad: The response is very short and lacks any concrete details. It provides no evidence of the candidate's skill. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses clear, jargon-free language. They articulate their thoughts with high precision. Mid: The language is simple and clear, but the delivery is somewhat informal. It is acceptable but not impressive. Bad: The candidate's explanation of their own communication is muddled. It is hard to see how they would be effective in a real meeting. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can interact with stakeholders from different departments. This is a highly valued skill in professional environments. Mid: The candidate can perform basic knowledge transfer but might struggle with more complex stakeholder management. They are adequate. Bad: The candidate's attitude would likely alienate non-technical team members. This is a major drawback for a collaborative role.|6|Tell me about a time you had to explain a complex idea to someone who did not have a technical background?|PASS|92|[\"Strict compliance with schema and 5-section rubric structure including Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions 5 and 6 are grammatically imperatives rather than interrogative sentences.\", \"Excellent differentiation between answer levels with concrete, junior-appropriate examples.\", \"Clear alignment with dimensions and junior scope across the entire set.\"]|3607d84bb5233f90884e268812db171326f361b0|4345b14b803a834e892aaa23acd5f0757d625c8c|Cloud Solutions Architect|65|d43b381d7ed694accdacedd75823506cdf0f4e53|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.259476Z
Cloud Solutions Architect|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I generally prefer to use the tools I already know because learning new things takes a lot of time away from my actual work. If a team changes tools, I usually wait for a formal training session before I try to use the new system myself.|During a group project, we decided to use a new version control system that I had never used before. I spent my weekend watching tutorials and practicing with a dummy repository so that I wouldn't slow the team down on Monday. By the time we started, I was able to not only use the tool but also help my teammates with basic commands.|In my last job, they changed the software we used for tracking tasks. I spent the first few days clicking around and asking my coworkers for help whenever I got stuck. I eventually got the hang of it after a week of using it every day for my work.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a high degree of initiative and self-directed learning. They are proactive about their own professional development. Mid: The candidate is able to learn but is reactive and relies heavily on others for support. They show a standard level of adaptability. Bad: The candidate is resistant to change and lacks curiosity. This is a negative trait in a rapidly evolving technical field. Structure check: Good: The candidate explains the situation, the specific actions they took to learn, and the positive result for the team. The flow is excellent. Mid: The candidate describes a slow process of learning through experience. The structure is a bit flat but understandable. Bad: The response is a statement of preference rather than an example of an action. It fails to follow the requested format. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific learning methods like tutorials and practice repositories. They show a deliberate strategy for skill acquisition. Mid: The candidate describes learning by doing but provides few details about how they overcame specific hurdles. The depth is limited. Bad: The response is extremely brief and provides no insight into the candidate's learning process. It is an insufficient answer. Clarity check: Good: The candidate expresses their enthusiasm for learning clearly. The narrative is easy to follow and very professional. Mid: The response is clear but lacks energy or specific detail. It sounds like a routine task rather than a challenge. Bad: The candidate's response is vague and doesn't clearly state what they learned or how. The communication is poor. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate is well-suited for a role that requires staying up-to-date with new technologies. They show the right mindset for growth. Mid: The candidate can adapt when forced to, but they won't lead the way in adopting new efficiencies. They are a baseline performer. Bad: The candidate's reluctance to learn independently would make them a burden on a modern technical team. This is a significant risk.|7|Describe a time you had to learn a new tool or process very quickly to complete a task for the team?|PASS|92|[\"Strict compliance with schema and 5-section rubric structure including Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions 5 and 6 are grammatically imperatives rather than interrogative sentences.\", \"Excellent differentiation between answer levels with concrete, junior-appropriate examples.\", \"Clear alignment with dimensions and junior scope across the entire set.\"]|3607d84bb5233f90884e268812db171326f361b0|4345b14b803a834e892aaa23acd5f0757d625c8c|Cloud Solutions Architect|66|d43b381d7ed694accdacedd75823506cdf0f4e53|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.259476Z
Cloud Solutions Architect|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I usually just trust that the default security settings of the platform are good enough for a basic application. If we need more security, I would probably just ask the security specialist to come in and look at it for me since that isn't my main job.|I start by ensuring that only the minimum required ports, such as 80 and 443, are open to the internet in the security group settings. Next, I verify that any administrative access requires multi-factor authentication and is restricted to our internal IP range. Finally, I check that all data in transit is encrypted using current certificates to protect user information.|I make sure that the website has a lock icon in the browser to show that the connection is secure. I also check the user database to make sure that everyone has a strong password and that we don't have any guest accounts that are still active from the testing phase.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a solid understanding of basic security principles and hands-on validation. They prioritize the principle of least privilege. Mid: The candidate has a surface-level understanding of security but lacks a comprehensive checklist. Their approach is focused on visible elements. Bad: The candidate is negligent regarding security and relies entirely on others. This indicates a lack of fundamental technical responsibility. Structure check: Good: The candidate follows a logical flow from network layer to identity management to data protection. It is a very structured answer. Mid: The candidate mentions a few disjointed checks. The structure is loose but the individual points are relevant. Bad: The response is a single sentence that dismisses the task. It has no structure whatsoever. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific technical concepts like ports, IP ranges, MFA, and encryption certificates. This is appropriate for a junior execution role. Mid: The candidate uses very general terms like 'lock icon' and 'strong passwords'. The depth is more aligned with a general user than a technician. Bad: The response is shallow and shows no technical knowledge. It fails to answer the question adequately. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains the technical steps in a way that is easy to follow and professional. The language is precise. Mid: The response is clear but uses very basic terminology. It communicates the intent but not the technical expertise. Bad: The response is vague and dismissive. The candidate does not seem to understand the importance of the question. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates they can handle basic security tasks which are essential for infrastructure work. They are a reliable choice for technical execution. Mid: The candidate can follow a security checklist if one is provided but shouldn't be left in charge of security. They are an average junior candidate. Bad: The candidate's lack of security awareness could lead to serious vulnerabilities. This is a disqualifying lack of skill.|8|Explain the specific checks you perform to make sure that a public-facing application is secured against common access vulnerabilities?|PASS|92|[\"Strict compliance with schema and 5-section rubric structure including Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions 5 and 6 are grammatically imperatives rather than interrogative sentences.\", \"Excellent differentiation between answer levels with concrete, junior-appropriate examples.\", \"Clear alignment with dimensions and junior scope across the entire set.\"]|3607d84bb5233f90884e268812db171326f361b0|4345b14b803a834e892aaa23acd5f0757d625c8c|Cloud Solutions Architect|67|d43b381d7ed694accdacedd75823506cdf0f4e53|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.259476Z
Cloud Solutions Architect|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I usually just wait for a few minutes to see if the slowdown goes away on its own because sometimes it's just a temporary internet problem. If it stays slow for an hour, I would probably just tell my boss that the system is having some issues and ask them what to do.|I begin by checking the monitoring logs to see if there are any spikes in CPU or memory usage during the slowdown period. If those are normal, I look at network latency and database query times to see if there is a bottleneck in data retrieval. Once I find the anomaly, I compare it with recent deployment logs to see if a specific change might have caused the issue.|I usually start by refreshing the application myself to see if I can feel the lag. Then I look at the server status page to see if it says everything is green or if there is a red warning. If I see a warning, I try to restart the service to see if that fixes the problem quickly.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a logical and evidence-based approach to troubleshooting. They use data and logs rather than just guessing. Mid: The candidate has a reactive and somewhat superficial approach. They rely on basic visual indicators and 'quick fixes' like restarting. Bad: The candidate is passive and lacks basic troubleshooting skills. This suggests they would be ineffective in a support or maintenance role. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear 'top-down' investigative path from general resource usage to specific code changes. It is very logical. Mid: The response is a series of steps but lacks a clear connection between them. The logic is somewhat fragmented. Bad: The response has no structure and suggests a lack of a plan. It is very difficult to follow. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific metrics like CPU, memory, latency, and deployment logs. This shows practical experience with monitoring tools. Mid: The candidate provides a very high-level overview without any technical detail. The depth is minimal. Bad: The response is shallow and fails to provide any insight into how they would actually solve a problem. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's explanation is articulate and uses professional terminology correctly. The narrative is very clear. Mid: The candidate uses simple, everyday language to describe technical work. It is understandable but not professional. Bad: The response is vague and indicates a lack of confidence in the candidate's own abilities. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they have the diagnostic skills needed to maintain a technical environment. This is a core requirement for the role. Mid: The candidate can handle simple issues but might get lost when faced with complex performance problems. They require more technical training. Bad: The candidate's lack of initiative and logic during a problem would make them a liability. They are not ready for this level of responsibility.|9|Can you walk me through your process for identifying the cause of a performance slowdown in an application you are supporting?|PASS|92|[\"Strict compliance with schema and 5-section rubric structure including Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions 5 and 6 are grammatically imperatives rather than interrogative sentences.\", \"Excellent differentiation between answer levels with concrete, junior-appropriate examples.\", \"Clear alignment with dimensions and junior scope across the entire set.\"]|3607d84bb5233f90884e268812db171326f361b0|4345b14b803a834e892aaa23acd5f0757d625c8c|Cloud Solutions Architect|68|d43b381d7ed694accdacedd75823506cdf0f4e53|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.259476Z
Cloud Solutions Architect|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would just pick the task that seems the most interesting to me or the one that I think I can finish the fastest. I figure it is better to finish at least one task perfectly than to try to do two and potentially fail at both of them.|I would first review the requirements for both tasks to estimate how long each will take. Then, I would speak with both project leads together to explain the conflict and ask which task takes priority for the team's immediate goals. If they cannot agree, I would consult my direct manager for a final decision to ensure I am working on the most valuable task.|I would try to work as fast as possible to get both things done, even if it meant skipping my lunch break. If it looked like I was going to miss a deadline, I would send an email to both of them late in the afternoon to let them know that I am still working on it.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows excellent communication and prioritization skills. They understand the importance of stakeholder alignment and transparency. Mid: The candidate is hardworking but lacks the communication skills to manage expectations. Their 'hero' approach often leads to burnout or poor quality. Bad: The candidate makes arbitrary decisions without consulting stakeholders. This shows a lack of professional judgment and team alignment. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear sequence of analysis, communication, and escalation. The logic is impeccable. Mid: The response is a simple plan of action but lacks the necessary communication steps. The structure is linear but incomplete. Bad: The response is a single choice with no consideration for the other task. It lacks a professional framework. Depth check: Good: The candidate considers time estimation, team goals, and organizational hierarchy. They show a mature understanding of workplace dynamics. Mid: The candidate focuses only on the effort required to do the work. The depth of their organizational awareness is low. Bad: The response is shallow and fails to account for the impact on the project leads or the team. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's strategy is communicated with high clarity and professional tone. The interviewer can see the candidate's path to a solution. Mid: The explanation is clear but the strategy itself is somewhat flawed. The candidate is easy to understand but lacks polish. Bad: The candidate sounds disorganized and their plan is not clearly articulated. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the ability to manage a busy workload in a professional environment. This is vital for any project-based role. Mid: The candidate is a good worker but might struggle in a high-pressure environment with competing demands. They need guidance on time management. Bad: The candidate's approach would likely cause friction between project leads and lead to missed deadlines. This is a significant concern for a new hire.|10|How would you handle a situation where two different project leads assigned you urgent tasks that are both due at the end of the day?|PASS|92|[\"Strict compliance with schema and 5-section rubric structure including Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Questions 5 and 6 are grammatically imperatives rather than interrogative sentences.\", \"Excellent differentiation between answer levels with concrete, junior-appropriate examples.\", \"Clear alignment with dimensions and junior scope across the entire set.\"]|3607d84bb5233f90884e268812db171326f361b0|4345b14b803a834e892aaa23acd5f0757d625c8c|Cloud Solutions Architect|69|d43b381d7ed694accdacedd75823506cdf0f4e53|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.259476Z
Cybersecurity Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I was on a team where no one could agree on anything, so I just decided to do my part of the work my own way. I didn't really talk to the others much because it was too frustrating to argue about different methods. In the end, our parts didn't really fit together well, and the project lead had to fix a lot of our mistakes.|During a recent project, our group was divided on whether to use a manual or automated approach for data entry. I suggested we list the pros and cons of each method on a shared document to compare them objectively. After seeing the time savings of automation versus the initial setup effort, we agreed on a hybrid approach that satisfied everyone. This allowed us to meet our deadline while ensuring the data was processed accurately.|I once worked on a project where my teammates couldn't agree on how to organize our final presentation. We spent a lot of time arguing about the layout and which sections to include first. Eventually, we just decided to vote on the best ideas so we could move forward. It wasn't perfect, but we managed to finish the presentation on time for the meeting.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The evaluator should look for an ability to facilitate consensus and focus on objective project goals rather than personal preferences. The candidate should demonstrate proactive collaboration. \\nMid: The response shows a willingness to move past conflict but lacks a sophisticated or proactive method for resolving the underlying disagreement. It relies on simple fixes like voting. \\nBad: The response indicates a tendency to work in isolation when faced with team conflict. It shows a lack of interest in collaborative success.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The response follows a clear Situation-Action-Result format that makes the sequence of events easy to track. It clearly defines the candidate's specific contribution to the solution. \\nMid: The response provides some context but is missing a clear description of the specific actions taken by the candidate. The result is mentioned but feels disconnected from the action. \\nBad: The response is disorganized and lacks a clear beginning or end. It fails to provide a logical flow of information.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate provides specific details about the different viewpoints and the reasoning behind the eventual compromise. They reflect on how their specific actions influenced the team. \\nMid: The candidate provides a general overview of the situation without much detail on the actual conflict or the resolution process. It feels like a surface-level summary. \\nBad: The candidate provides very little detail and avoids describing the actual interactions. The answer is too brief to assess their actual skills.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The language is professional and the explanation of the technical or procedural disagreement is easy to understand. The candidate remains neutral when describing the actions of others. \\nMid: The language is somewhat casual or vague in places. The evaluator might need to ask follow-up questions to understand what the different ideas actually were. \\nBad: The candidate uses confusing or overly simplistic language. The point of the story is lost in a lack of clear communication.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The answer demonstrates the collaborative mindset and maturity required for any junior role in a professional setting. It shows the candidate can handle common workplace friction. \\nMid: The answer shows a basic ability to function in a team but doesn't highlight strong interpersonal or problem-solving skills. It is acceptable for an entry-level position. \\nBad: The answer suggests the candidate may struggle with the collaborative nature of the job. It identifies a potential risk for team cohesion.|1|Describe a time you had to work on a team project where everyone had different ideas on how to finish the work?|PASS|98|[\"All required Question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Rubric sections and internal Good/Mid/Bad labels are perfectly maintained.\", \"High-quality junior-level alignment and answer differentiation.\", \"Question 003 uses an imperative structure rather than a strict interrogative sentence.\"]|1424b942d7fa3473e3a6e5af201ca96c3beb9780|37845433e9061692e909477fb3cdca130b19241d|Cybersecurity Analyst|70|4a4d64094000e82bca0b115ad2f4ae5041edab5e|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.239436Z
Cybersecurity Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I usually wait until someone shows me how to use a new tool because I don't want to make a mistake. In my last project, I just did things the old way until my manager finally gave me a training session. I find it difficult to learn new things on my own without a formal class or step-by-step instructions.|When I needed to learn a new data visualization tool for an internship project, I started by completing the official introductory tutorial to understand the basic features. I then looked for specific forums and documentation to solve the unique challenges I encountered while building my first report. Finally, I asked a senior team member to review my work and provide feedback on how I could use the tool more efficiently. This approach allowed me to become productive with the tool within a single week.|I had to learn how to use a new internal software for tracking tasks at my last job. I mainly just clicked around until I figured out how to enter my hours and update my project status. If I got stuck, I would usually ask the person sitting next to me for help. I eventually learned everything I needed to know to get my work done.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The response should demonstrate self-directed learning and a systematic approach to acquiring new knowledge. It shows the candidate is proactive and resourceful. \\nMid: The response shows the candidate can learn new things but relies heavily on trial and error or the help of others. It lacks a structured learning plan. \\nBad: The response indicates a lack of initiative and a dependency on others for training. It suggests the candidate might struggle in a fast-paced environment.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The candidate explains their learning process in a logical order from initial exposure to seeking feedback. Each stage of the process is clearly defined. \\nMid: The response mentions a few actions taken to learn but doesn't present them as a cohesive or repeatable process. It feels more like a list of random events. \\nBad: The response is very brief and does not describe a process at all. It fails to explain how the candidate moved from not knowing to knowing.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate identifies specific resources like official documentation and peer feedback. They explain how these resources helped them overcome specific hurdles. \\nMid: The candidate mentions learning the tool but provides very few details about what they actually did. The description of the learning process is very thin. \\nBad: The candidate provides no details about the tools or the methods used to learn them. The answer lacks any substance for evaluation.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate's explanation of their methodology is clear and easy to follow. They use professional terminology appropriately to describe their learning steps. \\nMid: The candidate uses very general language that makes it hard to visualize their learning process. Some parts of the explanation are a bit vague. \\nBad: The response is repetitive or uses confusing descriptions of the situation. It does not clearly communicate the candidate's capabilities.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The response shows the adaptability and curiosity essential for a junior employee who will need to learn many new things. It demonstrates a high level of professional readiness. \\nMid: The response meets the basic requirement for learning new tasks but doesn't show a strong drive for self-improvement. It suggests a standard level of junior performance. \\nBad: The response indicates that the candidate may require excessive supervision and hand-holding. This could be a burden on the team's efficiency.|2|How have you gone about learning a new skill or tool that was necessary for a project you were working on?|PASS|98|[\"All required Question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Rubric sections and internal Good/Mid/Bad labels are perfectly maintained.\", \"High-quality junior-level alignment and answer differentiation.\", \"Question 003 uses an imperative structure rather than a strict interrogative sentence.\"]|1424b942d7fa3473e3a6e5af201ca96c3beb9780|37845433e9061692e909477fb3cdca130b19241d|Cybersecurity Analyst|71|4a4d64094000e82bca0b115ad2f4ae5041edab5e|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.239436Z
Cybersecurity Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I try to finish my reports as quickly as possible so I can move on to my next task. I figure that if there are any big mistakes, the stakeholder will let me know and I can fix them later. I don't really have a specific process for checking my work other than a quick look at the final page.|I begin by reviewing the original project requirements to make sure I have addressed every necessary point. I then use a checklist to verify that all data points, dates, and technical terms are consistent throughout the document. After a self-review, I often ask a peer to look over the report for any clarity issues I might have missed. This multi-step process helps me catch small errors before they reach the stakeholder.|I usually read through my reports twice to make sure there are no typos or obvious mistakes in the numbers. I also make sure the formatting looks professional and that I've used the correct template. If I have time, I might ask a teammate to glance at it. Most of the time, this is enough to make sure everything is okay.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The candidate should demonstrate a high level of attention to detail and a commitment to quality. The response should show a systematic approach to error prevention. \\nMid: The response shows a basic level of care but lacks a rigorous or formalized process for ensuring accuracy. It relies mostly on a single manual review. \\nBad: The response indicates a lack of accountability and a disregard for the quality of the final product. It suggests the candidate is comfortable with submitting flawed work.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The response outlines a clear, step-by-step workflow for quality assurance. It flows logically from the initial draft to the final peer review. \\nMid: The response mentions a couple of things the candidate does but doesn't present them as a reliable system. The structure is loose and informal. \\nBad: The response has no structure and suggests the candidate has no plan for checking their work. It is a very weak explanation of their habits.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate mentions specific tools or techniques like checklists and peer reviews. They explain why each step is important for catching different types of errors. \\nMid: The candidate provides a very simple description of their review process. It lacks specific examples of what they are looking for when they check their work. \\nBad: The candidate provides a very short answer that lacks any detail. It gives the evaluator no insight into the candidate's actual work habits.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The explanation is clear, concise, and uses professional language. The candidate's logic for each step in their process is easy to understand. \\nMid: The explanation is somewhat repetitive or uses overly simple language. The candidate's process is clear but lacks professional polish. \\nBad: The response is difficult to follow and doesn't clearly state what the candidate actually does. It is not a professional level of communication.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The response demonstrates the reliability and thoroughness required for a role involving technical artifacts. It shows the candidate can produce trustworthy work independently. \\nMid: The response shows an acceptable level of effort for a junior role but might require some additional supervision. It is a safe but unremarkable answer. \\nBad: The response highlights a major risk regarding the candidate's reliability. Submitting unverified work is a significant failure for this level.|3|Walk me through the steps you take to ensure that your technical documentation or reporting is accurate before you submit it to a stakeholder?|PASS|98|[\"All required Question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Rubric sections and internal Good/Mid/Bad labels are perfectly maintained.\", \"High-quality junior-level alignment and answer differentiation.\", \"Question 003 uses an imperative structure rather than a strict interrogative sentence.\"]|1424b942d7fa3473e3a6e5af201ca96c3beb9780|37845433e9061692e909477fb3cdca130b19241d|Cybersecurity Analyst|72|4a4d64094000e82bca0b115ad2f4ae5041edab5e|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.239436Z
Cybersecurity Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I just keep an eye on the dashboard and wait for an alert to go off. If there's an alert, I'll look at it, but usually, I just pass it on to someone else because I'm not sure what counts as unusual. I don't really have a specific way of grouping things together unless the system does it for me.|I start by establishing a baseline of what normal activity looks like for that specific system or dataset during regular hours. When I notice a deviation, such as a sudden spike in traffic or an unexpected file modification, I document the timestamp and the specific parameters that changed. I then compare these findings against known common issues or previous reports to see if it is a recognized pattern. Finally, I escalate the findings to a senior teammate with a clear summary of why I believe the activity is worth investigating.|When I am looking at data, I look for things that look different from the rest of the numbers. If I see a big change, I usually check to see if it happened before. If it seems like a problem, I tell my supervisor about it so they can take a look. I try to stay organized so I can explain what I saw when they ask.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The response should show a logical and analytical approach to identifying anomalies. It demonstrates an understanding of the concept of baselining and documentation. \\nMid: The response shows the candidate can recognize basic differences but lacks a systematic or formal method for analysis. It is more reactive than proactive. \\nBad: The response indicates a lack of initiative and a total reliance on automated tools. It shows no analytical thinking or effort to understand the data.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The response moves logically from observation to analysis to escalation. It provides a clear framework that could be applied to different types of technical monitoring. \\nMid: The response mentions the main steps but skips the details of how the analysis is actually performed. It feels like a simplified version of a professional process. \\nBad: The response is very brief and does not provide a clear sequence of actions. It fails to explain how the candidate moves from seeing a problem to reporting it.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate uses specific technical concepts like baselines and timestamps. They explain the reasoning behind their categorization and escalation decisions. \\nMid: The candidate uses very general terms to describe their work. There is little evidence of deep technical or analytical reasoning in the answer. \\nBad: The candidate provides a minimal answer that lacks any specific details. It gives the evaluator no information about the candidate's actual skills.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate's explanation is precise and uses professional language to describe their technical workflow. It is easy for an evaluator to follow the logic. \\nMid: The candidate's language is a bit vague and could apply to many different types of work. It lacks the technical specificity expected for this kind of task. \\nBad: The response is poorly phrased and difficult to understand. It does not communicate a clear or professional approach to technical analysis.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The response demonstrates the analytical mindset and systematic approach needed for technical monitoring tasks. It shows the candidate can add value by filtering and organizing information. \\nMid: The response shows an acceptable ability to perform basic monitoring but might miss more subtle patterns. It meets the minimum requirements for a junior position. \\nBad: The response suggests the candidate may not be able to perform the core analytical tasks of the job. It identifies a significant skill gap for this role.|4|Explain how you identify and categorize unusual activity or patterns when you are monitoring a system or analyzing a dataset for the team?|PASS|98|[\"All required Question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Rubric sections and internal Good/Mid/Bad labels are perfectly maintained.\", \"High-quality junior-level alignment and answer differentiation.\", \"Question 003 uses an imperative structure rather than a strict interrogative sentence.\"]|1424b942d7fa3473e3a6e5af201ca96c3beb9780|37845433e9061692e909477fb3cdca130b19241d|Cybersecurity Analyst|73|4a4d64094000e82bca0b115ad2f4ae5041edab5e|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.239436Z
Cybersecurity Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would probably just start on the task that seems easier or more interesting to me. I would hope that the other person doesn't get too upset when I don't turn in their work on time. I don't really like to talk to people about deadlines because it feels like I'm complaining about having too much work.|First, I would quickly assess the scope of both tasks to see if it is physically possible to complete both. Then, I would speak to both team members to explain the conflict and ask about the relative priority or if one deadline is more flexible than the other. If they couldn't agree, I would go to my direct manager for guidance on which task should take precedence. This ensures that the most critical work gets done and everyone is kept informed.|I would try my best to work as fast as I can on both tasks at the same time. I might stay late to make sure everything gets finished before I go home. If I realize I can't finish one, I would send a quick email to that person apologizing for the delay. I usually try to handle these things myself without bothering my manager.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The response should demonstrate strong communication skills and an ability to prioritize based on organizational needs. It shows the candidate knows how to manage stakeholder expectations. \\nMid: The response shows a good work ethic but a poor strategy for managing conflicting priorities. It relies on working harder rather than working smarter or communicating. \\nBad: The response indicates a lack of professionalism and a failure to communicate. It suggests the candidate will simply let tasks fail without warning.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The response provides a logical progression from assessment to communication to escalation. It shows a mature approach to handling workplace pressure. \\nMid: The response describes a plan to just work harder, which is a simple but incomplete strategy. It lacks a clear communication or negotiation phase. \\nBad: The response is disorganized and shows no strategy for resolving the conflict. It is a very passive approach to a common problem.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate mentions specific actions like scope assessment and stakeholder negotiation. They explain the 'why' behind their decision to involve a manager as a last resort. \\nMid: The candidate provides a surface-level plan that doesn't account for the complexity of different stakeholder needs. There is no mention of priority or impact. \\nBad: The candidate provides almost no detail and avoids the core challenge of the question. It is an insufficient answer for a professional interview.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate's explanation is clear and professional. They use language that demonstrates an understanding of workplace hierarchies and team dynamics. \\nMid: The candidate's explanation is a bit simplistic and uses very general terms. The evaluator has to assume a lot about how the candidate would actually communicate. \\nBad: The response is vague and doesn't clearly state what the candidate would say or do. It is not an effective piece of communication.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The response shows the candidate has the soft skills and judgment necessary to navigate a busy work environment. It suggests they will be a reliable and professional team member. \\nMid: The response shows an acceptable willingness to work but lacks the strategic thinking needed for efficient task management. It is a mediocre answer for a junior role. \\nBad: The response highlights a risk that the candidate will be overwhelmed by normal workplace demands. This could lead to missed deadlines and poor team relationships.|5|What would you do if you were assigned two urgent tasks that were both due at the end of the day by different team members?|PASS|98|[\"All required Question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Rubric sections and internal Good/Mid/Bad labels are perfectly maintained.\", \"High-quality junior-level alignment and answer differentiation.\", \"Question 003 uses an imperative structure rather than a strict interrogative sentence.\"]|1424b942d7fa3473e3a6e5af201ca96c3beb9780|37845433e9061692e909477fb3cdca130b19241d|Cybersecurity Analyst|74|4a4d64094000e82bca0b115ad2f4ae5041edab5e|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.239436Z
Cybersecurity Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I had a coworker who was always doing things wrong, and it really bothered me. I eventually just told them they were making mistakes and that they should follow my way instead. They didn't really like that, and we didn't talk much for the rest of the project, but at least the work was done correctly.|In a group project, a peer and I disagreed on the best way to format our weekly status reports. Instead of arguing, I asked them to explain the benefits of their preferred layout while I shared my own reasoning. We realized that their format was better for high-level summaries while mine was better for technical details, so we combined them into a new template. This resolved the tension and improved the quality of our reports for the whole team.|I once had a disagreement with a coworker about who was responsible for a certain part of a shared task. We both thought the other person was supposed to do it, which led to some confusion. We eventually just sat down and divided the remaining work in half so we could get it finished on time. We didn't really talk about it much after that.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The evaluator should look for empathy, active listening, and a focus on a win-win resolution. The candidate should show they can maintain professional relationships despite differences. \\nMid: The response shows a basic ability to settle disputes but lacks a focus on understanding the other person's perspective. It's a functional but uninspired resolution. \\nBad: The response indicates a confrontational or dismissive attitude toward peers. It shows a lack of interpersonal skills and emotional intelligence.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The response follows a clear narrative path from the cause of the disagreement to the specific communication steps and the final outcome. It is a well-structured story. \\nMid: The response provides the basic facts of the disagreement but skips the details of the conversation or the process of reaching an agreement. It's a bit too brief. \\nBad: The response is poorly organized and focuses more on the candidate's frustration than the resolution. It lacks a clear structure or logical flow.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate explains the specific compromise and why it worked for both parties. They show a level of reflection on the value of diverse opinions. \\nMid: The candidate provides a very simple example of a disagreement that doesn't show much depth of thought. The resolution feels like a quick fix rather than a learned lesson. \\nBad: The candidate provides almost no details about the situation or the conversation. It is a very superficial response that hides their true behavior.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate uses professional and respectful language when describing their peer. The logic behind the compromise is very easy for the evaluator to follow. \\nMid: The candidate's language is a bit informal or vague. The evaluator might be unsure about the actual tone of the conversation described in the story. \\nBad: The candidate uses aggressive or judgmental language when describing their peer. The response is unprofessional and reflects poorly on the candidate's character.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The response shows the candidate can handle the inevitable personality and workflow conflicts that occur in any team. It demonstrates high potential for a positive team culture. \\nMid: The response shows the candidate can function in a team without causing major issues but doesn't show leadership or advanced conflict skills. It's an average junior response. \\nBad: The response suggests the candidate might be a source of friction within the team. This is a significant red flag for any collaborative environment.|6|Tell me about a time you had a disagreement with a peer and the steps you took to reach a professional resolution?|PASS|98|[\"All required Question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Rubric sections and internal Good/Mid/Bad labels are perfectly maintained.\", \"High-quality junior-level alignment and answer differentiation.\", \"Question 003 uses an imperative structure rather than a strict interrogative sentence.\"]|1424b942d7fa3473e3a6e5af201ca96c3beb9780|37845433e9061692e909477fb3cdca130b19241d|Cybersecurity Analyst|75|4a4d64094000e82bca0b115ad2f4ae5041edab5e|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.239436Z
Cybersecurity Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I made a mistake on a task once, but I realized that it wasn't a very big deal and probably no one would notice. I decided not to say anything and just hoped that it wouldn't cause any problems down the line. Luckily, no one ever mentioned it to me, so I just kept going with my other work as usual.|While working on a spreadsheet for a project, I realized I had used an outdated version of the data for my final calculations. As soon as I found the mistake, I informed my supervisor and explained that the report would be delayed by an hour while I corrected it. I then updated the numbers and double-checked the final result against the correct source. To prevent this from happening again, I created a new folder system to clearly mark the most recent data versions.|I once accidentally deleted a small section of a shared document that a teammate was working on. I felt bad about it, so I immediately tried to find an older version to restore the missing text. I managed to get most of it back and then I told my teammate what happened so they could check it. They were a bit annoyed, but it was fixed in the end.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The candidate should demonstrate honesty, accountability, and a proactive approach to fixing mistakes. They should also show they can learn from errors to prevent them in the future. \\nMid: The response shows a willingness to fix a mistake but lacks a focus on long-term prevention or professional transparency. It's a reactive but honest approach. \\nBad: The response indicates a lack of integrity and a tendency to hide mistakes. This is a major failure in terms of professional ethics and responsibility.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The response clearly outlines the discovery of the mistake, the immediate communication, the fix, and the preventative measure. It is a complete and logical story. \\nMid: The response describes the mistake and the fix but misses the part about informing stakeholders or changing future habits. The structure is somewhat incomplete. \\nBad: The response is very brief and focuses on the fact that nothing bad happened rather than how the situation was handled. It lacks a professional structure.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate provides specific details about the error and the specific steps taken to correct it. They demonstrate a high level of self-reflection and professional growth. \\nMid: The candidate provides a simple example of a mistake with minimal detail on the consequences or the process of fixing it. It feels like a very minor or unimportant story. \\nBad: The candidate provides almost no information about the event. The response is too shallow to allow for a proper evaluation of their accountability.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate's explanation is clear and direct. They take full responsibility for the error without making excuses or blaming others for the situation. \\nMid: The candidate's language is a bit defensive or minimizing of the error. While the facts are clear, the attitude behind the response is slightly unprofessional. \\nBad: The response is vague and doesn't clearly state what the mistake was or how it was resolved. It's a very poor level of communication for a professional setting.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The response shows the reliability and integrity required for any role where accuracy and trust are important. It suggests the candidate is a low-risk, high-accountability hire. \\nMid: The response shows an acceptable level of honesty for a junior role but lacks the professional maturity of a top-tier candidate. It's a standard and safe answer. \\nBad: The response highlights a significant risk to the team's quality and trust. Hiding errors is unacceptable in a professional environment.|7|Could you describe a situation where you realized you made an error in your work and how you handled the situation?|PASS|98|[\"All required Question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Rubric sections and internal Good/Mid/Bad labels are perfectly maintained.\", \"High-quality junior-level alignment and answer differentiation.\", \"Question 003 uses an imperative structure rather than a strict interrogative sentence.\"]|1424b942d7fa3473e3a6e5af201ca96c3beb9780|37845433e9061692e909477fb3cdca130b19241d|Cybersecurity Analyst|76|4a4d64094000e82bca0b115ad2f4ae5041edab5e|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.239436Z
Cybersecurity Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I usually just try different things until something works, even if I'm not sure why it fixed the problem. I don't really like to read long manuals or documentation because it takes too much time away from fixing things. If I can't figure it out in a few minutes, I usually just give the task to someone who knows more about it.|I start by gathering all the available information, such as error messages, timestamps, and what the user was doing when the issue occurred. Then, I try to reproduce the problem in a controlled environment to see if I can trigger it consistently. I use a process of elimination, testing one variable at a time while documenting the results of each test. If I still can't find the cause, I search internal knowledge bases and external documentation for similar issues before asking a senior for a fresh perspective.|When something isn't working, I usually start by restarting the application or the system to see if that fixes it. If it doesn't, I try to remember if I've seen something like this before or I look at the recent changes I made. I'll try a few different things to see if I can get it to work again. If I spend too much time on it, I'll just ask someone else to help me.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The candidate should demonstrate a systematic and logical approach to problem-solving. They should show they can isolate variables and use resources effectively before escalating. \\nMid: The response shows a basic level of troubleshooting but relies heavily on intuition or trial and error. It lacks a rigorous or repeatable methodology. \\nBad: The response indicates a haphazard approach to technical problems and a lack of patience or resourcefulness. It shows a poor understanding of basic technical logic.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The response provides a clear, step-by-step workflow that moves from data gathering to testing to research and escalation. It is easy for an evaluator to follow the logic. \\nMid: The response mentions some common troubleshooting steps but they are not organized into a logical sequence. It feels more like a collection of habits than a process. \\nBad: The response has no structure and suggests the candidate has no plan for solving difficult problems. It is a very weak explanation of their technical skills.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate mentions specific techniques like variable isolation and documentation of test results. They explain the importance of gathering data before taking action. \\nMid: The candidate provides a very simple description of their troubleshooting steps. It lacks the detail needed to show they understand the underlying technical principles. \\nBad: The candidate provides a minimal answer with no detail. It gives the evaluator no insight into the candidate's actual problem-solving capabilities.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate's explanation is precise and uses appropriate technical language. The logic behind each step in their process is clear and professional. \\nMid: The candidate's language is a bit vague and uses very general terms. The evaluator has to guess what the candidate means by 'trying different things'. \\nBad: The response is poorly phrased and difficult to follow. It does not communicate a clear or professional approach to technical troubleshooting.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The response shows the analytical and methodical mindset required for successful execution in a technical role. It suggests the candidate can handle complex tasks independently. \\nMid: The response shows an acceptable level of skill for a junior role but might require more guidance on difficult issues. it's a standard entry-level answer. \\nBad: The response highlights a major risk regarding the candidate's technical competence and work ethic. A lack of systematic troubleshooting is a significant weakness.|8|Walk me through your logical process for troubleshooting a technical issue when the cause of the problem is not immediately obvious to you?|PASS|98|[\"All required Question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Rubric sections and internal Good/Mid/Bad labels are perfectly maintained.\", \"High-quality junior-level alignment and answer differentiation.\", \"Question 003 uses an imperative structure rather than a strict interrogative sentence.\"]|1424b942d7fa3473e3a6e5af201ca96c3beb9780|37845433e9061692e909477fb3cdca130b19241d|Cybersecurity Analyst|77|4a4d64094000e82bca0b115ad2f4ae5041edab5e|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.239436Z
Cybersecurity Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I don't really have a formal way of organizing my day, I just do things as they come up or as people ask me for help. I usually remember my recurring tasks, but sometimes they get lost if a lot of other things are happening at once. I figure as long as the major projects are moving forward, it's okay if a few small things get missed.|I use a digital calendar and a task management tool to track all my recurring responsibilities, such as daily system checks and weekly reports. At the start of each morning, I review my list and prioritize high-impact tasks while blocking out specific times for routine monitoring. If unexpected tasks arise, I reassess my schedule to see what can be moved without missing a critical deadline. This ensures that the essential maintenance work never gets pushed aside by less important tasks.|I usually just make a list of everything I need to do on a piece of paper and cross things off as I finish them. I try to do the recurring tasks first thing in the morning so I don't forget about them later in the day. Sometimes if I get really busy, I might skip a small task, but I usually catch up on it the next day.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The candidate should demonstrate strong organizational skills and a commitment to reliability. They should show they understand the importance of routine maintenance for long-term project success. \\nMid: The response shows a basic ability to manage tasks but lacks a sophisticated or redundant system for ensuring nothing is missed. It relies mostly on memory and simple lists. \\nBad: The response indicates a lack of organization and a disregard for the importance of routine work. It suggests the candidate is prone to missing deadlines and losing track of tasks.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The response moves logically from planning to execution to adjustment. It provides a clear framework for how the candidate manages their time throughout the day. \\nMid: The response describes a simple habit but doesn't present it as a complete system for time management. It is a bit too informal and lacks professional depth. \\nBad: The response has no structure and shows the candidate has no plan for managing their workload. It is a very poor explanation of their professional habits.\\nDepth check: \\nGood: The candidate mentions specific tools like calendars and task managers. They explain how they handle the conflict between planned work and unexpected requests. \\nMid: The candidate provides a very simple description of their daily routine. It lacks detail on how they prioritize between different types of tasks. \\nBad: The candidate provides almost no information about their organization methods. The answer is too shallow to assess their actual capabilities.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The explanation is clear, professional, and easy to follow. The candidate's logic for their prioritization decisions is well-articulated. \\nMid: The candidate's language is a bit informal or repetitive. While the basic idea is clear, the response lacks the professional polish of a top-tier candidate. \\nBad: The response is vague and doesn't clearly state what the candidate actually does to stay organized. It is not an effective piece of professional communication.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The response shows the discipline and organization required for any role involving recurring technical duties. It suggests the candidate is a reliable and self-sufficient employee. \\nMid: The response shows an acceptable level of effort for a junior role but might need some help with complex scheduling. It is a safe and typical answer. \\nBad: The response highlights a significant risk that the candidate will be unreliable or disorganized. Missing recurring tasks can lead to serious system or project failures.|9|How do you organize and prioritize your daily tasks to ensure that all recurring maintenance or monitoring activities are completed on time?|PASS|98|[\"All required Question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Rubric sections and internal Good/Mid/Bad labels are perfectly maintained.\", \"High-quality junior-level alignment and answer differentiation.\", \"Question 003 uses an imperative structure rather than a strict interrogative sentence.\"]|1424b942d7fa3473e3a6e5af201ca96c3beb9780|37845433e9061692e909477fb3cdca130b19241d|Cybersecurity Analyst|78|4a4d64094000e82bca0b115ad2f4ae5041edab5e|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.239436Z
Cybersecurity Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would just try to guess what they wanted and finish the whole thing so I can show them that I'm a fast worker. If I get it wrong, I can always just redo it later after they give me better instructions. I don't really like to bother other team members with questions that were meant for someone else.|First, I would look for any existing documentation or previous project files that might give me more context on the request. If I still had questions, I would ask my teammates if they have worked on something similar or if they know more about the stakeholder's preferences. If I was still unsure, I would start working on a small, safe portion of the task and send an email to the stakeholder with my assumptions and a list of clarifying questions for them to review tomorrow.|I would probably just wait until the next day when the person is back so I can ask them for more details. I wouldn't want to start and do it all wrong, so I'd just focus on my other tasks in the meantime. Once they returned, I would make sure to get all the information I need before I begin the work.|Question intent check:\\nGood: The candidate should demonstrate resourcefulness and a proactive approach to ambiguity. They should show they can make progress without wasting time or causing errors. \\nMid: The response shows a cautious approach that avoids errors but also results in zero progress. It's an acceptable but uninspired way to handle the situation. \\nBad: The response indicates a reckless approach that is likely to lead to wasted effort and rework. It shows poor judgment and a lack of communication skills.\\nStructure check:\\nGood: The response outlines a logical sequence of steps from internal research to peer consultation to limited action. It shows a mature and balanced strategy. \\nMid: The response describes a simple 'wait and see' approach that is easy to follow but lacks any proactive elements. It is a very basic structure. \\nBad: The response is disorganized and focuses on speed over quality. It fails to show a logical or professional way of handling the problem.\\nDepth check:\\nGood: The candidate mentions specific resources like documentation and team members. They explain the importance of documenting their assumptions and asking clarifying questions. \\nMid: The candidate provides a very thin description of their plan. It lacks any detail on how they would spend their time while waiting for the stakeholder to return. \\nBad: The candidate provides a minimal answer that ignores the potential risks of guessing. It gives the evaluator no insight into the candidate's professional reasoning.\\nClarity check:\\nGood: The candidate's explanation is clear, professional, and demonstrates a high level of critical thinking. They use language that shows respect for the stakeholder's time. \\nMid: The candidate's language is a bit simplistic and doesn't fully explore the consequences of their actions. It's a clear but unremarkable response. \\nBad: The response is vague and doesn't clearly state a professional plan of action. It reflects poorly on the candidate's ability to handle common workplace challenges.\\nRelevance to role:\\nGood: The response shows the candidate has the initiative and common sense needed to work effectively in a real-world environment. It suggests they can handle small amounts of ambiguity on their own. \\nMid: The response shows an acceptable level of caution for a junior role but might be seen as lacking initiative. It is a mediocre answer for a competitive position. \\nBad: The response highlights a risk that the candidate will be a 'loose cannon' who causes more work for others by acting without information. This is a significant red flag.|10|What would you do if a stakeholder gave you a task with very vague instructions and then became unavailable for the rest of the day?|PASS|98|[\"All required Question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Rubric sections and internal Good/Mid/Bad labels are perfectly maintained.\", \"High-quality junior-level alignment and answer differentiation.\", \"Question 003 uses an imperative structure rather than a strict interrogative sentence.\"]|1424b942d7fa3473e3a6e5af201ca96c3beb9780|37845433e9061692e909477fb3cdca130b19241d|Cybersecurity Analyst|79|4a4d64094000e82bca0b115ad2f4ae5041edab5e|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.239436Z
Financial Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I had a teammate who didn't understand the assignment and kept trying to change my work. I told them that I had more experience with this specific task and that we should just stick to my original plan. They weren't happy, but I didn't want the project grade to suffer because of their lack of knowledge.|During a recent group project, a teammate and I disagreed on which data visualization style would be most effective for our final presentation. I scheduled a brief call to listen to their reasoning and then shared my perspective on clarity for the audience. We eventually decided to create a small sample of both styles and asked a third teammate for neutral feedback, which led us to a hybrid approach that satisfied both our concerns and improved the final output.|I once worked on a project where a peer wanted to use a different software than I preferred. We went back and forth for a while because I thought my way was faster, but eventually, I just agreed to do it their way to keep the peace. The project turned out okay, but it took longer than it should have because I wasn't used to their tool.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a mature ability to navigate interpersonal friction by seeking a compromise that benefits the project. This aligns with the good example where a neutral party was used to settle the matter professionally. Mid: The candidate shows a willingness to avoid conflict but lacks the skill to resolve the underlying issue effectively. The mid example illustrates this by simply giving in without a productive discussion. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of teamwork and a defensive attitude that prioritizes being right over collaboration. The bad example reflects a failure to value the input of others. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear situation-action-result format that is easy to follow. Mid: The response tells a story but misses a clear result or a logical progression of actions. Bad: The response is disorganized and focuses more on personal feelings than the sequence of events. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about the nature of the disagreement and the logic behind the solution. Mid: The candidate provides a vague description of the disagreement without explaining the 'how' of the resolution. Bad: The response is superficial and fails to explain the context or the reasoning for their actions. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses professional language and communicates their thought process clearly. Mid: The candidate uses somewhat casual language and the point of the story is slightly muddled. Bad: The candidate uses dismissive or unprofessional language that makes the interaction hard to interpret. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can work in a team environment where collaboration is essential for success. Mid: The candidate shows they can survive in a team but might struggle with contributing to a positive group dynamic. Bad: The candidate appears to be a potential source of friction in a professional team setting.|1|Tell me about a time when you had a disagreement with a teammate about how to complete a project task?|PASS|90|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric sectioning and labeling rules.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad answer examples.\", \"Question ID 4 uses an imperative sentence structure instead of a true interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and highly relevant to the junior level.\"]|0cdfe4bccad4a92aa9146ee2c59edf5635285fbb|5cca69475551a00078a06de66c4efee051057d6b|Financial Analyst|80|34ec28bce9c3f75334fc494c8b9d2cb64572f0da|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262334Z
Financial Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I don't really make many mistakes because I am very careful with my work. One time a teammate thought I had done something wrong on a project, but it turned out that the instructions I was given were just confusing, so it wasn't actually my fault.|In my last internship, I accidentally sent an internal draft of a report to a client before it was fully reviewed by my supervisor. As soon as I realized the error, I notified my manager, explained what happened, and then sent a follow-up email to the client to recall the message and apologize. I then created a new checklist for my email process to ensure I never send external documents without a final sign-off.|I once made a mistake on a data entry task where I swapped two columns of numbers by accident. My boss found it a few days later and pointed it out to me. I apologized and stayed late that evening to fix the entries and make sure everything was correct for the rest of the week.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows accountability and a focus on long-term prevention of errors. The good example highlights a proactive approach to admitting fault and implementing a system to avoid a recurrence. Mid: The candidate admits the mistake but only after it is caught by someone else. The mid example shows a reactive stance rather than a proactive one. Bad: The candidate avoids taking responsibility and blames external factors for the error. The bad example demonstrates a lack of self-awareness and growth potential. Structure check: Good: The response clearly identifies the mistake, the immediate action taken, and the learned outcome. Mid: The response describes the mistake and the fix but lacks a preventative conclusion. Bad: The response is defensive and does not provide a coherent narrative of learning. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the specific steps taken to mitigate the impact of the error. Mid: The candidate provides minimal detail about the impact or the steps taken to fix the issue. Bad: The response is brief and dismissive of the importance of making and learning from errors. Clarity check: Good: The candidate speaks clearly about their own role in the situation without making excuses. Mid: The candidate is somewhat vague about why the mistake happened or how they felt about it. Bad: The candidate's explanation is confusing and seeks to minimize the mistake's significance. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the integrity and attention to detail required for the job. Mid: The candidate shows basic competence but may require more supervision to ensure quality. Bad: The candidate’s lack of accountability poses a risk to the quality and reliability of the team’s work.|2|Can you describe a situation where you made a mistake at work or in an internship and explain how you handled it?|PASS|90|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric sectioning and labeling rules.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad answer examples.\", \"Question ID 4 uses an imperative sentence structure instead of a true interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and highly relevant to the junior level.\"]|0cdfe4bccad4a92aa9146ee2c59edf5635285fbb|5cca69475551a00078a06de66c4efee051057d6b|Financial Analyst|81|34ec28bce9c3f75334fc494c8b9d2cb64572f0da|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262334Z
Financial Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I trust the software I use to handle the data correctly, so I don't usually find many errors. If the formulas are set up right at the beginning, the data should be accurate. I focus more on making the final report look professional for the stakeholder.|To ensure accuracy, I use a multi-step validation process that includes cross-referencing the data with the original source and building simple audit totals in my spreadsheets. For example, I compare the sum of individual rows against the total provided in the raw file. I also take a break before doing a final manual scan to catch any obvious formatting errors or outliers that might have been missed during the technical check.|I usually just go through the data twice to make sure I didn't miss anything. I try to look at the biggest numbers specifically because those are the most important for the stakeholder. If I have time, I might ask a friend to glance at it, but mostly I just rely on my own double-checking.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate displays a systematic approach to quality control and understands the importance of verification. This is seen in the good example through the use of audit totals and manual scans. Mid: The candidate has a basic habit of double-checking but lacks a structured or repeatable process. The mid example shows an informal approach that might miss subtle errors. Bad: The candidate relies too heavily on tools and assumes accuracy without verification. The bad example demonstrates a dangerous lack of diligence for a data-focused role. Structure check: Good: The response outlines a logical, step-by-step workflow for validation. Mid: The response is a bit scattered and only mentions one or two informal checks. Bad: The response lacks any structure and focuses on the wrong priorities like aesthetics over accuracy. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the specific types of checks they perform, such as cross-referencing and auditing sums. Mid: The candidate provides very general statements about looking over the work. Bad: The response provides no technical or logical depth regarding data integrity. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their process in a way that is easy to understand and replicate. Mid: The candidate's explanation is a bit generic and doesn't give a clear picture of their routine. Bad: The response is unclear and fails to address the core of the question. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows the high level of precision and skepticism necessary for the job's tasks. Mid: The candidate shows an acceptable level of care but may miss errors in complex datasets. Bad: The candidate's approach is insufficient for maintaining the standards of the project.|3|How do you ensure the accuracy of your work when you are preparing a large set of data for a stakeholder?|PASS|90|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric sectioning and labeling rules.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad answer examples.\", \"Question ID 4 uses an imperative sentence structure instead of a true interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and highly relevant to the junior level.\"]|0cdfe4bccad4a92aa9146ee2c59edf5635285fbb|5cca69475551a00078a06de66c4efee051057d6b|Financial Analyst|82|34ec28bce9c3f75334fc494c8b9d2cb64572f0da|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262334Z
Financial Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I don't usually document much because I am the only one working on my specific tasks. If someone needs to know how I did something, they can just ask me and I will explain it to them. I find that writing everything down takes up too much time that I could spend on the actual project.|When I finish a task, I create a summary tab that outlines my key assumptions, the sources of the data, and a step-by-step log of the changes I made. I use clear labels for all files and include comments within my workbooks to explain complex formulas. Finally, I write a brief email or a readme note that directs the team member to the most important sections so they don't have to search for the results.|I try to keep my folders organized by date and use descriptive names for my files so people know what is inside. I usually leave a few notes in the document itself to explain what I was thinking. It's mostly about making sure the final numbers are easy to find on the first page.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate recognizes that work must be reproducible and accessible to the entire team. The good example shows a proactive effort to provide context and documentation. Mid: The candidate understands basic organization but doesn't go far enough to ensure others can follow the logic. The mid example shows a focus on file naming but lacks depth in explaining the 'why'. Bad: The candidate is indifferent to the needs of the team and views documentation as a waste of time. The bad example indicates a lack of collaborative mindset. Structure check: Good: The response follows a chronological path from the start of the project to the hand-off. Mid: The response mentions several helpful tips but doesn't present them as a unified process. Bad: The response is disorganized and fails to provide a coherent approach to documentation. Depth check: Good: The candidate specifies tools and methods like summary tabs, formula comments, and readme notes. Mid: The candidate only mentions general ideas like folder names and date stamps. Bad: The candidate provides no specific methods and dismisses the premise of the question. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's explanation is precise and shows they have a refined workflow. Mid: The candidate's explanation is somewhat vague and lacks professional polish. Bad: The response is confusing and reflects a disorganized work style. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the professional standards required for shared project work. Mid: The candidate shows they can maintain a basic level of organization but may hinder team efficiency. Bad: The candidate’s lack of documentation skills would likely cause bottlenecks for the team.|4|Walk me through the steps you take to organize and document your findings so that a team member can easily follow your logic?|PASS|90|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric sectioning and labeling rules.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad answer examples.\", \"Question ID 4 uses an imperative sentence structure instead of a true interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and highly relevant to the junior level.\"]|0cdfe4bccad4a92aa9146ee2c59edf5635285fbb|5cca69475551a00078a06de66c4efee051057d6b|Financial Analyst|83|34ec28bce9c3f75334fc494c8b9d2cb64572f0da|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262334Z
Financial Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would pick the task that I am better at so that I can finish it quickly and move on to the next. If the supervisors didn't coordinate with each other, it's not really my fault that I can't do both. I would just do what I can and hope they understand that I was busy.|First, I would review the requirements for both tasks to estimate the time needed for each. Then, I would speak with both supervisors to inform them of the conflict and ask for their guidance on which task takes priority for the team. If both remain urgent, I would propose a plan to complete the most critical parts of each or ask if a teammate has the capacity to assist with one of them.|I would probably just start working as fast as I can on the first task I received and then move to the second one. If it looks like I won't finish, I would send an email to the second supervisor later in the afternoon to let them know it might be late. I usually try to just get as much done as possible without complaining.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate prioritizes communication and team goals over personal effort. The good example shows a mature approach to resolving conflicting priorities through transparency. Mid: The candidate tries to work hard but fails to communicate early enough to manage expectations. The mid example shows a lack of strategic thinking regarding time management. Bad: The candidate avoids communication and makes arbitrary decisions based on personal preference. The bad example shows poor judgment and a lack of professionalism. Structure check: Good: The response clearly outlines a logical sequence: assess, communicate, and then act. Mid: The response is more about effort than strategy and lacks a clear plan. Bad: The response is reactive and lacks any structured approach to problem-solving. Depth check: Good: The candidate considers multiple solutions, such as prioritizing, partial completion, or asking for help. Mid: The candidate only considers working harder as a solution to the problem. Bad: The candidate does not provide any real solution and instead focuses on why the situation is unfair. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their reasoning clearly and focuses on professional outcomes. Mid: The candidate's explanation is a bit disorganized and focuses on the stress of the situation. Bad: The candidate's response is dismissive and does not address the need for resolution. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can handle the high-pressure, multi-tasking environment of the job. Mid: The candidate might struggle in a fast-paced environment due to a lack of communication skills. Bad: The candidate's approach would likely lead to missed deadlines and confused stakeholders.|5|What would you do if you were assigned two urgent tasks by different supervisors that were both due by the end of the day?|PASS|90|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric sectioning and labeling rules.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad answer examples.\", \"Question ID 4 uses an imperative sentence structure instead of a true interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and highly relevant to the junior level.\"]|0cdfe4bccad4a92aa9146ee2c59edf5635285fbb|5cca69475551a00078a06de66c4efee051057d6b|Financial Analyst|84|34ec28bce9c3f75334fc494c8b9d2cb64572f0da|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262334Z
Financial Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|When my project requirements changed, I just kept going with my original plan because I had already put so much work into it. I figured that the change wasn't that big of a deal and that it was better to finish what I started. My supervisor wasn't very happy, but I didn't want to start over from scratch.|During a project last semester, we were halfway through our analysis when the client updated the dataset with new variables. I immediately stopped our current work to assess how these changes affected our existing formulas. I then re-allocated the remaining hours to focus on the new data, ensuring we still met the original deadline without sacrificing the quality of the new insights.|I was working on a presentation once when the teacher told us we had to cut the length by five minutes. I was a bit frustrated because I had already finished my slides, but I went back through and deleted some of the less important parts. It wasn't as good as the original, but it fit the new time limit.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates flexibility and a focus on meeting the new needs of the project. The good example shows an immediate assessment of the impact of change. Mid: The candidate adjusts but shows some resistance or a lack of enthusiasm for the new direction. The mid example reflects a compliant but not proactive mindset. Bad: The candidate is rigid and refuses to adapt to new information. The bad example shows a lack of professional flexibility that could harm the team. Structure check: Good: The response follows the STAR method and emphasizes the transition from the old to the new plan. Mid: The response describes the change and the action but lacks a strong sense of the final outcome. Bad: The response is a simple narrative of refusal rather than a story of adjustment. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific steps like re-allocating hours and assessing formula impacts. Mid: The candidate gives a very simple example with little detail about the logic behind their adjustments. Bad: The candidate provides no depth and focuses on their own convenience. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains the situation and their response in a clear, professional manner. Mid: The candidate’s explanation is a bit casual and doesn't fully capture the complexity of the change. Bad: The candidate's explanation is defensive and focuses on their frustration. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows the adaptability required for the ever-changing priorities of the job. Mid: The candidate can adapt when forced but might struggle in highly dynamic environments. Bad: The candidate’s inability to adapt would be a significant liability in a professional setting.|6|Tell me about a time when you had to quickly adjust your approach to a task because the requirements changed unexpectedly?|PASS|90|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric sectioning and labeling rules.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad answer examples.\", \"Question ID 4 uses an imperative sentence structure instead of a true interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and highly relevant to the junior level.\"]|0cdfe4bccad4a92aa9146ee2c59edf5635285fbb|5cca69475551a00078a06de66c4efee051057d6b|Financial Analyst|85|34ec28bce9c3f75334fc494c8b9d2cb64572f0da|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262334Z
Financial Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I haven't really had the chance to change any processes yet because I am usually just told what to do by my supervisors. I think it's better to just follow the existing rules until I have more experience. I don't want to mess anything up by trying to change how things are done.|While working on a team project, I noticed that we were manually copying and pasting the same data into multiple sheets, which was slow and caused errors. I spent an afternoon learning how to use basic lookup functions to automate the data flow between our spreadsheets. This saved the team about two hours of work each week and significantly reduced our error rate.|I thought our team meetings were too long, so I suggested that we should have a written agenda every time. Everyone agreed, and I helped the team leader write the first one. It helped a little bit with staying on track, although we still went over time sometimes.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a proactive mindset and a desire to increase efficiency. The good example highlights a concrete technical improvement that had a measurable impact. Mid: The candidate shows some initiative but on a much smaller, less impactful scale. The mid example reflects a basic understanding of process improvement. Bad: The candidate is passive and lacks the confidence or interest to suggest improvements. The bad example shows a lack of the initiative expected even at the junior level. Structure check: Good: The response clearly identifies the problem, the solution, and the positive outcome. Mid: The response is a bit vague on the impact and the steps taken to implement the change. Bad: The response is a simple denial of the premise and lacks any narrative structure. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the specific technical tool used and the amount of time saved. Mid: The candidate provides very general information about the change they suggested. Bad: The candidate provides no depth or examples of critical thinking. Clarity check: Good: The candidate’s logic is easy to follow and their enthusiasm for improvement is clear. Mid: The candidate’s explanation is simple and lacks professional detail. Bad: The candidate’s response is brief and shows a lack of engagement with the question. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the value-added mindset that helps a team grow and improve. Mid: The candidate shows they can contribute to a positive environment but might not drive efficiency. Bad: The candidate’s passive approach would not contribute to the continuous improvement of the project.|7|Could you give me an example of a time when you identified a way to improve a process and took the initiative to implement it?|PASS|90|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric sectioning and labeling rules.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad answer examples.\", \"Question ID 4 uses an imperative sentence structure instead of a true interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and highly relevant to the junior level.\"]|0cdfe4bccad4a92aa9146ee2c59edf5635285fbb|5cca69475551a00078a06de66c4efee051057d6b|Financial Analyst|86|34ec28bce9c3f75334fc494c8b9d2cb64572f0da|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262334Z
Financial Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I don't really look for outliers unless someone specifically asks me to find them. I assume the data I am given is correct and that the trends are just what they are. If a number looks weird, I just figure it's part of the natural variation in the project.|I start by setting a baseline using historical data to understand what a normal range looks like for that specific metric. When I spot a value that falls outside that range, I first check for data entry errors or broken formulas. If the data is correct, I then look for external events, such as a holiday or a specific project launch, that might explain the variation before reporting it to my lead.|I usually just look for numbers that seem much higher or lower than the others in the column. If I find one, I ask the person who gave me the data if it's correct. Usually, it's just a one-time thing, so I don't spend too much time worrying about it unless it happens again.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a logical, step-by-step approach to data investigation. The good example shows they understand the difference between a technical error and a business anomaly. Mid: The candidate has a basic awareness of outliers but lacks a rigorous or independent method for investigation. The mid example shows a reliance on others to explain the data. Bad: The candidate lacks the critical thinking skills to question the data they are working with. The bad example shows a lack of the skepticism required for the job. Structure check: Good: The response outlines a clear process of identification, verification, and contextualization. Mid: The response is somewhat disorganized and focuses on a single, informal check. Bad: The response is a simple statement of non-action. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific techniques like historical baselining and checking for external events. Mid: The candidate provides very little detail about how they decide if a number is 'weird' or not. Bad: The response provides no technical or logical insight into data analysis. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their investigative process clearly and professionally. Mid: The candidate's explanation is a bit casual and lacks technical precision. Bad: The response is brief and fails to address the core of the question. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows the analytical mindset and attention to detail necessary for the job. Mid: The candidate might miss important insights due to a lack of a structured investigative process. Bad: The candidate’s lack of curiosity about the data would make them less effective in the role.|8|Describe the method you use to identify and investigate an unusual trend or an outlier in a dataset you are reviewing?|PASS|90|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric sectioning and labeling rules.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad answer examples.\", \"Question ID 4 uses an imperative sentence structure instead of a true interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and highly relevant to the junior level.\"]|0cdfe4bccad4a92aa9146ee2c59edf5635285fbb|5cca69475551a00078a06de66c4efee051057d6b|Financial Analyst|87|34ec28bce9c3f75334fc494c8b9d2cb64572f0da|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262334Z
Financial Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I prefer to wait until there is an official training session or until someone can show me exactly how to use it. I don't want to waste time trying to learn it on my own because I might learn it the wrong way. I usually just ask my supervisor to give me tasks that use tools I already know.|I start by searching for official documentation or introductory tutorials to understand the core functions of the tool. Next, I try to apply those functions to a small, low-risk sample of my project's data to see how it performs in practice. I also reach out to a teammate who is familiar with the tool for a few tips on best practices to ensure I'm using it efficiently from the start.|I usually just dive in and start trying to use the tool until I figure it out. If I get stuck, I'll look up a video on YouTube or search for the specific error on the internet. It takes me a little while, but I eventually get the hang of it through trial and error.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows they are a proactive and resourceful learner. The good example highlights a structured approach that combines theory with practical application and peer learning. Mid: The candidate is willing to learn but lacks a structured approach, relying on a 'trial and error' method that may be inefficient. The mid example shows basic initiative but no strategic planning. Bad: The candidate is resistant to independent learning and lacks the curiosity required for the job. The bad example indicates a high level of dependency on others. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear sequence: research, practice, and then consultation. Mid: The response is a bit scattered and describes a more reactive learning style. Bad: The response is a statement of avoidance rather than a process. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific resources like official documentation and low-risk testing. Mid: The candidate only mentions general ideas like watching videos or searching the internet. Bad: The candidate provides no depth and focuses on their reluctance to learn. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's explanation is logical and shows they have thought about their own learning style. Mid: The candidate's explanation is a bit generic and doesn't show much professional growth. Bad: The response is brief and reflects a lack of motivation. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the ability to keep up with the evolving technical needs of the job. Mid: The candidate can learn new things but may take longer to become productive. Bad: The candidate’s resistance to learning would likely hinder the team's ability to adopt new workflows.|9|Explain the process you follow when you need to learn a new software tool or a technical procedure to complete a project?|PASS|90|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric sectioning and labeling rules.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad answer examples.\", \"Question ID 4 uses an imperative sentence structure instead of a true interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and highly relevant to the junior level.\"]|0cdfe4bccad4a92aa9146ee2c59edf5635285fbb|5cca69475551a00078a06de66c4efee051057d6b|Financial Analyst|88|34ec28bce9c3f75334fc494c8b9d2cb64572f0da|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262334Z
Financial Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would just do my best to guess what they want and send it over whenever I finish it. I don't want to bother the stakeholder with too many questions because I know they are busy. I figure that some information is better than no information at all.|I would respond by asking for a brief meeting or sending a clarifying email to define the specific questions the report needs to answer and who the intended audience is. I would also propose a draft outline and a potential deadline based on my current workload to get their feedback. This ensures that I don't waste time on a report that doesn't meet their actual needs.|I would look at similar reports that we've done in the past and try to create something that follows that same format. I would then send it to the stakeholder as soon as I can and ask them if it's what they were looking for. If it isn't, I would just make the changes they ask for in the second version.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate understands the importance of defining requirements before starting work. The good example shows a proactive approach to managing stakeholder expectations. Mid: The candidate tries to be helpful but uses a 'guess and check' method that can lead to wasted effort. The mid example shows a lack of confidence in asking for clarification. Bad: The candidate is passive and makes assumptions that are likely to result in poor quality work. The bad example shows a lack of professional communication skills. Structure check: Good: The response clearly outlines the steps: clarify, propose, and confirm. Mid: The response is a bit reactive and focuses on fixing mistakes later rather than preventing them now. Bad: The response is disorganized and shows a lack of a professional plan. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific clarifying questions such as audience and core objectives. Mid: The candidate only mentions looking at past work without explaining why that might or might not be effective. Bad: The candidate provides no depth and focuses on avoiding communication. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their reasoning clearly and emphasizes the value of the stakeholder's time. Mid: The candidate's explanation is a bit muddled and focuses more on their own effort than the stakeholder's needs. Bad: The candidate's response is dismissive of the problem of vague instructions. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can handle the ambiguity that often comes with project-based work. Mid: The candidate might struggle in roles with complex stakeholder relationships due to poor communication. Bad: The candidate’s approach would likely lead to frustration for both the stakeholder and the team.|10|How would you handle a situation where a stakeholder gives you a vague request for a report without providing any specific parameters or deadlines?|PASS|90|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric sectioning and labeling rules.\", \"Strong differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad answer examples.\", \"Question ID 4 uses an imperative sentence structure instead of a true interrogative.\", \"Dimensions are distinct and highly relevant to the junior level.\"]|0cdfe4bccad4a92aa9146ee2c59edf5635285fbb|5cca69475551a00078a06de66c4efee051057d6b|Financial Analyst|89|34ec28bce9c3f75334fc494c8b9d2cb64572f0da|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.262334Z
Accountant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I usually prefer to work alone because other people often have styles that clash with mine and slow me down. When I had to work with a teammate who was disorganized, I just did most of the work myself to make sure it was done correctly. It was easier to just take over the tasks than to try and coordinate with someone who does things differently than I do.|In my last internship, I worked with a peer who preferred to finish all tasks at the last minute, while I like to work incrementally. I sat down with them early on to discuss our milestones and we agreed on a schedule where they handled the final review while I drafted the components early. This compromise allowed us to meet every deadline without creating unnecessary stress for either of us during the project.|I once worked on a project with someone who was very slow and detailed while I wanted to move faster. It was frustrating at times because we had different paces, but we eventually finished the work by just doing our own separate parts. We didn't talk much about it, but the project got done on time and the supervisor was satisfied with the final result.|Question intent check: \\nGood: The candidate shows a high level of self-awareness and demonstrates the ability to adapt their behavior to achieve a common goal. They focus on professional compromise and collaborative solutions.\\nMid: The candidate recognizes the difference in style but handles it passively or by simply avoiding the conflict. They achieve the goal but do not demonstrate active collaboration or growth.\\nBad: The candidate displays a rigid mindset and a lack of teamwork skills by taking over the work or complaining about others. They fail to show how they would effectively work within a diverse professional team.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The answer follows a clear narrative path with a specific situation, action, and positive outcome. It is easy for the evaluator to identify the candidate's specific contribution to the resolution.\\nMid: The response is generally organized but lacks a clear description of the specific actions taken to bridge the gap between styles. The outcome is mentioned but the process is vague.\\nBad: The response is disorganized and does not provide a clear sequence of events. It focuses more on personal feelings than on the professional steps taken to manage the situation.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: The candidate provides specific details about the different styles and the exact agreement reached with the teammate. This level of detail confirms the authenticity of the experience and their problem-solving ability.\\nMid: The response provides only surface-level details about the conflict and the resolution. It feels like a generic story that lacks the nuance of a real professional interaction.\\nBad: The response is extremely brief and fails to provide any meaningful detail about the situation. It does not give the interviewer enough information to judge the candidate's interpersonal skills.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The language used is professional and the points are articulated clearly without any confusing jargon or rambling. The candidate stays focused on the question throughout the entire response.\\nMid: The response is mostly clear but includes some repetitive phrasing or minor tangents that distract from the main point. The interviewer may need to prompt the candidate for more focus.\\nBad: The candidate's explanation is confusing or logically inconsistent, making it difficult to understand what actually happened. They may ramble or fail to address the core of the question.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: The response directly addresses the need for collaboration and interpersonal flexibility in a professional environment. It shows the candidate can thrive in a team setting without causing friction.\\nMid: The answer shows basic professional behavior but does not strongly demonstrate the proactive communication needed for high-functioning teams. It is a safe but unremarkable response for a junior position.\\nBad: The response indicates that the candidate may struggle in a team environment or refuse to adapt to others. This raises concerns about their fit for a project-based or collaborative work setting.|1|Tell me about a time you had to work with a teammate who had a very different working style than your own?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric section and internal labeling requirements.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\", \"Clear alignment with junior-level scope and role requirements.\", \"Questions meet all length and formatting constraints.\"]|639c4847e7be4a28d33b2f5867de09dad7ff4dd4|f8202ca1c4f38feb4124ae4d1bb7c8f80e076225|Accountant|90|3343177f2b54fd040e536e002d005b137df616f2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255848Z
Accountant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I try to be very careful so I don't really make mistakes often, but once a teammate told me I had some wrong numbers in a shared file. I told them to just change it if they were sure it was wrong because I was busy with other things at the time. It wasn't a big deal because the project was still in the early stages anyway.|During a data entry task for a project, I realized I had used an outdated version of a spreadsheet for several entries. As soon as I noticed the discrepancy, I informed my supervisor about the mistake and provided a timeline for when I would have it corrected. I then stayed late to cross-reference the data with the correct file and verified every entry to ensure total accuracy before resubmitting.|I once made a mistake on a report where I typed in the wrong dates for a series of events. When I saw the error later that day, I quickly went back into the system and changed the dates to the right ones before anyone else noticed. I made sure to check my work more carefully for the rest of the week so it wouldn't happen again.|Question intent check: \\nGood: The candidate demonstrates accountability by admitting the mistake and taking immediate, transparent action to fix it. They show a commitment to quality and honesty with their supervisors.\\nMid: The candidate fixes the mistake but lacks transparency by not informing others who might have been affected. They show some responsibility but miss the opportunity for professional communication.\\nBad: The candidate avoids taking responsibility for the error or dismisses its importance. They show a lack of ownership and a poor attitude toward maintaining high work standards.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response uses a clear format that highlights the discovery of the error, the immediate response, and the final resolution. The logic follows a professional path of escalation and correction.\\nMid: The response is structured but skips the communication step or the reflection on how to prevent the error in the future. It feels like a simple task description rather than a learning experience.\\nBad: The response is fragmented and does not clearly explain the steps taken to address the problem. It lacks a clear beginning and end, leaving the evaluator with questions about the outcome.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: The candidate provides specific details about the nature of the error and the exact steps taken to verify the corrected work. This shows a methodical approach to quality control.\\nMid: The candidate gives a general overview of the error but does not explain the \"how\" or \"why\" behind their correction process. The response lacks the detail needed to show true diligence.\\nBad: The response is very shallow and provides almost no detail about the situation or the candidate's thought process. It does not demonstrate any meaningful engagement with the problem.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate communicates the situation clearly and uses professional language to describe their actions. The narrative is easy to follow and the candidate's role is well-defined.\\nMid: The response is understandable but may be slightly vague in describing the technical or procedural aspects of the fix. The candidate may use overly simple language for a professional context.\\nBad: The response is muddled and fails to convey the significance of the error or the logic of the fix. The candidate may sound defensive or confused while explaining the situation.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: The answer reflects the high standards for accuracy and integrity required in a detail-oriented professional role. It shows the candidate can be trusted to handle errors professionally.\\nMid: The answer shows basic competence in fixing errors but lacks the professional maturity of being transparent with the team. It is an acceptable response for a very junior level but could be stronger.\\nBad: The response is a red flag for any role requiring accuracy and accountability. It suggests the candidate might hide mistakes or fail to take the necessary steps to ensure data integrity.|2|Describe a time when you realized you made an error in your work and explain how you went about fixing it?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric section and internal labeling requirements.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\", \"Clear alignment with junior-level scope and role requirements.\", \"Questions meet all length and formatting constraints.\"]|639c4847e7be4a28d33b2f5867de09dad7ff4dd4|f8202ca1c4f38feb4124ae4d1bb7c8f80e076225|Accountant|91|3343177f2b54fd040e536e002d005b137df616f2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255848Z
Accountant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I have always been naturally good with numbers, so I don't really have a specific process other than just typing them in as I see them. If I feel like I might have made a mistake, I'll go back and check that specific one, but otherwise, I trust my first pass. I think most errors are easy to spot if you just look at the final report at the end.|When I am entering data, I first organize my source documents numerically to prevent any missed pages or double entries. I use a double-entry verification method where I check my totals against the source at the end of every ten entries to catch errors early. Finally, I perform a total reconciliation at the end of the session to ensure the final sum matches the expected output exactly.|I usually just try to be very focused and avoid any distractions like my phone or loud music while I am typing in the data. After I finish a section, I will scroll back up and quickly scan the numbers to see if anything looks obviously wrong. This usually helps me catch most of the typos that might have happened while I was working.|Question intent check: \\nGood: The candidate describes a systematic, proactive process for ensuring data integrity and accuracy. They show they understand that relying on focus alone is not enough for professional-grade work.\\nMid: The candidate relies primarily on personal effort and concentration rather than a repeatable system. They show an interest in quality but lack the methodological rigor expected for precision tasks.\\nBad: The candidate lacks a structured approach and relies on overconfidence or intuition. They fail to demonstrate an understanding of the risks associated with manual data entry errors.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response is organized as a step-by-step workflow, making it easy for the interviewer to visualize the candidate's process. It moves logically from preparation to execution to final verification.\\nMid: The response is somewhat linear but lacks distinct phases of work. It sounds more like a collection of tips rather than a cohesive professional procedure.\\nBad: The response is unstructured and does not describe a process at all. It provides a vague statement of intent without explaining how that intent is translated into action.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: The candidate mentions specific techniques like batching, double-checking totals, and final reconciliation. These details demonstrate a practical understanding of work artifacts and quality control.\\nMid: The candidate provides general descriptions of being careful or focused. There is not enough detail to confirm that they have a reliable way to catch non-obvious errors.\\nBad: The response is extremely shallow and dismissive of the need for a rigorous process. It does not provide any evidence of the candidate's technical discipline or attention to detail.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The explanation is clear and logical, allowing the evaluator to follow the technical steps without confusion. The candidate uses precise language to describe their workflow.\\nMid: The explanation is understandable but uses vague terms like 'scanning' or 'checking' without defining what those actions entail. The logic is a bit loose but generally follows the prompt.\\nBad: The candidate's response is unclear and fails to describe any concrete actions. They may ramble about their general abilities rather than answering the specific question about their steps.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: The answer is highly relevant to a role that demands absolute precision and a high volume of data handling. It shows the candidate possesses the necessary discipline for the project.\\nMid: The answer shows a basic understanding of the importance of accuracy but lacks the professional maturity of a systematic approach. It is an acceptable but weak response for the job.\\nBad: The response is poorly aligned with the requirements of a detail-oriented role. It suggests a lack of awareness regarding the consequences of errors and a lack of professional methodology.|3|Can you explain the specific steps you take to ensure that the financial data you are entering is completely accurate and error-free?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric section and internal labeling requirements.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\", \"Clear alignment with junior-level scope and role requirements.\", \"Questions meet all length and formatting constraints.\"]|639c4847e7be4a28d33b2f5867de09dad7ff4dd4|f8202ca1c4f38feb4124ae4d1bb7c8f80e076225|Accountant|92|3343177f2b54fd040e536e002d005b137df616f2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255848Z
Accountant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I don't really do much planning for repetitive tasks because they are usually pretty simple and don't require a lot of thought. I just sit down and start working on whatever is at the top of the pile until the day is over. I don't think it's necessary to have a special workflow for things that are basically the same every day.|To maintain high quality during repetitive work, I break the total volume into manageable batches with set goals for each morning and afternoon. I schedule short breaks between batches to refresh my focus, and I always use a checklist to ensure I don't skip any steps in the process. At the start of each new day, I spend ten minutes reviewing the previous day's work to ensure consistency across the whole project.|I try to get as much done as possible at the beginning of the week while I have the most energy and focus. If the work is very repetitive, I might listen to a podcast to keep myself from getting bored, which helps me stay in my seat longer. I usually just work straight through until the task is finished so I don't lose my place in the files.|Question intent check: \\nGood: The candidate demonstrates an understanding of the mental fatigue associated with repetitive work and has strategies to mitigate it. They focus on consistency, batching, and self-review.\\nMid: The candidate has some personal strategies for staying engaged but they may actually compromise quality, such as using distractions. They focus on speed and endurance rather than consistent accuracy.\\nBad: The candidate underestimates the difficulty of maintaining detail in repetitive work and lacks any organizational strategy. They show a lack of professional foresight and a risk of burnout or errors.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response is well-structured, detailing a daily and weekly rhythm for managing the workload. It clearly connects the organization of time to the quality of the output.\\nMid: The response is somewhat organized but focuses more on personal comfort than on a professional workflow. It lacks a clear connection between the steps taken and the maintenance of detail.\\nBad: The response is unstructured and dismissive. It does not provide a narrative of how the work is handled from start to finish.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: The candidate identifies specific tools like checklists and techniques like batching and next-day reviews. This shows they have reflected on their own work habits and optimized them for results.\\nMid: The candidate mentions basic ideas like working hard or avoiding boredom but lacks specific professional techniques. The response is surface-level and doesn't show deep reasoning.\\nBad: The response lacks any depth or specific examples of how the candidate manages their time or tasks. It fails to provide evidence of a professional approach to workload management.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate explains their workflow clearly and logically. The interviewer can easily understand how the candidate manages their focus and ensures the project's success.\\nMid: The response is clear but the logic of using distractions while doing detailed work is questionable. The candidate's points are understandable but could be better articulated.\\nBad: The response is vague and doesn't clearly answer the question. The candidate seems to struggle with the concept of 'workflow' and provides a non-answer.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: The response is highly relevant to a junior role that often involves high-volume, detailed execution. It shows the candidate is prepared for the reality of the team's daily operations.\\nMid: The response is somewhat relevant but suggests a lack of experience with professional-grade quality control. It is a mediocre response that would require significant supervision.\\nBad: The response is irrelevant and suggests the candidate is not suited for tasks requiring sustained attention to detail. It shows a lack of alignment with the basic requirements of the job.|4|How do you organize your workflow when you are responsible for completing repetitive tasks that require high attention to detail over several days?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric section and internal labeling requirements.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\", \"Clear alignment with junior-level scope and role requirements.\", \"Questions meet all length and formatting constraints.\"]|639c4847e7be4a28d33b2f5867de09dad7ff4dd4|f8202ca1c4f38feb4124ae4d1bb7c8f80e076225|Accountant|93|3343177f2b54fd040e536e002d005b137df616f2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255848Z
Accountant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would just pick the task from the person who seems the most stressed or who is the most senior and work on that one first. I don't like to bother my boss with my schedule, so I would just try to handle it all myself. If I can't finish everything, I just hope they understand that I was given too much work to do in one day.|I would first list all the tasks and estimate the time required for each to see if finishing everything is realistically possible. Then, I would reach out to my direct supervisor to clarify which stakeholders have the highest priority or if any deadlines can be shifted. If I still have too much on my plate, I would communicate with the stakeholders to manage their expectations and provide a clear update on when their specific task will be completed.|I would try my best to work as fast as possible on every task to see if I can get them all done by the deadline. I would probably start with the easiest ones first so I can cross them off the list quickly and feel like I'm making progress. If I can't finish something, I would send an email at the end of the day saying it will be ready tomorrow.|Question intent check: \\nGood: The candidate demonstrates strong prioritization skills and understands the importance of upward communication and stakeholder management. They focus on proactive problem-solving rather than just working faster.\\nMid: The candidate focuses on effort and speed but lacks a strategic approach to prioritization or communication. They risk missing important deadlines by focusing on 'easy' tasks rather than 'important' ones.\\nBad: The candidate makes arbitrary decisions about priority and avoids communication. They show a lack of professional judgment and an inability to manage workplace pressure effectively.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response follows a logical sequence: assessment, escalation/clarification, and communication. It provides a clear framework for decision-making under pressure.\\nMid: The response is somewhat organized but the logic of 'easiest first' is not always the best professional practice. It feels reactive rather than proactive.\\nBad: The response is unstructured and describes a disorganized approach to a high-pressure situation. It lacks a clear plan for how to handle conflicting demands.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: The candidate explains the reasoning behind each step, such as time estimation and expectation management. This shows they understand the broader impact of their work on the team.\\nMid: The candidate provides a basic description of working hard but doesn't go into detail about how they would determine what is actually 'urgent.' The response is relatively shallow.\\nBad: The response is very brief and doesn't address the complexities of managing multiple stakeholders. It shows a very limited understanding of professional responsibility.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate uses clear, professional language to describe a complex situation. Their strategy is easy to follow and the communication steps are well-defined.\\nMid: The response is clear enough to understand the candidate's intent, but the strategy is a bit simplistic. The candidate's points are a bit repetitive.\\nBad: The response is muddled and fails to provide a clear answer to the scenario. The candidate seems to be guessing at what to do rather than providing a reasoned approach.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: The response is perfectly aligned with the needs of a project-based environment where priorities can shift quickly. It shows the candidate is ready for the realities of the job.\\nMid: The response is acceptable for a junior candidate but shows a need for more training on professional prioritization. It is a standard but unexceptional answer.\\nBad: The response is poorly aligned with the role's requirements for communication and organization. It suggests the candidate would struggle in a fast-paced or multi-stakeholder environment.|5|What would you do if you were assigned multiple urgent tasks by different stakeholders that all needed to be finished by the end of the day?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric section and internal labeling requirements.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\", \"Clear alignment with junior-level scope and role requirements.\", \"Questions meet all length and formatting constraints.\"]|639c4847e7be4a28d33b2f5867de09dad7ff4dd4|f8202ca1c4f38feb4124ae4d1bb7c8f80e076225|Accountant|94|3343177f2b54fd040e536e002d005b137df616f2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255848Z
Accountant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I usually find it difficult to explain my work to people who don't already understand the basics because there are so many details involved. I once tried to explain a project to a friend, but they got confused, so I just told them it's too complicated to explain quickly. I think some things you just have to learn by doing them yourself over a long period of time.|During a group project, I had to explain our data analysis methodology to a teammate from a different academic background. I avoided using technical terms and instead used a comparison to a common daily activity to help them visualize the process. I also paused frequently to ask if they had any questions and provided a one-page summary with the key points for them to refer to later.|I once had to explain how to use a specific software tool to a new intern who had never seen it before. I just sat down with them and showed them exactly what I do every day while they watched me work. They seemed to get it after a while, although I had to repeat a few things when they tried to do it themselves later that afternoon.|Question intent check: \\nGood: The candidate demonstrates empathy for the listener and uses effective communication strategies like analogies and summarizing. They show a commitment to ensuring the other person actually understands the information.\\nMid: The candidate uses a 'watch and learn' approach which is basic but not always effective for complex topics. They show a willingness to help but lack a structured pedagogical approach.\\nBad: The candidate displays a lack of patience and an inability to simplify information for others. They fail to show the communication skills necessary for working across different departments or with clients.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response is well-structured, describing the challenge, the specific communication techniques used, and the successful outcome. It highlights the candidate's proactive role in the interaction.\\nMid: The response follows a simple narrative but lacks detail on the specific communication strategies used. It focuses more on the act of showing rather than the act of explaining.\\nBad: The response is disorganized and does not provide a clear example of a successful communication event. It focuses on the failure to communicate rather than a positive professional effort.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: The candidate mentions specific tools like analogies, summaries, and check-back questions. This shows a deep understanding of what makes communication effective for non-experts.\\nMid: The candidate provides a surface-level description of a common workplace task. The response lacks the detail needed to show they have a thoughtful approach to communication.\\nBad: The response is very shallow and dismissive. It does not provide any insight into the candidate's communication style or their ability to collaborate with non-technical stakeholders.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate's own explanation is clear and easy to follow, which reinforces their claim of being a good communicator. The points are articulated in a logical and professional manner.\\nMid: The response is clear but a bit informal. The candidate's points are understandable but they could use more professional terminology to describe their communication methods.\\nBad: The response is confusing and fails to convey a clear message. The candidate's struggle to answer the question about communication suggests they may actually struggle with communication itself.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: The response is highly relevant for a role that requires explaining findings or processes to stakeholders who may not have the same technical background. It shows great potential for growth.\\nMid: The response shows basic helpfulness but doesn't demonstrate the level of communication skill needed for more complex stakeholder interactions. It is a standard junior-level answer.\\nBad: The response is a significant concern for any role that involves teamwork or client interaction. It suggests the candidate might be a 'siloed' worker who cannot effectively share information with others.|6|Tell me about a time when you had to explain a complex or detailed piece of information to someone who was not familiar with the topic?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric section and internal labeling requirements.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\", \"Clear alignment with junior-level scope and role requirements.\", \"Questions meet all length and formatting constraints.\"]|639c4847e7be4a28d33b2f5867de09dad7ff4dd4|f8202ca1c4f38feb4124ae4d1bb7c8f80e076225|Accountant|95|3343177f2b54fd040e536e002d005b137df616f2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255848Z
Accountant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I usually just follow the processes that are already in place because they were created by people with more experience than me. I haven't really tried to change anything because I don't want to make a mistake or step on anyone's toes. I think it's better to just do the job the way I was told to do it when I started.|In my previous role, I noticed that we were manually renaming dozens of files every week, which was very time-consuming and prone to errors. I did some research and set up a simple template that automated the naming convention based on the date and project code. This saved the team about an hour of work each week and ensured that our digital files were always easy to find.|I noticed that the way we were filing our paper receipts was getting a bit messy and hard to navigate for the rest of the team. I decided to start using color-coded folders to separate them by month so that anyone could find what they needed quickly. My supervisor said it was a good idea and we kept using that system for the rest of my time there.|Question intent check: \\nGood: The candidate shows initiative and a focus on efficiency. They demonstrate the ability to identify a problem, research a solution, and implement a change that benefits the whole team.\\nMid: The candidate shows a helpful mindset but the improvement is relatively simple and lacks a technical or systematic component. They show initiative but in a more limited, 'housekeeping' capacity.\\nBad: The candidate lacks initiative and is passive about their work environment. They fail to demonstrate the critical thinking or problem-solving mindset expected of a proactive professional.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response clearly identifies the problem, the specific action taken, and the measurable benefit to the team. It follows a strong 'Problem-Action-Result' format.\\nMid: The response is structured but the 'result' is less defined. It describes a nice gesture rather than a significant process improvement with a clear impact on efficiency.\\nBad: The response is unstructured and fails to provide any example of initiative. It is a defensive statement about why the candidate does not try to improve things.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: The candidate explains the logic behind the change and the specific steps they took to implement it. They show they considered the long-term benefits for the team and the project.\\nMid: The candidate provides a basic description of a simple change. The response lacks the detail needed to show a high level of critical thinking or technical effort.\\nBad: The response is extremely shallow and provides no evidence of professional engagement. It suggests a lack of interest in the quality or efficiency of the work being performed.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate communicates the problem and the solution clearly. The interviewer can easily understand the value of the initiative and the candidate's role in the process.\\nMid: The response is clear but the example is a bit trivial. The candidate's explanation is easy to follow but doesn't show much professional sophistication.\\nBad: The response is vague and doesn't clearly answer the question. The candidate seems to struggle with the concept of 'initiative' and provides a weak or non-existent example.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: The response is very relevant for a role where improving workflows and ensuring data accuracy are key. it shows a candidate who will look for ways to make the team more efficient.\\nMid: The response shows basic competence but doesn't strongly suggest a high level of proactive problem-solving. It is an acceptable answer for an entry-level position.\\nBad: The response is poorly aligned with the role's need for continuous improvement and efficiency. It suggests a candidate who will only do the bare minimum without thinking about the process.|7|Could you describe a situation where you identified a small way to improve a process you were working on and took the initiative to change it?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric section and internal labeling requirements.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\", \"Clear alignment with junior-level scope and role requirements.\", \"Questions meet all length and formatting constraints.\"]|639c4847e7be4a28d33b2f5867de09dad7ff4dd4|f8202ca1c4f38feb4124ae4d1bb7c8f80e076225|Accountant|96|3343177f2b54fd040e536e002d005b137df616f2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255848Z
Accountant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I usually just ask a more senior teammate to look at it because they are better at finding errors than I am. If they are busy, I might just try to adjust one of the numbers until the two reports match so that I can finish the task on time. I don't think small differences in reports are usually a big enough problem to worry about too much.|First, I re-verify the date range and filters on both reports to ensure I am comparing the exact same data set. If the mismatch persists, I compare the totals of smaller sub-categories to isolate which specific area the error is coming from. Once I find the discrepancy, I trace the individual transactions back to the original source documents to identify the root cause, such as a double entry or a missing value.|When I see a mismatch, I usually start by re-running both reports to see if it was just a temporary glitch in the system. If the numbers are still different, I will go through line by line and try to find the one that doesn't match up with the other list. Usually, after a bit of looking, I can spot the mistake and fix it so the totals finally match.|Question intent check: \\nGood: The candidate describes a systematic and logical troubleshooting process. They focus on isolation, root-cause analysis, and verification rather than just 'looking' for the error.\\nMid: The candidate has a basic approach but it is less efficient and relies more on manual 'searching' than on logical elimination. They show persistence but lack a sophisticated troubleshooting methodology.\\nBad: The candidate lacks a professional approach and suggests unethical or lazy practices like forcing numbers to match. They show a lack of integrity and a poor understanding of the importance of accuracy.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response is organized as a clear, step-by-step logical process. It moves from high-level verification to granular investigation and finally to the resolution.\\nMid: The response is somewhat linear but feels a bit disorganized. It describes a trial-and-error approach rather than a structured professional workflow.\\nBad: The response is unstructured and does not describe a valid process. It suggests a lack of discipline and a failure to understand the basic requirements of the task.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: The candidate mentions specific techniques like sub-category comparison and source document tracing. This shows a deep practical understanding of how to manage data discrepancies.\\nMid: The candidate provides a surface-level description of 'line-by-line' checking. It is a common junior response that lacks the efficiency of more structured methods.\\nBad: The response is extremely shallow and dismissive of the complexity of the task. It provides no evidence of the candidate's analytical skills or attention to detail.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate's explanation is clear and professional. The logic is easy to follow and the candidate's role in solving the problem is well-defined.\\nMid: The response is understandable but a bit repetitive. The candidate's points are clear but the language is a bit informal for a professional context.\\nBad: The response is confusing and fails to convey a clear logical path. The candidate's suggestion of forcing numbers to match is a significant red flag for their professional clarity.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: The response is perfectly aligned with a role that requires high levels of reconciliation and data validation. It shows the candidate has the right mindset for the job.\\nMid: The response shows basic competence but lacks the technical sophistication of a stronger candidate. It is an acceptable but uninspiring answer for a junior position.\\nBad: The response is a disqualifying red flag. It suggests a lack of integrity and a failure to understand the fundamental responsibilities of a data-focused role.|8|Walk me through the logical steps you follow when you identify a mismatch between two different sets of records or reports?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric section and internal labeling requirements.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\", \"Clear alignment with junior-level scope and role requirements.\", \"Questions meet all length and formatting constraints.\"]|639c4847e7be4a28d33b2f5867de09dad7ff4dd4|f8202ca1c4f38feb4124ae4d1bb7c8f80e076225|Accountant|97|3343177f2b54fd040e536e002d005b137df616f2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255848Z
Accountant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I don't think documentation is that important as long as the final number is correct and the project is finished on time. Most of the work I do is pretty straightforward, so I can usually remember what I did if anyone actually asks me about it. Writing everything down just feels like a waste of time that could be spent on more important tasks.|Clear documentation is essential because it allows a teammate or supervisor to review and verify my work without me needing to explain it every time. It also creates a 'trail' that I can refer back to months later if a stakeholder has a question about a specific figure. This ensures that our conclusions are transparent, reproducible, and can stand up to any internal or external audit of our process.|It's important to keep good notes so that you don't forget how you got your answer if someone asks you about it later. I find that if I don't write down my steps, I have to spend a lot of time re-doing the work just to explain it to my boss. Having documentation just makes the whole review process go a lot faster for everyone involved in the project.|Question intent check: \\nGood: The candidate understands the importance of transparency, auditability, and team continuity. They see documentation as a professional standard rather than just a personal memory aid.\\nMid: The candidate sees documentation primarily as a way to save themselves time or to help them remember their own work. They miss the broader professional implications of auditability and transparency.\\nBad: The candidate dismisses the importance of documentation and fails to understand its role in professional accountability. They show a lack of awareness regarding the standards of the industry.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response is well-structured, providing multiple reasons for the importance of documentation (verification, auditability, efficiency). It builds a strong case for professional standards.\\nMid: The response is structured but focuses on a single, personal reason. It lacks the breadth of a more professional and comprehensive answer.\\nBad: The response is unstructured and dismissive. It fails to provide any valid reasons for maintaining good documentation and instead argues against the practice.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: The candidate identifies specific concepts like reproducibility and audit trails. This shows a sophisticated understanding of how their work fits into the larger organizational framework.\\nMid: The candidate provides a surface-level explanation of documentation as a way to avoid repeating work. It is a common junior-level perspective that lacks professional depth.\\nBad: The response is very shallow and shows a lack of engagement with the requirements of the role. It suggests the candidate might be resistant to following established professional protocols.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate's explanation is clear, logical, and uses professional terminology appropriately. Their points are well-articulated and easy for the evaluator to follow.\\nMid: The response is clear enough to understand the candidate's personal perspective, but it lacks a professional tone. The candidate's language is a bit informal.\\nBad: The response is muddled and fails to convey any positive reasons for documentation. The candidate's argument against documentation is logically weak and unprofessional.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: The answer is highly relevant for any role where work must be verified by others or where numerical conclusions are used for significant decisions. It shows a high level of professional maturity.\\nMid: The answer shows a basic understanding of workplace efficiency but lacks the commitment to high standards required for complex projects. It is a mediocre response for this level.\\nBad: The response is poorly aligned with the role's requirements for accountability and precision. It suggests the candidate would be difficult to manage and their work would be hard to verify.|9|Why is it important to maintain clear and organized documentation of the steps you took to reach a specific numerical conclusion in your work?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric section and internal labeling requirements.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\", \"Clear alignment with junior-level scope and role requirements.\", \"Questions meet all length and formatting constraints.\"]|639c4847e7be4a28d33b2f5867de09dad7ff4dd4|f8202ca1c4f38feb4124ae4d1bb7c8f80e076225|Accountant|98|3343177f2b54fd040e536e002d005b137df616f2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255848Z
Accountant|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I wouldn't want to start the project and do it completely wrong, so I would probably just wait until the supervisor comes back to ask for more details. I would spend the afternoon working on other smaller tasks that I already know how to do so that I'm not wasting any time. It's better to be safe than to have to re-do the whole project tomorrow morning.|I would first review all the materials provided to see if I can find clues about the project's goals or similar past examples. I would then draft a brief outline of my planned approach and a list of specific questions for my supervisor when they return. In the meantime, I would work on the parts of the task that I am confident about to ensure that I am still making progress without making assumptions.|I would probably ask a more experienced teammate if they have ever done a project like this before and if they can explain what the supervisor usually expects. If no one else is around to help, I would just try to do what I think they want based on the little bit of information I have. I'd rather have something to show them when they get back than to have done nothing at all.|Question intent check: \\nGood: The candidate shows initiative and the ability to work independently under ambiguity. They focus on gathering information, planning, and making safe progress rather than just waiting for help.\\nMid: The candidate relies on others for guidance but is still willing to try and make progress. They show some initiative but are more likely to make errors by guessing at the requirements.\\nBad: The candidate is passive and avoids the ambiguity altogether by waiting for the supervisor. They fail to show the problem-solving mindset or the independence expected of a professional team member.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response follows a clear strategy: internal review, planning, and incremental execution. It provides a logical framework for handling a common workplace challenge.\\nMid: The response is somewhat organized but the strategy relies heavily on the availability of others. It lacks a clear plan for how the candidate would handle the situation on their own.\\nBad: The response is unstructured and describes a reactive approach to the situation. It fails to provide a positive or proactive plan for managing the ambiguity.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: The candidate mentions specific actions like looking for past examples and drafting an approach outline. This shows they have a practical toolkit for dealing with unclear instructions.\\nMid: The candidate provides a surface-level description of asking for help or guessing. The response lacks the detail needed to show they can think critically about the project's goals.\\nBad: The response is very shallow and shows a lack of engagement with the task. It suggests a candidate who is easily paralyzed by a lack of perfect information.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate's explanation is clear and logical. Their strategy for managing the afternoon is easy for the interviewer to visualize and evaluate.\\nMid: The response is clear enough to understand the candidate's intent, but the strategy is a bit weak. The candidate's points are understandable but not particularly impressive.\\nBad: The response is muddled and fails to provide a clear answer to the scenario. The candidate seems to be avoiding the core of the question about handling ambiguity.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: The response is highly relevant for a junior role where instructions may not always be perfectly clear. it shows a candidate who can add value even without constant supervision.\\nMid: The response shows basic competence but suggests a high level of dependence on others. It is an acceptable but weak answer for a professional position.\\nBad: The response is poorly aligned with the role's need for independence and proactive problem-solving. It suggests the candidate would require a high level of hand-holding from their supervisor.|10|How would you handle a situation where a supervisor gave you a project with very vague instructions and then left the office for the afternoon?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent adherence to complex rubric section and internal labeling requirements.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\", \"Clear alignment with junior-level scope and role requirements.\", \"Questions meet all length and formatting constraints.\"]|639c4847e7be4a28d33b2f5867de09dad7ff4dd4|f8202ca1c4f38feb4124ae4d1bb7c8f80e076225|Accountant|99|3343177f2b54fd040e536e002d005b137df616f2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:39:17.255848Z
Compliance Officer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I had a teammate who was doing everything wrong, so I just did my part of the work and ignored them. I didn't want to get into a fight, so I stayed quiet and let the supervisor handle it if they noticed anything wrong later on.|During a group project, a teammate wanted to skip the final review phase to save time. I explained that skipping this step could lead to errors, so I suggested we divide the remaining check-list items between us to finish faster without compromising quality. We ended up completing the review on time and found two significant errors before submission.|I once worked with someone who didn't like my method for organizing our shared files. We had a brief argument about it, but eventually, I just decided to use their method because it wasn't worth the trouble of fighting. The project got done, but I think my way was slightly more efficient.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a proactive approach to resolving conflict while keeping project goals in mind. They show the ability to negotiate and find a compromise. Mid: The candidate avoids the conflict rather than resolving it professionally. They prioritize harmony over the best technical outcome. Bad: The candidate displays a lack of teamwork and accountability. They refuse to engage in problem-solving and shift responsibility to others. Structure check: Good: The response follows the STAR method clearly with a specific situation and result. The actions taken are logical and well-explained. Mid: The response provides some context but lacks a strong description of the actions taken. The result is mentioned but not detailed. Bad: The response is vague and lacks a clear sequence of events. It does not provide enough information to evaluate the candidate's behavior. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about the conversation and the reasoning behind their choice. This shows a high level of self-reflection. Mid: The candidate provides a surface-level account of the disagreement. They do not explore the underlying causes or the impact of their actions. Bad: The candidate offers very brief answers with no specific details. It is impossible to tell if the situation actually occurred. Clarity check: Good: The language used is professional, clear, and easy to follow. The candidate communicates their thoughts effectively. Mid: The candidate uses some informal language or slightly confusing phrasing. The core message is present but requires effort to understand. Bad: The candidate is difficult to understand or rambles. Their point is lost in unnecessary or confusing detail. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can handle interpersonal friction in a way that protects the project's integrity. This is vital for maintaining standards in a team. Mid: The candidate shows basic professional conduct but lacks the initiative to improve team processes. They are reactive rather than proactive. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of professional maturity. Their approach could lead to team dysfunction or missed errors.|1|Tell me about a time when you had a disagreement with a teammate about how to complete a project task?|PASS|100|[\"All expected IDs are present and unique.\", \"Excellent adherence to strict rubric structure including all mandatory internal labels.\", \"Questions perfectly align with the specified level and competency dimensions.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level depth.\"]|457767929f48120c005854de431402b58b8c935f|b251bd2963ae7dd754437702611574efe7edc143|Compliance Officer|100|8e5d697846491b3adedec5686ab9e9bc9c77ecc2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:30.463604Z
Compliance Officer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I made a mistake on a project once, but I realized it right before the deadline. I hoped nobody would notice because it was a small error, and since no one said anything, I just left it as it was to avoid making a scene.|In my previous internship, I accidentally sent an internal draft to a stakeholder before it was finalized. As soon as I realized the error, I contacted my supervisor to inform them, then sent a follow-up email to the stakeholder with the correct version and an apology. I then created a new email protocol to ensure I double-check recipient lists in the future.|I once forgot to include a specific data point in a report I submitted to my professor. When I noticed it the next day, I quickly updated the document and sent the new version over. It wasn't a huge deal, and they accepted the update without any points being deducted.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows high ownership and transparency when dealing with errors. They demonstrate a commitment to learning and preventing future issues. Mid: The candidate fixes the mistake but does not show a deep understanding of the impact. They treat the error as a minor inconvenience rather than a learning opportunity. Bad: The candidate lacks accountability and tries to hide mistakes. This behavior poses a significant risk to the integrity of any project. Structure check: Good: The response clearly outlines the mistake, the immediate reaction, and the long-term solution. It is a well-structured narrative. Mid: The response identifies the mistake and the fix but misses the preventative steps. The flow is acceptable but incomplete. Bad: The response is disorganized and fails to provide a clear resolution. The candidate does not explain the outcome of their actions. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the logic behind their corrective actions. They show they can think critically under pressure. Mid: The candidate provides only the basic facts of the event. There is little reflection on why the mistake happened or how they felt. Bad: The candidate provides almost no detail. The answer feels generic and lacks the substance of a real experience. Clarity check: Good: The explanation is concise and professional. The candidate gets straight to the point without unnecessary jargon. Mid: The candidate's explanation is a bit wordy but eventually makes sense. Some parts of the story are slightly unclear. Bad: The candidate is vague and difficult to follow. Their communication style makes it hard to trust the account. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the reliability and honesty required for the job. They show they can be trusted with sensitive tasks. Mid: The candidate shows they can perform basic duties but may need more supervision to ensure quality. They are not yet fully self-correcting. Bad: The candidate's lack of transparency is a disqualifying trait. They do not demonstrate the ethical standards required for professional work.|2|Describe a time you made a mistake at work or school and how you went about fixing it?|PASS|100|[\"All expected IDs are present and unique.\", \"Excellent adherence to strict rubric structure including all mandatory internal labels.\", \"Questions perfectly align with the specified level and competency dimensions.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level depth.\"]|457767929f48120c005854de431402b58b8c935f|b251bd2963ae7dd754437702611574efe7edc143|Compliance Officer|101|8e5d697846491b3adedec5686ab9e9bc9c77ecc2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:30.463604Z
Compliance Officer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I trust that my first draft is usually pretty good, so I just do a quick scan of the pages. If there are no obvious red squiggles from the spell-checker, I go ahead and submit it so I can move on to the next task.|I start by reviewing the document against the original source data to ensure all figures match perfectly. Next, I use a specific checklist I developed to verify that all required sections and formatting standards are met. Finally, I read the text aloud to catch any grammatical errors or awkward phrasing that I might have missed during a silent read.|I usually read through my reports two or three times to make sure everything looks correct. I check for spelling mistakes using the built-in software and make sure the names of the stakeholders are spelled right. If I have time, I might ask a friend to glance at it too.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate has a systematic and disciplined approach to quality control. They use multiple methods to verify their work. Mid: The candidate relies on basic tools and simple reviews. Their process is present but lacks rigor and structure. Bad: The candidate is careless and overconfident in their initial work. They do not demonstrate a commitment to accuracy. Structure check: Good: The response is organized into a clear, step-by-step process. Each step serves a specific purpose in the verification workflow. Mid: The response lists a few actions but they do not feel like a cohesive system. The order of operations is somewhat random. Bad: The response lacks any structure. It suggests a lack of planning and a reactive approach to work quality. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains why they take each step, such as reading aloud to catch specific types of errors. This shows professional insight. Mid: The candidate describes what they do but not why they do it. The answer is functional but lacks depth. Bad: The candidate provides no detail on their methods. They treat accuracy as an afterthought rather than a core responsibility. Clarity check: Good: The steps are described clearly and are easy for an evaluator to visualize. The communication is crisp. Mid: The explanation is a bit vague. It is not entirely clear how the candidate moves from one step to the next. Bad: The response is too brief to be clear. It provides no useful information about the candidate's actual habits. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the meticulous attention to detail required for the project's success. They are likely to produce high-quality artifacts. Mid: The candidate's work would likely be acceptable but might require additional rounds of review. They are not yet fully independent in quality assurance. Bad: The candidate's lack of a verification process is a risk. They are likely to submit work with avoidable errors.|3|Walk me through the steps you take to ensure that a document or report is fully accurate before you submit it?|PASS|100|[\"All expected IDs are present and unique.\", \"Excellent adherence to strict rubric structure including all mandatory internal labels.\", \"Questions perfectly align with the specified level and competency dimensions.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level depth.\"]|457767929f48120c005854de431402b58b8c935f|b251bd2963ae7dd754437702611574efe7edc143|Compliance Officer|102|8e5d697846491b3adedec5686ab9e9bc9c77ecc2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:30.463604Z
Compliance Officer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I just try to remember everything in my head because I have a pretty good memory. If something is really important, someone will usually send me a reminder or ask me about it, so I don't feel the need to write every little thing down.|I use a digital tracking sheet where I list every activity along with its current status and upcoming deadlines. Every morning, I spend fifteen minutes updating the sheet and flagging any tasks that are behind schedule or need immediate attention. This allows me to see the big picture and ensures that nothing is overlooked as the project progresses.|I keep a lot of notes in my calendar and use sticky notes on my desk for the most important things. I try to check my emails frequently to see if anyone has sent an update on the various tasks I am tracking. It works well enough most of the time.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate uses structured tools and consistent habits to manage complexity. They show an understanding of the importance of systematic tracking. Mid: The candidate has a loose system that relies on memory and disjointed notes. This approach is prone to failure as the workload increases. Bad: The candidate has no system for tracking tasks. They rely on external pressure rather than internal organization to manage their work. Structure check: Good: The candidate explains their routine clearly, including the 'when' and 'how' of their organization. The logic is easy to follow. Mid: The candidate describes a collection of habits rather than a structured workflow. The response is a bit scattered. Bad: The response is a single statement of intent with no description of a process. It does not answer the 'how' part of the question. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific behaviors like morning reviews and status flagging. This shows they have actually implemented these strategies. Mid: The candidate provides generic examples like using a calendar. They do not explain how they use these tools to solve the problem of multiple tasks. Bad: The candidate provides no detail. Their answer suggests they haven't thought about workflow management before. Clarity check: Good: The response is articulate and uses professional terminology appropriately. The candidate’s method is perfectly clear. Mid: The candidate's description is a bit messy. It takes some interpretation to understand how they actually stay organized. Bad: The response is unclear and defensive. It does not provide a coherent explanation of their work habits. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can handle the administrative burden of the job. They are organized and reliable. Mid: The candidate might struggle in a fast-paced environment. Their current methods may not scale well with more responsibility. Bad: The candidate is likely to lose track of details. This lack of organization is a major weakness for this type of role.|4|How do you organize your workflow when you have to monitor and track multiple ongoing project activities simultaneously?|PASS|100|[\"All expected IDs are present and unique.\", \"Excellent adherence to strict rubric structure including all mandatory internal labels.\", \"Questions perfectly align with the specified level and competency dimensions.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level depth.\"]|457767929f48120c005854de431402b58b8c935f|b251bd2963ae7dd754437702611574efe7edc143|Compliance Officer|103|8e5d697846491b3adedec5686ab9e9bc9c77ecc2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:30.463604Z
Compliance Officer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would probably just start the new task immediately because the supervisor said it was urgent. If I miss the original deadline, I would just tell them later that I was busy with the new assignment they gave me.|I would first quickly assess the requirements of the new task and then have a brief conversation with my supervisor. I would explain my current progress on the existing deadline and ask them to help me prioritize which task should come first. This ensures I am focusing on the most important goal while being transparent about my capacity.|I would try my best to work faster and stay late to get both tasks done on time. I don't want to tell my supervisor I can't do something, so I would just push myself to handle the extra load even if it is stressful.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate understands the importance of communication and resource management. They seek alignment with leadership before making assumptions. Mid: The candidate is eager to please but lacks the ability to manage expectations. This approach leads to burnout and potential quality issues. Bad: The candidate is reactive and does not communicate. They allow one task to fail without warning the stakeholder. Structure check: Good: The response follows a logical decision-making path. It starts with assessment, followed by communication, and then action. Mid: The response focuses only on the effort and not the process. It jumps straight to the 'working harder' part. Bad: The response shows a lack of planning. The candidate’s plan is simply to hope for the best without any strategy. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the 'why' behind their communication strategy. They show awareness of the impact of their choices on the team. Mid: The candidate offers a simple solution of working harder. They do not consider the risks of multitasking or missed deadlines. Bad: The candidate provides a very shallow response. They don't seem to realize that missing a deadline is a serious issue. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's logic is clear and professional. They communicate their plan with confidence and clarity. Mid: The candidate's response is a bit emotional. They focus on stress rather than a professional workflow. Bad: The candidate's response is blunt and lacks professional polish. It is difficult to see how this approach would work in a real office. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows the maturity to handle shifting priorities. This is a key skill for any junior professional. Mid: The candidate shows a good work ethic but needs to develop better communication skills. They are currently a 'yes person' which can be risky. Bad: The candidate's approach is unprofessional. Their lack of communication would create unnecessary problems for the team.|5|What would you do if your supervisor gave you a new urgent task while you were already working toward a tight deadline?|PASS|100|[\"All expected IDs are present and unique.\", \"Excellent adherence to strict rubric structure including all mandatory internal labels.\", \"Questions perfectly align with the specified level and competency dimensions.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level depth.\"]|457767929f48120c005854de431402b58b8c935f|b251bd2963ae7dd754437702611574efe7edc143|Compliance Officer|104|8e5d697846491b3adedec5686ab9e9bc9c77ecc2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:30.463604Z
Compliance Officer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I was asked to follow a new set of rules once, but I thought the old way was easier, so I just kept doing it that way for a while. I figured I would learn the new way eventually when I had more free time.|When I started a new project, I was told I needed to use a specific documentation format I had never seen before. I spent my lunch break reading the user manual and looking at past examples from the team archives. By the end of the day, I was able to complete my first assignment using the new format without any major errors.|I had to learn how to use a new software tool for a class project last semester. I watched a few videos online and asked the teacher a lot of questions whenever I got stuck. It took me a bit longer than the others, but I eventually figured it out and finished the work.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate is proactive and takes initiative to close their own knowledge gaps. They show a high degree of adaptability. Mid: The candidate is willing to learn but relies heavily on others for help. They show a reactive rather than proactive learning style. Bad: The candidate is resistant to change and lacks the drive to learn. This mindset is a hindrance to growth and team progress. Structure check: Good: The response clearly identifies the challenge, the specific steps taken to learn, and the successful outcome. Mid: The response is a bit vague about the learning process. It mentions 'watching videos' but doesn't show much self-directed effort. Bad: The response is short and doesn't show a completed learning cycle. It focuses on the candidate's reluctance rather than the task. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific resources they used, like manuals and archives. This adds credibility to the story. Mid: The candidate gives a very general account of learning. There is no sense of the difficulty or the candidate's specific actions. Bad: The candidate provides no detail on how they learn. The answer is purely focused on their opinion of the new rule. Clarity check: Good: The candidate describes the situation and their actions in a very clear, professional manner. Mid: The candidate's writing is a bit informal. The story is easy to follow but lacks professional polish. Bad: The candidate's point is confusing. They don't clearly explain if they ever actually learned the new process. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can keep up with the fast pace of a changing project. They are a quick and independent learner. Mid: The candidate can learn new things but might slow the team down. They require significant support to get up to speed. Bad: The candidate’s refusal to adapt is a major red flag. They are unlikely to succeed in a role that requires following updated guidelines.|6|Can you give an example of a time you had to learn a new rule or process very quickly to finish a task?|PASS|100|[\"All expected IDs are present and unique.\", \"Excellent adherence to strict rubric structure including all mandatory internal labels.\", \"Questions perfectly align with the specified level and competency dimensions.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level depth.\"]|457767929f48120c005854de431402b58b8c935f|b251bd2963ae7dd754437702611574efe7edc143|Compliance Officer|105|8e5d697846491b3adedec5686ab9e9bc9c77ecc2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:30.463604Z
Compliance Officer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I would just explain it once very quickly and hope they are smart enough to get it. I don't have a lot of time to sit around and teach people basic things, so they would just have to learn by doing.|I would start by identifying the most important goal of the instructions so the person understands the 'why' behind the task. Then, I would break the process down into five or six simple steps, avoiding any technical jargon. I would ask them to repeat the steps back to me to ensure they have understood everything correctly before they start.|I would just give them a copy of the manual and tell them to read it carefully. If they have any questions, I would tell them they can come and find me. I would try to explain the hard parts if they get confused while they are working on it.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows empathy and a strong grasp of effective communication techniques. They understand the importance of verification. Mid: The candidate is willing to help but lacks a structured approach to teaching. They rely on the other person's initiative rather than their own clarity. Bad: The candidate is impatient and lacks basic communication skills. They do not value the success of their teammates. Structure check: Good: The response outlines a clear method: goal setting, breaking down steps, and verification. It is a logical and complete plan. Mid: The response is a bit disorganized. It suggests a 'wait and see' approach rather than a prepared explanation. Bad: The response is very brief and shows no consideration for the other person's needs. It is more of an excuse than a plan. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific techniques like 'avoiding jargon' and 'checking for understanding.' This shows they have thought about this before. Mid: The candidate provides a very simple answer. They don't mention any specific strategies for making complex things simple. Bad: The candidate provides no detail. Their answer suggests they don't see communication as part of their job. Clarity check: Good: The candidate’s own explanation is a great example of the clarity they are describing. It is easy to understand. Mid: The candidate is a bit vague about how they would actually explain the 'hard parts.' The answer lacks concrete examples. Bad: The candidate's response is dismissive and unclear. It reflects a poor attitude toward collaboration. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate would be an asset to any team that requires collaboration. They can help bridge the gap between different levels of expertise. Mid: The candidate is a functional communicator but might struggle to train others. They are best as an individual contributor for now. Bad: The candidate’s attitude would likely cause friction and errors within a team. They are not suited for collaborative environments.|7|Explain how you would describe a complex set of instructions to someone who has no prior knowledge of the topic?|PASS|100|[\"All expected IDs are present and unique.\", \"Excellent adherence to strict rubric structure including all mandatory internal labels.\", \"Questions perfectly align with the specified level and competency dimensions.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level depth.\"]|457767929f48120c005854de431402b58b8c935f|b251bd2963ae7dd754437702611574efe7edc143|Compliance Officer|106|8e5d697846491b3adedec5686ab9e9bc9c77ecc2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:30.463604Z
Compliance Officer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|If something doesn't look right, I just ignore it if it's only a small difference. Usually, these guidelines are just suggestions anyway, and as long as the project is moving forward, a little bit of bad data won't hurt anyone.|When I find a discrepancy, I first double-check my own understanding of the guidelines to make sure I haven't made an error. If the mismatch is real, I document exactly where the information fails to meet the standard. I then bring this evidence to my project lead so we can decide whether to correct the data or update the record.|I would probably just change the information so that it fits the rules. If the rules say it should be one way and it is another, I just fix it myself to save everyone time. I might mention it to my teammate later if it seems important.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a high level of integrity and follows a formal process for handling errors. They understand the danger of 'fixing' things without authorization. Mid: The candidate is well-intentioned but takes unauthorized shortcuts. Their approach could lead to loss of data audit trails. Bad: The candidate is negligent and does not take standards seriously. This behavior is a major risk to the project's quality. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear path: verify, document, and report. This is the correct professional sequence. Mid: The response jumps straight to 'fixing' without the necessary steps of verification or documentation. Bad: The response shows no structure or professional logic. It is purely based on the candidate's personal opinion of the rules. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains why they document the error and who they would report it to. This shows an understanding of team hierarchy. Mid: The candidate gives a very brief explanation of their actions. They don't seem to understand the potential consequences of their 'quick fixes.' Bad: The candidate provides no detail and shows a lack of concern for the topic. The answer is very shallow. Clarity check: Good: The candidate communicates their process clearly and uses professional terminology. The answer is very easy to follow. Mid: The candidate's explanation is a bit casual. It is clear what they would do, but it doesn't sound very professional. Bad: The candidate is vague and dismissive. Their communication style is not appropriate for a professional setting. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the exact mindset needed for maintaining high standards. They are disciplined and reliable. Mid: The candidate needs more training on the importance of data integrity and reporting procedures. They are a bit too independent. Bad: The candidate’s disregard for guidelines makes them a poor fit for any role that requires strict adherence to standards.|8|Describe the process you follow when you notice a piece of information does not match the required standards or guidelines?|PASS|100|[\"All expected IDs are present and unique.\", \"Excellent adherence to strict rubric structure including all mandatory internal labels.\", \"Questions perfectly align with the specified level and competency dimensions.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level depth.\"]|457767929f48120c005854de431402b58b8c935f|b251bd2963ae7dd754437702611574efe7edc143|Compliance Officer|107|8e5d697846491b3adedec5686ab9e9bc9c77ecc2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:30.463604Z
Compliance Officer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I usually just pick the things that make me look good and put those at the top. If something went wrong, I try to leave it out or describe it in a way that doesn't sound too bad so the stakeholder doesn't get worried.|I focus on three main areas: the current status of the project, any risks that might cause delays, and the specific actions we need the stakeholder to take. I leave out the minor daily tasks that don't affect the overall outcome to ensure the report stays concise and actionable for a busy reader.|I try to include everything that happened since the last report just to be safe. I don't want the stakeholder to think I'm hiding anything, so I just write down all the facts and let them decide what they think is important.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate understands the purpose of a summary report is to facilitate decision-making. They know how to filter information based on the audience's needs. Mid: The candidate lacks the ability to prioritize information. They provide a 'data dump' which is inefficient for the reader. Bad: The candidate is biased and lacks transparency. They are more concerned with their image than with providing an accurate status. Structure check: Good: The response provides a clear framework for selecting information. It is organized by category (status, risk, action). Mid: The response is a bit vague. It explains the philosophy of 'including everything' but doesn't have a clear structure for the report itself. Bad: The response is disorganized and shows a lack of professional ethics. It focuses on manipulation rather than reporting. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains why they leave out minor details. This shows they understand the value of a stakeholder's time. Mid: The candidate provides a simple explanation. They don't show much thought about the needs of the audience. Bad: The candidate provides almost no detail. Their answer is focused on a very narrow and incorrect goal. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's explanation is very clear and professional. Their logic is easy to grasp. Mid: The candidate is a bit repetitive. Their point is simple but they take a long time to say it. Bad: The candidate's response is confusing and reflects a poor understanding of the task. They are not communicating effectively. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate would be very effective at keeping stakeholders informed and projects on track. They show great potential for growth. Mid: The candidate needs coaching on how to synthesize information. They are currently providing too much noise and not enough signal. Bad: The candidate's lack of transparency would be a liability. They cannot be trusted to provide honest and accurate reports.|9|How do you decide which details are important enough to include when drafting a summary report for a stakeholder?|PASS|100|[\"All expected IDs are present and unique.\", \"Excellent adherence to strict rubric structure including all mandatory internal labels.\", \"Questions perfectly align with the specified level and competency dimensions.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level depth.\"]|457767929f48120c005854de431402b58b8c935f|b251bd2963ae7dd754437702611574efe7edc143|Compliance Officer|108|8e5d697846491b3adedec5686ab9e9bc9c77ecc2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:30.463604Z
Compliance Officer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would just do whatever the teammate says because they probably have more experience than I do. If they think it's okay to skip a step, then it's their responsibility if something goes wrong, not mine.|I would explain to my teammate that skipping the verification step could lead to much bigger problems and delays later if an error is discovered by a stakeholder. I would suggest we look for other ways to save time, like focusing only on the most critical parts of the project, but I would insist on completing the mandatory checks.|I would probably feel very pressured and might agree to skip it just this once if the deadline is really important. I would make sure to go back and check the work later when I have more time, even if the project is already submitted.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate has a strong professional backbone and understands the importance of following procedures even under pressure. They offer constructive alternatives. Mid: The candidate is easily influenced and lacks the courage to stand up for standards. Their plan to 'check later' is often unrealistic in a busy environment. Bad: The candidate abdicates responsibility and is willing to compromise quality to avoid conflict or pressure. This is a significant performance risk. Structure check: Good: The response starts with a clear refusal, followed by an explanation and a helpful alternative. It is a very professional response. Mid: The response is hesitant and shows a lack of a clear plan. It focuses on the candidate's internal feelings of pressure. Bad: The response is passive and lacks any professional reasoning. It suggests a total lack of ownership. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the long-term risks of skipping steps. They show they can think about the project's reputation and success. Mid: The candidate provides a very simple 'maybe' answer. They don't consider the ethical or practical implications of their choice. Bad: The candidate provides no detail. Their answer is based on shifting blame rather than doing the right thing. Clarity check: Good: The candidate communicates their position clearly and firmly. Their language is professional and respectful. Mid: The candidate is a bit wishy-washy. It's not entirely clear if they would actually say no or just feel bad about saying yes. Bad: The candidate is very blunt and unprofessional. Their attitude is not conducive to a high-quality work environment. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate is highly suited for a role where following rules is critical. They are a reliable guardian of project standards. Mid: The candidate would need a lot of supervision to ensure they don't cut corners when things get difficult. They are not yet fully reliable under pressure. Bad: The candidate's willingness to skip steps is a disqualifying trait. They would be a liability to the team's integrity.|10|How would you respond if a teammate asked you to skip a standard verification step to meet a project deadline?|PASS|100|[\"All expected IDs are present and unique.\", \"Excellent adherence to strict rubric structure including all mandatory internal labels.\", \"Questions perfectly align with the specified level and competency dimensions.\", \"Strong differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level depth.\"]|457767929f48120c005854de431402b58b8c935f|b251bd2963ae7dd754437702611574efe7edc143|Compliance Officer|109|8e5d697846491b3adedec5686ab9e9bc9c77ecc2|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:30.463604Z
Manufacturing Process Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I had a disagreement with a coworker who was doing everything the wrong way and causing us to fall behind. I just ignored their suggestions and did the work my way because I knew it was the only way to get a good grade. It is usually easier to just do it yourself than to argue with people who don't understand the goal.|During a senior design project, a teammate and I disagreed on which material to use for a prototype because of cost concerns. I suggested we create a small comparison chart of the pros and cons for each material and present it to the whole group for a vote. We ultimately chose a compromise material that met our budget while maintaining the quality we needed for the project to succeed.|I once worked with a peer who did not agree with my timeline for completing our shared tasks. I explained why I thought my timeline was better, but they didn't really listen so we just ended up working separately. We finished the work on time, but it was a bit awkward between us for the rest of the semester.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a professional and constructive approach to handling interpersonal conflict. They show an ability to listen and find collaborative solutions that benefit the project. Mid: The candidate acknowledges the conflict but fails to resolve it in a truly collaborative way. They show limited growth or reflection on how the interaction could have been improved. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of teamwork skills by avoiding the conflict or steamrolling others. They do not demonstrate the maturity required to work in a professional team environment. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear and logical narrative structure that is easy for the evaluator to follow. It provides specific details about the situation and a clear resolution. Mid: The response is somewhat organized but lacks a distinct beginning or a meaningful conclusion. It may provide a general summary rather than a specific instance. Bad: The response is disorganized and lacks any coherent structure. The evaluator is left confused about what actually happened or what the candidate did. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about the nature of the disagreement and their personal reasoning. They explain the logic behind their actions and the resulting impact. Mid: The candidate provides a surface-level description of the event without much detail. They skip over the specific actions they took to address the problem. Bad: The candidate gives a very brief and vague answer that lacks any substance. There is no evidence of critical thinking or self-awareness in the response. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses clear and professional language to describe the situation. Their message is delivered concisely and without unnecessary filler. Mid: The candidate uses some vague or confusing language that requires the evaluator to ask follow-up questions. The main point is present but not emphasized. Bad: The candidate is confusing or uses inconsistent details in their story. The response is difficult to interpret or lacks a clear point. Relevance to role: Good: The answer shows strong collaboration skills which are essential for any team-based project. It reflects a mindset focused on group success and professional communication. Mid: The answer shows basic social skills but lacks the proactive collaboration needed for the job. It is only partially relevant to professional working conditions. Bad: The answer indicates that the candidate may struggle with team dynamics or cooperation. It does not align with the expectations for a junior professional in a team setting.|1|Tell me about a time when you had a disagreement with a team member while working on a project and how you resolved it?|PASS|96|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric structure requirements including all nested Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example performance levels across all questions.\", \"Clear alignment with the specified role and junior level constraints.\", \"Comprehensive coverage of diverse behavioral and situational dimensions.\"]|c5c4610942b134f2b9bbcf9d16eddde8f3b0b227|4b16d2f5713edf98dedd40d7949821fb3efbcec5|Manufacturing Process Engineer|110|53cec52d4277d842d5854cba273cdc74b8308d2d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:41.158142Z
Manufacturing Process Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I made a mistake on a project once, but it wasn't really my fault because the instructions I was given were very confusing. I didn't say anything because I didn't want to get in trouble, and luckily nobody noticed it so it didn't end up being a problem. I think mistakes happen to everyone so it is best to just move on and forget about them.|During my internship, I accidentally entered the wrong specifications into a tracking sheet which could have delayed a shipment. As soon as I realized the error, I notified my supervisor and stayed late to manually audit the entries to ensure everything else was correct. I then created a simple checklist for myself to follow in the future to prevent similar data entry mistakes from happening again.|I once missed a deadline for a small report because I was focused on a larger project and lost track of time. I told my professor about it and they gave me an extension so I could finish it over the weekend. I got it done eventually, but I felt bad about missing the initial date and tried to be more careful after that.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate takes full ownership of their mistake without making excuses. They demonstrate a proactive approach to fixing the error and a commitment to long-term improvement. Mid: The candidate admits the mistake but describes a reactive solution rather than a proactive one. They show some regret but do not explain a clear plan to prevent it in the future. Bad: The candidate avoids responsibility or blames others for their errors. They fail to show any learning or growth from the experience. Structure check: Good: The response is structured around a specific event with a clear problem, action, and result. The steps taken to fix the mistake are clearly outlined. Mid: The response is a bit vague and doesn't clearly separate the mistake from the resolution. It lacks a strong concluding point about what was learned. Bad: The response is rambling and does not clearly identify what the mistake was or how it was handled. It lacks a logical flow. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the specific consequences of their mistake and the logic behind their fix. They provide concrete examples of the preventative measures they implemented. Mid: The candidate provides a general overview of the mistake without much detail on the fix. The explanation of their reasoning is thin and lacks detail. Bad: The candidate provides almost no detail about the situation. The answer feels like a generic response rather than a real-life example. Clarity check: Good: The candidate communicates the story in a professional and straightforward manner. The language used is appropriate and easy to understand. Mid: The candidate is mostly clear but includes some irrelevant details that distract from the main story. Some parts of the explanation are a bit muddled. Bad: The candidate is incoherent or provides a confusing timeline of events. The response is difficult to follow and lacks clarity. Relevance to role: Good: The answer shows a high level of accountability and a focus on quality. These traits are critical for a junior professional responsible for accurate task execution. Mid: The answer shows a basic level of responsibility but lacks the proactive mindset needed for the role. It is an acceptable but not strong response. Bad: The answer suggests a lack of professional integrity or a tendency to hide errors. This is a significant red flag for any role requiring reliability.|2|Describe a time when you made a mistake at work or school and explain the steps you took to correct it?|PASS|96|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric structure requirements including all nested Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example performance levels across all questions.\", \"Clear alignment with the specified role and junior level constraints.\", \"Comprehensive coverage of diverse behavioral and situational dimensions.\"]|c5c4610942b134f2b9bbcf9d16eddde8f3b0b227|4b16d2f5713edf98dedd40d7949821fb3efbcec5|Manufacturing Process Engineer|111|53cec52d4277d842d5854cba273cdc74b8308d2d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:41.158142Z
Manufacturing Process Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I just write down the numbers as they appear on the equipment screen and assume that the machine is working correctly. I don't usually have time to check them twice because I have to move on to the next task quickly. As long as the data is submitted on time, I think it is fine to trust the initial results.|I always verify my data by performing a second set of measurements and comparing them to my initial results to check for any discrepancies. I also maintain a detailed log that includes the date, time, and any environmental conditions that might have influenced the data. Finally, I run a quick sanity check against historical data to ensure the new numbers fall within an expected range.|I try to be very careful when I am recording my findings so that I do not make any mistakes in the spreadsheet. I usually read back through the numbers once before I send them to my manager. If something looks really weird, I might try to measure it one more time just to be sure.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate describes a systematic approach to data verification and integrity. They show an understanding of why data quality matters and how to achieve it. Mid: The candidate has a basic sense of checking their work but lacks a rigorous or repeatable process. They rely more on effort than on a structured method. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of concern for data accuracy. They do not demonstrate any steps to validate their work before submission. Structure check: Good: The answer provides a logical list of steps taken to ensure accuracy. It is presented in a clear, sequential order that is easy to follow. Mid: The response mentions a few things the candidate does but they are not organized into a clear process. The answer feels a bit disorganized. Bad: The response is a single statement that does not provide any process or structure. It is far too brief to be useful. Depth check: Good: The candidate specifies multiple methods of validation, such as secondary measurements and historical comparisons. They explain why these steps are necessary for reliability. Mid: The candidate gives a very simple explanation without much detail on why their method works. They only mention one or two basic actions. Bad: The candidate provides no depth or detail. They do not seem to understand the technical requirements of data collection. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses precise language and explains technical steps clearly. There is no ambiguity in the process they describe. Mid: The candidate uses some vague terms like 'being careful' without explaining what that actually means. The response is understandable but not professional. Bad: The candidate is unclear and fails to describe a coherent action. The response does not answer the core of the question. Relevance to role: Good: The answer shows the candidate understands the high stakes of data accuracy in the project. It reflects the attention to detail required for the team. Mid: The answer shows a minimum level of competence but lacks the precision needed for more complex tasks. It is only partially aligned with professional standards. Bad: The answer suggests the candidate might provide unreliable information to the team. This would be a major issue in any task-oriented environment.|3|How do you ensure that the data you collect during a project or production run is accurate and reliable before you present it?|PASS|96|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric structure requirements including all nested Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example performance levels across all questions.\", \"Clear alignment with the specified role and junior level constraints.\", \"Comprehensive coverage of diverse behavioral and situational dimensions.\"]|c5c4610942b134f2b9bbcf9d16eddde8f3b0b227|4b16d2f5713edf98dedd40d7949821fb3efbcec5|Manufacturing Process Engineer|112|53cec52d4277d842d5854cba273cdc74b8308d2d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:41.158142Z
Manufacturing Process Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I just keep trying to run the equipment because sometimes these issues just go away on their own if you wait long enough. If it stays broken, I just leave a note for the next person on the shift to look at it. I don't really know how to fix things myself so I just wait for a technician to show up.|When I find a problem, I first stop the task to prevent further issues and then document exactly what was happening when the failure occurred. I check the technical manual for common troubleshooting steps and look for any obvious physical causes like a loose connection. If I cannot resolve it myself, I prepare a clear summary of what I have already tried before I escalate the issue to a senior team member.|I usually start by restarting the equipment or the software to see if that fixes the glitch. If it is still broken, I look around to see if anyone else is having the same problem and ask them how they fixed it. If nobody knows, I eventually go and find my supervisor to ask for help.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a logical and safe approach to troubleshooting. They show initiative in trying to solve the problem while knowing when it is appropriate to ask for help. Mid: The candidate has a basic troubleshooting instinct but lacks a structured or documented approach. They rely heavily on trial and error or on other people. Bad: The candidate is passive and does not take any responsibility for solving the problem. They show a lack of technical curiosity and a disregard for safety or efficiency. Structure check: Good: The response is organized as a step-by-step procedure. It flows logically from identification to documentation to resolution or escalation. Mid: The response mentions several actions but they are not in a clear order. It feels more like a list of random ideas than a process. Bad: The response is extremely brief and provides no logical sequence of events. It does not answer the question about a 'process'. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific tools or resources they would use, such as manuals or error logs. They explain the reasoning behind each step they take. Mid: The candidate provides very little detail about what they actually do. They mention 'restarting' but don't explain what else they would look for. Bad: The candidate provides no detail at all. They do not demonstrate any technical understanding of how to diagnose an issue. Clarity check: Good: The candidate describes the process in clear, easy-to-understand language. They avoid unnecessary jargon while remaining professional. Mid: The candidate is mostly clear but uses some informal language. The steps are understandable but could be more precisely defined. Bad: The candidate's explanation is confusing and lacks a clear direction. It is hard to tell what their first priority would be. Relevance to role: Good: The answer shows the candidate has the technical mindset needed to handle daily challenges on the project. It reflects a proactive and analytical personality. Mid: The answer shows the candidate can follow basic instructions but may struggle with independent problem-solving. They are an average candidate for this level. Bad: The answer indicates that the candidate might be a liability or cause delays in the workflow. It is not a suitable response for the job.|4|Explain the step-by-step process you follow when you encounter a technical issue with equipment or a workflow that is not performing as expected?|PASS|96|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric structure requirements including all nested Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example performance levels across all questions.\", \"Clear alignment with the specified role and junior level constraints.\", \"Comprehensive coverage of diverse behavioral and situational dimensions.\"]|c5c4610942b134f2b9bbcf9d16eddde8f3b0b227|4b16d2f5713edf98dedd40d7949821fb3efbcec5|Manufacturing Process Engineer|113|53cec52d4277d842d5854cba273cdc74b8308d2d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:41.158142Z
Manufacturing Process Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would just stop what I am doing and start the new task immediately because the person asking for it sounds like they are in a hurry. I think it is important to keep everyone happy even if it means missing my original deadline. My boss will understand that I was just trying to be helpful to the other team.|I would first thank the stakeholder for reaching out and then ask for more details about the priority and deadline of the new request. I would then check my current project timeline to see if there is any flexibility to accommodate both tasks. If I could not do both, I would present the conflict to my manager with a proposed plan for which task to prioritize and ask for their final guidance.|I would try to work faster on my current project so that I could start the new task as soon as possible. I would probably stay late to get both done because I don't want to tell anyone no. If it got too stressful, I would eventually have to tell the stakeholder that their task might be a little bit late.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates strong prioritization and communication skills. They show an understanding of how to manage expectations and involve management when conflicts arise. Mid: The candidate tries to do everything themselves without communicating the conflict clearly. This approach shows a risk of burnout or poor quality work due to rushing. Bad: The candidate is reactive and fails to manage their time or priorities. They do not understand the impact of missing deadlines on the overall project. Structure check: Good: The answer follows a clear sequence of evaluate, communicate, and resolve. It shows a professional and structured way of thinking about workload. Mid: The response is a bit scattered and suggests a lack of a formal plan. The candidate seems to react to the situation rather than manage it. Bad: The response is a single unhelpful action. It does completedly ignore the importance of the initial project deadline. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the 'why' behind their actions, such as the need for manager alignment and task clarification. They provide a realistic solution for a junior professional. Mid: The candidate provides a simple 'work harder' answer without much depth. They don't consider the long-term consequences of their choice. Bad: The candidate provides no depth or reasoning. They simply state they would switch tasks without any further thought. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses professional language to explain a potentially stressful situation. The logic is sound and the delivery is confident. Mid: The candidate is clear but sounds a bit overwhelmed by the scenario. Their solution is understandable but lacks professional polish. Bad: The candidate's response is confusing and suggests they would handle the situation poorly. The communication is not effective. Relevance to role: Good: The answer reflects the reality of working in a busy environment with competing demands. It shows the candidate can handle the pressure of the job. Mid: The answer shows a willingness to work hard but a lack of organizational maturity. It is an acceptable response for a very junior candidate. Bad: The answer shows poor judgment and a lack of understanding of professional accountability. It does not meet the requirements for the role.|5|What would you do if a stakeholder requested an urgent task while you were already working toward a critical deadline for another project?|PASS|96|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric structure requirements including all nested Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example performance levels across all questions.\", \"Clear alignment with the specified role and junior level constraints.\", \"Comprehensive coverage of diverse behavioral and situational dimensions.\"]|c5c4610942b134f2b9bbcf9d16eddde8f3b0b227|4b16d2f5713edf98dedd40d7949821fb3efbcec5|Manufacturing Process Engineer|114|53cec52d4277d842d5854cba273cdc74b8308d2d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:41.158142Z
Manufacturing Process Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I had to explain a technical process to a teammate who was new to the project, but I just gave them the manual because it was too hard to explain it in simple terms. I told them to read the whole thing and come back to me if they had any questions. It is usually better to just let people read the documentation themselves anyway.|While working on a volunteer project, I had to explain how our database worked to a non-technical staff member. I avoided using technical terms and instead used the analogy of a physical filing cabinet to describe how information was stored and retrieved. This helped them understand how to enter their data correctly and reduced the number of errors we saw in the system.|I once had to explain my school research to my family members during a holiday dinner. I tried to speak slowly and I showed them some pictures on my phone so they could see what I was talking about. They seemed to understand the basics, but I think some of the more difficult parts were still a bit confusing for them.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows empathy for their audience and can adapt their communication style to ensure understanding. They use creative methods like analogies to bridge knowledge gaps. Mid: The candidate makes an effort to simplify their language but lacks a strategic approach to communication. They show some success but the result is not fully impactful. Bad: The candidate is dismissive of the need to explain things clearly. They rely on jargon or documentation instead of trying to help the other person learn. Structure check: Good: The response follows the STAR method and provides a clear example of a successful communication event. The outcome is well-defined and positive. Mid: The response is somewhat chronological but lacks a strong focus on the candidate's specific actions. It is a bit generic in its description. Bad: The response is very short and does not describe a real situation. It lacks any formal structure. Depth check: Good: The candidate describes the specific analogy they used and why they chose it. They explain the specific improvement in the system as a result of their communication. Mid: The candidate provides some detail about the setting but not much about the actual method they used to explain the idea. The response is a bit superficial. Bad: The candidate provides no detail and avoids answering the core of the question. They do not demonstrate any communication skills. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's own explanation is very clear and easy to follow, mirroring the skill they are describing. The narrative is well-paced. Mid: The candidate is understandable but could be more concise. Some parts of the story feel unnecessary or slightly confusing. Bad: The candidate's explanation is ironically confusing and hard to follow. They fail to demonstrate the clarity they are being asked about. Relevance to role: Good: The answer shows that the candidate can interact effectively with different types of stakeholders on the project. This is a key skill for a professional environment. Mid: The answer shows basic communication ability but lacks the professional focus needed for the team. It is an average response for this level. Bad: The answer suggests that the candidate might be difficult to work with or unable to support others. It is not aligned with the collaborative needs of the job.|6|Tell me about a time you had to explain a complex idea to someone who did not have the same background as you?|PASS|96|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric structure requirements including all nested Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example performance levels across all questions.\", \"Clear alignment with the specified role and junior level constraints.\", \"Comprehensive coverage of diverse behavioral and situational dimensions.\"]|c5c4610942b134f2b9bbcf9d16eddde8f3b0b227|4b16d2f5713edf98dedd40d7949821fb3efbcec5|Manufacturing Process Engineer|115|53cec52d4277d842d5854cba273cdc74b8308d2d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:41.158142Z
Manufacturing Process Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I haven't really had the chance to do that because I usually just wait for my boss to tell me what needs to be done. I think it is safer to just stick to my assigned tasks so that I don't accidentally do something wrong or overstep my boundaries. I like to follow the rules and stay in my lane at work.|At my last job, I noticed that we were wasting a lot of time searching for common supplies because the storage area was unorganized. On a slow afternoon, I designed a simple labeling system and reorganized the shelves by category to make everything easier to find. My supervisor was very happy with the result, and it saved the whole team several minutes of searching every day.|I once saw that a file we used for tracking our project hours was getting very messy and hard to read. I spent some time fixing the formatting and adding some color coding to make it look a lot nicer for everyone. A few people thanked me for making it easier to use, which made me feel like I did something helpful.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a proactive mindset and a desire to contribute beyond their basic job description. They identify a real problem and take sensible steps to fix it. Mid: The candidate shows some initiative but on a very small scale. Their example is positive but does not show a high level of problem-solving or impact. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of initiative and a passive attitude toward their work. They seem to prefer being told what to do at all times. Structure check: Good: The response clearly identifies the problem, the specific action taken, and the measurable outcome. It is a complete story. Mid: The response describes a situation but the actions are a bit vague. The outcome is mentioned but not explained in terms of its value to the team. Bad: The response is defensive and does not provide an example of the requested behavior. It is essentially a non-answer. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the reasoning behind their choice to act and the specific benefit to the team's efficiency. They show they can think about the bigger picture. Mid: The candidate provides some detail about the task but doesn't explain why it was important or how they decided to handle it. The reasoning is weak. Bad: The candidate provides no depth and misses the point of the question entirely. They do not demonstrate any self-driven behavior. Clarity check: Good: The candidate communicates their story clearly and professionally. The language is direct and the point of the story is obvious from the start. Mid: The candidate is clear but the story is a bit simple. The message is received but it doesn't leave a strong impression. Bad: The candidate is muddled and fails to articulate any clear action. The response is not effective for an interview. Relevance to role: Good: The answer shows the candidate will be a valuable and proactive member of the team. This trait is highly desirable in a junior professional. Mid: The answer shows the candidate is a reliable worker who can do basic tasks. It is a safe but uninspiring response for the role. Bad: The answer suggests the candidate might be too passive to thrive in a dynamic environment. It is not a strong match for the job.|7|Describe a time you took initiative to improve a task or solve a problem without being asked to do so by a supervisor?|PASS|96|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric structure requirements including all nested Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example performance levels across all questions.\", \"Clear alignment with the specified role and junior level constraints.\", \"Comprehensive coverage of diverse behavioral and situational dimensions.\"]|c5c4610942b134f2b9bbcf9d16eddde8f3b0b227|4b16d2f5713edf98dedd40d7949821fb3efbcec5|Manufacturing Process Engineer|116|53cec52d4277d842d5854cba273cdc74b8308d2d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:41.158142Z
Manufacturing Process Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I don't think documentation is very helpful because processes change so fast that the documents become outdated immediately. I prefer to just show people how to do things in person because it is much faster than writing everything down. If someone forgets how to do a step, they can just come and ask me again.|I start by performing the task myself and taking detailed notes on every single step, including screenshots or photos where helpful. Then, I write a draft using clear, numbered steps and ask a teammate who is unfamiliar with the task to try following my instructions while I watch. Based on where they get confused, I refine the documentation until it is completely clear and easy to follow.|I would write down the main steps of the process in a document and share it with my manager to see if they like it. I would try to use bullet points so that it isn't just a big wall of text. I think as long as the main parts are there, most people should be able to figure the rest out on their own.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate understands the importance of clear, user-focused documentation. They demonstrate a verification process (testing with others) that ensures the quality of their work. Mid: The candidate has a basic idea of how to document a task but lacks a thorough process for ensuring clarity. They assume that others will fill in the gaps themselves. Bad: The candidate dismisses the value of documentation entirely. This shows a lack of understanding of professional standards and team scalability. Structure check: Good: The response is organized logically as a process. It moves from data gathering to drafting to testing and finalization. Mid: The response is a bit fragmented and doesn't show a complete workflow. It feels like a list of separate ideas rather than a single approach. Bad: The response is a single opinion rather than a process. It fails to answer the question as asked. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific techniques like using visuals and user testing. They explain why these steps are necessary for high-quality documentation. Mid: The candidate gives very little detail about how they would actually write the document. They focus more on the format than the content or the clarity. Bad: The candidate provides no depth and shows no interest in the subject. They do not understand the technical requirements of the task. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's explanation is easy to follow and uses professional language. The steps are clearly defined and easy to visualize. Mid: The candidate is understandable but uses vague terms like 'main parts' or 'figure it out'. The response is a bit unprofessional in its delivery. Bad: The candidate is confusing and their argument against documentation is weak. The response is not well-articulated. Relevance to role: Good: The answer shows the candidate can contribute to the long-term knowledge base of the team. This is an important skill for maintaining project standards. Mid: The answer shows the candidate can perform basic administrative tasks but lacks a high-quality mindset. It is an average response. Bad: The answer suggests the candidate might be a bottleneck for the team because they refuse to share knowledge formally. It is not a good fit for the role.|8|Can you walk me through your approach to documenting a new workflow or procedure so that others can follow it without your help?|PASS|96|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric structure requirements including all nested Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example performance levels across all questions.\", \"Clear alignment with the specified role and junior level constraints.\", \"Comprehensive coverage of diverse behavioral and situational dimensions.\"]|c5c4610942b134f2b9bbcf9d16eddde8f3b0b227|4b16d2f5713edf98dedd40d7949821fb3efbcec5|Manufacturing Process Engineer|117|53cec52d4277d842d5854cba273cdc74b8308d2d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:41.158142Z
Manufacturing Process Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I don't really have a specific list of checks because I usually know if I did a good job while I am working. I think that if you are careful during the project, you don't really need to spend a lot of time checking it again at the end. I just submit it and wait for feedback if something is wrong.|I always begin by reviewing the original project requirements and creating a final checklist to compare against my results. I also perform a manual peer-review where I ask a colleague to look for any errors I might have missed. Finally, I use a standardized validation tool to check for any technical non-compliance before I officially submit the work for approval.|I usually just go back over my work one last time before I hand it in to make sure everything looks right. I check for common mistakes like spelling or missing data points in the final report. If I am not sure about something, I might look back at my notes from the beginning of the project.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a rigorous and multi-layered approach to quality control. They show they are detail-oriented and take pride in the accuracy of their final output. Mid: The candidate has a basic quality check routine but it is not systematic or thorough. They rely on their own intuition rather than objective standards. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of concern for quality and validation. They do not have a process for catching errors before they reach the final stage. Structure check: Good: The response is well-structured and covers different types of checks (self-review, peer-review, and tool-based). It follows a logical order. Mid: The response is a bit repetitive and doesn't clearly differentiate between different types of quality checks. It feels like a single action described in multiple ways. Bad: The response is brief and provides no structure at all. It does not answer the question about 'specific checks'. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions using checklists and validation tools, which shows a higher level of professional maturity. They explain how these steps ensure compliance. Mid: The candidate provides very little detail about what they are actually looking for during their review. The explanation of their reasoning is surface-level. Bad: The candidate provides no detail and shows no understanding of the technical requirements of quality assurance. The answer is insufficient. Clarity check: Good: The candidate communicates their process in a clear and professional manner. The language is precise and the steps are well-defined. Mid: The candidate is mostly clear but uses some vague language like 'looks right'. The response is understandable but lacks professional precision. Bad: The candidate's explanation is muddled and fails to articulate a clear process. The response is not effective. Relevance to role: Good: The answer shows the candidate is a reliable and high-quality worker who will minimize errors. This is a vital trait for the success of the team and the project. Mid: The answer shows the candidate can produce acceptable work but may require extra supervision to ensure quality. It is a mediocre response. Bad: The answer suggests the candidate might submit low-quality work, which could cause significant problems for the team. It is a poor match for the role.|9|What specific checks or validation steps do you perform to ensure that your final output meets all the required quality standards and specifications?|PASS|96|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric structure requirements including all nested Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example performance levels across all questions.\", \"Clear alignment with the specified role and junior level constraints.\", \"Comprehensive coverage of diverse behavioral and situational dimensions.\"]|c5c4610942b134f2b9bbcf9d16eddde8f3b0b227|4b16d2f5713edf98dedd40d7949821fb3efbcec5|Manufacturing Process Engineer|118|53cec52d4277d842d5854cba273cdc74b8308d2d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:41.158142Z
Manufacturing Process Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would just wait for more information to be given to me because I don't want to start working on something if I am not 100% sure what to do. If nobody says anything, I will just assume the task isn't that important and I will keep working on my other projects instead. I think it is the supervisor's job to be clear.|I would first take a few minutes to identify the specific parts of the task that are unclear to me. Then, I would schedule a brief meeting with the person who assigned the task to ask clarifying questions and propose a reasonable deadline based on my current workload. This ensures that I am working on the right things and that my supervisor's expectations are met.|I would probably start by doing what I think the task is and then show it to my boss after a few days to see if I am on the right track. I would also ask them when they need it done by so that I can make sure I don't miss any other important deadlines I might have.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a proactive and professional approach to managing ambiguity. They show that they can communicate effectively to resolve uncertainty without wasting time. Mid: The candidate tries to move forward but in a way that might lead to wasted effort. They are willing to ask for a deadline but their overall approach is reactive. Bad: The candidate is passive and uses the lack of clarity as an excuse to do nothing. They show a lack of initiative and a poor understanding of professional responsibility. Structure check: Good: The response is structured as a clear plan of action: analyze, communicate, and confirm. It shows a logical and organized mindset. Mid: The response is a bit informal and doesn't show a clear sequence of steps. The candidate seems to be guessing at how they would handle the situation. Bad: The response is a single statement that shows a lack of effort. It does not provide any structure or plan. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the logic of identifying gaps before asking questions, which shows respect for the supervisor's time. They provide a specific way to reach a resolution. Mid: The candidate provides some detail about asking for a deadline but doesn't explain how they would clarify the task itself. The answer is a bit incomplete. Bad: The candidate provides no depth and fails to address the core challenges of the scenario. They do not demonstrate any problem-solving skills. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses professional language and describes their plan clearly. The response is easy to follow and the logic is sound. Mid: The candidate is clear but their tone is a bit hesitant. The response is understandable but lacks the confidence of a strong professional. Bad: The candidate's response is confusing and suggests they would handle the situation poorly. The communication is not effective. Relevance to role: Good: The answer shows the candidate can handle the messy reality of a fast-paced work environment. This is an essential skill for a junior professional on a project team. Mid: The answer shows the candidate can eventually get the job done but may need more direction than is ideal. It is an acceptable response for this level. Bad: The answer suggests the candidate would struggle in any environment that isn't perfectly defined. This would make them a difficult hire for most teams.|10|How would you handle a situation where you were assigned a task with very vague instructions and no clear deadline provided?|PASS|96|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric structure requirements including all nested Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example performance levels across all questions.\", \"Clear alignment with the specified role and junior level constraints.\", \"Comprehensive coverage of diverse behavioral and situational dimensions.\"]|c5c4610942b134f2b9bbcf9d16eddde8f3b0b227|4b16d2f5713edf98dedd40d7949821fb3efbcec5|Manufacturing Process Engineer|119|53cec52d4277d842d5854cba273cdc74b8308d2d|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:41.158142Z
Bioprocess Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I had a teammate who was very difficult to work with and wouldn't listen to any of my suggestions. I ended up doing most of the work myself because it was easier than arguing with them all the time. I didn't really talk to them for the rest of the project and just turned in the work.|In a university lab project, my partner and I disagreed on which data analysis method to use for our final report. I suggested we both trial our preferred methods on a small subset of the data to see which yielded clearer results. After comparing the outcomes, we agreed that her method was more efficient, so we moved forward with that approach and finished the project early.|I once worked with a teammate who didn't want to follow the project schedule I created. We had a brief argument about the timeline, but eventually, we just decided to split the work and do our own parts separately. It wasn't the best way to work, but we managed to get the project submitted on time.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate identifies a specific conflict and focuses on a collaborative resolution. They demonstrate emotional intelligence and a willingness to find a middle ground. Mid: The candidate mentions a disagreement but the resolution is passive or avoids the core issue. The focus is more on getting the task done than improving the working relationship. Bad: The candidate avoids the question or describes a situation where they took over the work. They show no self-reflection or attempt at conflict resolution. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear Situation-Action-Result format with logical flow. It provides enough context for the listener to understand the stakes involved. Mid: The response is somewhat organized but skips over the specific actions taken to resolve the issue. It focuses too much on the problem and not enough on the resolution. Bad: The response is disorganized or lacks a clear beginning, middle, and end. It is difficult to follow the timeline of events. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the reasoning behind their actions and reflects on the outcome. They provide specific details about the conversation and the logic used. Mid: The response provides only surface-level details about the interaction. It lacks insight into the candidate's thought process or feelings. Bad: The response is extremely brief and provides no detail about the nature of the disagreement. It fails to meet the minimum requirements for a behavioral answer. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses clear language and avoids blaming others for the situation. The narrative is easy to follow and professional. Mid: The candidate uses vague terms like 'we just figured it out' without explaining how. The tone may be slightly defensive or unclear. Bad: The candidate uses aggressive language or speaks poorly of their former teammates. The answer is confusing and lacks professional polish. Relevance to role: Good: The response shows the candidate can handle the interpersonal pressures of a collaborative team environment. It reflects the maturity needed for a junior professional role. Mid: The response shows an acceptable level of cooperation but lacks proactive communication skills. It suggests the candidate might struggle with more complex team dynamics. Bad: The response suggests the candidate is unable to work effectively with others. This is a significant red flag for a role requiring teamwork.|1|Tell me about a time you had a disagreement with a teammate and how you worked together to resolve it?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric section labeling requirements across all questions.\", \"Strong alignment with junior-level scope and professional constraints.\", \"Excellent differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Clear dimension uniqueness and high-quality interrogative sentence structure.\"]|447749b1dd9026bac937afc68e0b06b0557906ec|0fff2c0cbe74f0c5307f63d0b1e92cd4e7a89869|Bioprocess Engineer|120|e98856f6babb1af8ea55ea84cc962d250a4ffbc6|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:42.540161Z
Bioprocess Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I don't really make many mistakes because I am very careful with my work. One time a teammate thought I did something wrong, but it turned out the instructions were just confusing. I think if everyone just followed the rules, mistakes wouldn't happen as much.|During my internship, I once mislabeled a set of samples which could have led to incorrect test results. As soon as I realized the error, I notified my supervisor and helped re-trace the samples using the logbook entries from that morning. We corrected the labels before the testing began, and I created a new double-check checklist to prevent this from happening again.|I once made an error while entering data into a spreadsheet for a class project. I noticed it a few days later and quickly changed the numbers before the professor graded it. It didn't really cause any problems because I caught it myself, but I try to be more careful now when I am typing.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate takes full ownership of a specific error and explains the corrective actions. They show they prioritize accuracy and transparency over their own ego. Mid: The candidate describes a minor error but downplays the impact or the necessity of reporting it. The response lacks a sense of accountability for the process. Bad: The candidate denies making mistakes or blames external factors like instructions. They show a lack of self-awareness and professional responsibility. Structure check: Good: The answer clearly defines the error, the immediate response, and the long-term lesson learned. The narrative flows logically from the problem to the solution. Mid: The answer is a bit disjointed and doesn't clearly explain the resolution. It feels like a brief anecdote rather than a structured behavioral response. Bad: The answer is defensive and lacks any logical structure. It does not address the 'how you handled it' part of the question. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about the mistake and the preventive measures implemented. They show a deep understanding of why the error occurred and how to stop it. Mid: The response is generic and lacks specific details about the mistake. It provides only a surface-level explanation of the lesson learned. Bad: The response is shallow and provides no evidence of learning or growth. It fails to demonstrate any critical thinking about the incident. Clarity check: Good: The language is professional and the candidate speaks honestly about their actions. The explanation is easy to follow and concise. Mid: The candidate uses vague descriptions of the mistake and the fix. It is hard to tell exactly what went wrong or how it was corrected. Bad: The candidate is evasive or uses confusing language to hide the details of the error. The response is unprofessional and unclear. Relevance to role: Good: The response demonstrates the integrity and attention to detail required for the job. It shows the candidate can be trusted with responsibilities. Mid: The response shows an acceptable level of honesty but lacks the proactive mindset needed for quality control. It suggests a reactive approach to problems. Bad: The response indicates the candidate might hide mistakes or fail to learn from them. This is a high-risk behavior for the team.|2|Describe a time you made a mistake at work or in a project and how you handled the situation?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric section labeling requirements across all questions.\", \"Strong alignment with junior-level scope and professional constraints.\", \"Excellent differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Clear dimension uniqueness and high-quality interrogative sentence structure.\"]|447749b1dd9026bac937afc68e0b06b0557906ec|0fff2c0cbe74f0c5307f63d0b1e92cd4e7a89869|Bioprocess Engineer|121|e98856f6babb1af8ea55ea84cc962d250a4ffbc6|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:42.540161Z
Bioprocess Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I just start the task and get things as I need them because I know the process pretty well by now. If something is missing, I just go grab it from the shelf or ask a teammate where it is kept. I don't really see the point in checking everything twice if it was fine yesterday.|I start by reviewing the standard operating procedure and gathering all the necessary tools and reagents listed. I then check the expiration dates and calibration stickers on all equipment to ensure everything is within its valid range. Finally, I clear my workspace of unnecessary items and lay out my materials in the order they will be used to ensure a smooth workflow.|I usually just look at the list of what I need and go find the items in the storage area. I make sure I have enough of everything before I start so I don't have to stop in the middle of the task. I try to keep my desk clean so I don't get confused while I am working.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a systematic approach to preparation and verification. They emphasize safety, compliance, and efficiency in their workflow. Mid: The candidate shows a basic understanding of preparation but lacks a formal verification step. Their approach is more intuitive than procedural. Bad: The candidate is disorganized and relies on luck or memory rather than a structured process. They show a disregard for standard procedures and quality checks. Structure check: Good: The response provides a clear step-by-step walkthrough of the preparation phase. Each action is logically connected to the goal of readiness. Mid: The response is a bit scattered and doesn't follow a chronological order. It mentions some important steps but misses others. Bad: The response is a single sentence that doesn't explain the 'how' of the process. It lacks any detail or sequence. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific checks like calibration dates and expiration, showing attention to detail. They explain the reasoning for their workspace layout. Mid: The candidate provides generic information about gathering supplies. They don't mention any specific quality or safety checks. Bad: The response is very superficial and suggests the candidate does not value thorough preparation. It fails to address the 'verifying' part of the question. Clarity check: Good: The instructions are clear enough that another person could follow the logic. The candidate uses precise terms for tools and actions. Mid: The candidate uses vague terms like 'stuff' or 'things' instead of specific materials. The explanation is somewhat muddled. Bad: The response is confusing and suggests a chaotic work style. It is not professional in tone or content. Relevance to role: Good: The response reflects the disciplined mindset required for technical execution. It shows the candidate understands the importance of setup for quality results. Mid: The response shows an entry-level ability to organize tasks but needs more focus on compliance. It suggests they might require significant supervision. Bad: The response shows a lack of fundamental organizational skills. This could lead to safety issues or failed projects in the job.|3|How do you go about preparing and verifying that your workstation and materials are ready before beginning a standard procedure?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric section labeling requirements across all questions.\", \"Strong alignment with junior-level scope and professional constraints.\", \"Excellent differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Clear dimension uniqueness and high-quality interrogative sentence structure.\"]|447749b1dd9026bac937afc68e0b06b0557906ec|0fff2c0cbe74f0c5307f63d0b1e92cd4e7a89869|Bioprocess Engineer|122|e98856f6babb1af8ea55ea84cc962d250a4ffbc6|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:42.540161Z
Bioprocess Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I just remember the main results and put them into the final report after the project is done. Most of the data doesn't change much, so I don't think it is necessary to write every single thing down every time. I just focus on the final numbers that the manager needs.|I record all data points in real-time directly into the logbook or digital system to avoid relying on memory. I double-check every entry against the equipment display and initial the log to confirm the verification was performed. If I see an unusual reading, I immediately flag it and note the surrounding conditions so we can investigate it later.|I write down the numbers on a notepad while I am working and then transfer them to the computer at the end of the day. I try to make sure I don't make any typos when I am entering the data into the system. It is usually pretty accurate because I do it carefully.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate understands the importance of real-time documentation and verification. They show a commitment to data integrity and traceability. Mid: The candidate documents data but uses a multi-step process that introduces the risk of errors. They rely on memory or temporary notes which is not ideal. Bad: The candidate treats documentation as an afterthought and does not value raw data. They show a lack of understanding regarding scientific or professional standards. Structure check: Good: The response details a clear sequence of recording, checking, and flagging anomalies. It flows from the start of the data collection to the final verification. Mid: The response is somewhat fragmented and doesn't clearly explain the verification step. It focuses more on the recording than the accuracy check. Bad: The response is vague and does not describe a coherent process. It lacks any formal structure for data management. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains 'why' they initial logs and 'how' they handle outliers. This shows a deeper understanding of quality assurance principles. Mid: The response is very basic and only mentions the act of writing things down. It provides no insight into how they ensure repeatability. Bad: The response is shallow and dismissive of the need for detailed documentation. It fails to address the core requirements of the question. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses professional terminology and describes a logical, easy-to-follow system. The tone is serious and focused. Mid: The candidate's explanation is a bit casual and doesn't sound like a standardized process. It is clear but lacks professional rigor. Bad: The candidate is unclear about how they manage data. The response is messy and suggests a lack of care. Relevance to role: Good: The response aligns with the high standards for data accuracy required in the project. It shows the candidate is ready for regulated environments. Mid: The response shows a basic understanding but might need training on professional documentation standards. It suggests some risky habits. Bad: The response indicates a disregard for data integrity. This could lead to serious failures or compliance issues in the job.|4|Could you explain how you document and verify data points during a project to ensure that the results are accurate and repeatable?|PASS|98|[\"Perfect adherence to complex rubric section labeling requirements across all questions.\", \"Strong alignment with junior-level scope and professional constraints.\", \"Excellent differentiation between Good, Mid, and Bad example answers.\", \"Clear dimension uniqueness and high-quality interrogative sentence structure.\"]|447749b1dd9026bac937afc68e0b06b05579