Bioprocess Engineer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would just start the task based on my best guess so that I don't fall behind on the schedule. If I get it wrong, I can always fix it later once someone tells me what I was supposed to do. It is better to show progress than to wait around asking questions.|If I found the instructions unclear, I would first review any available documentation to see if I could find the answer myself. If it remained ambiguous, I would approach the person who assigned the task, explain exactly what I found confusing, and ask for clarification before starting. This ensures I don't waste time doing the work incorrectly.|I would probably ask a coworker what they think the instructions mean before I start working. If they aren't sure either, I would just try my best to do what I think is right and hope for the best. I don't want to bother the manager with too many questions if I can help it.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows initiative and a desire for accuracy by seeking clarification. They demonstrate they value time and quality over just 'getting it done.' Mid: The candidate is hesitant to ask for help and relies on peers rather than the source. They are willing to guess, which introduces unnecessary risk. Bad: The candidate prioritizes speed over correctness and is willing to perform rework. They show a lack of professional judgment and communication. Structure check: Good: The response follows a logical progression of self-research, targeted questioning, and prevention of errors. It clearly outlines the steps they would take. Mid: The response is a bit indecisive and doesn't have a clear plan of acti