Marketing Specialist|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I usually just read my notes during presentations because I want to make sure I don't forget any of the details. I don't really like to use slides because I think they are distracting for the audience. If people don't understand, I figure they will just ask me later if it is really important to them.|When I was proposing a new project idea to my internship team, I prepared a short visual deck to support my main points. I made sure to define any internal terms I used and paused after each section to ask if anyone had questions. At the end, I sent a follow-up email with a summary of the key takeaways to ensure everyone was on the same page.|I had to present my research findings to my classmates during a group project. I spoke slowly and tried to look at everyone in the room while I was talking so I could see if they were paying attention. I asked if there were any questions at the very end of the talk, and a few people asked for more info.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate understands that communication is a two-way process. They use multiple methods (visual, verbal, written) to ensure clarity and engagement. Mid: The candidate focuses on the delivery but lacks a strategy for ensuring comprehension. They rely on basic public speaking tips rather than a communication plan. Bad: The candidate is indifferent to the audience's needs and lacks professional presentation skills. They show no effort to engage or clarify. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear path: preparation, delivery, and follow-up. This shows a comprehensive approach to communication. Mid: The candidate describes the act of presenting in a linear fashion. The structure is simple but lacks the professional polish of the 'good' answer. Bad: The response is disorganized and focused on the candidate's own comfort rather than the audience's understanding. There is no clear structure to their approach. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific tools like a visual deck and follow-up emails. They explain the reasoning behind pausing for questions throughout the talk. Mid: The candidate mentions looking at the audience and speaking slowly. These are basic points and do not show a deep understanding of professional communication. Bad: The candidate provides almost no detail and focuses on what they don't like to do. They offer no insight into how they manage group interactions. Clarity check: Good: The response is articulate and professional. The candidate's methods for ensuring clarity are themselves explained very clearly. Mid: The response is a bit vague and informal. The candidate's explanation of how they 'know' people understood is weak. Bad: The response is confusing and demonstrates poor communication skills. The candidate fails to provide a convincing example of a successful presentation. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can represent the team's ideas effectively to stakeholders. They demonstrate the communication skills necessary for cross-functional collaboration. Mid: The candidate shows they can handle basic speaking tasks but may struggle with more complex or high-stakes presentations. They are an average communicator. Bad: The candidate lacks the basic communication skills required for the role. They would likely struggle to get buy-in for their ideas or report clearly on their work.|7|Can you explain a situation where you had to present your ideas to a group of people and how you ensured they understood your message?|PASS|98|[\"Excellent alignment with the junior level and specified dimensions.\", \"Rubric structure is fully compliant with all required per-section labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between good, mid, and bad answer examples.\", \"Questions are clear, single-sentence interrogatives.\"]|7d8fc7a4932afa51a819d69d7093e53566671803|70577dae38d7d04ae00edd5eee87a8c645c41c89|Marketing Specialist|166|d36bf113562e600219e295aefb0cf64150ee9073|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:56.058398Z
Marketing Specialist|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I don't really think you need to do a lot of research because most people like the same kinds of things anyway. I just try to come up with a message that sounds exciting and hope that it reaches as many people as possible. I think over-analyzing the audience can actually make the project less creative.|I start by looking at the demographic data from our previous projects to see who has engaged with us the most. I also spend time researching online forums and social media groups where our potential audience spends their time to see what topics they are discussing. I then summarize these findings into a few key interests that I use to guide the tone and content of the new strategy.|I usually just try to think about what I would like to see if I were the customer for this project. I also look at what our competitors are doing to see what seems to be working for them at the moment. I then try to write things that sound similar to what I found during my research of other companies.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate uses data and external research to build an audience profile. They show an understanding of why audience research is necessary for a successful strategy. Mid: The candidate relies on personal intuition and competitor imitation. They lack a rigorous or original approach to audience analysis. Bad: The candidate dismisses the importance of audience research. They show a lack of professional methodology and a reliance on guesswork. Structure check: Good: The candidate provides a logical flow from data review to external research to final summary. The process is clear and repeatable. Mid: The candidate describes a few disconnected actions they take. The structure is loose and does not show a cohesive plan for analysis. Bad: The candidate provides a disorganized response that focuses on their personal opinion. There is no clear process or structure to their work. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific sources like demographic data and online forums. They explain how the research directly influences the 'tone and content' of their work. Mid: The candidate mentions 'thinking like a customer' and 'looking at competitors'. These are very general ideas that lack specific execution details. Bad: The candidate provides no detail and offers no evidence of having ever performed audience research. Their answer is based on a lack of experience. Clarity check: Good: The response is clear and professional. The candidate uses appropriate terms for the field and communicates their process effectively. Mid: The candidate uses simple and somewhat vague language. It is clear they have a general idea of the task but lack professional depth. Bad: The candidate's response is confusing and demonstrates a lack of understanding of the job requirements. Their reasoning is unprofessional. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows the ability to conduct the foundational research required for effective communication. This is a key technical skill for the team. Mid: The candidate shows they can follow a general direction but may struggle to find unique insights. They would require significant guidance on research methods. Bad: The candidate lacks the research and analytical skills necessary for the role. Their work would likely miss the mark with the intended audience.|8|Explain the process you use to identify and analyze the interests of a target audience before developing a new communication strategy?|PASS|98|[\"Excellent alignment with the junior level and specified dimensions.\", \"Rubric structure is fully compliant with all required per-section labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between good, mid, and bad answer examples.\", \"Questions are clear, single-sentence interrogatives.\"]|7d8fc7a4932afa51a819d69d7093e53566671803|70577dae38d7d04ae00edd5eee87a8c645c41c89|Marketing Specialist|167|d36bf113562e600219e295aefb0cf64150ee9073|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:56.058398Z
Marketing Specialist|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I think that the computer usually catches most of the errors for me, so I don't spend a lot of time on a final review. I have a lot of projects to do, so I usually just trust that my first draft was good enough to send out. If there is a small mistake, I can always just fix it later and send an update to everyone.|I always use a final checklist that I developed specifically for this purpose to ensure I don't miss anything. I manually click every link to make sure it goes to the right page and I read through all the dates and names out loud to catch typos. Finally, I ask a teammate to do a quick 'second pair of eyes' review if the project is going to a large stakeholder group.|I usually just read through the whole project one last time before I hit the send button to make sure it looks right. I try to click on a few of the links just to be safe, especially if they are new ones I haven't used before. I usually find most of the mistakes myself if I have enough time to look at it closely.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a rigorous and systematic approach to quality control. They value accuracy and understand the importance of a final check. Mid: The candidate has a casual approach to quality control. They rely on their memory rather than a structured process like a checklist. Bad: The candidate is careless and lacks attention to detail. They prioritize speed over accuracy and show a lack of professional accountability. Structure check: Good: The candidate describes a clear sequence of actions: checklist, manual verification, and peer review. This shows a high level of professional discipline. Mid: The candidate describes a single-step process (reading it through). The structure is very basic and does not show multiple layers of verification. Bad: The candidate provides a defensive response that avoids the question. There is no structure to their approach because they do not have a process. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific techniques like reading out loud and using a checklist. This shows they have thought about how to catch human errors. Mid: The candidate gives a general overview of 'reading it over'. They do not mention any specific tools or techniques that help them ensure accuracy. Bad: The candidate provides no detail and dismisses the need for the task. They show no understanding of the risks associated with errors in professional work. Clarity check: Good: The response is very clear and the candidate's dedication to quality is obvious. The language is professional and the steps are easy to understand. Mid: The response is a bit vague and informal. The candidate sounds like they perform these checks sporadically rather than as a rule. Bad: The candidate's response is confusing and highlights a negative attitude toward quality control. They fail to explain how they maintain professional standards. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the high attention to detail required for the job. They show they can be trusted to produce error-free work. Mid: The candidate shows a basic level of care but would likely miss subtle errors. They would need a supervisor to perform final checks for them. Bad: The candidate's lack of attention to detail would be a liability for the team. They demonstrate a mindset that leads to unprofessional outputs.|9|What specific steps do you take to verify that all links, dates, and names are correct before a final project is published or sent out?|PASS|98|[\"Excellent alignment with the junior level and specified dimensions.\", \"Rubric structure is fully compliant with all required per-section labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between good, mid, and bad answer examples.\", \"Questions are clear, single-sentence interrogatives.\"]|7d8fc7a4932afa51a819d69d7093e53566671803|70577dae38d7d04ae00edd5eee87a8c645c41c89|Marketing Specialist|168|d36bf113562e600219e295aefb0cf64150ee9073|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:56.058398Z
Marketing Specialist|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would be very upset because their mistake makes me look bad to the boss. I would probably just tell the manager right away that I can't do my work because the other person is lazy and missed their deadline. I don't think I should have to do anything else until they finish their part of the project.|I would check in with the teammate as soon as the deadline passed to see if they had a new estimated completion time. I would then inform my project lead about the delay and explain how it might shift my own delivery date. To stay productive, I would focus on other parts of my work that do not depend on my teammate's input until their part is ready.|I would probably send a few reminder emails to the teammate to see where their work is and when they will be done. I would wait for them to finish before I started my own part, because I need their information to do my job correctly. I would hope that the manager doesn't get mad at me for being late too.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows professionalism, adaptability, and clear communication. They focus on maintaining productivity despite the setback. Mid: The candidate is reactive and depends entirely on the other person. They lack the initiative to manage their own time or communicate with the lead. Bad: The candidate is defensive and quick to blame others. They show a lack of teamwork and a lack of accountability for the overall project success. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear, logical sequence: check in, communicate up, and redirect effort. This shows strong project management skills for a junior level. Mid: The candidate describes a simple cycle of waiting and reminding. The structure is linear but passive. Bad: The candidate provides an emotional response without a constructive plan. The structure is based on complaints rather than actions. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific actions like focusing on independent tasks and updating the project lead. This shows they understand work dependencies. Mid: The candidate only mentions sending reminders. They do not elaborate on how they would manage their own workload in the meantime. Bad: The candidate offers no professional detail. They only focus on their frustration with the teammate. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's plan is clear and professional. They communicate their priorities and their communication strategy effectively. Mid: The response is somewhat vague and the candidate sounds frustrated. It is not entirely clear how they would handle the actual work delay. Bad: The response is clear in its negativity but shows poor professional judgment. The reasoning is based on personal feelings rather than the project's needs. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the maturity and problem-solving skills needed for the team. They show they can handle common workplace obstacles. Mid: The candidate shows they are a follower who may struggle when things don't go according to plan. They would require a lot of supervision during delays. Bad: The candidate's attitude would likely create toxic team dynamics. They show they are not a collaborative or resilient team member.|10|How would you handle a situation where a teammate missed a deadline that was critical for you to finish your own part of the project?|PASS|98|[\"Excellent alignment with the junior level and specified dimensions.\", \"Rubric structure is fully compliant with all required per-section labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between good, mid, and bad answer examples.\", \"Questions are clear, single-sentence interrogatives.\"]|7d8fc7a4932afa51a819d69d7093e53566671803|70577dae38d7d04ae00edd5eee87a8c645c41c89|Marketing Specialist|169|d36bf113562e600219e295aefb0cf64150ee9073|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:40:56.058398Z
New Reporter|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I usually don't have disagreements because I try to avoid conflict at all costs in the workplace. If a teammate is being difficult, I will just go to the supervisor and ask to be moved to a different team or project to avoid any further issues.|During a group project, a teammate and I disagreed on the best way to structure our final presentation. I invited them to coffee so we could discuss our reasoning without the pressure of the whole group watching. We found that our goals were actually aligned, so we merged our ideas into a hybrid structure that satisfied both of us and improved the final result.|I once worked with someone who wanted to do things differently than me on a project. We argued for a bit about which method was faster. Eventually, I just decided to do my part my way and let them do their part their way so we could finish on time without more fighting.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a proactive and collaborative approach to resolving interpersonal tension. They focus on mutual goals rather than personal winning. Mid: The candidate shows they can complete a task despite conflict but relies on avoidance or silos. They do not truly resolve the underlying disagreement. Bad: The candidate lacks conflict resolution skills or avoids responsibility entirely. They may show an over-reliance on authority to solve minor peer issues. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear Situation-Action-Result format with logical flow. It highlights specific steps taken by the candidate. Mid: The response provides some context but is thin on the specific actions taken to resolve the issue. The result is mentioned but lacks detail. Bad: The response is disorganized and fails to provide a clear narrative or outcome. It focuses more on the problem than the solution. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about the conversation and the reasoning behind their actions. They reflect on what was learned from the encounter. Mid: The candidate provides a generic description of the event without much detail. There is little to no reflection on the interpersonal dynamics. Bad: The response is extremely brief or avoids the question's premise. It provides no insight into the candidate's thought process. Clarity check: Good: The language is professional and the explanation of the conflict is easy to follow. There is no ambiguity about the candidate's role in the resolution. Mid: The explanation is somewhat muddled or uses vague terms to describe the disagreement. It takes effort to understand the actual sequence of events. Bad: The response is confusing or contradictory in its description of the events. It fails to convey a professional tone. Relevance to role: Good: The answer shows high emotional intelligence which is critical for working in small teams. It demonstrates a junior-appropriate level of initiative. Mid: The answer is acceptable for an entry-level position but shows a lack of maturity in handling professional relationships. It reflects a 'just get it done' attitude without growth. Bad: The answer suggests the candidate would be difficult to work with or would create friction in the team. It does not align with the collaborative nature of the project.|1|Tell me about a time you had a disagreement with a teammate and how you worked to resolve it?|PASS|98|[\"Strong alignment with junior level expectations.\", \"Strict adherence to rubric structural requirements including internal labels.\", \"Clear differentiation across all performance levels.\"]|ee47e02a0692a070a3b2f37e163c076211db3d99|6550a4a3516bbcbf04d322b6640d0d7d2776353b|New Reporter|170|ed3cdd07f89217945445a8b196c92db5c4789d81|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.244506Z
New Reporter|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I haven't really received much negative feedback because I am usually very thorough with my work from the start. If someone tells me to change something, I usually just do it without asking questions because they are the boss and I want to stay out of trouble.|During my internship, my supervisor told me that my initial drafts were too wordy and lacked clear focus. I took their advice by creating a stricter outline before writing and setting a personal goal to reduce my word count by twenty percent. My next three submissions were praised for being much more concise and easier to read.|My teacher once told me that I needed to check my citations more carefully on my research projects. I made sure to look over them one more time before turning in the next assignment. I think the next project was better because I spent a little more time on that part.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate displays a growth mindset and a willingness to improve based on external input. They show a clear link between feedback and behavioral change. Mid: The candidate acknowledges feedback but treats it as a one-time correction rather than a learning opportunity. The improvement described is minimal or vague. Bad: The candidate is defensive or claims they never receive feedback. This suggests a lack of self-awareness or an inability to handle professional critique. Structure check: Good: The response identifies the specific feedback, the actions taken to improve, and the positive outcome. It is a complete story of professional development. Mid: The response mentions feedback but the 'action' and 'result' steps are underdeveloped. It feels more like a simple correction than a process. Bad: The response lacks a clear structure and fails to address the 'implementation' part of the question. It may focus entirely on the feedback itself. Depth check: Good: The candidate describes a specific strategy they developed to address the critique. They show ownership of their professional growth. Mid: The candidate provides a superficial account of the feedback. They do not explain the 'why' or 'how' of their improvement in detail. Bad: The response is overly brief and lacks any concrete examples of change. It does not demonstrate any real effort to evolve. Clarity check: Good: The explanation of the feedback is clear and professional. The candidate's response to the feedback is easy to understand. Mid: The feedback described is a bit vague, making it hard to see how significant the change was. The tone is neutral but uninspired. Bad: The response is unclear and may come across as dismissive of the feedback process. It is difficult to tell what actually changed in the work. Relevance to role: Good: This shows the candidate can be mentored and coached, which is vital for a junior project member. It demonstrates accountability and self-regulation. Mid: The candidate is coachable but may require significant hand-holding. They show a passive approach to self-improvement. Bad: The candidate may be difficult to manage or train. Their response suggests they might repeat mistakes if they don't value the feedback process.|2|Can you describe a situation where you received constructive feedback on your work and how you implemented it?|PASS|98|[\"Strong alignment with junior level expectations.\", \"Strict adherence to rubric structural requirements including internal labels.\", \"Clear differentiation across all performance levels.\"]|ee47e02a0692a070a3b2f37e163c076211db3d99|6550a4a3516bbcbf04d322b6640d0d7d2776353b|New Reporter|171|ed3cdd07f89217945445a8b196c92db5c4789d81|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.244506Z
New Reporter|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I mostly just use the first source I find if it seems like a reliable place. If I am unsure about something, I might ask a teammate what they think, but usually, I just trust that the information I found is good enough for the task.|First, I identify the primary source of the information to ensure it is credible and current. Then, I cross-reference that data with at least two other independent sources to check for consistency. Finally, I double-check all dates, names, and figures against my original notes to prevent any transcription errors before final submission.|I usually search for the information online and see if I can find it on a few different websites. If the sites look professional and they all say the same thing, I assume the information is correct. I try to be careful not to make any big mistakes when I am writing it down.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a rigorous and methodical approach to fact-checking and data integrity. They understand the importance of primary sources and cross-verification. Mid: The candidate has a basic understanding of verification but relies on potentially unreliable methods like general web searches. Their process is less structured. Bad: The candidate lacks a formal process for verification and relies on intuition or single sources. This poses a risk to the quality of the project. Structure check: Good: The response is a step-by-step walkthrough that is easy to follow. It moves logically from identification to final checking. Mid: The response mentions a few actions but they are not organized into a clear, repeatable process. It feels more like a collection of habits. Bad: The response is disorganized and does not provide a clear sequence of events. It fails to answer the 'walk me through' prompt. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the 'why' behind each step, such as avoiding transcription errors. They show attention to detail at a granular level. Mid: The candidate provides a high-level overview without much detail on specific techniques. They do not explain how they handle conflicting information. Bad: The response is very shallow and suggests the candidate does not take accuracy seriously. It lacks any mention of specific tools or standards. Clarity check: Good: The steps are described using clear, professional language. The candidate's commitment to accuracy is evident. Mid: The explanation is a bit fuzzy and uses informal language. It is clear what they do, but not necessarily how well they do it. Bad: The response is vague and doesn't actually describe a verification process. It is hard to see how they ensure their work is correct. Relevance to role: Good: For a junior role, this level of detail suggests the candidate will produce reliable work with minimal supervision. It demonstrates strong foundational habits. Mid: The candidate is likely to produce acceptable work but may miss subtle errors. They will require more oversight during the quality assurance phase. Bad: The candidate's work may be unreliable and require extensive checking by others. This does not align with the needs of the team.|3|Walk me through the specific steps you take to verify the accuracy of information before including it in a project?|PASS|98|[\"Strong alignment with junior level expectations.\", \"Strict adherence to rubric structural requirements including internal labels.\", \"Clear differentiation across all performance levels.\"]|ee47e02a0692a070a3b2f37e163c076211db3d99|6550a4a3516bbcbf04d322b6640d0d7d2776353b|New Reporter|172|ed3cdd07f89217945445a8b196c92db5c4789d81|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.244506Z
New Reporter|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I don't really have a set system for organizing my notes before I start. I usually just start writing and then look back through my notebooks or files whenever I feel like I need to find a specific fact or detail to include.|I start by categorizing my notes into key themes or sections that align with the project goals. I use digital folders to keep raw data, interview transcripts, and secondary research separate so I can find things quickly. Before drafting, I create a detailed outline where I map specific pieces of evidence to each section of the document.|I usually keep all my notes in one big document so that I don't lose anything. I try to highlight the most important parts with different colors so I can see them when I start writing. It can get a little messy, but I usually know where everything is located.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows strong organizational skills and a systematic approach to handling information. They understand that organization is the foundation of a good draft. Mid: The candidate has a basic method for keeping track of information but it lacks scalability. Their system relies on memory or messy documents. Bad: The candidate is disorganized and lacks a workflow for transitioning from research to production. This approach is likely to lead to missed details or slow output. Structure check: Good: The response describes a clear workflow: categorize, store, and map. It shows a logical progression from raw data to a structured outline. Mid: The response describes a few habits but they don't form a cohesive system. It is more about 'saving' things than 'organizing' them. Bad: The response lacks any sense of structure or process. It suggests a chaotic way of working that would be difficult to replicate. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific techniques like theme categorization and mapping evidence to sections. They show they have thought about how to make the drafting process efficient. Mid: The candidate provides very little detail about how they actually use their notes. They mention highlighting but not how that translates to a finished product. Bad: The response is extremely brief and shows no depth of thought regarding productivity or work quality. It is a very reactive way of working. Clarity check: Good: The language is precise and describes a professional workflow. The candidate's methods are easy for an evaluator to visualize. Mid: The description is a bit informal and the process seems a bit cluttered. It is clear they try to stay organized but may struggle with large amounts of data. Bad: The response is vague and suggests the candidate hasn't really considered how they organize their work. It is difficult to understand their workflow. Relevance to role: Good: This level of organization is excellent for a junior staff member who needs to manage multiple tasks. It suggests they will be efficient and reliable. Mid: The candidate will likely be able to handle simple tasks but may feel overwhelmed by complex projects. They will need guidance on better workflows. Bad: The candidate's lack of organization will likely lead to delays and errors. They do not demonstrate the basic professional practices required for the job.|4|How do you typically organize your notes and gathered data when you are preparing to draft a new piece of work?|PASS|98|[\"Strong alignment with junior level expectations.\", \"Strict adherence to rubric structural requirements including internal labels.\", \"Clear differentiation across all performance levels.\"]|ee47e02a0692a070a3b2f37e163c076211db3d99|6550a4a3516bbcbf04d322b6640d0d7d2776353b|New Reporter|173|ed3cdd07f89217945445a8b196c92db5c4789d81|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.244506Z
New Reporter|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would just pick one and ignore the other until I was finished with the first one. I don't think it is fair for people to give me two things at once, so they should understand if one of them is late or not done at all.|I would first assess the scope of both tasks to see if it is realistically possible to complete both by working more efficiently. If not, I would immediately reach out to both stakeholders to explain the situation and ask for clarification on the relative priority of each task. I would then work with my direct lead to ensure that the most critical project is finished first while negotiating a small extension for the other.|I would probably just pick the task that seems more important or the one that I think I can finish faster. I would work as hard as I could to get both done, but if I couldn't, I would just tell the second person that I ran out of time at the last minute.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates strong prioritization skills and proactive communication. They understand the need to manage stakeholder expectations and involve leadership when conflicts arise. Mid: The candidate tries to solve the problem through effort alone rather than communication. Their plan for failure (telling the person at the last minute) is unprofessional. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of accountability and poor communication skills. They do not understand how to manage professional commitments or workplace pressure. Structure check: Good: The response follows a logical sequence: assess, communicate, escalate, and resolve. It shows a clear path for decision-making under pressure. Mid: The response is a bit scattered and focuses more on the effort of working hard than the strategy of managing the situation. The outcome is uncertain. Bad: The response is defensive and does not offer a constructive way to handle the conflict. It fails to provide a professional solution. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific actions like scope assessment and priority negotiation. They show an understanding of workplace hierarchy and team communication. Mid: The candidate provides a very simple 'I will try my best' answer without much tactical depth. They miss the importance of early communication. Bad: The response is shallow and suggests the candidate would fold under pressure. It lacks any professional reasoning or reflection. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's approach is stated clearly and professionally. The logic behind their decision-making is easy to follow. Mid: The response is a bit vague about how they decide which task is more important. The communication plan is also a bit weak. Bad: The response is unprofessional in tone and unclear in its execution. It doesn't provide a viable way to manage the workload. Relevance to role: Good: This is a critical skill for any junior employee in a fast-paced team. It shows they can handle the realities of shifting priorities without burning out. Mid: The candidate is willing to work hard but lacks the communication skills to manage their workload effectively. They may need significant supervision to avoid missing deadlines. Bad: The candidate's attitude is a red flag for any team-based role. They are likely to cause project delays and stakeholder frustration.|5|What would you do if you were assigned two urgent tasks by different stakeholders that both had the same deadline?|PASS|98|[\"Strong alignment with junior level expectations.\", \"Strict adherence to rubric structural requirements including internal labels.\", \"Clear differentiation across all performance levels.\"]|ee47e02a0692a070a3b2f37e163c076211db3d99|6550a4a3516bbcbf04d322b6640d0d7d2776353b|New Reporter|174|ed3cdd07f89217945445a8b196c92db5c4789d81|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.244506Z
New Reporter|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I would just keep telling them why my idea is right until they eventually give in and agree with me. If they are being stubborn, I might just go and do the idea myself to show them that it works better than whatever they were thinking.|I would start by asking the teammate to explain their concerns in detail so I can fully understand their perspective. Instead of just arguing for my idea, I would present data or examples that show how my approach solves the specific problems they are worried about. If we still disagreed, I would suggest a small trial or a pilot version of my idea to see if it works before committing the whole team to it.|I would try to explain my idea again in a different way to see if they understand it better the second time. I would tell them all the reasons why I think it is the best way to do the project. If they still didn't like it, I would probably just ask the rest of the team to vote on it.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate uses empathy, evidence, and compromise to influence others. They focus on listening and problem-solving rather than just 'winning' an argument. Mid: The candidate relies on repetition and group pressure rather than true persuasion. They show a basic ability to advocate for themselves but lack sophisticated influence skills. Bad: The candidate is aggressive or dismissive of others' opinions. They show a lack of teamwork and a 'my way or the highway' mentality. Structure check: Good: The response moves from listening to evidence-based persuasion and then to a compromise (the pilot). This is a very strong, structured approach to influence. Mid: The response is a bit linear and doesn't account for the other person's feedback. It feels more like a lecture than a conversation. Bad: The response lacks structure and suggests a confrontational approach. It does not provide a professional pathway to agreement. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific tactics like active listening and using a pilot project. They show they understand how to de-escalate tension while still moving the project forward. Mid: The candidate's tactics are very basic, such as repeating themselves or voting. They don't show much insight into why the other person might be resistant. Bad: The response is shallow and suggests the candidate hasn't thought about how to work effectively with people who have different opinions. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's reasoning is clear and the tone is professional and respectful. The steps are easy to understand and replicate. Mid: The response is a bit vague and doesn't clearly show how they would change the other person's mind. The tone is okay but unconvincing. Bad: The response is blunt and lacks professional polish. It suggests a lack of interpersonal skills that would be problematic in a team. Relevance to role: Good: This demonstrates high potential for growth and collaboration. It shows the candidate can contribute ideas without causing friction. Mid: The candidate is a standard junior contributor who may need help navigating team dynamics. They are not yet a strong influencer but are willing to try. Bad: The candidate's approach would likely create a toxic team environment. They do not demonstrate the necessary soft skills for a collaborative workplace.|6|Explain how you would go about persuading a teammate to adopt your idea when they initially seem resistant?|PASS|98|[\"Strong alignment with junior level expectations.\", \"Strict adherence to rubric structural requirements including internal labels.\", \"Clear differentiation across all performance levels.\"]|ee47e02a0692a070a3b2f37e163c076211db3d99|6550a4a3516bbcbf04d322b6640d0d7d2776353b|New Reporter|175|ed3cdd07f89217945445a8b196c92db5c4789d81|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.244506Z
New Reporter|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I once had a project that was just too difficult because the instructions were bad and my teammates didn't help. I eventually just did the best I could with what I had, but the final grade wasn't very good because the situation was out of my control.|In my final year project, our main data source became unavailable two weeks before the deadline. I spent a weekend researching alternative public datasets and reached out to a professor for advice on how to adjust our methodology. By being proactive and putting in extra hours, I found a replacement source that actually provided more detailed results than the original.|I once had a computer problem where I lost some of the work I had done on a big assignment. I had to stay up really late for a few nights to rewrite everything from memory and from some old notes I had. It was very stressful but I managed to turn it in on time.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows resilience, problem-solving skills, and a high level of ownership. They seek out resources and put in the necessary effort to overcome a challenge. Mid: The candidate shows resilience but the problem was somewhat self-inflicted or resolved through brute force (staying up late) rather than strategic thinking. Bad: The candidate displays a victim mentality and lacks agency. They blame external factors for poor results rather than trying to find a solution. Structure check: Good: The response clearly identifies the obstacle, the specific actions taken to solve it, and the positive result. It is a well-rounded narrative of success. Mid: The response focus mostly on the struggle and the stress rather than the strategic steps taken to fix the situation. The result is just 'getting it done'. Bad: The response is poorly structured and focuses on the negative aspects of the experience. It fails to show any constructive action. Depth check: Good: The candidate describes a multi-pronged approach: research, seeking advice, and working hard. They show they can think critically under pressure. Mid: The candidate provides a very simple story of just re-doing work. It doesn't show much ingenuity or learning from the experience. Bad: The response is shallow and provides no evidence of professional growth. It suggests the candidate might give up when things get hard. Clarity check: Good: The situation and the candidate's response are described in clear, professional terms. The success of the outcome is well-defined. Mid: The explanation is a bit focused on the emotional side of the obstacle. The actual steps taken are clear but uninspired. Bad: The response is vague and it's hard to tell what the actual obstacle was or what the candidate did to address it. Relevance to role: Good: This demonstrates the grit and initiative needed for a junior role in an environment where things don't always go as planned. It shows high potential. Mid: The candidate is reliable enough to finish tasks but might not be the one to find creative solutions to problems. They show basic competence. Bad: The candidate's lack of initiative is a concern for a role that requires troubleshooting and persistence. They are unlikely to excel in a challenging environment.|7|Describe a time when you encountered a significant obstacle while working on a task and how you pushed through it?|PASS|98|[\"Strong alignment with junior level expectations.\", \"Strict adherence to rubric structural requirements including internal labels.\", \"Clear differentiation across all performance levels.\"]|ee47e02a0692a070a3b2f37e163c076211db3d99|6550a4a3516bbcbf04d322b6640d0d7d2776353b|New Reporter|176|ed3cdd07f89217945445a8b196c92db5c4789d81|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.244506Z
New Reporter|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I usually just listen and try to remember the most important parts. I find that if I spend too much time writing, I can't really pay attention to what is being said. I might jot down a few words at the end if I think I might forget them.|I always prepare a list of key questions and objectives beforehand so I stay focused on what needs to be gathered. During the conversation, I use a digital note-taking tool to record main points, but I also keep a physical notebook for quick diagrams or follow-up questions. Immediately after the meeting, I review and clean up my notes while the information is still fresh in my mind.|I try to write down everything the person says as fast as I can so I don't miss anything. Sometimes I use my phone to record the audio if they let me, and then I listen to it later to make sure I got all the quotes right. It takes a long time but it works.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate has a structured system for information capture and recognizes the importance of preparation and immediate review. They use tools effectively to support their memory. Mid: The candidate relies on transcription or recording, which is a bit inefficient. They show effort but lack a strategic approach to identifying 'necessary' vs 'all' details. Bad: The candidate relies almost entirely on memory, which is a high-risk approach for a professional setting. They do not show any formal technique for accuracy. Structure check: Good: The response follows a chronological order: before, during, and after. This shows a complete workflow for information management. Mid: The response mentions a few things they do during the meeting but lacks the preparation or post-meeting review steps. It is a partial workflow. Bad: The response is disorganized and does not provide a clear method. It suggests a very haphazard approach to gathering information. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific tools (digital vs physical) and a specific post-meeting habit (reviewing while fresh). They show they have refined this process over time. Mid: The candidate provides very little detail about how they actually organize the information they capture. It is a very 'brute force' approach to note-taking. Bad: The response is shallow and shows no understanding of the importance of detail in a professional context. It suggests a lack of diligence. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's method is clear, professional, and easy to understand. The benefits of their system are evident in their explanation. Mid: The explanation is a bit basic and the tone is more casual. It's clear what they do, but it doesn't sound very professional. Bad: The response is vague and doesn't actually describe a technique. It's hard to imagine how they would accurately capture complex information. Relevance to role: Good: This is a vital skill for a junior role that involves research and reporting back to a team. It ensures that the team has accurate data to work with. Mid: The candidate will likely be accurate but slow. Their current process might not scale well as their workload increases. Bad: The candidate's approach is likely to lead to missing or incorrect information. This would be a significant liability for the project and the team.|8|Tell me about the techniques you use to ensure you capture all necessary details during a meeting or interview?|PASS|98|[\"Strong alignment with junior level expectations.\", \"Strict adherence to rubric structural requirements including internal labels.\", \"Clear differentiation across all performance levels.\"]|ee47e02a0692a070a3b2f37e163c076211db3d99|6550a4a3516bbcbf04d322b6640d0d7d2776353b|New Reporter|177|ed3cdd07f89217945445a8b196c92db5c4789d81|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.244506Z
New Reporter|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I generally trust that my first draft is pretty good because I am a careful writer. I'll give it a quick scan before I hit send, but usually, I am finishing it right at the deadline so I don't have much time for a big review process.|I finish my work at least a few hours before the deadline so I can step away and look at it with fresh eyes later. I use a checklist that covers common errors like spelling, formatting, and factual consistency. Finally, I read the entire document aloud because that helps me catch awkward phrasing or logical gaps that I might miss when reading silently.|I usually run a spell-check on the document and then read through it once or twice to make sure it makes sense. I try to look for any names or numbers that might be wrong. If I have time, I might ask a friend to take a quick look at it for me.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a rigorous and multi-layered approach to quality control. They understand the value of a 'fresh eyes' perspective and systematic checking. Mid: The candidate has a basic proofreading routine but it lacks depth. They rely heavily on automated tools and don't have a structured way to find non-obvious errors. Bad: The candidate is overconfident or lacks time management skills, leading to a high risk of errors. They do not see quality control as a separate, essential step in the process. Structure check: Good: The response identifies a clear sequence: time buffer, checklist, and read-aloud. It shows a disciplined approach to finishing work. Mid: The response lists a few common actions but doesn't feel like a committed process. It is more about 'checking' than 'verifying'. Bad: The response lacks any structure and suggests a very rushed final stage. It fails to provide a professional workflow. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific techniques like the read-aloud method and the use of a checklist. They explain why these steps are effective at catching different types of errors. Mid: The candidate provides a very high-level description of proofreading. They don't show much insight into what specific kinds of inconsistencies they are looking for. Bad: The response is shallow and suggests the candidate doesn't value the 'finishing' stage of a project. It shows a lack of professional standards. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's explanation is precise and their commitment to high-quality output is clear. The tone is professional and diligent. Mid: The description is a bit vague and informal. It sounds like they do the bare minimum to avoid being called out for mistakes. Bad: The response is dismissive and unprofessional. It is hard to trust that their work would be error-free based on this answer. Relevance to role: Good: This is an excellent trait for a junior employee. It reduces the burden on the lead and ensures that the team's output is professional and accurate. Mid: The candidate will likely produce acceptable work but will still need regular checking by a senior team member. They show basic competence. Bad: The candidate's work is likely to contain frequent errors. This would be a significant drain on the lead's time and could damage the team's reputation.|9|What is your process for checking your finished work for errors or inconsistencies before you submit it to your lead?|PASS|98|[\"Strong alignment with junior level expectations.\", \"Strict adherence to rubric structural requirements including internal labels.\", \"Clear differentiation across all performance levels.\"]|ee47e02a0692a070a3b2f37e163c076211db3d99|6550a4a3516bbcbf04d322b6640d0d7d2776353b|New Reporter|178|ed3cdd07f89217945445a8b196c92db5c4789d81|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.244506Z
New Reporter|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would just do the task based on my best guess and hope for the best. I don't want to look like I don't know what I'm doing by asking too many questions, so I'll just turn it in and wait for them to tell me if it's wrong.|I would start by reviewing the request and identifying the specific areas where I need more information, such as the target audience or the final format. I would then schedule a brief check-in with the person who assigned it to ask my specific questions and confirm my understanding of the goal. I would also look for similar past projects to use as a template so I'm not starting from scratch without any guidance.|I would probably just start working on what I think they want and then show them a draft as soon as possible to see if I'm on the right track. If I get stuck, I'll ask a teammate if they know what the person usually expects for this kind of task.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows initiative and the ability to navigate ambiguity through proactive communication. They use resources (past projects) and strategic questioning to clarify their path. Mid: The candidate uses a 'trial and error' approach, which is okay but less efficient. They are willing to ask for help but only after they've already started the work. Bad: The candidate is afraid of appearing incompetent and would rather waste time doing the wrong thing than ask for clarity. This is a high-risk approach for a professional environment. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear logic: analyze, ask, and research. It shows a systematic way to turn a vague request into a concrete plan. Mid: The response is a bit more reactive. It describes a sequence of 'start, check, and ask' which is a common but less professional junior workflow. Bad: The response lacks a clear plan and focuses on the candidate's internal fears rather than the task at hand. It fails to provide a constructive solution. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific things they would ask about (audience, format) and specific resources they would look for (templates). They show they know how to gather requirements. Mid: The candidate's approach is very simple and doesn't show much strategic thinking. They don't mention what kind of questions they would actually ask. Bad: The response is shallow and suggests the candidate lacks the confidence or skills to handle unclear assignments. It shows no professional maturity. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's approach is stated clearly and the tone is professional. They describe a workflow that makes sense for a junior team member. Mid: The response is a bit informal and the strategy is somewhat vague. It's clear what they would do, but it doesn't sound very efficient. Bad: The response is confusing and suggests a lack of professional judgment. It is hard to see how they would ever successfully complete a vague task. Relevance to role: Good: This is a vital skill in any dynamic workplace where instructions are often brief. It shows the candidate can take ownership and reduce uncertainty for themselves and the team. Mid: The candidate is willing to try but will likely require more guidance than a high-performer. They show they are manageable but not yet independent. Bad: The candidate's approach would likely lead to wasted time and frustrated stakeholders. They do not demonstrate the necessary communication skills for the job.|10|How would you handle a situation where you were asked to complete a task but the instructions provided were very vague?|PASS|98|[\"Strong alignment with junior level expectations.\", \"Strict adherence to rubric structural requirements including internal labels.\", \"Clear differentiation across all performance levels.\"]|ee47e02a0692a070a3b2f37e163c076211db3d99|6550a4a3516bbcbf04d322b6640d0d7d2776353b|New Reporter|179|ed3cdd07f89217945445a8b196c92db5c4789d81|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.244506Z
Graphic Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I had a teammate who was very difficult and didn't listen to any of my suggestions during our last project. I just did my own part of the work and let them do theirs so we wouldn't have to talk to each other anymore. We finished the project, but the final version looked disjointed because we never collaborated.|During a group project, a teammate and I had different ideas about the visual direction for our presentation. I suggested we both create a single slide draft to compare our styles objectively against the project brief. We eventually combined elements from both designs, which led to a more balanced result that our supervisor praised for its clarity.|I once worked with someone who didn't like my ideas for a project layout. We talked about it for a while and eventually decided to go with their idea because they had more experience than I did. It worked out okay in the end, but I wish I had pushed a bit more for my own concepts.|Question intent check: \\nGood: Candidate demonstrates a collaborative approach to conflict by seeking common ground and focusing on project goals. They show emotional maturity by suggesting objective ways to resolve the impasse.\\nMid: Candidate identifies a conflict but resolves it through passive compliance rather than active collaboration. They lack the initiative to lead a constructive dialogue.\\nBad: Candidate avoids the conflict entirely or blames the teammate for the breakdown in communication. They show no effort to find a professional middle ground.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response follows a clear narrative path from the initial disagreement to the specific actions taken and the final result. It is easy for the interviewer to follow the logic of the story.\\nMid: The response is mostly organized but skips over the specific steps taken to reach the resolution. It feels more like a summary than a detailed account.\\nBad: The response is disorganized and lacks a clear conclusion or outcome. It focuses heavily on the problem without providing a structured solution.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: Candidate provides specific details about the nature of the disagreement and the reasoning behind their chosen resolution. They reflect on why the final outcome was successful.\\nMid: Candidate provides only surface-level details about the situation. They fail to explain the 'why' behind their actions or the impact of the resolution.\\nBad: Candidate gives a very brief answer that lacks any meaningful detail or context. The response feels dismissive of the importance of team dynamics.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The language used is professional, clear, and easy to understand. The candidate avoids vague generalities and speaks directly to their personal experience.\\nMid: The language is somewhat informal or repetitive, making the point harder to grasp. The candidate uses 'we' too much without specifying their own contribution.\\nBad: The candidate uses confusing or contradictory language. It is unclear what actually happened or what the candidate's specific role was in the situation.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: The scenario is highly relevant to a junior professional working within a creative or technical team. It shows they can handle the inevitable friction of collaborative work.\\nMid: The scenario is generic and could apply to any situation, lacking specific professional context. It does not clearly demonstrate readiness for a collaborative environment.\\nBad: The scenario is irrelevant or suggests the candidate would be difficult to work with. It raises red flags about their ability to take direction or work with others.|1|Tell me about a time you had a disagreement with a teammate on a project and how you reached a resolution?|PASS|92|[\"Perfect structural compliance with all 5 rubric sections and mandatory Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"High-quality differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level detail.\", \"Questions are single interrogative sentences exceeding word count requirements.\", \"Rubrics consistently include the specific role title despite instructions to avoid it.\"]|c8ff19dfec325e8b700aa82285026e3019a896fa|7936bd65c41b9b1b7f2bfe6aef1b121639f474dc|Graphic Designer|180|84fcaed4efb510f5518998c1f00076e8d3794881|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.651456Z
Graphic Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I worked really hard on a project, but a stakeholder said they didn't like the colors I chose. I told them that those colors were trending, but they made me change them anyway. I think my original version was better, but I changed it just to get the project finished.|During my internship, a senior lead told me that my initial drafts were too cluttered and didn't follow the brand guidelines. I asked for a follow-up meeting to clarify the specific brand constraints I had missed and then created a checklist to use for all future tasks. My next submission was approved immediately because I had incorporated all the feedback precisely.|I once turned in a project and was told it wasn't what they were looking for at all. I felt a bit discouraged but I went back and changed most of the things they mentioned in the email. The second version was accepted, though I wasn't entirely sure why they liked it better.|Question intent check: \\nGood: Candidate shows a growth mindset by treating feedback as an opportunity to improve their output. They take proactive steps to ensure the mistake is not repeated.\\nMid: Candidate accepts feedback but does so reluctantly or without a clear understanding of the improvement process. They follow instructions but do not demonstrate internal learning.\\nBad: Candidate is defensive or dismissive of the feedback provided. They show a lack of accountability and a preference for their own opinion over project requirements.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response clearly identifies the feedback, the candidate's reaction, and the systemic change they implemented. It shows a logical progression from problem to solution.\\nMid: The response describes the feedback and the change but lacks a clear explanation of the candidate's thought process. It feels somewhat reactive rather than proactive.\\nBad: The response is a simple statement of what happened without any real structure. It fails to show any resolution or positive change in behavior.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: Candidate explains the specific tools or methods they used to improve, such as a checklist or a follow-up meeting. This shows a high level of professional conscientiousness.\\nMid: Candidate gives a general overview of the situation but lacks specific details about how they improved. The response feels a bit superficial.\\nBad: Candidate provides no detail about the feedback or the subsequent actions. It is impossible to gauge if any actual learning took place.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate speaks clearly and maintains a professional tone throughout the explanation. They distinguish between their feelings and the professional requirements of the task.\\nMid: The candidate's tone is slightly uncertain or overly apologetic. The distinction between the feedback received and the actions taken is a bit blurry.\\nBad: The candidate's tone is bitter or confused. They fail to communicate the situation in a way that reflects well on their professional maturity.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: The response demonstrates that the candidate is coachable, which is a vital trait for any junior professional. It shows they can handle the iterative nature of the job.\\nMid: The response shows the candidate can follow orders but doesn't necessarily show they will grow as a professional. It is an acceptable but uninspiring answer.\\nBad: The response suggests the candidate may be difficult to manage or train. It indicates a potential for repeated mistakes due to a lack of openness to critique.|2|Describe a situation where you received negative feedback on your work and what steps you took afterwards?|PASS|92|[\"Perfect structural compliance with all 5 rubric sections and mandatory Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"High-quality differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level detail.\", \"Questions are single interrogative sentences exceeding word count requirements.\", \"Rubrics consistently include the specific role title despite instructions to avoid it.\"]|c8ff19dfec325e8b700aa82285026e3019a896fa|7936bd65c41b9b1b7f2bfe6aef1b121639f474dc|Graphic Designer|181|84fcaed4efb510f5518998c1f00076e8d3794881|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.651456Z
Graphic Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I usually just open the software and start trying different things until something looks good to me. If I get stuck, I might look at some other projects for ideas, but I mostly just work until I think it is finished. Then I send the file to the person who asked for it.|I start by thoroughly researching the project goals and looking for inspiration that fits the intended audience. Then, I create several rough sketches or concepts to explore different directions before presenting the best ones for early feedback. Once a direction is chosen, I refine the details and perform quality checks before delivering the final assets.|First, I read the brief to make sure I know what is needed for the task. Then I start working on the project using the software I think is best for the job. I usually send a draft over to see if they like it and then I make some final tweaks based on what they say.|Question intent check: \\nGood: Candidate demonstrates a structured and professional workflow that includes research, ideation, and iteration. They show an understanding of the importance of early feedback.\\nMid: Candidate has a basic process but it is somewhat disorganized and lacks a clear research or refinement phase. They rely too much on the software rather than the planning.\\nBad: Candidate has no clear process and relies on trial and error. They do not mention research, briefs, or feedback as part of their standard work cycle.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response is organized chronologically, making it easy to see the logical flow of the candidate's work. Each phase of the project is clearly defined.\\nMid: The response is mostly chronological but some steps are mentioned out of order. It lacks the clear 'step-by-step' feeling requested in the question.\\nBad: The response is a jumble of ideas without any clear beginning or end. It does not follow a professional project lifecycle.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: Candidate mentions specific actions like researching the audience and performing quality checks. This shows they understand the nuances of professional production.\\nMid: Candidate provides very few details about what they actually do during each step. The description of 'working' is too vague to be useful for evaluation.\\nBad: Candidate provides no detail at all about their methodology. They fail to explain how they ensure the quality or relevance of their work.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate uses precise terminology and explains their process in a way that is easy to visualize. They sound confident in their professional habits.\\nMid: The candidate uses generic language that could apply to almost any creative task. It is difficult to tell if they have a truly professional approach.\\nBad: The language is unclear and suggests a lack of experience with structured projects. The candidate seems to struggle to articulate how they actually spend their time.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: This workflow aligns perfectly with the expectations for a junior professional who must manage their own tasks effectively. It shows they are ready for real-world project cycles.\\nMid: The process is acceptable for a student but lacks the rigor needed for a fast-paced professional environment. It suggests a need for close supervision.\\nBad: The lack of process would likely lead to missed deadlines or poor quality work. It is not a sustainable way to handle professional assignments.|3|Walk me through the steps you take to move a visual project from the initial brief to the final polished draft?|PASS|92|[\"Perfect structural compliance with all 5 rubric sections and mandatory Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"High-quality differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level detail.\", \"Questions are single interrogative sentences exceeding word count requirements.\", \"Rubrics consistently include the specific role title despite instructions to avoid it.\"]|c8ff19dfec325e8b700aa82285026e3019a896fa|7936bd65c41b9b1b7f2bfe6aef1b121639f474dc|Graphic Designer|182|84fcaed4efb510f5518998c1f00076e8d3794881|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.651456Z
Graphic Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I just save the project as a PDF or an image and send it over to the team. If there is a problem with the file, they usually tell me and then I try to save it a different way. I don't really have a specific list of things I check every time.|I always double-check the project requirements for resolution, color mode, and file format before I begin exporting. I use a standardized naming convention to keep versions organized and perform a final inspection of the assets at 100% scale to check for any visual errors. Finally, I ensure all fonts and external links are properly packaged or embedded.|I usually just look at the settings when I am saving the file to make sure they match what was asked for in the email. I try to name the files correctly so people can find them, but sometimes I forget if I am in a hurry. I mostly just use the default settings for export.|Question intent check: \\nGood: Candidate demonstrates technical diligence and a proactive approach to quality control. They understand the importance of technical specifications like color modes and resolution.\\nMid: Candidate is aware of technical requirements but lacks a rigorous or consistent process for checking them. They are reactive rather than proactive.\\nBad: Candidate shows a complete lack of technical standards for final delivery. They rely on others to catch their mistakes and don't understand the basics of file optimization.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response follows a logical sequence of checks from initial export settings to final packaging. It shows a systematic approach to technical tasks.\\nMid: The response mentions a few different things they check but without a clear order or system. It feels a bit haphazard.\\nBad: The response lacks any structure and suggests that the candidate does not have a formal process for finishing their work.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: Candidate mentions specific technical terms like 'color mode', 'packaging fonts', and 'standardized naming'. This proves they have practical, hands-on experience.\\nMid: Candidate uses very general terms and avoids technical details. It is unclear if they actually know how to perform the necessary checks.\\nBad: Candidate provides no technical details and seems to rely entirely on the software's default settings. They show no understanding of professional production requirements.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The explanation is clear, concise, and professional. The candidate communicates their technical knowledge effectively without over-complicating the answer.\\nMid: The candidate's explanation is a bit fuzzy, suggesting they might not be fully confident in their technical skills. The language is somewhat imprecise.\\nBad: The candidate's answer is confusing and reflects a lack of technical literacy. They struggle to explain basic file preparation concepts.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: This is a critical skill for a junior professional who will be responsible for preparing assets for the rest of the team. It shows they can be trusted with final deliverables.\\nMid: The candidate's level of care is barely sufficient for a professional role. They would likely require significant oversight and frequent corrections.\\nBad: The lack of attention to detail would cause delays and errors in production. This is a significant red flag for a role focused on asset creation.|4|Explain how you ensure that your final files are correctly formatted and optimized for high-quality production or digital use?|PASS|92|[\"Perfect structural compliance with all 5 rubric sections and mandatory Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"High-quality differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level detail.\", \"Questions are single interrogative sentences exceeding word count requirements.\", \"Rubrics consistently include the specific role title despite instructions to avoid it.\"]|c8ff19dfec325e8b700aa82285026e3019a896fa|7936bd65c41b9b1b7f2bfe6aef1b121639f474dc|Graphic Designer|183|84fcaed4efb510f5518998c1f00076e8d3794881|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.651456Z
Graphic Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I wouldn't be able to start the project because I wouldn't want to waste time doing something wrong. I would just wait until the stakeholder came back from vacation so I could ask them exactly what they wanted. I don't think it's my job to guess what they are thinking.|I would first look through the team's archive for similar past projects to see if I can find a pattern or standard format. I would then create a few very basic options or a brief outline and share them with a senior teammate to see if I am on the right track. This allows me to keep the project moving forward while waiting for the stakeholder to return.|I would probably just wait a couple of days to see if they send more info, and if not, I'd try to start something simple. I wouldn't want to do too much work in case I have to change it all later. I'd mostly just focus on my other tasks until they get back.|Question intent check: \\nGood: Candidate shows initiative and problem-solving skills in the face of ambiguity. They understand how to use internal resources and teammates to maintain momentum.\\nMid: Candidate shows a lack of urgency and a tendency to wait for perfect information. They are willing to work but won't take the lead to resolve the uncertainty.\\nBad: Candidate is completely blocked by ambiguity and shows no initiative. They view the situation as an excuse to stop working rather than a problem to be solved.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response outlines a clear step-by-step plan: research, draft, and consult. It shows a logical way to handle a difficult professional situation.\\nMid: The response is a bit vague about the actual steps taken. It sounds like the candidate would mostly just wait and hope for the best.\\nBad: The response has no structure and essentially says 'I will do nothing'. It fails to address the core problem of the project being delayed.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: Candidate mentions specific resources like 'project archives' and 'senior teammates'. This shows they understand how a professional environment actually functions.\\nMid: Candidate provides very little detail about how they would actually spend their time. The response lacks any concrete examples of proactive behavior.\\nBad: Candidate provides no detail at all. They do not demonstrate any understanding of how to work independently or solve problems.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate's plan is easy to understand and sounds very professional. They communicate a sense of responsibility for the project's progress.\\nMid: The candidate sounds a bit unsure of themselves. Their language reflects a passive attitude toward the situation.\\nBad: The candidate's response is blunt and dismissive. They fail to communicate any sense of professional accountability.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: Handling ambiguity is a major part of many junior roles where instructions aren't always perfect. This shows the candidate can survive and thrive in a real-world office.\\nMid: The candidate's approach is safe but slow. They might struggle in a fast-paced environment where they need to make progress independently.\\nBad: The candidate's refusal to work without perfect instructions would be a major liability for the team. It shows a lack of professional maturity.|5|What would you do if a stakeholder gave you a very vague project description and then left for a week-long vacation?|PASS|92|[\"Perfect structural compliance with all 5 rubric sections and mandatory Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"High-quality differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level detail.\", \"Questions are single interrogative sentences exceeding word count requirements.\", \"Rubrics consistently include the specific role title despite instructions to avoid it.\"]|c8ff19dfec325e8b700aa82285026e3019a896fa|7936bd65c41b9b1b7f2bfe6aef1b121639f474dc|Graphic Designer|184|84fcaed4efb510f5518998c1f00076e8d3794881|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.651456Z
Graphic Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I think I might have made a mistake on a file once, but I don't really remember the details. If something goes wrong, I usually just wait for someone to tell me, and then I fix it if I have to. Everyone makes mistakes sometimes, so it's not a big deal.|I once realized after submitting a project that I had used an outdated logo version. I immediately notified my project lead, explained the error, and provided the corrected file within twenty minutes. I also updated my personal asset library to ensure that only the current, approved logos were available for future use.|I made a typo in a final document once and didn't notice until it was already sent out. When my manager pointed it out, I felt really bad and fixed it right away. I apologized for the mistake and tried to be much more careful with my spelling on the next project.|Question intent check: \\nGood: Candidate takes full ownership of the mistake and acts quickly to minimize the impact on the team. They also show they learned a lesson to prevent future errors.\\nMid: Candidate admits to the mistake but only after it is discovered by someone else. They show remorse but don't demonstrate a proactive change in their workflow.\\nBad: Candidate downplays the mistake or fails to take any responsibility for it. They don't seem to understand the professional consequences of their errors.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response follows a clear 'discovery, action, and prevention' structure. It is easy to see how the candidate moved from identifying the problem to solving it.\\nMid: The response is mostly about the mistake itself and less about the p