'how' of the middle part. It feels like a very simple account of working hard.\\nBad: The response is disorganized and fails to provide any evidence of planning or scheduling. It reflects a very chaotic approach to work.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: Candidate mentions specific techniques like 'hourly milestones' and 'teammate dependencies'. This shows they have a sophisticated understanding of project management.\\nMid: Candidate provides only vague details about their work habits. They don't explain how they actually decided what to work on and when.\\nBad: Candidate provides no detail and seems proud of their lack of structure. This shows a lack of professional maturity and planning ability.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate's explanation is clear and professional. They sound like someone who is in control of their workload and can handle pressure well.\\nMid: The candidate sounds a bit overwhelmed by the situation they are describing. Their language is a bit repetitive and lacks professional polish.\\nBad: The candidate's language is unprofessional and suggests they are difficult to work with. They fail to communicate a respect for the project's timeline.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: Time management is essential in a role with multiple stakeholders and shifting deadlines. This shows the candidate is ready for a professional workload.\\nMid: The candidate can meet deadlines but might burn out or cause stress for the team. They would benefit from learning more formal prioritization techniques.\\nBad: The candidate's approach is incompatible with a professional environment. Their lack of respect for deadlines would cause major issues for the project team.|7|Tell me about how you managed your schedule when you had multiple project tasks due at the exact same time?|PASS|92|[\"Perfect structural compliance with all 5 rubric sections and mandatory Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"High-quality differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level detail.\", 