Graphic Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I just pick my favorite colors or whatever style I am interested in at the moment. I think the most important thing is that the project looks cool and reflects my personal style as a creator. I don't really think about the audience because I want my work to be unique.|I start by analyzing the target audience and the primary message the stakeholder wants to convey. For example, if the project needs to feel trustworthy, I might look into cooler blue tones and clean, traditional layouts. I then create a mood board to test these ideas before committing to a final visual direction for the project.|I usually look at what other people are doing for similar projects and try to do something that looks just as good. I pick colors that I think look nice together and that seem to fit the general vibe of the task. I sometimes ask a friend what they think about my choices.|Question intent check: \\nGood: Candidate demonstrates a goal-oriented and audience-focused approach to visual decisions. They use research and tools like mood boards to justify their creative choices.\\nMid: Candidate relies on intuition and imitation rather than a structured analysis of project goals. Their choices are acceptable but lack a strong strategic foundation.\\nBad: Candidate prioritizes personal preference over project requirements and audience needs. They show an ego-driven approach that is inappropriate for a professional role.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response moves logically from analysis (audience/message) to execution (color choice) to validation (mood boards). It shows a professional creative process.\\nMid: The response is a bit scattered and doesn't clearly show how the candidate gets from a goal to a final visual style. It feels more like a list of habits.\\nBad: The response has no structure and basically says 'I do what I want'. It fails to address the 'how' of the question in a professional way.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: Candidate explains the psychological or strategic reasoning behind their choices, such as using blue for trust. This shows they have mastered the fundamentals of their craft.\\nMid: Candidate gives very surface-level reasons for their choices. They don't show a deep understanding of why certain visual styles work better than others.\\nBad: Candidate provides no reasoning at all. They seem to view visual style as purely subjective and ignore the functional goals of the project.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate uses professional terminology accurately and explains their thoughts clearly. They sound like an expert in their junior-level domain.\\nMid: The candidate's language is a bit vague and informal. It is difficult to tell if they are making informed decisions or just guessing.\\nBad: The candidate's language is self-centered and unprofessional. They fail to communicate how their work serves the needs of the client or the project.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: This strategic approach to creative work is what separates a professional from a hobbyist. It shows the candidate can contribute meaningfully to the team's objectives.\\nMid: The candidate's approach is fine for simple tasks but might struggle with more complex briefs. They need more training on how to align visuals with business goals.\\nBad: The candidate's attitude would make them very difficult to work with on a professional team. They do not understand that their work must serve a specific purpose.|8|How do you go about selecting a visual style or color palette that aligns with the specific goals of a new project?|PASS|92|[\"Perfect structural compliance with all 5 rubric sections and mandatory Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"High-quality differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level detail.\", \"Questions are single interrogative sentences exceeding word count requirements.\", \"Rubrics consistently include the specific role title despite instructions to avoid it.\"]|c8ff19dfec325e8b700aa82285026e3019a896fa|7936bd65c41b9b1b7f2bfe6aef1b121639f474dc|Graphic Designer|187|84fcaed4efb510f5518998c1f00076e8d3794881|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.651456Z
Graphic Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I usually just save everything to my desktop while I'm working so I can find it quickly. I don't really have a naming system, I just name the files whatever comes to mind at the time. I've never really had a problem finding my own work before.|I use a consistent folder structure that separates raw assets, working files, and final exports. My naming convention always includes the project name, the date, and a version number, such as 'ProjectX_Logo_20231027_v01'. This ensures that anyone on the team can jump into my project and know exactly which file is the most recent.|I try to keep all my files for one project in the same folder so they don't get lost. I name the final files 'FINAL' so people know which one to use, but sometimes I end up with multiple versions called 'FINAL_v2' or 'FINAL_v3' which can be a bit confusing.|Question intent check: \\nGood: Candidate understands the importance of collaborative efficiency and technical organization. They use a systematic naming convention and folder structure that benefits the whole team.\\nMid: Candidate has a basic idea of organization but uses a system that is prone to errors (like multiple 'final' versions). They are organized enough to work alone but not well enough for a team.\\nBad: Candidate is completely disorganized and doesn't see the value in structured file management. Their habits would create significant friction for any team they join.\\n\\nStructure check: \\nGood: The response clearly describes the folder structure and provides a specific example of a naming convention. It is a very practical and clear answer.\\nMid: The response is a bit vague and doesn't give a clear example of what their file names actually look like. It sounds like they are still working on their system.\\nBad: The response is disorganized and basically admits to a lack of professional standards. It fails to answer the question in a meaningful way.\\n\\nDepth check: \\nGood: Candidate explains the 'why' behind their system—specifically mentioning version control and team accessibility. This shows professional foresight.\\nMid: Candidate provides very little detail about how they organize their work. They don't seem to have thought much about how their habits affect others.\\nBad: Candidate provides no detail and seems to think that personal convenience is more important than team organization. They show a lack of professional awareness.\\n\\nClarity check: \\nGood: The candidate's system is explained in a way that is easy to visualize and implement. The language is precise and professional.\\nMid: The candidate's explanation is a bit messy, mirroring their described file system. The language is informal and lacks clarity.\\nBad: The candidate's language is dismissive of the question. They fail to communicate any understanding of why file organization matters in a professional setting.\\n\\nRelevance to role: \\nGood: This is a vital skill for a junior professional who will be handing off files to seniors or other departments. It shows they are a 'clean' and efficient worker.\\nMid: The candidate's habits are acceptable but will likely cause minor issues for the team. They would need to be taught the company's specific standards immediately.\\nBad: The candidate's lack of organization is a significant liability. It suggests they would be difficult to collaborate with and would likely lose important work.|9|Could you explain the system you use for naming and organizing your project assets to ensure your team can find them easily?|PASS|92|[\"Perfect structural compliance with all 5 rubric sections and mandatory Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"High-quality differentiation in example answers with realistic junior-level detail.\", \"Questions are single interrogative sentences exceeding word count requirements.\", \"Rubrics consistently include the specific role title despite instructions to avoid it.\"]|c8ff19dfec325e8b700aa82285026e3019a896fa|7936bd65c41b9b1b7f2bfe6aef1b121639f474dc|Graphic Designer|188|84fcaed4efb510f5518998c1f00076e8d3794881|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:41:12.651456Z
