Logistics Coordinator|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I try to type very carefully the first time so that I don't have to spend a lot of time checking it later. Checking takes too long and I usually get it right anyway. If there is a mistake, someone will probably notice it eventually and let me know so I can fix it.|When I am finalizing records, I perform a side-by-side comparison between the original source data and my final entry. I check for common errors like transposed numbers or missing fields, and I always take a five-minute break before a final review to ensure I have fresh eyes. Finally, I use any built-in validation tools in the software to catch formatting issues.|I usually just read through the data one more time after I finish typing it to make sure it looks correct. If I see something that looks weird, I'll go back and check the original file. This usually catches most of the big mistakes before I send the sheet to my manager.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate has a defined, multi-step verification process that includes manual and tool-based checks. They show an awareness of human error and how to mitigate it. Mid: The candidate performs a basic review but lacks a structured methodology for finding errors. They rely on visual 'looks' rather than systematic verification. Bad: The candidate dismisses the importance of verification or expects others to catch their mistakes. This shows a lack of diligence and quality control. Structure check: Good: The answer is step-based and logical. It starts with comparison, moves to error-types, and ends with software validation. Mid: The answer is a single-step process that is only briefly explained. It doesn't show a clear workflow. Bad: The response is unstructured and defensive. It does not provide any actual steps for verification. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific techniques like the 'fresh eyes' approach and checking for specific error types. This shows practical experience and reasoning. Mid: The candidate provides very little detail about what they are actually looking for during their review. It is a generic 'I check it' response. Bad: The candidate provides no depth and seems to find the task of verification unimportant. Clarity check: Good: The explanation is very clear and uses terminology that suggests the candidate is familiar with data entry tasks. Mid: The response is clear enough to understand but lacks the precision of a professional workflow. Bad: The candidate is vague and doesn't clearly explain what they do. It's difficult to see if they have any real process at all. Relevance to role: Good: Accuracy is critical in junior roles, and this candidate shows they take it seriously. They demonstrate the habits of a reliable individual contributor. Mid: The candidate has the right idea but needs more training on formal quality control. They are likely to miss subtle errors. Bad: The candidate is not suitable for a role where data accuracy is important. Their attitude toward quality is poor.|4|Can you explain the steps you take to verify that internal records or data sheets are completely accurate before you finalize them?|PASS|94|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric section and internal labeling requirements (Good/Mid/Bad).\", \"Strong differentiation in answer examples across all performance levels.\", \"Questions are well-constructed single interrogative sentences aligned with junior scope.\", \"Rubrics include specific role titles instead of generic references.\"]|32e8a74141e42a85807240898640567c7293acb2|c05faaa870eaaced7b455f812554f4e4b8c42860|Logistics Coordinator|203|60790e6a4dea6364280bcc9a7f2456aef4b9f0a4|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:04.359858Z
Logistics Coordinator|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would just pick the task from the person I like the most and do that one first. I wouldn't say anything to the others because I don't want to start an argument about who is more important. If I can't finish them all, I'll just leave them for tomorrow and hope nobody gets too upset.|First, I would briefly review all three tasks to understand their scope and impact. I would then speak with each of the three people to clarify their specific deadlines and see if any task can be slightly reprioritized. If all remain urgent, I would ask my direct supervisor for guidance on which task is the highest priority for the team's overall goals.|I would try my best to work as fast as I could to finish all three tasks by the end of the day. If I saw that I was running out of time, I would tell the people who assigned them that I might be a little late. I'd probably just start with the easiest one first to get it out of the way.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates strong communication and prioritization skills. They know when to escalate to a supervisor and how to manage stakeholder expectations. Mid: The candidate tries to work hard but lacks a strategy for managing conflicting demands. They rely on speed rather than communication or smart prioritization. Bad: The candidate makes arbitrary decisions without communication. They avoid conflict in a way that creates more problems later. Structure check: Good: The answer follows a logical progression: assess, communicate, and escalate if needed. It is a standard professional approach to multitasking. Mid: The response is a bit reactive. It focuses on the 'work harder' aspect rather than the 'work smarter' aspect of the problem. Bad: The response is disorganized and suggests a lack of professional judgment. It doesn't offer a real solution to the conflict. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the reasoning behind checking with a supervisor and the stakeholders. They show an understanding of team goals. Mid: The candidate doesn't go into detail about how they would decide which task is most important. Their approach is very surface-level. Bad: The answer has no depth and ignores the reality of workplace constraints. Clarity check: Good: The candidate’s plan of action is very clear and easy to visualize. They use professional and proactive language. Mid: The response is clear enough, but it sounds a bit overwhelmed by the situation. Bad: The candidate’s explanation of their choice (picking the person they like) is unprofessional and confusing in a work context. Relevance to role: Good: This scenario is common for junior staff, and the good answer shows they can navigate it professionally. They demonstrate maturity and team-mindedness. Mid: The candidate is well-intentioned but may cause bottlenecks because they don't communicate priorities. They would need significant supervision. Bad: The candidate’s approach would lead to missed deadlines and confused stakeholders. This is a poor fit for a collaborative project environment.|5|What would you do if you were assigned three urgent tasks by different people that all needed to be completed by the end of the day?|PASS|94|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric section and internal labeling requirements (Good/Mid/Bad).\", \"Strong differentiation in answer examples across all performance levels.\", \"Questions are well-constructed single interrogative sentences aligned with junior scope.\", \"Rubrics include specific role titles instead of generic references.\"]|32e8a74141e42a85807240898640567c7293acb2|c05faaa870eaaced7b455f812554f4e4b8c42860|Logistics Coordinator|204|60790e6a4dea6364280bcc9a7f2456aef4b9f0a4|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:04.359858Z
Logistics Coordinator|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I don't like it when requirements change because it wastes all the work I already did. When it happened to me, I just kept working on the old version for a while because I thought it was better anyway. Eventually, I had to change it, but I was very unhappy about it and the result wasn't very good.|During a group presentation, our instructor changed the required format from a slide deck to a written report only two days before the due date. I immediately organized a brief meeting with my group to re-assign tasks based on writing strengths rather than design skills. We successfully pivoted and submitted a high-quality report by the original deadline.|A project I was on once had its goal changed halfway through by the client. It was frustrating, but I just stopped what I was doing and started working on the new requirements as quickly as I could. I had to stay late for a few nights, but I managed to get it done in the end.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows flexibility and the ability to reorganize work effectively under pressure. They focus on the solution rather than the frustration of the change. Mid: The candidate is willing to change but their response is reactive and lacks a strategic adjustment. They focus on effort (staying late) rather than planning. Bad: The candidate is resistant to change and shows a poor attitude. This indicates they would struggle in a dynamic work environment. Structure check: Good: The answer follows the STAR method well, providing a clear situation, task, action, and result. It highlights the candidate's leadership in the pivot. Mid: The response tells a story but skips over the specific actions taken to reorganize the work. It is a bit too focused on the result alone. Bad: The response is short and focuses mostly on the candidate's personal feelings. It does not provide a clear narrative of the event. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains how they reassessed the team's strengths to meet the new requirement. This shows an analytical approach to problem-solving. Mid: The candidate provides a simple 'I just did it' explanation. There is no reflection on how they managed the transition or what they learned. Bad: The answer lacks any detail and shows a lack of professional adaptability. Clarity check: Good: The language is professional and the scenario is clearly described. The candidate’s role as an organizer is evident. Mid: The response is clear but a little generic. It could apply to almost any situation involving extra work. Bad: The response is confusing and the candidate’s actions seem counter-productive to the project's success. Relevance to role: Good: Change is constant in many projects, and this answer shows the candidate can handle it gracefully. They are a resilient team member. Mid: The candidate can handle change but may need a lot of support to stay focused. They don't yet show the initiative to lead a pivot. Bad: The candidate's resistance to change is a red flag for any role that requires collaboration and adaptability.|6|Walk me through a time when a project requirement changed suddenly and how you adjusted your approach to meet the new goal?|PASS|94|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric section and internal labeling requirements (Good/Mid/Bad).\", \"Strong differentiation in answer examples across all performance levels.\", \"Questions are well-constructed single interrogative sentences aligned with junior scope.\", \"Rubrics include specific role titles instead of generic references.\"]|32e8a74141e42a85807240898640567c7293acb2|c05faaa870eaaced7b455f812554f4e4b8c42860|Logistics Coordinator|205|60790e6a4dea6364280bcc9a7f2456aef4b9f0a4|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:04.359858Z
Logistics Coordinator|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I usually try to avoid giving bad news because I don't want people to be mad at me. If something is going to be late, I just wait until the last minute and hope they don't notice, or I send an email right before I leave for the day. It's easier than dealing with an awkward conversation.|I had to tell a project lead that a task I was working on was going to be delayed by two days due to a software issue. I prepared by having a clear explanation of the problem and a revised timeline ready before I spoke to them. I delivered the news in person to ensure there were no misunderstandings and asked if the new date worked for the overall schedule.|I once had to tell a teammate that I couldn't help them with their part of a project because I was too busy with my own. I just sent them a quick message explaining my situation and told them I was sorry. They seemed to understand, and we didn't have any issues after that.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows honesty and preparation when communicating difficult news. They prioritize clarity and the needs of the stakeholder over their own comfort. Mid: The candidate communicates the news but does so in a way that might be too informal or lacks a solution. They focus on the 'telling' rather than the 'ensuring understanding' part. Bad: The candidate avoids communication or uses unprofessional tactics to delay the news. This suggests a lack of maturity and reliability. Structure check: Good: The answer shows preparation, the communication method, and the follow-up. It is a complete professional interaction. Mid: The answer describes a single action (sending a message) without much context or preparation. It's a very simple story. Bad: The response is vague and doesn't describe a successful communication event. It highlights a failure in professional conduct. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains why they chose a specific communication channel and how they prepared a solution beforehand. This shows high emotional intelligence. Mid: The candidate provides very little detail about the stakeholder's reaction or how they ensured the message was received correctly. Bad: The answer is extremely brief and lacks any professional substance. Clarity check: Good: The explanation is clear and professional. The candidate sounds confident in their ability to handle tough conversations. Mid: The response is understandable but lacks the professional polish of the 'good' example. The situation described is very minor. Bad: The response is confusing and reflects a poor communication style. Relevance to role: Good: Effective communication with stakeholders is vital for coordination roles. This candidate shows they can handle the pressure of reporting issues. Mid: The candidate can handle simple communication but may struggle with more high-stakes stakeholder management. Bad: The candidate's avoidance of bad news makes them a liability for any team project or client-facing role.|7|Explain a time when you had to relay difficult information to a stakeholder and how you ensured they understood the situation clearly?|PASS|94|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric section and internal labeling requirements (Good/Mid/Bad).\", \"Strong differentiation in answer examples across all performance levels.\", \"Questions are well-constructed single interrogative sentences aligned with junior scope.\", \"Rubrics include specific role titles instead of generic references.\"]|32e8a74141e42a85807240898640567c7293acb2|c05faaa870eaaced7b455f812554f4e4b8c42860|Logistics Coordinator|206|60790e6a4dea6364280bcc9a7f2456aef4b9f0a4|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:04.359858Z
Logistics Coordinator|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I don't really have a process for that because delays are usually someone else's fault. I just wait for the person to finish their work or I tell my boss that I'm waiting on them. There isn't much I can do if the workflow stops somewhere else.|When I notice a delay, I first review the project timeline to see exactly where the bottleneck started. I then check the communication logs and task status updates to see if there were any missing inputs or technical errors at that stage. Finally, I talk to the person responsible for that step to understand the context before proposing a fix to my supervisor.|If something is late, I usually just ask the person who was supposed to do it what happened. I listen to their explanation and then try to help them finish the task if I have time. This usually gets things moving again pretty quickly without much trouble.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate uses an analytical approach to find the root cause of an issue. They combine data review with interpersonal communication to get the full picture. Mid: The candidate relies entirely on others' explanations rather than investigating the process themselves. This is a reactive and less reliable way to solve problems. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of initiative and blames others for delays. They don't see themselves as part of the solution. Structure check: Good: The answer follows a clear 'assess, investigate, communicate, propose' structure. It is logical and professional. Mid: The response is simple and lacks a structured investigation. It's more of an informal reaction than a professional process. Bad: The response is disorganized and lacks any clear steps. It does not answer the 'how' of identifying a root cause. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific things they would check, like timelines and logs. This shows they understand the mechanics of project tracking. Mid: The candidate provides very little detail about how they would verify what they are told. They take information at face value. Bad: The answer has no depth and shows a lack of interest in process improvement. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's explanation is precise and uses professional terminology. Their role in the process is clear. Mid: The response is easy to understand but lacks the detail of a professional workflow. Bad: The response is vague and does not show a clear understanding of what a 'root cause' is. Relevance to role: Good: Identifying bottlenecks is a key skill for any execution-focused role. This candidate shows they can help keep projects on track. Mid: The candidate can help in simple situations but lacks the analytical skills for more complex coordination. Bad: The candidate is likely to let projects stall because they don't know how to troubleshoot delays.|8|Could you describe the process you follow to identify the root cause of a delay in a standard workflow or scheduled task?|PASS|94|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric section and internal labeling requirements (Good/Mid/Bad).\", \"Strong differentiation in answer examples across all performance levels.\", \"Questions are well-constructed single interrogative sentences aligned with junior scope.\", \"Rubrics include specific role titles instead of generic references.\"]|32e8a74141e42a85807240898640567c7293acb2|c05faaa870eaaced7b455f812554f4e4b8c42860|Logistics Coordinator|207|60790e6a4dea6364280bcc9a7f2456aef4b9f0a4|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:04.359858Z
Logistics Coordinator|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I don't really have a special method for that because I've always been good at typing. I trust that my first version is correct most of the time. If there is an error, I can always fix it later if someone points it out to me.|I use a 'self-audit' method where I complete a batch of data and then review it against the source document after a short break to reset my focus. I also use Excel's conditional formatting to highlight potential outliers or duplicate entries automatically. This two-step process helps me catch both manual typos and logical errors.|I just try to be very slow and careful while I'm typing so that I don't make many mistakes. Then I scroll through the finished file to see if anything looks wrong or if I missed a row. It's a simple way to check my work before I hand it in.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate uses a structured approach combining manual review with technical tools. They understand the value of a 'reset' break to maintain high accuracy. Mid: The candidate has a basic check but it is unstructured and relies on 'looking' rather than 'verifying'. They are likely to miss small but important errors. Bad: The candidate is overconfident and lacks a quality control process. This is a high-risk approach for any role involving data. Structure check: Good: The answer describes a clear two-step process (manual audit and tool-based validation). It is organized and easy to follow. Mid: The response is a single, vague step. It doesn't show a clear beginning or end to the quality check. Bad: The response is unstructured and dismissive of the need for a process. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains 'why' they take a break and 'how' they use specific tools like conditional formatting. This shows real-world experience. Mid: The candidate provides no detail on what they are looking for during their review. It's a very surface-level answer. Bad: The response lacks any detail or professional substance. Clarity check: Good: The language is clear and the candidate’s workflow is easy to replicate. They sound very reliable. Mid: The response is understandable but lacks the professional tone of a high-quality candidate. Bad: The candidate sounds unprofessional and their lack of a process is concerning. Relevance to role: Good: Data integrity is vital for junior roles, and this candidate shows they have the necessary discipline. They are a safe hire for detail-oriented tasks. Mid: The candidate has the right intentions but needs more training on formal verification methods. They may be prone to fatigue-based errors. Bad: The candidate's lack of focus on accuracy makes them a poor fit for a role that relies on correct documentation.|9|What methods do you use to double-check your data entry work to ensure that errors are caught before they impact the next stage?|PASS|94|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric section and internal labeling requirements (Good/Mid/Bad).\", \"Strong differentiation in answer examples across all performance levels.\", \"Questions are well-constructed single interrogative sentences aligned with junior scope.\", \"Rubrics include specific role titles instead of generic references.\"]|32e8a74141e42a85807240898640567c7293acb2|c05faaa870eaaced7b455f812554f4e4b8c42860|Logistics Coordinator|208|60790e6a4dea6364280bcc9a7f2456aef4b9f0a4|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:04.359858Z
Logistics Coordinator|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would probably just wait until the supervisor becomes available again because I don't want to do the task wrong. It's not my fault the instructions were vague, so it's better to just wait. I might work on other things, but I wouldn't touch that task until I get more help.|I would first look for any existing documentation or past examples of similar tasks to see if I could find a template. I would then draft a brief outline of how I plan to complete the task and send it to the supervisor via email, so they can see my progress when they return. This allows me to keep moving forward while providing a chance for them to course-correct me later.|I would ask a more senior teammate if they knew what the supervisor wanted me to do. If they weren't sure either, I would just try my best to do what I think is right based on the little bit of info I have. I'd rather do something than nothing while I wait for them to come back.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows initiative and problem-solving skills when faced with ambiguity. They use resources (documentation) and proactive communication (the outline) to manage the situation. Mid: The candidate shows some initiative by asking others, but their fallback is to 'guess' rather than use a structured approach. They are a bit too reliant on others. Bad: The candidate stops working and waits for direction, which shows a lack of independence and poor time management. Structure check: Good: The answer follows a logical sequence: research, plan, and communicate. It shows a professional way to handle a common workplace challenge. Mid: The response is a bit reactive. It focuses on asking for help rather than trying to figure it out independently first. Bad: The response is disorganized and suggests a passive attitude toward work. It doesn't offer a constructive solution. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the reasoning behind sending an email outline—to show progress and allow for future correction. This shows foresight. Mid: The candidate doesn't explain how they would decide what is 'right' if they have to guess. There is no mention of using project resources. Bad: The answer has no depth and ignores the responsibility of a junior employee to be productive. Clarity check: Good: The candidate’s plan of action is very clear and professional. They sound like a self-starter. Mid: The response is clear but sounds a bit uncertain about the best way to handle the problem. Bad: The candidate’s explanation is clear but reflects a poor work ethic and a lack of accountability. Relevance to role: Good: Junior roles often involve some ambiguity, and this answer shows the candidate can handle it without being paralyzed. They demonstrate a high level of professional maturity. Mid: The candidate can function with some ambiguity but will likely require a lot of support from their peers. They aren't quite ready to work independently. Bad: The candidate's tendency to stall when instructions are unclear is a major drawback for any role requiring task completion and coordination.|10|How would you handle a situation where a supervisor gave you a task with very vague instructions and then became unavailable for questions?|PASS|94|[\"Perfect adherence to rubric section and internal labeling requirements (Good/Mid/Bad).\", \"Strong differentiation in answer examples across all performance levels.\", \"Questions are well-constructed single interrogative sentences aligned with junior scope.\", \"Rubrics include specific role titles instead of generic references.\"]|32e8a74141e42a85807240898640567c7293acb2|c05faaa870eaaced7b455f812554f4e4b8c42860|Logistics Coordinator|209|60790e6a4dea6364280bcc9a7f2456aef4b9f0a4|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:04.359858Z
Environmental Sustainability Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I had a teammate who didn't like my ideas, so I just decided to work on my part of the task alone. We didn't really talk much after that, but we both turned in our separate sections to the lead. It was easier to just avoid the conflict than to try and convince them that my way was right.|During a recent group project, a teammate and I disagreed on how to categorize our collected data. I suggested we sit down and review the project guidelines together to see which method aligned best with our goals. By having a calm discussion and focusing on the shared objective, we agreed on a hybrid approach that satisfied both of our concerns and improved the project's accuracy.|I once had a disagreement with a coworker about our meeting schedule because we were both very busy. We talked about it for a few minutes and decided to just meet every other day instead of every day. It wasn't the perfect solution, but it allowed us to finish the work we needed to do for the project.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate identifies that the question evaluates their conflict resolution skills and emotional intelligence. They show a desire to maintain a productive team environment. Mid: The candidate identifies the question is about a disagreement but focuses mostly on the problem. They do not fully explain the importance of reaching a mutual understanding. Bad: The candidate does not see the value in resolving conflicts effectively. They describe a situation where they either ignored the issue or let it fester without action. Structure check: Good: The response follows the STAR method by providing context, action, and a clear result. This makes the narrative easy for the interviewer to follow. Mid: The response has some structure but lacks a clear result or takeaway. The transition between the conflict and the solution is somewhat abrupt. Bad: The response is disorganized and lacks a clear beginning or end. It is difficult to determine what steps were actually taken to address the situation. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about the conversation and the logic behind their actions. They show a high level of reflection on the experience. Mid: The candidate provides some details but keeps the explanation at a very high level. They do not provide enough information to understand the nuances of the situation. Bad: The response is very brief and lacks any meaningful detail. It provides a generic summary without any specific examples of behavior. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses professional language and communicates their thoughts without confusion. The logic of their decision-making is clearly presented. Mid: The candidate is mostly clear but uses some vague phrasing or filler words. A few parts of the story require additional clarification to be understood. Bad: The response is confusing and uses inconsistent logic throughout the story. The interviewer is left with many unanswered questions about what happened. Relevance to role: Good: This response demonstrates the level of maturity expected from a junior professional in a collaborative project. They show they can work well within a team structure. Mid: This response shows that the candidate can function in a team but may need help with interpersonal dynamics. They are at an acceptable but not advanced level for a junior. Bad: This response suggests that the candidate may be a difficult teammate to work with on a project. They do not show the necessary skills to handle common professional disagreements.|1|Can you tell me about a time you had a disagreement with a teammate and how you worked to resolve it?|PASS|92|[\"Rubrics correctly include all five required sections and internal performance labels.\", \"Questions are high-quality, single-sentence interrogatives with junior-level scope.\", \"Strong, actionable differentiation between performance levels in all example answers.\", \"The role acronym appears in multiple rubric sections, violating a negative constraint.\"]|fc911f5e7cfb5dab5f5cb446bb2e6612e2c7478f|a9ecc418c6b61cb241a9209078fb2798a5aac9e9|Environmental Sustainability Analyst|210|9427309006e3a4ddb04e96d8baadc68df849466a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:05.527110Z
Environmental Sustainability Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I made a mistake on a project once, but I didn't tell anyone because I was worried I would get in trouble. I just hoped that nobody would notice the error in the final document. Eventually, I think someone else fixed it later on, so it didn't really cause any major problems for the team.|In my last internship, I accidentally sent an internal draft of a report to a client before it was finalized. As soon as I realized the error, I contacted my supervisor to explain what happened and then sent a follow-up email to the client with the correct version and a professional apology. I then created a checklist for myself to ensure all future external communications are double-checked before being sent.|I once made a mistake on a calculation in a spreadsheet which led to some slightly incorrect results in a team meeting. I pointed out the error once I found it and fixed the numbers in the master file later that afternoon. My manager was okay with it because the error wasn't very big and didn't change the main outcome.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates accountability and a growth mindset by taking ownership of their errors. They show they are focused on both immediate correction and long-term prevention. Mid: The candidate admits to the mistake but shows a more reactive approach to the situation. They fix the problem but do not demonstrate a strong focus on learning from the experience. Bad: The candidate avoids responsibility or tries to hide their errors from the team. This indicates a lack of professional integrity and a fear of feedback. Structure check: Good: The candidate clearly outlines the mistake, their immediate reaction, and the preventive measures taken. The flow of the story is logical and easy to understand. Mid: The candidate describes the mistake and the fix but skips over the reasoning or the outcome. The structure is functional but lacks a compelling narrative arc. Bad: The response is fragmented and does not provide a clear sequence of events. It is hard to tell exactly what happened or how the situation was resolved. Depth check: Good: The response includes specific details about the nature of the mistake and the communication involved. It shows a high level of self-awareness and professional maturity. Mid: The response is somewhat generic and lacks the detail needed to fully assess the candidate's judgment. The explanation of the fix is surface-level. Bad: The candidate provides a very short answer that lacks any real substance. There is no reflection on the impact of the mistake or what was learned. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains the situation using clear, professional language. Their communication style is transparent and easy for the listener to follow. Mid: The candidate's explanation is mostly clear but could benefit from more precise language. Some parts of the explanation are a bit vague or repetitive. Bad: The response is muddled and difficult to follow. The candidate fails to communicate the severity of the mistake or the logic of their response. Relevance to role: Good: This response shows the candidate has the integrity and problem-solving skills needed for a junior role. They are capable of handling setbacks professionally. Mid: This response suggests the candidate is a reliable worker but may need encouragement to take full ownership. They meet basic expectations for a junior employee. Bad: This response indicates the candidate is not yet ready for the responsibilities of a professional project. Their lack of transparency is a significant concern.|2|Could you describe a situation where you made a mistake at work or on a project and the steps you took to correct it?|PASS|92|[\"Rubrics correctly include all five required sections and internal performance labels.\", \"Questions are high-quality, single-sentence interrogatives with junior-level scope.\", \"Strong, actionable differentiation between performance levels in all example answers.\", \"The role acronym appears in multiple rubric sections, violating a negative constraint.\"]|fc911f5e7cfb5dab5f5cb446bb2e6612e2c7478f|a9ecc418c6b61cb241a9209078fb2798a5aac9e9|Environmental Sustainability Analyst|211|9427309006e3a4ddb04e96d8baadc68df849466a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:05.527110Z
Environmental Sustainability Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I don't really have a specific process for checking the data because I assume that the people who provided it already checked it. I just take the files I am given and copy the information directly into the report template. This allows me to finish my reports much faster than if I double-checked everything.|I always start by verifying the source of the data to ensure it is from a credible and up-to-date provider. Next, I perform a range check in my spreadsheet to identify any extreme outliers or impossible values that might indicate an entry error. Finally, I perform a manual spot check of about ten percent of the records against the raw source files to confirm everything was imported correctly.|I usually look through the dataset to see if any numbers look obviously wrong or out of place. If I see something strange, I try to find where it came from and fix it before I put it into the final report. I mostly rely on my own experience to tell if the data looks like it makes sense.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a systematic approach to quality control and understands the importance of data integrity. They demonstrate a proactive attitude toward preventing reporting errors. Mid: The candidate understands that data should be checked but lacks a formal or thorough methodology. They rely more on intuition than on structured validation steps. Bad: The candidate shows a disregard for data accuracy and quality. They do not understand the risks associated with publishing unverified information. Structure check: Good: The response is organized into clear, sequential steps that outline a logical workflow. The candidate uses transition words to guide the listener through their process. Mid: The response lists a few actions but does not present them as a coherent or repeatable process. The structure is a bit loose and harder to follow. Bad: The response is a single statement that lacks any procedural structure. It does not provide any insight into how the candidate actually performs the work. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific techniques like range checks and spot checks. They provide enough detail to show they have practical experience with data validation. Mid: The candidate gives a general overview of their approach but lacks specific examples of techniques. The response is a bit too high-level for a technical workflow question. Bad: The response is extremely brief and provides no technical or procedural detail. It suggests a lack of experience or interest in the fundamental tasks of the job. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their technical process in simple, clear terms that are easy to understand. They avoid unnecessary jargon while remaining professional. Mid: The candidate's explanation is mostly clear but could be more concise. Some parts of the process are described in a way that is a bit confusing. Bad: The response is vague and does not clearly state what the candidate actually does. The language is unprofessional or overly simplistic for a technical task. Relevance to role: Good: This response demonstrates that the candidate has the attention to detail required for the project. They show they can be trusted with sensitive data tasks. Mid: This response suggests the candidate can perform basic tasks but may require additional training on quality standards. They are at an entry-level stage of development. Bad: This response indicates that the candidate's work may be unreliable and could lead to errors. They do not demonstrate the necessary professional habits for this type of work.|3|Can you walk me through the steps you take to ensure the accuracy and reliability of data before you include it in a final report?|PASS|92|[\"Rubrics correctly include all five required sections and internal performance labels.\", \"Questions are high-quality, single-sentence interrogatives with junior-level scope.\", \"Strong, actionable differentiation between performance levels in all example answers.\", \"The role acronym appears in multiple rubric sections, violating a negative constraint.\"]|fc911f5e7cfb5dab5f5cb446bb2e6612e2c7478f|a9ecc418c6b61cb241a9209078fb2798a5aac9e9|Environmental Sustainability Analyst|212|9427309006e3a4ddb04e96d8baadc68df849466a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:05.527110Z
Environmental Sustainability Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I just put all of my notes and the raw data tables into a single document and send it over as soon as I am done. I think it is better to give the stakeholders all the information I have so they can decide for themselves what is important. I don't really worry about the formatting as long as the data is there.|I begin by identifying the three most important takeaways from my research to ensure the core message is clear. I then use a standardized template with clear headings, bulleted lists for key data points, and a brief executive summary at the top. This structure allows a stakeholder to quickly grasp the essential information even if they only have a few minutes to read.|I usually write a few paragraphs about what I found and put the most important chart at the beginning of the page. I try to keep the language simple so that anyone can read it, and I make sure to include a concluding sentence at the end. It's a pretty basic document, but it usually gets the point across to the team.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate understands that the goal of documentation is to communicate insights effectively to an audience. They prioritize clarity and ease of use for the reader. Mid: The candidate focuses on the act of writing rather than the goal of communication. They show a basic understanding of formatting but don't consider the user's needs as much. Bad: The candidate does not understand the purpose of a summary document. They believe that providing raw information is the same as providing an analysis. Structure check: Good: The response describes a clear, logical method for building a document. The candidate explains why they choose specific structural elements like headings or summaries. Mid: The response mentions a few things they do when writing but doesn't present a cohesive strategy. The structure of the answer is a bit disorganized. Bad: The response lacks any sense of structure or organization. It suggests a chaotic approach to one of the primary tasks of the job profile. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific examples of how they organize content, such as using executive summaries and bullet points. They show they have thought about the psychology of the reader. Mid: The candidate gives a surface-level explanation of their writing process. They mention basic tools but don't explain the reasoning behind their choices. Bad: The response is very short and contains no detail about the candidate's actual workflow. It provides no evidence of competence in professional writing. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's explanation is highly clear and uses professional terminology appropriately. Their response is a good example of the clear communication they are describing. Mid: The candidate is mostly clear but uses some repetitive language. The response is understandable but not particularly articulate or polished. Bad: The response is vague and difficult to interpret. The candidate fails to explain their process in a way that would give an interviewer confidence in their skills. Relevance to role: Good: This response shows the candidate is ready to contribute meaningful reports to the project. They demonstrate the communication skills necessary for a junior professional. Mid: This response suggests the candidate can handle basic documentation tasks but may need templates or guidance. They show potential but lack a refined approach. Bad: This response indicates a lack of readiness for professional reporting. Their approach to documentation would likely create more work for senior team members.|4|Could you explain how you organize your findings into a summary document so that stakeholders can easily understand the main points?|PASS|92|[\"Rubrics correctly include all five required sections and internal performance labels.\", \"Questions are high-quality, single-sentence interrogatives with junior-level scope.\", \"Strong, actionable differentiation between performance levels in all example answers.\", \"The role acronym appears in multiple rubric sections, violating a negative constraint.\"]|fc911f5e7cfb5dab5f5cb446bb2e6612e2c7478f|a9ecc418c6b61cb241a9209078fb2798a5aac9e9|Environmental Sustainability Analyst|213|9427309006e3a4ddb04e96d8baadc68df849466a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:05.527110Z
Environmental Sustainability Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would stop working on the task and wait until the project lead was available again so I could get more clarification. I don't want to waste my time doing something that might be completely wrong. I would just work on my other assignments until I could get a better set of instructions from my supervisor.|If I received a vague task, I would first look through our internal project archives to see if a similar task had been completed in the past. If that didn't help, I would write down a list of my assumptions and a proposed plan of action, then share it with a senior teammate for a quick sanity check. This allows me to keep making progress while ensuring I am not heading in the wrong direction.|I would probably just start working on the task based on what I think the lead wanted me to do. If I got stuck, I would try to ask another peer if they knew what was going on or if they had more information. I would try my best to finish it, and if it was wrong, I would just fix it later when the lead came back.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates initiative and the ability to work through ambiguity without becoming paralyzed. They show they can use available resources to solve problems independently. Mid: The candidate shows a willingness to work but relies mostly on guesswork. They demonstrate some initiative but lack a structured approach to verifying their assumptions. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of initiative and a dependency on constant supervision. They are unable to make progress without explicit, detailed instructions at every step. Structure check: Good: The response follows a logical progression of steps, from researching resources to seeking peer feedback. The candidate explains the 'why' behind each action they take. Mid: The response lists a few possible actions but doesn't present them as a coherent plan. The logic is a bit reactive rather than proactive. Bad: The response is a single, negative decision that lacks any procedural logic. It does not offer a constructive solution to the problem presented. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific strategies like checking archives and documenting assumptions. This shows they have a toolkit for handling workplace uncertainty. Mid: The candidate's answer is a bit generic and doesn't provide many details on how they would actually handle the ambiguity. It is a safe but unremarkable response. Bad: The response lacks any detail or reflection on the situation. It indicates a very passive approach to professional responsibilities and challenges. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their thought process clearly and professionally. They communicate a sense of competence and reliability in their answer. Mid: The candidate is mostly clear but their response is a bit brief. They could have provided more detail on how they would evaluate their own progress. Bad: The response is vague and doesn't clearly state a plan of action. The candidate's lack of clarity mirrors their struggle with the hypothetical vague task. Relevance to role: Good: This response shows the candidate is a self-starter who can thrive in a typical fast-paced team environment. They are well-suited for a junior role with some autonomy. Mid: This response suggests the candidate is a steady worker but may require more hands-on management. They are capable of basic tasks but might struggle with complex ambiguity. Bad: This response indicates that the candidate would likely struggle in a professional setting where instructions are not always perfect. They show a lack of the adaptability required for the job.|5|How would you proceed if a project lead gave you a task with very vague instructions and then became unavailable for questions?|PASS|92|[\"Rubrics correctly include all five required sections and internal performance labels.\", \"Questions are high-quality, single-sentence interrogatives with junior-level scope.\", \"Strong, actionable differentiation between performance levels in all example answers.\", \"The role acronym appears in multiple rubric sections, violating a negative constraint.\"]|fc911f5e7cfb5dab5f5cb446bb2e6612e2c7478f|a9ecc418c6b61cb241a9209078fb2798a5aac9e9|Environmental Sustainability Analyst|214|9427309006e3a4ddb04e96d8baadc68df849466a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:05.527110Z
Environmental Sustainability Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I usually just tell people that my way is the standard way of doing things because I have more experience in that area. I don't really like to argue with people, so if they don't listen, I just do my part of the work my way and let them do their part their way. We usually just merge the work at the end.|During a data collection phase, a peer wanted to record notes manually on paper. I explained that using a shared digital document would allow us to analyze the data in real-time and reduce the chance of losing information. I showed them how the mobile app worked, and once they saw it saved time, they were happy to switch to my digital approach.|I once worked with a student who wanted to use a different software than the one I preferred for our project. I told them that I was already very good at using my software and that it would be faster for both of us if we just used that one. They eventually agreed because they didn't have a strong preference either way.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate understands that persuasion is about demonstrating value and building consensus. They show they can use logic and evidence to influence others positively. Mid: The candidate sees persuasion as a matter of convenience or personal preference. They focus more on getting their way than on what is best for the project. Bad: The candidate does not understand how to influence others or lacks the desire to collaborate on a unified approach. They show a tendency toward working in silos. Structure check: Good: The response identifies the conflicting ideas, the reasoning used for the change, and the final positive outcome. It is a well-structured narrative of professional influence. Mid: The response describes a situation where they got their way but doesn't clearly explain the process of persuasion. The structure is simple and lacks detail. Bad: The response is disorganized and does not show a clear resolution. It suggests a lack of skill in navigating interpersonal dynamics on a team. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific reasons for their approach and describes the peer's reaction. This level of detail shows a high degree of social awareness and tactical thinking. Mid: The candidate's explanation is surface-level and lacks specific details about the conversation. It shows they can communicate but not necessarily persuade effectively. Bad: The response is very brief and provides no insight into the candidate's communication style. It lacks any evidence of a successful professional interaction. Clarity check: Good: The candidate communicates their ideas with professional clarity. The logic of their persuasion is easy for the interviewer to understand and evaluate. Mid: The candidate is mostly clear but uses some informal language. The response is easy to follow but lacks the polish of a strong professional answer. Bad: The response is confusing and fails to explain how the candidate actually convinced their peer. The interviewer is left with a poor impression of the candidate's communication skills. Relevance to role: Good: This response demonstrates the communication and teamwork skills necessary for a successful junior professional. They show they can lead from within a peer group. Mid: This response suggests the candidate can work with others but may rely on seniority or ease rather than logic to influence peers. They meet basic entry-level standards. Bad: This response indicates that the candidate may struggle to integrate into a team that requires shared workflows. Their lack of collaborative spirit is a concern for the project.|6|Can you tell me about a time you had to convince a peer to adopt your approach to a task instead of their own?|PASS|92|[\"Rubrics correctly include all five required sections and internal performance labels.\", \"Questions are high-quality, single-sentence interrogatives with junior-level scope.\", \"Strong, actionable differentiation between performance levels in all example answers.\", \"The role acronym appears in multiple rubric sections, violating a negative constraint.\"]|fc911f5e7cfb5dab5f5cb446bb2e6612e2c7478f|a9ecc418c6b61cb241a9209078fb2798a5aac9e9|Environmental Sustainability Analyst|215|9427309006e3a4ddb04e96d8baadc68df849466a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:05.527110Z
Environmental Sustainability Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|When my project goals changed, I was very frustrated because I had already done a lot of work that was now useless. I kept working on the old goal for a few more days just to finish what I started before I finally moved on to the new task. It took me a long time to catch up with the rest of the team.|Halfway through a research project, the client decided they wanted to focus on a different geographic region than we had originally planned. I immediately paused my current data search, reorganized my folders to separate the old files, and created a new research plan for the new region. This allowed me to pivot quickly without losing any of the work I had already done.|My manager once told me that the deadline for a report was moved up by three days, so I had to work faster to finish it. I spent a few extra hours in the office that week and focused only on the most important parts of the document. I managed to get it done on time, even though it was a bit stressful for me.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates adaptability and a professional attitude toward shifting priorities. They show they can manage their emotions and reorganize their work efficiently. Mid: The candidate shows they can react to change but lacks a proactive strategy for managing it. They focus more on the effort required than on the process of adjusting. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of flexibility and a resistance to change. They demonstrate an inability to prioritize the needs of the project over their own personal frustrations. Structure check: Good: The response clearly outlines the change, the candidate's immediate organizational response, and the final outcome. It shows a logical approach to a disruptive event. Mid: The response describes the change and the fact that they worked harder, but doesn't explain how they reorganized their task load. The structure is a bit simplistic. Bad: The response focuses on the candidate's feelings rather than their actions. It lacks a clear sequence of events and does not show a successful resolution. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific actions like reorganizing folders and creating a new plan. This shows they have a structured way of thinking about project management. Mid: The candidate provides some general details about working more hours but doesn't describe any specific changes in their workflow. The answer is somewhat lacking in substance. Bad: The response is very short and provides no detail about how the candidate actually handled the change. It suggests a lack of experience with professional project environments. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains the situation and their response in clear, professional language. They communicate their ability to remain calm and focused under pressure. Mid: The candidate's explanation is mostly clear but a bit repetitive. They could have been more concise in describing their reaction to the change. Bad: The response is muddled and focuses on irrelevant details. The candidate fails to communicate a clear plan or a positive professional attitude. Relevance to role: Good: This response shows the candidate has the resilience and organizational skills needed for a dynamic work environment. They are well-prepared for the realities of the job. Mid: This response suggests the candidate can handle change but may find it stressful or difficult to manage independently. They meet the basic requirements for a junior role. Bad: This response indicates that the candidate may have difficulty keeping up with the changing needs of a project. Their lack of adaptability would be a hindrance to the team.|7|Could you describe a time when a project goal changed suddenly and how you adjusted your work to meet the new requirement?|PASS|92|[\"Rubrics correctly include all five required sections and internal performance labels.\", \"Questions are high-quality, single-sentence interrogatives with junior-level scope.\", \"Strong, actionable differentiation between performance levels in all example answers.\", \"The role acronym appears in multiple rubric sections, violating a negative constraint.\"]|fc911f5e7cfb5dab5f5cb446bb2e6612e2c7478f|a9ecc418c6b61cb241a9209078fb2798a5aac9e9|Environmental Sustainability Analyst|216|9427309006e3a4ddb04e96d8baadc68df849466a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:05.527110Z
Environmental Sustainability Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I don't really have a specific process for finding trends because I think the data usually speaks for itself. I just look through the rows of numbers until I see something that looks interesting or different from the rest. I don't think it is necessary to use complex tools or charts for basic analysis tasks.|I start by cleaning the data to remove duplicates and errors, then I use pivot tables in Excel to group the data by different time periods or categories. After that, I create line graphs to visualize the changes over time and calculate the percentage change between key dates. This helps me identify the most significant trends that need to be highlighted in my final summary.|I usually look at the data in a spreadsheet and try to sort the columns to see which numbers are the highest and lowest. I might make a few charts to see if there is a pattern that stands out to me. Once I find a trend, I write it down and show it to my team to see if they agree with my findings.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows they have a logical and repeatable process for data analysis. They understand that analysis involves both preparation and visualization to find meaningful insights. Mid: The candidate has a basic understanding of analysis but relies more on unstructured observation than on a defined workflow. They show a limited use of analytical tools. Bad: The candidate lacks a fundamental understanding of how to perform quantitative analysis. They do not value the use of systematic methods or tools to ensure accuracy. Structure check: Good: The candidate provides a step-by-step explanation of their workflow, from cleaning to visualization and reporting. This shows they have a structured way of approaching their work. Mid: The candidate mentions a few things they do with data but doesn't present them as a coherent process. The response is a bit fragmented and harder to follow logically. Bad: The response is a single statement that lacks any sense of procedure. It does not provide any information about how the candidate actually performs an analysis task. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific tools like pivot tables and line graphs and explains why they use them. This demonstrates a practical, junior-level technical competency. Mid: The candidate's explanation is very high-level and lacks specific details about the methods they use. It is a safe but unremarkable answer that doesn't show much technical depth. Bad: The response is extremely brief and provides no technical or procedural detail. It suggests a lack of experience or interest in the analytical core of the job. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's explanation is very clear and uses professional terminology appropriately. They describe their technical process in a way that is easy for a non-expert to follow. Mid: The candidate's explanation is mostly clear but uses some vague phrasing. Some parts of the process are described in a way that is a bit confusing or redundant. Bad: The response is vague and doesn't clearly state what the candidate actually does. The language is unprofessional or overly simplistic for a technical task. Relevance to role: Good: This response shows the candidate has the fundamental analytical skills required for the project. They can be trusted to handle basic data tasks with minimal supervision. Mid: This response suggests the candidate can perform simple analyses but may need guidance on more complex datasets. They are at an acceptable entry-level stage. Bad: This response indicates that the candidate's analytical work may be unreliable or lack depth. They do not demonstrate the necessary technical habits for this role.|8|Can you walk me through your process for performing a quantitative analysis on a new dataset to identify trends or patterns?|PASS|92|[\"Rubrics correctly include all five required sections and internal performance labels.\", \"Questions are high-quality, single-sentence interrogatives with junior-level scope.\", \"Strong, actionable differentiation between performance levels in all example answers.\", \"The role acronym appears in multiple rubric sections, violating a negative constraint.\"]|fc911f5e7cfb5dab5f5cb446bb2e6612e2c7478f|a9ecc418c6b61cb241a9209078fb2798a5aac9e9|Environmental Sustainability Analyst|217|9427309006e3a4ddb04e96d8baadc68df849466a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:05.527110Z
Environmental Sustainability Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I just use the examples from old projects that we have done in the past because I assume the standards haven't changed much since then. It is much faster to copy what has already been approved than to spend time searching for new rules every time. I only look for new guidelines if someone tells me I have to.|I always begin by searching official government or industry body websites to ensure I am looking at the most current version of any regulations. I then cross-reference these with our internal project wiki and check with a senior teammate to verify my interpretation. This three-step process ensures that my work is always compliant with the latest standards and internal expectations.|I usually search for the specific guidelines on the internet and download the most recent PDF that looks like it is from an official source. I try to read through the main sections to see how they apply to my current project. If I am really unsure about something, I might ask a coworker for help with the document.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate understands the importance of working with accurate and current information. They show a proactive and thorough approach to research and compliance. Mid: The candidate shows a basic awareness of the need for standards but has a less rigorous process for verifying their information. They rely on single sources or past experience. Bad: The candidate shows a disregard for professional standards and a lack of diligence in their research. They are willing to use outdated information to save time. Structure check: Good: The response describes a clear, multi-step process for finding and verifying information. The candidate explains why they include each step in their research workflow. Mid: The response mentions a few things they do when researching but doesn't present a cohesive strategy. The structure of the answer is a bit disorganized. Bad: The response lacks any sense of structure or organization. It suggests a lazy or haphazard approach to an important professional responsibility. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific types of sources like government websites and internal wikis. They show they understand the difference between finding information and verifying it. Mid: The candidate's explanation is surface-level and doesn't provide many details on how they ensure the information they find is correct. It is a basic, functional answer. Bad: The response is very short and provides no detail about the candidate's actual research habits. It provides no evidence of competence in information management. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their research process in clear, professional language. Their response is easy to follow and gives the interviewer confidence in their work habits. Mid: The candidate is mostly clear but uses some repetitive language. The response is understandable but lacks the polish of a strong professional answer. Bad: The response is vague and difficult to interpret. The candidate fails to explain their process in a way that would give an interviewer confidence in their skills. Relevance to role: Good: This response shows the candidate has the research skills and attention to detail necessary for the project. They demonstrate the professionalism required for a junior role. Mid: This response suggests the candidate can perform basic research but may need guidance on which sources are the most reliable. They show potential but need some training. Bad: This response indicates a lack of readiness for professional tasks. Their approach to research would likely lead to errors or compliance issues for the team.|9|How do you go about finding and verifying the current standards or guidelines relevant to a specific technical task you are assigned?|PASS|92|[\"Rubrics correctly include all five required sections and internal performance labels.\", \"Questions are high-quality, single-sentence interrogatives with junior-level scope.\", \"Strong, actionable differentiation between performance levels in all example answers.\", \"The role acronym appears in multiple rubric sections, violating a negative constraint.\"]|fc911f5e7cfb5dab5f5cb446bb2e6612e2c7478f|a9ecc418c6b61cb241a9209078fb2798a5aac9e9|Environmental Sustainability Analyst|218|9427309006e3a4ddb04e96d8baadc68df849466a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:05.527110Z
Environmental Sustainability Analyst|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would just pick the task that I find more interesting or easier to finish and focus all of my energy on that one first. I wouldn't say anything to the other manager because I don't want to admit that I can't handle the workload. I would just turn in the other task whenever I eventually find the time to finish it.|I would first review the requirements for both tasks to estimate how long each will take to complete. Then, I would speak with both project managers together to explain the conflict and ask which task should take ultimate priority based on the team's goals. This transparent communication allows me to manage my time effectively while ensuring the most critical work is finished first.|I would try to work on both tasks at the same time and see if I can get them both done by the end of the day. If I realize I can't finish them, I would send an email to both managers letting them know that I am struggling to meet the deadline. I would hope that one of them would offer me an extension on my work.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates strong communication and prioritization skills. They show they understand how to manage stakeholder expectations in a professional and proactive manner. Mid: The candidate shows a willingness to work hard but lacks a strategic approach to managing their time or their managers. They are reactive rather than proactive in their communication. Bad: The candidate shows poor judgment and a lack of transparency. They avoid communication and fail to take responsibility for managing their professional commitments. Structure check: Good: The candidate outlines a clear sequence of actions: analysis, communication, and resolution. The logic of their approach to conflict management is very easy to follow. Mid: The response lists a few possible actions but doesn't present them as a coherent or effective plan. The logic is a bit scattered and lacks a clear strategy. Bad: The response is a single, poorly thought-out decision that lacks any professional logic. It does not offer a constructive solution to the workload problem presented. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific strategies like time estimation and facilitating a joint discussion between managers. This shows they have a high level of professional maturity. Mid: The candidate's answer is a bit generic and doesn't provide much detail on how they would actually handle the conversation with their managers. It is a safe but unremarkable response. Bad: The response lacks any detail or reflection on the situation. It indicates a very passive and unprofessional approach to handling workplace pressure and deadlines. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their thought process clearly and professionally. They communicate a sense of reliability and competence in their ability to handle conflicting demands. Mid: The candidate is mostly clear but their response is a bit brief. They could have provided more detail on how they would evaluate the priority of the tasks themselves. Bad: The response is vague and doesn't clearly state a professional plan of action. The candidate's lack of clarity suggests they would struggle to manage their time effectively. Relevance to role: Good: This response shows the candidate is a responsible professional who can handle the typical pressures of a project-based role. They are well-suited for a junior position. Mid: This response suggests the candidate is a hard worker but may need help learning how to manage their time and communicate with supervisors. They meet basic expectations. Bad: This response indicates that the candidate would likely struggle in a work environment with multiple projects. Their lack of communication would create risks for the team's deadlines.|10|What would you do to manage your workload if two different project managers assigned you high-priority tasks due on the same day?|PASS|92|[\"Rubrics correctly include all five required sections and internal performance labels.\", \"Questions are high-quality, single-sentence interrogatives with junior-level scope.\", \"Strong, actionable differentiation between performance levels in all example answers.\", \"The role acronym appears in multiple rubric sections, violating a negative constraint.\"]|fc911f5e7cfb5dab5f5cb446bb2e6612e2c7478f|a9ecc418c6b61cb241a9209078fb2798a5aac9e9|Environmental Sustainability Analyst|219|9427309006e3a4ddb04e96d8baadc68df849466a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:05.527110Z
Teacher|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I usually don't have disagreements with people because I prefer to work alone whenever possible to avoid drama. If a teammate tries to argue with me, I just ignore them and do my own part of the job exactly how I think it should be done. This prevents the conflict from getting worse and ensures my tasks are completed correctly.|During a group project, a teammate and I disagreed on the best way to format our final report for the stakeholder. I suggested we meet briefly to discuss our perspectives, where I listened to their concerns about clarity and shared my ideas on visual impact. We ultimately compromised by using their structure while incorporating my visual aids, which resulted in a project that was well-received by the team.|I once worked with someone who wanted to do things differently than I did regarding our project timeline. We talked about it for a few minutes and I eventually just agreed to do it their way so we could finish on time. It was a bit frustrating, but the work got done without any more arguments occurring between us.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates active listening and a collaborative mindset toward solving interpersonal issues. Mid: The candidate shows a passive approach to conflict, opting to yield rather than finding a constructive middle ground. Bad: The candidate displays an avoidant or dismissive attitude that would be detrimental to a healthy team environment.\\nStructure check: Good: The response follows a clear narrative path from the conflict to the specific actions taken and the final result. Mid: The response is somewhat linear but lacks detail on the specific communication strategies used during the resolution. Bad: The response is fragmented and does not provide a coherent story about how the situation was managed.\\nDepth check: Good: The candidate reflects on why the compromise was effective and how it benefited the project as a whole. Mid: The candidate provides a surface-level description of the event without explaining the reasoning behind their actions. Bad: The candidate offers no reflection or depth, suggesting they have not learned from the experience.\\nClarity check: Good: The language is professional and the explanation of the disagreement is easy to follow without unnecessary tangents. Mid: The candidate uses vague terms and does not clearly define what the actual disagreement was about. Bad: The answer is confusing and fails to convey a clear message about the candidate's conflict resolution skills.\\nRelevance to role: Good: The answer shows the candidate can handle the social complexities of working in a professional team for the job. Mid: The answer indicates the candidate can survive in a team but may not contribute to a positive culture. Bad: The answer suggests the candidate is not suited for roles requiring consistent collaboration and communication.|1|Tell me about a time you had a disagreement with a teammate and how you went about resolving it?|PASS|98|[\"All required question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Questions are professionally formatted and level-appropriate.\", \"Rubrics strictly adhere to the five-section format with internal Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\"]|103d98e3dc0a680acff3387d1d9a080a2625efed|24a17b7031a5f44444ba94164fd0fb0a01bdac8c|Teacher|220|29369188a20ba817ec2bd34f71d66614fd1ea740|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:06.306588Z
Teacher|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I try very hard not to make mistakes, but if something goes wrong, it is usually because the instructions I was given were not very clear. If I notice a mistake, I usually just wait to see if anyone else notices it before I spend time trying to fix it. Most of the time, the errors are so small that they don't even matter for the final outcome of the job.|In my previous internship, I accidentally sent an incomplete data report to a stakeholder before double-checking the final figures. As soon as I realized the error, I contacted the stakeholder to apologize and informed my supervisor of the situation. I then stayed late to correct the data and resubmitted the accurate report within an hour, ensuring minimal disruption to the project.|I once forgot to include a few documents in a package I was preparing for the team's weekly meeting. I noticed it right as the meeting started, so I quickly ran back to my desk to print them out and brought them in late. It was a small mistake, but I fixed it as fast as I could so everyone had what they needed.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate takes full ownership of the mistake and prioritizes immediate correction and communication. Mid: The candidate fixes the error but does not show a proactive approach to communicating the issue to others. Bad: The candidate avoids responsibility and demonstrates a lack of accountability for their own work quality.\\nStructure check: Good: The response identifies the mistake, the immediate reaction, the corrective action, and the final result clearly. Mid: The response focuses mostly on the mistake itself and provides limited detail on the steps taken to prevent it from happening again. Bad: The response is disorganized and fails to show a clear timeline of events from error to resolution.\\nDepth check: Good: The candidate explains the impact of the mistake and shows they understand the importance of accuracy in their role. Mid: The candidate treats the mistake as a minor inconvenience and does not reflect on personal growth or process improvement. Bad: The candidate provides no insight into their thinking and seems to dismiss the importance of the error.\\nClarity check: Good: The candidate uses direct and honest language to describe the situation without making excuses for the failure. Mid: The candidate's explanation is a bit repetitive and could be more concise in describing the corrective steps. Bad: The response is defensive and uses unclear language that makes it difficult to understand what actually happened.\\nRelevance to role: Good: The answer demonstrates the integrity and attention to detail required for a junior professional in the job. Mid: The answer shows basic competence but lacks the high level of accountability expected for the project. Bad: The response suggests a lack of professional maturity and a potential risk to the team's work standards.|2|Describe a time when you realized you made a mistake at work and what steps you took to correct it?|PASS|98|[\"All required question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Questions are professionally formatted and level-appropriate.\", \"Rubrics strictly adhere to the five-section format with internal Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\"]|103d98e3dc0a680acff3387d1d9a080a2625efed|24a17b7031a5f44444ba94164fd0fb0a01bdac8c|Teacher|221|29369188a20ba817ec2bd34f71d66614fd1ea740|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:06.306588Z
Teacher|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I don't really have a specific process for preparation because I prefer to be spontaneous and adapt to the room when I arrive. I usually just grab whatever materials are available right before the session starts and hope for the best. Planning too much ahead of time makes the session feel too stiff and less natural for the participants.|I begin my preparation by reviewing the objectives of the session and creating a checklist of all necessary documents and digital assets. Two days before the event, I verify that all equipment is functioning and that any printed materials are organized in the order they will be used. Finally, I do a dry run of the presentation to ensure the flow is logical and that I can answer potential questions from the participants.|I usually look over the plan the night before and make sure I have all the files saved on my laptop. I try to print out a few copies of the main handouts just in case someone needs them during the session. It is a pretty simple process that helps me feel a bit more prepared for the team project.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a structured and disciplined approach to preparation that minimizes the risk of technical or logistical failure. Mid: The candidate performs basic preparation but lacks a comprehensive checklist or a validation step. Bad: The candidate relies on improvisation and fails to acknowledge the importance of professional preparation.\\nStructure check: Good: The candidate provides a step-by-step timeline of their preparation process from start to finish. Mid: The response mentions a few tasks but does not present them as a cohesive or repeatable workflow. Bad: The response is vague and does not provide any concrete steps that the interviewer can evaluate.\\nDepth check: Good: The candidate explains the reasoning behind their preparation, such as the need for redundancy with printed materials. Mid: The candidate describes what they do but does not explain why those actions are important for the success of the session. Bad: The candidate provides no detail and seems to underestimate the complexity of organizing professional materials.\\nClarity check: Good: The explanation is logical and uses clear, professional terminology to describe the workflow. Mid: The candidate uses casual language and does not sound as prepared or professional as expected for the job. Bad: The candidate's answer is confusing and suggests they do not actually have a preparation routine.\\nRelevance to role: Good: The answer demonstrates the organizational skills and reliability necessary for delivering high-quality sessions in the job. Mid: The answer shows the candidate can handle simple tasks but might struggle with more complex organizational needs. Bad: The answer indicates a lack of professionalism that could lead to disorganized and ineffective outcomes for the project.|3|Walk me through the steps you take to prepare for a session to ensure all materials are ready and organized?|PASS|98|[\"All required question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Questions are professionally formatted and level-appropriate.\", \"Rubrics strictly adhere to the five-section format with internal Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\"]|103d98e3dc0a680acff3387d1d9a080a2625efed|24a17b7031a5f44444ba94164fd0fb0a01bdac8c|Teacher|222|29369188a20ba817ec2bd34f71d66614fd1ea740|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:06.306588Z
Teacher|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I assume that if someone has a problem, they will come to me and ask for help whenever they need it. I don't think it is necessary to monitor people constantly because they should be responsible for their own progress and goals. If the final project fails, then I will know that they were not doing their work correctly.|I use a combination of regular check-in meetings and a simple tracking spreadsheet to record key milestones achieved by each individual. During our sessions, I ask open-ended questions to assess their understanding and provide immediate feedback on their performance. This allows me to adjust my support style in real-time and ensure that everyone is staying on track to meet our project deadlines.|I mostly just talk to the people I am working with and ask them if they are doing okay with their tasks. If they say they are confused, I try to explain things again, but I don't really write anything down or track it formally. It seems to work well enough for the smaller projects I have been involved in.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a proactive and systematic approach to monitoring progress and providing feedback. Mid: The candidate relies on informal check-ins and lacks a clear method for documenting or measuring success. Bad: The candidate is hands-off and does not take responsibility for ensuring the individuals they support succeed.\\nStructure check: Good: The answer details the tools used, the frequency of monitoring, and the response to identified issues. Mid: The answer is a bit disorganized and focuses only on verbal communication without any structural support. Bad: The response is very brief and does not describe a process or a logical flow of actions.\\nDepth check: Good: The candidate explains the value of real-time adjustments and how they help maintain the project's overall momentum. Mid: The candidate describes a very basic interaction model that lacks professional depth or reasoning. Bad: The candidate shows no understanding of why monitoring is a critical part of the job.\\nClarity check: Good: The response is easy to follow and clearly defines the candidate's role in the progress-tracking cycle. Mid: The candidate uses repetitive phrases and does not clearly state how they know if someone is actually improving. Bad: The answer is vague and does not provide enough information for the interviewer to assess their skills.\\nRelevance to role: Good: The answer aligns with the need for data-driven and supportive interaction in the job. Mid: The answer shows a friendly approach but lacks the rigor required for professional progress tracking. Bad: The answer suggests a lack of engagement that would likely lead to missed goals for the team.|4|How do you monitor the progress of individuals you are supporting to ensure they are meeting their specific goals?|PASS|98|[\"All required question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Questions are professionally formatted and level-appropriate.\", \"Rubrics strictly adhere to the five-section format with internal Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\"]|103d98e3dc0a680acff3387d1d9a080a2625efed|24a17b7031a5f44444ba94164fd0fb0a01bdac8c|Teacher|223|29369188a20ba817ec2bd34f71d66614fd1ea740|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:06.306588Z
Teacher|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would keep going with the plan exactly as I wrote it because the information is important and they need to hear it regardless of their mood. It is the participants' responsibility to pay attention and stay engaged during the session, not my job to entertain them. I spent a lot of time preparing the activity, so I wouldn't want to change it at the last minute.|If I noticed engagement was low, I would pause the activity and ask the participants for quick feedback on which parts are confusing or less interesting. Based on their input, I would pivot to a more interactive format, such as a small-group discussion or a practical hands-on exercise, to re-energize the room. I believe it is more important to meet the needs of the participants than to strictly follow a pre-written plan.|I would probably try to speak a little louder or use more hand gestures to try and get their attention back on the material. If that didn't work, I would maybe skip a few slides and move to the end of the activity a bit earlier than planned. It is hard to keep everyone interested all the time during a long project session.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates flexibility and a participant-centered approach to delivering content. Mid: The candidate tries to fix the problem with superficial changes but doesn't address the underlying cause of disengagement. Bad: The candidate is rigid and blames the participants for the failure of the activity.\\nStructure check: Good: The response outlines a clear process: identifying the issue, seeking feedback, and implementing a specific change. Mid: The response is a bit reactive and lacks a clear strategy for how to transition between different activity styles. Bad: The response is one-dimensional and shows no intention of changing the candidate's behavior based on the situation.\\nDepth check: Good: The candidate understands the trade-off between sticking to a plan and achieving the actual goal of participant understanding. Mid: The candidate shows a basic awareness of engagement but doesn't offer sophisticated solutions for re-engaging a group. Bad: The candidate lacks empathy and fails to see the value of adapting to the audience's needs.\\nClarity check: Good: The explanation is concise and paints a clear picture of how the candidate handles pressure in a live setting. Mid: The candidate's suggestions are somewhat vague and could be interpreted in many different ways. Bad: The answer is blunt and shows a lack of professional communication skills.\\nRelevance to role: Good: The answer shows the candidate can handle the dynamic nature of group sessions in the job effectively. Mid: The answer suggests the candidate might struggle when things don't go exactly as planned. Bad: The answer indicates a level of rigidity that would be inappropriate for a role requiring group interaction.|5|How would you adjust if you were in the middle of a planned activity and realized the participants were not engaged?|PASS|98|[\"All required question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Questions are professionally formatted and level-appropriate.\", \"Rubrics strictly adhere to the five-section format with internal Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\"]|103d98e3dc0a680acff3387d1d9a080a2625efed|24a17b7031a5f44444ba94164fd0fb0a01bdac8c|Teacher|224|29369188a20ba817ec2bd34f71d66614fd1ea740|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:06.306588Z
Teacher|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I usually just tell people to go read the manual or look up the instructions online if they don't understand what I am saying. I find that repeating myself is a waste of time and it is better for people to learn by doing things on their own. Most of the time, they eventually figure it out if you just leave them alone to work through it.|I once had to explain a new technical workflow to a teammate who was unfamiliar with the software we were using. I broke the process down into three simple steps and used a real-world analogy of an assembly line to make the concepts more relatable. I checked in after each step to ensure they were comfortable before moving on, which eventually helped them complete the task independently.|I was trying to explain how a certain project rule worked to a new member of the team who was very confused. I repeated the explanation several times using different words, and eventually, they seemed to get the hang of it after a while. It took a lot of patience, but we finally got through the whole explanation together.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate uses structured techniques like analogies and scaffolding to facilitate understanding. Mid: The candidate relies on repetition rather than adapting their communication style to the listener's needs. Bad: The candidate is unhelpful and lacks the patience or interest required to support a teammate.\\nStructure check: Good: The answer follows the STAR method, clearly describing the situation, the specific teaching method, and the successful outcome. Mid: The answer provides the context but the description of the actual communication method is thin. Bad: The response is disorganized and does not show a clear path to a resolution.\\nDepth check: Good: The candidate understands that checking for understanding is a critical part of effective communication. Mid: The candidate shows a basic effort to help but doesn't demonstrate a high level of pedagogical awareness. Bad: The candidate dismisses the importance of clear communication and expects others to be self-sufficient even when confused.\\nClarity check: Good: The candidate's own explanation is very clear, demonstrating they can practice what they preach regarding communication. Mid: The response is a bit wordy and could be more direct about the specific analogy or method used. Bad: The candidate's answer is confusing, which suggests they might struggle to explain complex topics to others.\\nRelevance to role: Good: The answer shows the candidate possesses the communication skills necessary for teaching or mentoring in the job. Mid: The answer shows the candidate can be helpful but may not be efficient at conveying difficult information. Bad: The answer indicates a lack of the foundational communication skills needed for the project.|6|Tell me about a time you had to explain a complex idea to someone who was struggling to understand?|PASS|98|[\"All required question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Questions are professionally formatted and level-appropriate.\", \"Rubrics strictly adhere to the five-section format with internal Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\"]|103d98e3dc0a680acff3387d1d9a080a2625efed|24a17b7031a5f44444ba94164fd0fb0a01bdac8c|Teacher|225|29369188a20ba817ec2bd34f71d66614fd1ea740|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:06.306588Z
Teacher|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I usually only learn new things if my supervisor tells me that I absolutely have to for the job. I think that my current skills are enough for the work I am doing, so I don't see much reason to spend my own time studying extra topics. If the company wants me to learn something, they should provide a formal training session during work hours.|During my last project, I realized that my data visualization skills were slowing down the team's reporting process. I spent my weekends taking a free online course on basic design principles and applied those new skills to our next monthly presentation. The team noted that the reports were much easier to read, and it saved us time during our stakeholder meetings.|I decided to learn more about how to use our team's scheduling tool because I was having some trouble keeping track of my tasks. I watched a couple of videos on the internet and started using some of the extra features in the app. It helped me stay a little more organized than I was before I started the project.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate identifies a performance gap and takes independent action to resolve it. Mid: The candidate learns a new skill to solve a minor personal inconvenience but doesn't show broad initiative. Bad: The candidate is resistant to self-improvement and lacks a growth mindset.\\nStructure check: Good: The response clearly identifies the problem, the specific learning action, and the positive impact on the team. Mid: The response is simple and focuses more on the tool than on the initiative or the measurable outcome. Bad: The response is negative and does not provide an example of learning at all.\\nDepth check: Good: The candidate shows they can connect their personal growth to the overall success of the project. Mid: The candidate describes a basic learning event without much reflection on why it was important for their career. Bad: The candidate shows a complete lack of interest in professional development or proactive learning.\\nClarity check: Good: The candidate describes the skill and the application clearly, making it easy to understand the value added. Mid: The language is a bit casual and doesn't fully highlight the candidate's effort or dedication. Bad: The answer is short and dismissive, providing very little content for evaluation.\\nRelevance to role: Good: The answer demonstrates the self-driven nature and adaptability required for a junior role in the job. Mid: The answer shows the candidate is willing to learn but may not seek out opportunities independently. Bad: The answer suggests the candidate will stagnate in the role and may not keep up with changing project needs.|7|Can you give an example of a time you took the initiative to learn a new skill to improve your performance?|PASS|98|[\"All required question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Questions are professionally formatted and level-appropriate.\", \"Rubrics strictly adhere to the five-section format with internal Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\"]|103d98e3dc0a680acff3387d1d9a080a2625efed|24a17b7031a5f44444ba94164fd0fb0a01bdac8c|Teacher|226|29369188a20ba817ec2bd34f71d66614fd1ea740|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:06.306588Z
Teacher|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I don't think it is my job to manage the mood of the group; everyone should just show up and do their work professionally. I focus entirely on the tasks and I don't really engage in small talk or trying to make people feel good about their performance. As long as the work is being finished on time, the environment doesn't really matter that much to me.|I maintain a positive environment by establishing clear expectations for collaboration and acknowledging individual contributions early in the project. I also make it a point to use positive reinforcement when someone does a good job, which helps build confidence within the group. If tensions arise, I address them privately and promptly to ensure the focus remains on our shared tasks and goals.|I try to be friendly to everyone and I always make sure to say hello when we start our meetings. I think that if the leader is in a good mood, then everyone else will be in a good mood too. I also try to avoid talking about anything that might be controversial or cause an argument during work hours.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate has a proactive strategy for building culture, including clear expectations and recognition. Mid: The candidate relies on being 'nice' but lacks a professional framework for managing group dynamics. Bad: The candidate ignores the importance of a positive environment and focuses exclusively on task completion.\\nStructure check: Good: The answer covers preventive measures, positive reinforcement, and conflict management in a logical sequence. Mid: The answer is a bit one-dimensional, focusing only on the candidate's personal mood rather than group management. Bad: The response is very brief and does not offer any actionable methods for the interviewer to consider.\\nDepth check: Good: The candidate understands that a positive environment directly impacts productivity and group morale. Mid: The candidate has a superficial understanding of group dynamics and doesn't show how they handle difficult situations. Bad: The candidate lacks any insight into how their behavior affects the overall team atmosphere.\\nClarity check: Good: The response uses professional language and clearly articulates a philosophy of leadership and collaboration. Mid: The candidate's explanation is a bit vague and lacks specific examples of how they have used these methods. Bad: The answer is blunt and dismissive of the social aspects of the job.\\nRelevance to role: Good: The answer shows the candidate can foster the kind of supportive environment needed for successful outcomes in the job. Mid: The answer suggests the candidate is a pleasant teammate but may not be able to manage a group effectively. Bad: The answer indicates the candidate might create a cold or unsupportive environment that could hinder team success.|8|Explain the methods you use to maintain a positive and productive environment when working with a group of people?|PASS|98|[\"All required question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Questions are professionally formatted and level-appropriate.\", \"Rubrics strictly adhere to the five-section format with internal Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\"]|103d98e3dc0a680acff3387d1d9a080a2625efed|24a17b7031a5f44444ba94164fd0fb0a01bdac8c|Teacher|227|29369188a20ba817ec2bd34f71d66614fd1ea740|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:06.306588Z
Teacher|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I generally don't modify materials because they were created by experts and should be good enough for everyone to use as they are. If someone can't understand the materials, they probably just need to work harder or ask a teammate for help during the session. Changing the materials too much can lead to confusion and might lower the standards of the project.|When modifying materials, I first analyze the varying skill levels and backgrounds of the participants to identify potential barriers to understanding. I then simplify complex jargon, add visual aids for different learning styles, and create optional 'challenge' tasks for those who are more advanced. Finally, I ask a colleague to review the modified materials to ensure they are inclusive and meet the original project objectives.|I usually just look for the hardest parts of the documents and try to make the sentences a bit shorter so they are easier to read. I might also add some pictures if I think the page looks too boring or has too much text on it. It takes a little extra time, but it usually helps most of the people understand the main points.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a thoughtful approach to inclusivity and uses specific techniques to adapt content. Mid: The candidate makes superficial changes like shortening sentences but lacks a deep understanding of participant needs. Bad: The candidate is resistant to differentiation and shows a lack of empathy for diverse learners.\\nStructure check: Good: The answer follows a logical workflow of analysis, modification, and peer review. Mid: The answer is a bit disorganized and focuses on random changes rather than a systematic process. Bad: The response is rigid and does not describe any steps for modification at all.\\nDepth check: Good: The candidate understands that 'one size does not fit all' and demonstrates a commitment to high-quality outcomes for everyone. Mid: The candidate shows a basic effort to be helpful but doesn't demonstrate professional expertise in material design. Bad: The candidate lacks the ability to see things from the perspective of others who might struggle with the content.\\nClarity check: Good: The explanation is clear and uses specific examples of how they adjust content for different needs. Mid: The candidate uses vague terms like 'easier' without explaining what that actually looks like in practice. Bad: The answer is short and does not provide enough detail to understand the candidate's approach.\\nRelevance to role: Good: The answer shows the candidate can handle the essential task of tailoring information for different audiences in the job. Mid: The answer suggests the candidate can make basic adjustments but might struggle with highly diverse groups. Bad: The answer indicates the candidate would likely fail to meet the needs of all participants in the project.|9|What steps do you follow when you need to modify existing materials to better suit a diverse group of participants?|PASS|98|[\"All required question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Questions are professionally formatted and level-appropriate.\", \"Rubrics strictly adhere to the five-section format with internal Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\"]|103d98e3dc0a680acff3387d1d9a080a2625efed|24a17b7031a5f44444ba94164fd0fb0a01bdac8c|Teacher|228|29369188a20ba817ec2bd34f71d66614fd1ea740|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:06.306588Z
Teacher|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would probably get very stressed out and try to work on all three tasks at the same time to make sure they are all getting done. I don't like to ask for help because I think it makes me look like I can't handle the responsibilities of the job. I would just keep working until I was finished, even if it meant stay very late or making some mistakes.|I would start by evaluating each task based on its overall impact on the project and the needs of the primary stakeholders. I would then check with my supervisor to see if any of the deadlines are flexible or if a teammate can assist with the smaller tasks. Once I have identified the most critical item, I would focus on it entirely while keeping the relevant parties updated on my progress with the other two.|I would probably just start with the task that I think I can finish the fastest so that I can get it off my plate quickly. After that, I would work on the other two in the order that they were assigned to me by my manager. I always try to work as hard as I can to finish everything before the end of the day.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate uses a logical prioritization matrix (impact/stakeholder) and communicates with leadership for guidance. Mid: The candidate uses a simplistic 'fastest first' approach that might ignore the most important project goals. Bad: The candidate lacks prioritization skills and risks burnout or poor quality by multitasking under pressure.\\nStructure check: Good: The response moves from assessment to consultation to execution and finally to communication. Mid: The response is a bit impulsive and doesn't show a clear decision-making framework. Bad: The response describes a chaotic reaction rather than a professional strategy for managing workload.\\nDepth check: Good: The candidate understands that professional prioritization often requires collaboration and transparency with a supervisor. Mid: The candidate treats prioritization as a solo activity and doesn't consider the broader impact on the team. Bad: The candidate shows poor self-awareness and a lack of understanding regarding efficient work habits.\\nClarity check: Good: The candidate's reasoning is easy to follow and their professional boundaries are clearly stated. Mid: The response is a bit generic and sounds like a typical answer without much personal conviction. Bad: The answer is disorganized and suggests the candidate might panic in high-pressure situations.\\nRelevance to role: Good: The answer shows the candidate has the organizational maturity required to handle the multiple responsibilities of the job. Mid: The answer shows the candidate is a hard worker but might need significant supervision to stay on track. Bad: The answer indicates a high risk of failure or poor performance when faced with the typical pressures of the project.|10|How would you decide which task to prioritize first if you had three urgent deadlines that all occurred at the same time?|PASS|98|[\"All required question IDs are present and unique.\", \"Questions are professionally formatted and level-appropriate.\", \"Rubrics strictly adhere to the five-section format with internal Good/Mid/Bad labels.\", \"Strong differentiation between example answer quality levels.\"]|103d98e3dc0a680acff3387d1d9a080a2625efed|24a17b7031a5f44444ba94164fd0fb0a01bdac8c|Teacher|229|29369188a20ba817ec2bd34f71d66614fd1ea740|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:06.306588Z
UX/UI Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I had a teammate who didn't like my ideas for a project we were doing. I tried to explain why my way was better but they wouldn't listen to me at all. I eventually just did my part of the work and let them do theirs without talking much. It was a frustrating experience and I prefer to work alone if the other person is going to be difficult.|In a recent university project, a teammate and I disagreed on the best layout for our presentation. I suggested we look at the project requirements together to see which approach aligned better with the goals. By focusing on the shared objectives rather than our personal preferences, we agreed on a hybrid version that satisfied both our ideas and met the project criteria. This resulted in a high grade and a stronger working relationship for the rest of the term.|I once worked on a group project where another student wanted to use a different tool than the one I preferred. We talked about it for a while and eventually decided to use his choice because he was more familiar with it. It worked out okay in the end, although I had to spend extra time learning how to use that specific software. We finished the task on time and didn't have any more arguments after that.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates an ability to prioritize team goals over personal ego. They show active listening and collaborative problem-solving skills. Mid: The candidate shows a willingness to compromise but lacks a structured approach to conflict resolution. They may be too passive in their interactions. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of conflict resolution skills or a tendency to avoid collaboration. They focus on blame rather than solutions. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear sequence of situation, action, and positive outcome. It is easy to follow the logic of their decision. Mid: The response is somewhat organized but the connection between the conflict and the resolution is weak. It lacks a clear concluding reflection. Bad: The response is disorganized or fails to describe a specific event. It reads more like a general opinion than a behavioral example. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about the disagreement and the reasoning behind their actions. They reflect on what they learned from the experience. Mid: The candidate provides a basic overview of the event but omits specific details about the conversation. The reflection is superficial or missing. Bad: The response is very brief and provides no insight into the candidate's thought process. It lacks any meaningful detail about the situation. Clarity check: Good: The language is professional and the explanation of the resolution is very easy to understand. There is no ambiguity in their role during the conflict. Mid: The explanation is mostly clear but some parts of the story feel vague or rushed. The candidate's specific contribution to the fix is slightly unclear. Bad: The response is confusing or uses repetitive language that does not add value. It is difficult to understand how the conflict was actually resolved. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the interpersonal maturity needed to function well in a collaborative team environment. They show they can handle common workplace friction professionally. Mid: The candidate shows they can get along with others but may require guidance when conflicts arise. They are a safe but not necessarily proactive teammate. Bad: The candidate's approach suggests they may create friction within a team or struggle with feedback. They do not demonstrate the necessary soft skills for a professional setting.|1|Tell me about a time when you had a disagreement with a teammate over how to complete a task and how you reached a resolution?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent role and level alignment across all questions.\", \"Rubric sections and internal labels strictly followed for all items.\", \"Clear differentiation between answer quality levels with concrete examples.\", \"Question 1 uses an imperative structure but functions as a valid prompt.\"]|9a236f4d545843dd899abcf4ffecb95903d4fb8e|ca39ece0334cd4bea21c2d6fa27a8e53b40d0e0f|UX/UI Designer|230|29a5bc09c80eb4e68b1208babf4c9c8328773437|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608590Z
UX/UI Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|My boss told me I was doing something wrong with our filing system and that I needed to change it. I didn't really agree because I thought my way was faster, but I did what he said anyway because he is the boss. I think feedback is often just a matter of opinion and it doesn't always make the work better. I just try to avoid making mistakes so people don't have to give me feedback.|During my internship, my supervisor pointed out that my draft reports were too wordy and lacked clear headings. I thanked them for the feedback and spent the afternoon researching better ways to structure professional documents. I then revised my report to include bullet points and concise summaries, which my supervisor later praised for being much easier to read. Now, I always create an outline first to ensure my writing stays focused and professional.|I once turned in an assignment and the teacher told me I needed to add more citations to support my arguments. I went back to the library and found three more sources to include in my bibliography before resubmitting the work. The second version got a better grade, so I realized that adding sources is important for academic projects. I try to remember to do that now whenever I am writing a paper.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a growth mindset and a proactive attitude toward improving their performance. They view feedback as a tool for development rather than a personal attack. Mid: The candidate accepts feedback but does so in a reactive or compliance-driven manner. They show limited initiative in seeking deeper improvement. Bad: The candidate is defensive or dismissive regarding constructive criticism. They do not show a desire to learn or adapt their behavior. Structure check: Good: The response clearly identifies the feedback, the specific actions taken to improve, and the resulting outcome. The narrative flow is logical and complete. Mid: The response follows a basic structure but the steps taken to incorporate the feedback are not very detailed. The outcome is mentioned briefly. Bad: The response lacks structure and fails to clearly describe the actual feedback or the steps taken. It is more of an emotional reaction than a professional summary. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains why the feedback was valuable and how they changed their long-term habits. They show self-awareness and professional maturity. Mid: The candidate provides a surface-level description of a single correction. They do not demonstrate that they learned a broader lesson from the experience. Bad: The response is extremely shallow and does not explain the candidate's internal reasoning. It provides no evidence of professional growth. Clarity check: Good: The language is clear and the candidate expresses their thoughts in a professional tone. The specific context of the feedback is easy to visualize. Mid: The response is understandable but lacks precision in the language used to describe the improvements. Some parts of the story feel a bit vague. Bad: The response is mumbled or poorly phrased, making it hard to follow the timeline of events. The candidate's attitude comes across as unprofessional. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates that they will be easy to coach and are committed to high-quality work. This is essential for a junior employee who needs to learn quickly. Mid: The candidate shows they can follow directions but might not actively seek to improve beyond the minimum requirement. They are an acceptable learner but lack drive. Bad: The candidate's attitude suggests they might resist training or repeat errors. They do not show the adaptability required for a new professional role.|2|Describe a situation where you received constructive feedback on your work and explain the steps you took to incorporate that advice?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent role and level alignment across all questions.\", \"Rubric sections and internal labels strictly followed for all items.\", \"Clear differentiation between answer quality levels with concrete examples.\", \"Question 1 uses an imperative structure but functions as a valid prompt.\"]|9a236f4d545843dd899abcf4ffecb95903d4fb8e|ca39ece0334cd4bea21c2d6fa27a8e53b40d0e0f|UX/UI Designer|231|29a5bc09c80eb4e68b1208babf4c9c8328773437|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608590Z
UX/UI Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I just start working in the software and try to make it look good as I go along. I don't really have a set process because every project is different and I like to be creative in the moment. Usually, I just pick a template and change the colors and text to fit what I need for that specific task. It usually doesn't take me very long to finish a layout this way.|I start by gathering all the requirements and understanding the goal of the layout, such as who the audience is. Next, I sketch several rough ideas on paper to explore different arrangements without getting bogged down in details. Once I have a solid direction, I move to a digital tool to build a low-fidelity wireframe to check the spacing and hierarchy. Finally, I add colors and typography, ensuring the final result is clean and serves the intended purpose of the project.|When I start a new layout, I usually look for inspiration online to see what other people have done for similar projects. Then I open my design software and start placing the images and text where I think they look best. I try a few different fonts and colors until the whole thing looks professional and organized. After that, I show it to someone else to see if they like it before I finish it up.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a structured, methodical approach to creative production. They show they understand the importance of planning before execution. Mid: The candidate has a process but it relies heavily on external inspiration or trial and error. They show some understanding of workflow but lack rigor. Bad: The candidate lacks a professional process and relies on intuition or templates. They do not show an understanding of the fundamental steps of production. Structure check: Good: The response follows a logical, step-by-step progression from research to final polish. Each stage of the process is clearly defined. Mid: The response lists some steps but the order feels a bit disjointed. It misses some key phases like initial research or wireframing. Bad: The response is a single, vague statement about working until it looks good. It does not describe a sequence of professional actions. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the 'why' behind each step, such as using sketches to explore ideas quickly. They show a professional level of technical reasoning. Mid: The candidate describes 'what' they do but provides little explanation of the benefits of their approach. The details are somewhat generic. Bad: The response is very thin and provides no detail about the tools or techniques used. It shows a lack of technical depth for a junior level. Clarity check: Good: The steps are explained with professional terminology and the narrative is very easy to follow. The candidate speaks with confidence about their workflow. Mid: The response is clear enough to understand the basic idea but the language is a bit informal. Some steps are described vaguely. Bad: The explanation is confusing and makes the candidate's process seem chaotic. It is difficult to understand how they get from a blank page to a finished product. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they have the foundational skills to handle execution-focused tasks independently. Their process ensures consistency and quality in the output. Mid: The candidate can produce work but may need more supervision to ensure they are following best practices. They show potential but need more structure. Bad: The candidate's lack of process would likely lead to inconsistent quality or missed requirements. They do not demonstrate the technical discipline needed for the job.|3|Walk me through the steps you take when you are asked to create a visual layout from scratch for a new project?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent role and level alignment across all questions.\", \"Rubric sections and internal labels strictly followed for all items.\", \"Clear differentiation between answer quality levels with concrete examples.\", \"Question 1 uses an imperative structure but functions as a valid prompt.\"]|9a236f4d545843dd899abcf4ffecb95903d4fb8e|ca39ece0334cd4bea21c2d6fa27a8e53b40d0e0f|UX/UI Designer|232|29a5bc09c80eb4e68b1208babf4c9c8328773437|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608590Z
UX/UI Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I don't really worry about accessibility unless someone specifically asks me to include it in the project. Most of the time, I just focus on making the assets look as good as possible and assume they will work for everyone. If there is a technical problem later, I can usually fix it quickly after someone points it out to me. I think the visual design is more important than the technical back-end stuff.|I use a checklist of common accessibility standards, like checking color contrast ratios and ensuring all images have descriptive alternative text. I also run my files through automated validation tools to catch any technical errors I might have missed during production. Before finishing, I manually test the assets in different formats to make sure they function correctly for all users. This systematic approach helps me catch issues early and ensures the project is inclusive.|I try to keep accessibility in mind by choosing colors that are easy to read and making sure my text is large enough. I usually look up the requirements for the specific project to make sure I am following the rules they gave me. If I am not sure about something, I ask a more senior team member to check my work for any technical mistakes. This helps me learn the standards as I go.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate recognizes that quality and accessibility are core responsibilities, not optional extras. They show a commitment to inclusive design and technical accuracy. Mid: The candidate is aware of standards but treats them as a secondary task or something they need help with. They show some effort but lack a proactive system. Bad: The candidate dismisses the importance of technical standards or accessibility. They show a lack of professional responsibility for the quality of their output. Structure check: Good: The response identifies specific methods, such as checklists and validation tools, and explains how they are applied. The logic is clear and practical. Mid: The response mentions a few disparate actions but doesn't describe a cohesive system. It relies more on ad-hoc checks than a steady process. Bad: The response is disorganized and does not provide a clear answer to how requirements are met. It lacks any sense of a structured workflow. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific examples like contrast ratios and alt-text, showing they understand the actual work involved. They demonstrate technical knowledge. Mid: The candidate uses general terms like 'making it readable' but lacks the technical vocabulary associated with the standards. The details are sparse. Bad: The response provides no technical details or specific examples. It shows a significant gap in the candidate's understanding of the topic. Clarity check: Good: The candidate communicates their process clearly and uses professional terms correctly. The explanation is easy for a stakeholder to follow. Mid: The response is understandable but uses very simple or informal language. It lacks the professional polish expected in a technical discussion. Bad: The explanation is vague or contradicts itself, making it hard to trust the candidate's technical ability. The tone may be overly casual or dismissive. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can produce high-quality, professional-grade assets that meet modern standards. This reduces the need for constant oversight and rework. Mid: The candidate is capable of meeting standards but will likely need significant guidance and reminders. They are an entry-level practitioner who is still learning the basics. Bad: The candidate's disregard for standards could lead to legal or technical issues for the project. They do not demonstrate the necessary attention to detail for the role.|4|How do you ensure that the digital assets you produce meet the necessary accessibility standards and technical requirements for the project?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent role and level alignment across all questions.\", \"Rubric sections and internal labels strictly followed for all items.\", \"Clear differentiation between answer quality levels with concrete examples.\", \"Question 1 uses an imperative structure but functions as a valid prompt.\"]|9a236f4d545843dd899abcf4ffecb95903d4fb8e|ca39ece0334cd4bea21c2d6fa27a8e53b40d0e0f|UX/UI Designer|233|29a5bc09c80eb4e68b1208babf4c9c8328773437|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608590Z
UX/UI Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would just pick the requirement that seems the most logical to me and start working on that one so I don't fall behind. I don't think it's my job to resolve arguments between stakeholders, so I would just wait for them to notice the conflict themselves. If they get upset later, I will just tell them that I was doing what I thought was best at the time. I try to avoid getting involved in office politics.|If I received conflicting requirements, I would first document the differences clearly to ensure I understood the conflict. Then, I would schedule a brief meeting with both stakeholders to present the two options and explain how each one impacts the project goals. My goal would be to facilitate a discussion so they can reach an agreement, ensuring that I have a clear, unified direction before I continue working. This prevents wasted effort and keeps the project on track.|I would probably go to my direct manager and ask them which stakeholder I should listen to first. I would explain that I am getting mixed messages and that I don't want to make the wrong choice on my own. Once my manager tells me which path to take, I would follow those instructions and let the other stakeholder know why I made that decision. This seems like the safest way to handle it.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates proactive communication and the ability to manage ambiguity. They show they can act as a facilitator to solve project-level problems. Mid: The candidate relies on authority to resolve the issue. While this is safe, it shows a lack of initiative in managing stakeholder relationships directly. Bad: The candidate takes a passive-aggressive or avoidant approach that could lead to project failure. They do not understand the importance of alignment. Structure check: Good: The response outlines a clear three-step process: identification, facilitation, and resolution. The logic is sound and easy to follow. Mid: The response is a bit linear and relies heavily on one action (asking the manager). It lacks a broader strategy for handling the conflict. Bad: The response is a single-step reaction that ignores the complexity of the situation. It does not provide a plan for resolving the underlying conflict. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions documenting the conflict and focusing on project goals, which are professional best practices. They show they understand the nuances of stakeholder management. Mid: The candidate provides a simple solution but does not go into detail about how they would communicate with the stakeholders. The answer is a bit thin. Bad: The response shows no depth of thought regarding the consequences of conflicting requirements. It suggests a lack of professional experience or awareness. Clarity check: Good: The explanation is clear, professional, and confident. The candidate's role in the process is well-defined and easy to understand. Mid: The response is clear but the tone is a bit hesitant. It sounds like the candidate is describing what they think they should do rather than a confident plan. Bad: The response is vague and the candidate's reasoning is difficult to follow. It leaves the listener unsure about how the situation would actually end. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows the maturity to handle the realistic pressures of a multi-stakeholder project environment. They are a valuable asset who can help maintain project momentum. Mid: The candidate is a reliable worker who can follow directions but may struggle in highly ambiguous or fast-paced situations. They need a strong manager to support them. Bad: The candidate's approach could cause delays and interpersonal tension within the project team. They do not show the communication skills necessary for the job.|5|Can you explain how you would handle a situation where two different stakeholders give you conflicting requirements for the same task?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent role and level alignment across all questions.\", \"Rubric sections and internal labels strictly followed for all items.\", \"Clear differentiation between answer quality levels with concrete examples.\", \"Question 1 uses an imperative structure but functions as a valid prompt.\"]|9a236f4d545843dd899abcf4ffecb95903d4fb8e|ca39ece0334cd4bea21c2d6fa27a8e53b40d0e0f|UX/UI Designer|234|29a5bc09c80eb4e68b1208babf4c9c8328773437|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608590Z
UX/UI Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I made a mistake once, but I realized it right away and fixed it before anyone else could see it. I didn't think it was necessary to tell the rest of the team because it didn't really change the final outcome of the project. I think it's better to just fix things quietly and move on so you don't look like you don't know what you're doing. Mistakes happen to everyone, so it's not a big deal.|Once I accidentally used the wrong version of a data set for a group project analysis. As soon as I realized the error, I notified my team and took full responsibility for the mistake. I spent the evening re-running the calculations with the correct data and updated our final report before the deadline. My team appreciated the honesty, and I now use a color-coding system to keep track of file versions to prevent this from happening again.|I once made a typo in a project title that was printed on a few copies of a report. When I saw it, I told my supervisor about the mistake and offered to print out new versions with the correct spelling. It was a small error, but I felt bad about it and made sure to double-check my spelling on the new copies. My supervisor said it was fine as long as it was fixed before the meeting.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates accountability, honesty, and a proactive approach to problem-solving. They show they value the integrity of the work over their own image. Mid: The candidate admits to the mistake but the error described is very minor, or the correction is purely reactive. They show some responsibility but limited reflection. Bad: The candidate shows a tendency to hide mistakes or downplay their importance. They do not demonstrate the transparency needed in a professional team. Structure check: Good: The response clearly follows the STAR method: Situation, Task, Action, and Result. The transition between identifying the mistake and fixing it is clear. Mid: The response is a bit disorganized but eventually gets to the point. The connection between the mistake and the future prevention is weak. Bad: The response is very brief and fails to explain the steps taken to fix the problem. It lacks a clear narrative arc. Depth check: Good: The candidate explains the specific steps they took to rectify the error and describes a concrete change in their workflow. They show significant self-reflection. Mid: The candidate describes the fix but doesn't explain how they will prevent the mistake in the future. The level of detail is just enough to be acceptable. Bad: The response provides no detail about the mistake or the correction. It feels like a generic answer that avoids the actual question. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses clear language and a professional tone. The story is easy to follow and the candidate's actions are well-justified. Mid: The response is understandable but the language is a bit informal. Some details of the situation are a bit fuzzy or skipped over. Bad: The response is confusing or defensive, making it hard to understand what actually happened. The candidate's explanation is not convincing. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they are a reliable and trustworthy team member who can be counted on to own their work. This is a critical trait for any junior employee. Mid: The candidate is likely to do the right thing when caught in a mistake but might not be as proactive as desired. They are an average professional in this regard. Bad: The candidate's lack of transparency could lead to larger issues down the line. They do not demonstrate the ethical standards required for the project.|6|Describe a time you realized you made a mistake on a project and what steps you took to correct the error?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent role and level alignment across all questions.\", \"Rubric sections and internal labels strictly followed for all items.\", \"Clear differentiation between answer quality levels with concrete examples.\", \"Question 1 uses an imperative structure but functions as a valid prompt.\"]|9a236f4d545843dd899abcf4ffecb95903d4fb8e|ca39ece0334cd4bea21c2d6fa27a8e53b40d0e0f|UX/UI Designer|235|29a5bc09c80eb4e68b1208babf4c9c8328773437|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608590Z
UX/UI Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I was told I had to use a new tool for a project, but I found it really confusing and I didn't think it was better than the old way. I tried to use it for a while but I kept making mistakes, so I just asked someone else on the team to do that part of the work for me. I think the team should have stuck with the tool we already knew how to use. I don't really like having to change how I work all the time.|In my last project, the team decided to switch to a new project management tool that I had never used before. To catch up, I spent my weekend watching tutorial videos and practicing with the features so I wouldn't slow the team down. By Monday, I was able to help my teammates navigate the new interface and keep our tasks organized. This experience taught me how to find learning resources independently and adapt to new technology on the fly.|I had to learn how to use a specific type of spreadsheet software for a summer job because the team used it for tracking inventory. I asked a coworker to show me the basic functions and then I spent a few hours practicing with some dummy data. I was able to do the work, although I still had to ask questions every now and then when I got stuck. It took me about a week to feel comfortable with it.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a proactive, self-driven approach to learning and a commitment to team success. They show they are not afraid of new challenges. Mid: The candidate learns when required but relies heavily on others for help. They show an average level of adaptability but lack the drive for independent mastery. Bad: The candidate is resistant to learning new things and may be a burden on the team during transitions. They do not show the flexibility needed for a modern workplace. Structure check: Good: The response clearly identifies the challenge, the specific learning steps, and the positive impact on the team. The flow is logical and results-oriented. Mid: The response is structured but the 'action' part is a bit weak. It describes a passive learning process rather than an active one. Bad: The response lacks a clear structure and fails to show a successful outcome. It focuses more on the difficulty of the task than the solution. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific resources they used, like tutorials, and explains how they helped the team. They show a high level of engagement with the learning process. Mid: The candidate provides a general overview but lacks specific details about how they learned or what they can now do. The response is a bit superficial. Bad: The response is extremely brief and provides no evidence of actual learning. It doesn't describe the tool or the process in any meaningful way. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains the situation and their actions in a professional and concise manner. Their enthusiasm for learning comes through clearly. Mid: The response is clear but the tone is a bit uninspired. The candidate sounds like they are just checking a box rather than sharing a meaningful experience. Bad: The response is mumbled or negative, making it hard to see the candidate as a capable learner. The language is unprofessional or overly casual. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can keep up with a fast-changing environment and will not require constant hand-holding. They are an ideal junior hire for a technical team. Mid: The candidate is a capable worker who will eventually learn what they need to know, but they might need more time and support. They are an acceptable but not standout hire. Bad: The candidate's resistance to new tools is a significant red flag for any role that requires growth and adaptation. They are likely to struggle in the job.|7|Explain a time when you had to learn a new tool or process quickly to contribute to the success of your team?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent role and level alignment across all questions.\", \"Rubric sections and internal labels strictly followed for all items.\", \"Clear differentiation between answer quality levels with concrete examples.\", \"Question 1 uses an imperative structure but functions as a valid prompt.\"]|9a236f4d545843dd899abcf4ffecb95903d4fb8e|ca39ece0334cd4bea21c2d6fa27a8e53b40d0e0f|UX/UI Designer|236|29a5bc09c80eb4e68b1208babf4c9c8328773437|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608590Z
UX/UI Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I don't really have a set way to prioritize things; I just try to fit everything on the screen and then shrink the icons if they are too big. If the user interface is complex, I think the user should just scroll more to see all the information they need. I don't think you should have to remove anything just because the screen is smaller. I just keep adjusting the layout until it all fits inside the borders.|I start by identifying the core tasks that a user needs to complete on that specific screen, such as 'submitting a form' or 'viewing a total.' I prioritize the elements that directly support those primary actions and move secondary information into expandable menus or separate tabs. I also use visual hierarchy, like making primary buttons more prominent than secondary ones, to guide the user's eye. This ensures the mobile experience is focused and easy to navigate even on a smaller screen.|I usually look at what other mobile apps are doing and try to copy their layout for the most important parts. I make sure the most popular buttons are at the top where people can see them easily and I hide the rest of the stuff if the screen gets too crowded. I try to keep it simple so it doesn't look messy on a small phone. It's mostly about making sure the main thing is visible.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates an understanding of user-centered design and the technical constraints of mobile platforms. They show a logical approach to prioritization. Mid: The candidate has a basic understanding of simplification but relies more on imitation than on fundamental design principles. They show some awareness of user needs. Bad: The candidate lacks an understanding of mobile-specific constraints or the importance of prioritization. They show a poor grasp of basic design fundamentals. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear logic: identifying goals, choosing key elements, and applying visual hierarchy. It is a well-organized technical explanation. Mid: The response is a bit scattered and mentions several disparate ideas without a clear framework. It's understandable but lacks a professional structure. Bad: The response is a single statement that doesn't follow any logical order. It fails to answer the 'how' part of the question effectively. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific techniques like 'expandable menus' and 'visual hierarchy,' showing they have the technical knowledge for the task. They explain the reasoning behind their choices. Mid: The candidate provides some general ideas but lacks the technical vocabulary to explain their process in detail. The answer is a bit surface-level. Bad: The response is very thin and shows no technical depth. It suggests the candidate has not actually performed this type of task before. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses professional terminology correctly and explains their process in a way that is easy to visualize. The tone is confident and professional. Mid: The response is clear enough to follow the general idea but uses very simple language. It lacks the precision expected of a practitioner in the field. Bad: The response is confusing or uses terms incorrectly, making the candidate's technical ability seem questionable. The explanation is hard to follow. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they have the foundational skills to contribute to digital product work immediately. Their approach ensures that the output is functional and user-friendly. Mid: The candidate can do the work but will need more guidance to ensure they are following modern design standards. They are a typical junior-level practitioner. Bad: The candidate's lack of understanding of prioritization would lead to poor user experiences. They do not demonstrate the necessary skills for the job.|8|How do you decide which components or elements to prioritize when you are simplifying a complex user interface for a mobile device?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent role and level alignment across all questions.\", \"Rubric sections and internal labels strictly followed for all items.\", \"Clear differentiation between answer quality levels with concrete examples.\", \"Question 1 uses an imperative structure but functions as a valid prompt.\"]|9a236f4d545843dd899abcf4ffecb95903d4fb8e|ca39ece0334cd4bea21c2d6fa27a8e53b40d0e0f|UX/UI Designer|237|29a5bc09c80eb4e68b1208babf4c9c8328773437|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608590Z
UX/UI Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I don't really have a process for organizing files because I can usually find everything I need even if the names are a bit messy. I just save everything to my desktop and then upload it all at once when the project is done. If someone else needs to find something, they can just ask me and I will tell them where it is. I think spending too much time on file names is a waste of energy.|I always follow a consistent naming convention for all my files and layers, such as using 'ProjectName_Date_Version.' I also group related elements into clearly labeled folders and remove any unused or redundant assets before sharing the file. Additionally, I include a small text note or a 'read-me' file that explains the structure and lists any external dependencies. This ensures that anyone who opens the project can find what they need quickly without asking me for help.|I try to keep my files organized by giving them names that make sense to me, like 'Final_Draft_1' or 'Revised_Logo.' I put everything in one main folder so it's all in the same place and easy to send over email or upload to a shared drive. I don't usually group everything perfectly, but I make sure the most important files are at the top of the list. It's usually good enough for my teammates to figure it out.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates professional discipline and a collaborative mindset. They understand that their work is part of a larger team effort. Mid: The candidate shows some effort toward organization but it is inconsistent or individualized. They show an average level of professional responsibility. Bad: The candidate is disorganized and dismissive of the needs of their teammates. They do not demonstrate the habits needed for professional collaboration. Structure check: Good: The response outlines a clear, multi-step process for preparation: naming, grouping, and documenting. The logic is sound and thorough. Mid: The response lists a few basic actions but lacks a comprehensive system. It focuses on the bare minimum needed to share a file. Bad: The response is a single statement that ignores the question's focus on team usability. It provides no clear process for organization. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific practices like 'naming conventions' and 'external dependencies,' showing they understand the complexities of file sharing. They provide concrete examples. Mid: The candidate provides a general overview but lacks specific details about how they organize their internal project structure. The answer is a bit basic. Bad: The response is very thin and shows no awareness of professional file management standards. It suggests a lack of experience in a collaborative environment. Clarity check: Good: The candidate communicates their process clearly and uses professional terms correctly. The benefits of their approach are obvious and well-explained. Mid: The response is understandable but the tone is a bit informal. The candidate's description of their file names is a bit vague. Bad: The response is confusing or defensive, making the candidate seem difficult to work with. The explanation is hard to follow. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they are a 'low-friction' team member who will make the team's workflow more efficient. This is a highly valued trait in any professional setting. Mid: The candidate will be an acceptable team member but might cause small delays or frustrations due to their organizational habits. They need to develop more consistency. Bad: The candidate's lack of organization would likely cause significant friction and lost time within the project team. They do not demonstrate the professional maturity required.|9|Could you describe your process for preparing and organizing your files so that another team member can easily understand and use them?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent role and level alignment across all questions.\", \"Rubric sections and internal labels strictly followed for all items.\", \"Clear differentiation between answer quality levels with concrete examples.\", \"Question 1 uses an imperative structure but functions as a valid prompt.\"]|9a236f4d545843dd899abcf4ffecb95903d4fb8e|ca39ece0334cd4bea21c2d6fa27a8e53b40d0e0f|UX/UI Designer|238|29a5bc09c80eb4e68b1208babf4c9c8328773437|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608590Z
UX/UI Designer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would probably just wait for the other person to realize they forgot to give me the information and send it over later. I don't want to bother them if they are busy, so I would just work on other things until I have everything I need to start the new task. If the deadline passes and I haven't finished, I'll just explain that it wasn't my fault because I didn't have all the instructions from the beginning.|I would immediately reach out to the task owner to explain exactly what information is missing and why it is critical for the project. I would propose a temporary workaround or ask for a prioritized list of what can be done with the information currently available to keep the project moving while I wait for the rest. This shows I am taking ownership of the deadline while being transparent about the constraints I'm facing. I would also follow up quickly if I don't hear back within a few hours.|I would send an email to the person who gave me the task and ask them for the missing details as soon as possible. While waiting for their reply, I would start working on the parts of the task that I already understand so that I'm not just sitting around doing nothing. I would hope that they get back to me in time so that I can still finish the whole thing by the deadline. If not, I would just tell them why I couldn't finish it.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates proactive communication, problem-solving under pressure, and a strong sense of ownership. They focus on maintaining project momentum despite obstacles. Mid: The candidate is reactive and relies on others to provide information. While they take some action, they lack the urgency needed for a tight deadline. Bad: The candidate is passive and avoids responsibility. They are likely to miss deadlines because they do not take initiative to solve problems. Structure check: Good: The response outlines a clear plan: immediate communication, prioritization, and follow-up. The logic is focused on the project's success. Mid: The response is simple and focuses on a single action (sending an email). It lacks a broader strategy for managing the time effectively. Bad: The response is a single-step reaction that shows a lack of planning. It does not provide a realistic solution for meeting the deadline. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions proposing a 'workaround' and 'prioritizing' tasks, showing they can think critically about project constraints. They demonstrate professional judgment. Mid: The candidate provides a basic answer but doesn't explain how they would handle the situation if the information still didn't arrive. The answer is a bit thin. Bad: The response shows no depth of thought and fails to acknowledge the importance of the deadline. It suggests a lack of professional accountability. Clarity check: Good: The candidate expresses their plan clearly and with a professional tone. Their actions are well-justified and easy to follow. Mid: The response is clear but the tone is a bit passive. It sounds like the candidate is waiting for things to happen rather than making them happen. Bad: The response is vague or defensive, making the candidate's reliability seem questionable. The explanation is hard to follow. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows the maturity to handle the realistic pressures of a deadline-driven project environment. They are a valuable asset who can help mitigate risks. Mid: The candidate is a reliable worker who can follow directions but may struggle in fast-paced or ambiguous situations. They need more supervision to ensure deadlines are met. Bad: The candidate's approach could cause significant project delays and missed milestones. They do not show the communication or time management skills necessary for the job.|10|What would you do if you were assigned a task with a very tight deadline and you realized you did not have all the information needed to start?|PASS|96|[\"Excellent role and level alignment across all questions.\", \"Rubric sections and internal labels strictly followed for all items.\", \"Clear differentiation between answer quality levels with concrete examples.\", \"Question 1 uses an imperative structure but functions as a valid prompt.\"]|9a236f4d545843dd899abcf4ffecb95903d4fb8e|ca39ece0334cd4bea21c2d6fa27a8e53b40d0e0f|UX/UI Designer|239|29a5bc09c80eb4e68b1208babf4c9c8328773437|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608590Z
Lawyer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|1|Behavioral ​|I usually don't have disagreements because I try to stay quiet and just do whatever the other person wants to do to avoid any drama. One time a teammate was doing something wrong, but I didn't want to start an argument, so I just fixed it myself later without telling them. This way the project stayed on track and we didn't have to waste time talking about our feelings.|During an internship project, a teammate and I disagreed on how to categorize our research data. I suggested we meet for fifteen minutes to compare our two different methods and evaluate which one would make the final report easier for the project lead to read. We eventually decided to combine elements of both methods, which allowed us to finish the project ahead of schedule and improved our collaboration for the remainder of the term.|I once worked on a project where my partner wanted to do things differently than I did. We talked about it for a while and eventually decided to go with my way because I had more experience with the software we were using. It was a bit tense for a few days, but we got the work done and the project was submitted on time without any more issues.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates the ability to handle interpersonal conflict with a focus on professional outcomes and collaborative problem-solving. Mid: The candidate shows they can resolve a conflict but may rely on authority or lack a truly collaborative mindset. Bad: The candidate avoids conflict entirely or handles it in a way that damages the team dynamic or transparency. Structure check: Good: The response follows a clear path from identifying the conflict to the specific actions taken and the final result. Mid: The response mentions the conflict and the result but is vague about the specific steps taken to resolve the issue. Bad: The response lacks any structure and fails to explain how the situation was actually resolved. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about the nature of the disagreement and the reasoning behind their chosen resolution. Mid: The candidate provides only surface-level details and does not explain the logic used to settle the disagreement. Bad: The response is very brief and provides no insight into the candidate's thought process or interpersonal skills. Clarity check: Good: The candidate uses clear language and describes the situation in a way that is easy for a non-expert to understand. Mid: The candidate is somewhat clear but uses vague terms like things or stuff when describing the conflict. Bad: The response is confusing or rambling and does not clearly articulate what the problem was. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can work effectively within a team which is essential for project-based execution. Mid: The candidate shows basic teamwork skills but may not yet understand the importance of proactive communication. Bad: The candidate demonstrates a lack of teamwork skills that could lead to issues in a collaborative environment.|1|Tell me about a time when you had a disagreement with a teammate and how you reached a resolution?|PASS|78|[\"Full compliance with schema, ID completeness, and required performance labels.\", \"Rubrics include the specific role title, violating a negative constraint.\", \"Generic boilerplate utilized across several grading rubric sections.\", \"Thematic overlap between several question pairs, such as IDs 4 and 22.\"]|8fc063bcae1044b7a1a5abf09f8d54343ec24901|7f0b3e4db528d9a2a57b6c746d2602c5902b5726|Lawyer|240|18a2eb6ff5e99132ec364e8a0127900dfb44e41a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608696Z
Lawyer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|2|Behavioral ​|I don't really make many mistakes because I am very careful, but if I do, I usually try to fix them before anyone else sees them so there isn't a problem. If someone else finds a mistake I made, I explain that the instructions I was given were probably not clear enough to begin with. Usually, mistakes are just small things that don't really affect the final outcome of the project anyway.|While working on a research assignment, I realized I had used an outdated version of a project template after I had already completed half the work. I immediately notified my supervisor to explain the error and then stayed late that evening to migrate all my data into the correct format. I also created a checklist for myself to ensure that I verify the correct templates and requirements at the start of every future task.|I once made a mistake in a spreadsheet where I accidentally deleted some rows of data before submitting it. When I noticed it a few hours later, I went back into the version history and restored the missing information as quickly as I could. My boss didn't notice the mistake, but I made sure to be more careful with the delete key from that point forward.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate shows a high level of accountability and a proactive approach to fixing errors and preventing them in the future. Mid: The candidate acknowledges the mistake and fixes it but focuses more on hiding the error than on systemic improvement. Bad: The candidate avoids taking responsibility or blames external factors for their own errors. Structure check: Good: The response clearly identifies the mistake, the immediate action taken, and the long-term lesson learned. Mid: The response describes the mistake and the fix but lacks a clear explanation of the resulting improvement. Bad: The response is disorganized and does not provide a clear sequence of events. Depth check: Good: The candidate describes the specific impact of the mistake and the logical steps taken to rectify it. Mid: The candidate provides minimal detail about the mistake and focuses only on the fact that it was eventually resolved. Bad: The candidate provides no detail and dismisses the importance of the situation. Clarity check: Good: The response is articulated clearly and demonstrates professional reflection on one's own performance. Mid: The response is understandable but lacks the professional tone expected in a workplace setting. Bad: The response is vague and fails to communicate a coherent story. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the integrity and attention to detail required for handling sensitive professional tasks. Mid: The candidate shows they can perform tasks but may need more supervision to ensure quality. Bad: The candidate shows a lack of reliability that would be a risk to the team's output.|2|Describe a situation where you realized you made a mistake on a project and the steps you took to correct it?|PASS|78|[\"Full compliance with schema, ID completeness, and required performance labels.\", \"Rubrics include the specific role title, violating a negative constraint.\", \"Generic boilerplate utilized across several grading rubric sections.\", \"Thematic overlap between several question pairs, such as IDs 4 and 22.\"]|8fc063bcae1044b7a1a5abf09f8d54343ec24901|7f0b3e4db528d9a2a57b6c746d2602c5902b5726|Lawyer|241|18a2eb6ff5e99132ec364e8a0127900dfb44e41a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608696Z
Lawyer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|3|Specific|I just search for the project name and see what comes up in the system from previous years. If I find something that looks similar, I just copy those parts and use them for the new project so that I don't have to start from scratch. I don't really have a specific process other than looking for things that look like they might work.|When I start a new research task, I first define the core keywords and parameters to ensure my search is targeted. I then use several authoritative databases to cross-reference the information and look for the most recent examples or precedents that align with our current project needs. Finally, I organize my findings into a summary document that highlights the most relevant points and citations for my team to review.|I usually start by typing the main topic into the search bar of the primary database we use at the office. I look through the first few results to see if they look useful and then save the ones that seem to match what I am looking for. If I can't find anything there, I might try a general search engine to see if there are any other examples I missed.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a methodical and thorough approach to research and information retrieval. Mid: The candidate has a basic research process but lacks depth in verification and cross-referencing. Bad: The candidate's approach is disorganized and relies on shortcuts rather than rigorous investigation. Structure check: Good: The response outlines a logical step-by-step workflow from definition to search to organization. Mid: The response mentions a few steps but does not present them as a coherent or repeatable process. Bad: The response is scattered and does not follow a logical progression. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific strategies like keyword definition, cross-referencing, and summarization. Mid: The candidate provides only general descriptions of their actions without explaining the why behind them. Bad: The response is extremely brief and shows a lack of familiarity with professional research standards. Clarity check: Good: The explanation is clear and professional, showing the candidate's ability to communicate their technical workflow. Mid: The explanation is somewhat clear but lacks the precision needed for complex tasks. Bad: The response is muddled and fails to describe a functional workflow. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows the analytical skills and attention to detail necessary for junior-level execution. Mid: The candidate shows they can handle simple tasks but might struggle with more complex research requirements. Bad: The candidate's lack of process suggests they may produce incomplete or inaccurate work.|3|Walk me through the specific steps you take when searching through professional databases to find specific precedents or previous examples for a new project?|PASS|78|[\"Full compliance with schema, ID completeness, and required performance labels.\", \"Rubrics include the specific role title, violating a negative constraint.\", \"Generic boilerplate utilized across several grading rubric sections.\", \"Thematic overlap between several question pairs, such as IDs 4 and 22.\"]|8fc063bcae1044b7a1a5abf09f8d54343ec24901|7f0b3e4db528d9a2a57b6c746d2602c5902b5726|Lawyer|242|18a2eb6ff5e99132ec364e8a0127900dfb44e41a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608696Z
Lawyer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|4|Specific|I usually just rely on the built-in spellcheck and grammar tools in the word processor to catch any mistakes for me. If the software says there are no errors, I assume the document is ready to go and send it to my supervisor for the final check. I don't really have a specific system because I'm naturally good at spotting errors while I'm typing them.|I use a multi-pass review process where I focus on one specific element at a time, such as checking all dates and names in the first pass and then verifying all cross-references in the second pass. I also utilize a checklist provided by the team and read the document aloud or in reverse order to catch any small typos that my eyes might otherwise skip. This ensures that every detail matches the required standards before I submit it for final approval.|I read through the document very carefully from start to finish to make sure everything looks right. I check for any red underlines from the spellchecker and make sure that the font and margins are consistent throughout the whole thing. If I have enough time, I will read it a second time just to be sure I didn't miss anything obvious.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a rigorous and disciplined approach to quality control and document accuracy. Mid: The candidate shows a basic effort toward accuracy but relies on standard reading rather than a specialized system. Bad: The candidate over-relies on automated tools and lacks a personal sense of accountability for the final product. Structure check: Good: The response describes a clear, multi-step method that involves different techniques for catching errors. Mid: The response describes a simple linear review process with little variation in technique. Bad: The response lacks a structured approach to the task. Depth check: Good: The candidate identifies specific techniques like multi-pass reviews, reading aloud, and using checklists. Mid: The candidate provides general statements about being careful without explaining how they ensure that care is effective. Bad: The candidate provides no detail on how they actually verify the accuracy of their work. Clarity check: Good: The candidate articulates their process clearly, showing a high level of professional awareness. Mid: The candidate is clear but describes a very basic level of performance. Bad: The response is vague and does not clearly explain a method. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they are capable of performing high-stakes proofreading and verification tasks independently. Mid: The candidate may require additional rounds of review by seniors to ensure no errors are missed. Bad: The candidate's approach is likely to result in errors reaching the final version of the project.|4|Explain the systematic method you use to check a long agreement for specific clerical details or formatting requirements to ensure absolute accuracy?|PASS|78|[\"Full compliance with schema, ID completeness, and required performance labels.\", \"Rubrics include the specific role title, violating a negative constraint.\", \"Generic boilerplate utilized across several grading rubric sections.\", \"Thematic overlap between several question pairs, such as IDs 4 and 22.\"]|8fc063bcae1044b7a1a5abf09f8d54343ec24901|7f0b3e4db528d9a2a57b6c746d2602c5902b5726|Lawyer|243|18a2eb6ff5e99132ec364e8a0127900dfb44e41a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608696Z
Lawyer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|A|5|Situational​|I would just start working on the task that I received first and then do the second one whenever I finish the first. I don't think it is my place to tell a senior lead that I am busy with someone else's work, so I would just stay quiet and hope I can get everything done. If I can't finish, I will just apologize the next morning and explain that I was overwhelmed.|I would first look at the requirements for both tasks to understand the time and effort needed for each. I would then politely inform both project leads of the situation and ask them to help me prioritize based on the broader team goals. If they are unable to agree on the priority, I would seek guidance from my direct supervisor to ensure I am focusing on the most critical task first.|I would try my best to finish both tasks by working through my lunch break and staying late if necessary. I would start with the task that seems easier so I can get it out of the way quickly and then spend the rest of my time on the harder one. If I realized I couldn't finish both, I would send a quick email to the second person letting them know it might be late.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates strong prioritization skills and the ability to communicate upward when resources are constrained. Mid: The candidate shows a willingness to work hard but lacks the communication skills to manage expectations effectively. Bad: The candidate is passive and fails to address the conflict, which leads to missed deadlines and poor transparency. Structure check: Good: The response follows a logical path of assessment, communication, and escalation if necessary. Mid: The response focuses on the effort rather than the management of the situation. Bad: The response is reactive and does not provide a plan for handling the conflict. Depth check: Good: The candidate identifies the need to understand task requirements and team goals before making a decision. Mid: The candidate provides a very simple solution that does not account for the complexity of professional priorities. Bad: The candidate offers no reasoning for their actions. Clarity check: Good: The candidate explains their logic clearly and professionally. Mid: The candidate's explanation is simple but understandable. Bad: The response is confusing and does not clearly state how the problem is solved. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows the professional maturity required to work in a high-pressure, multi-stakeholder environment. Mid: The candidate may experience burnout or missed deadlines due to poor task management. Bad: The candidate's approach is likely to cause frustration for senior staff and project delays.|5|How would you handle a situation where two senior project leads give you urgent tasks that need to be completed by the end of the day?|PASS|78|[\"Full compliance with schema, ID completeness, and required performance labels.\", \"Rubrics include the specific role title, violating a negative constraint.\", \"Generic boilerplate utilized across several grading rubric sections.\", \"Thematic overlap between several question pairs, such as IDs 4 and 22.\"]|8fc063bcae1044b7a1a5abf09f8d54343ec24901|7f0b3e4db528d9a2a57b6c746d2602c5902b5726|Lawyer|244|18a2eb6ff5e99132ec364e8a0127900dfb44e41a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608696Z
Lawyer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|6|Behavioral ​|I don't really like it when the process changes right in the middle of a project because it is very confusing and leads to errors. When my team changed tools once, I asked if I could just keep using the old way for one more week so I didn't mess anything up. Eventually, I had to change, but I only learned the bare minimum needed to get my specific tasks done.|In my last role, our team switched to a new document management system two days before a major deadline. I spent my first morning going through the training videos and then created a one-page cheat sheet of the most common functions I needed for my specific tasks. This allowed me to stay productive and I ended up helping two other teammates who were struggling with the new interface.|I once had to use a new type of software to create a report because the old program was no longer supported. I just played around with the buttons and looked up things on the internet whenever I got stuck on a specific feature. It took me a bit longer than usual, but I eventually figured it out and got the report finished by the end of the week.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates adaptability, initiative, and a structured approach to self-directed learning. Mid: The candidate is able to learn new things but lacks a proactive or efficient method for doing so. Bad: The candidate is resistant to change and struggles to adapt to new requirements or technologies. Structure check: Good: The response identifies the challenge, the specific learning actions taken, and the positive outcome. Mid: The response describes the change and the fact that they eventually learned it, but the process is vague. Bad: The response is focused more on the candidate's personal feelings about the change than on the actions they took. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific strategies like watching training videos and creating a cheat sheet. Mid: The candidate describes a general trial-and-error approach without much detail. Bad: The candidate provides very little information about how they actually learned the new tool. Clarity check: Good: The explanation is clear, logical, and easy to follow. Mid: The response is clear but lacks professional detail. Bad: The response is disorganized or overly negative. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows the flexibility and fast-learning capability required in a fast-paced professional setting. Mid: The candidate is capable of change but may be slower to adapt than preferred. Bad: The candidate may become a bottleneck when the team needs to implement new workflows.|6|Tell me about a time when you had to learn a new tool or process quickly to complete a task on time?|PASS|78|[\"Full compliance with schema, ID completeness, and required performance labels.\", \"Rubrics include the specific role title, violating a negative constraint.\", \"Generic boilerplate utilized across several grading rubric sections.\", \"Thematic overlap between several question pairs, such as IDs 4 and 22.\"]|8fc063bcae1044b7a1a5abf09f8d54343ec24901|7f0b3e4db528d9a2a57b6c746d2602c5902b5726|Lawyer|245|18a2eb6ff5e99132ec364e8a0127900dfb44e41a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608696Z
Lawyer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|7|Behavioral ​|I usually find that if I just tell people that I have a lot of experience with a certain task, they will just listen to me without me having to show them any evidence. One time someone wanted to do something a different way, but I just explained that my way was the standard way we were taught in school. They didn't really argue with me after that, so we just did what I wanted.|During a project, a stakeholder wanted to skip a specific validation step to save time. I gathered data from our previous three projects showing that skipping this step had led to significant errors that took twice as long to fix later. I presented this evidence in a brief meeting, and the stakeholder agreed that maintaining the validation step was the most efficient choice for the project's success.|I once had to convince a teammate to use a different layout for our presentation because I thought the original one was too cluttered. I showed them a few examples of professional presentations I found online and explained why they looked better. They weren't completely convinced at first, but they eventually agreed to try it my way for the first few slides.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates the ability to use data and logic to influence others professionally and constructively. Mid: The candidate tries to persuade others but relies more on personal opinion or external examples than on project-specific data. Bad: The candidate uses authority or personal preference to force their ideas on others rather than using persuasion. Structure check: Good: The response clearly outlines the situation, the evidence gathered, the presentation of that evidence, and the result. Mid: The response mentions the disagreement and the outcome but is vague about the logical evidence used. Bad: The response does not provide a clear sequence of events or a logical argument. Depth check: Good: The candidate provides specific details about the data they used and the reasoning for their position. Mid: The candidate provides general details but does not explain the logic behind their persuasion. Bad: The candidate provides no evidence of a structured or logical approach. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's explanation is clear and demonstrates professional communication skills. Mid: The candidate is clear but the example is relatively simple. Bad: The response is confusing or fails to describe a successful persuasion. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can protect the quality of work by effectively managing stakeholder expectations. Mid: The candidate shows some potential for communication but may need guidance on how to use data effectively. Bad: The candidate demonstrates a lack of collaborative communication skills.|7|Describe a situation where you had to persuade a stakeholder to follow a specific course of action by presenting logical evidence?|PASS|78|[\"Full compliance with schema, ID completeness, and required performance labels.\", \"Rubrics include the specific role title, violating a negative constraint.\", \"Generic boilerplate utilized across several grading rubric sections.\", \"Thematic overlap between several question pairs, such as IDs 4 and 22.\"]|8fc063bcae1044b7a1a5abf09f8d54343ec24901|7f0b3e4db528d9a2a57b6c746d2602c5902b5726|Lawyer|246|18a2eb6ff5e99132ec364e8a0127900dfb44e41a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608696Z
Lawyer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|8|Specific|I don't usually take notes during the meeting because I find that I can remember the most important things just by listening carefully. If I am asked to provide a summary later, I just write down the three or four biggest points that I remember and send them in a quick email. I think people prefer short summaries anyway because they don't have time to read long documents.|During a meeting, I take structured notes by dividing my page into sections for key discussion points, decisions made, and specific action items with assigned owners. Immediately after the meeting, I review my notes to clarify any shorthand and then draft a formal summary that I send to the attendees within twenty-four hours. This ensures that everyone is aligned on the next steps while the information is still fresh in their minds.|I try to write down almost everything that everyone says during the meeting so that I don't miss any important details. After the meeting is over, I type up my notes into a clean document and then read through it once to make sure it makes sense. I then save it in the project folder so that anyone who missed the meeting can read it later if they need to.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a structured and professional approach to documentation and information management. Mid: The candidate takes notes but lacks a system for prioritizing information or ensuring timely follow-up. Bad: The candidate is disorganized and lacks a reliable method for capturing or sharing information. Structure check: Good: The response outlines a clear process: preparation during the meeting, immediate review, and timely distribution. Mid: The response describes a simple note-taking and filing process without much detail on the structure of the notes. Bad: The response lacks any coherent process or structure. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific techniques like categorizing notes into decisions and action items. Mid: The candidate provides only general statements about writing things down and typing them up. Bad: The candidate provides no detail on how they ensure the summary is comprehensive or useful. Clarity check: Good: The explanation is clear and shows the candidate's understanding of professional standards. Mid: The explanation is understandable but describes a very basic level of task execution. Bad: The response is muddled and shows a lack of professional awareness. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate demonstrates the organizational and communication skills necessary to support team coordination. Mid: The candidate can perform basic tasks but may miss critical details in complex discussions. Bad: The candidate's lack of documentation skills could lead to confusion and missed deadlines for the team.|8|Can you walk me through your method for preparing a comprehensive summary of a meeting to ensure all key points and action items are captured?|PASS|78|[\"Full compliance with schema, ID completeness, and required performance labels.\", \"Rubrics include the specific role title, violating a negative constraint.\", \"Generic boilerplate utilized across several grading rubric sections.\", \"Thematic overlap between several question pairs, such as IDs 4 and 22.\"]|8fc063bcae1044b7a1a5abf09f8d54343ec24901|7f0b3e4db528d9a2a57b6c746d2602c5902b5726|Lawyer|247|18a2eb6ff5e99132ec364e8a0127900dfb44e41a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608696Z
Lawyer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|9|Specific|I usually just keep all my files in one big folder on my desktop until the project is finished and then I upload everything to the shared drive all at once. I don't really worry about the file names because the search function in the computer is usually good enough to find whatever I'm looking for. As long as the files are somewhere on the server, I consider the job done.|I follow a strict naming convention that includes the date, project code, and version number for every file I archive. I also create a summary index at the top of the folder that describes the contents of each sub-folder and any specific dependencies between the files. Finally, I double-check the access permissions to ensure that the appropriate team members can find and open the documents when they need them.|I make sure to put all the final versions of the documents into a folder labeled Final and then move all the old drafts into an Archive folder. I try to name the files clearly so that I know what they are, like Project_Report_v2 or Meeting_Notes_June. This keeps the main workspace clean and makes it easier for me to find things if I need to look back at them later.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates a high level of organization and a commitment to long-term information usability and team collaboration. Mid: The candidate shows basic organizational skills but lacks a systemic approach that would benefit the wider team. Bad: The candidate is disorganized and does not consider the needs of others who might need to access the information. Structure check: Good: The response follows a logical sequence of naming, indexing, and verifying access. Mid: The response describes a simple file-moving process without a clear system for categorization. Bad: The response lacks any structure or professional methodology. Depth check: Good: The candidate mentions specific practices like naming conventions, indexing, and permission checks. Mid: The candidate provides general information about moving files into folders. Bad: The candidate provides no detail on how they ensure the quality or accessibility of the archive. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's process is explained clearly and professionally. Mid: The explanation is simple and easy to understand but lacks technical depth. Bad: The response is vague and shows a lack of effort. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows they can be trusted with the critical task of maintaining accurate and accessible project records. Mid: The candidate may require guidance on team-wide organizational standards. Bad: The candidate's lack of organization is likely to lead to lost information and wasted time for the team.|9|What specific steps do you take when archiving project documents to ensure that they are categorized correctly and are easily accessible for future use?|PASS|78|[\"Full compliance with schema, ID completeness, and required performance labels.\", \"Rubrics include the specific role title, violating a negative constraint.\", \"Generic boilerplate utilized across several grading rubric sections.\", \"Thematic overlap between several question pairs, such as IDs 4 and 22.\"]|8fc063bcae1044b7a1a5abf09f8d54343ec24901|7f0b3e4db528d9a2a57b6c746d2602c5902b5726|Lawyer|248|18a2eb6ff5e99132ec364e8a0127900dfb44e41a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608696Z
Lawyer|Junior\\n0 to 2 years of experience or fresh graduate\\nUnderstands fundamental concepts relevant to the role and basic professional practices\\nHas completed academic projects, internships, or collaborated with team members or stakeholders\\nNot expected to independently own high-level strategy or lead large-scale initiatives end-to-end|B|10|Situational​|I would probably just stop working on that specific task and focus on my other responsibilities until the project lead was available again. It is better to wait for clear instructions than to do the work incorrectly and have to start over from the beginning. I would send an email explaining that I am waiting for more information and then wait for their reply.|I would first review all available project documentation to see if I could find context or previous examples of similar tasks. I would then draft a brief project plan outlining my intended approach and assumptions and share it with a more accessible teammate for a quick sanity check. This allows me to make progress while demonstrating that I am taking initiative to resolve the ambiguity responsibly.|I would look at what other people have done for similar tasks in the past and try to copy their format as much as possible. If I still wasn't sure what to do, I would wait a few hours to see if the project lead came back online before starting. I would eventually just do my best guess so that I had something to show them when they finally returned.|Question intent check: Good: The candidate demonstrates strong problem-solving skills, initiative, and the ability to work independently under ambiguous conditions. Mid: The candidate shows some initiative but may be prone to guesswork or unnecessary delays. Bad: The candidate is passive and stops working when faced with a lack of clear direction. Structure check: Good: The response outlines a clear plan of action: internal research, drafting a proposal, and seeking a peer review. Mid: The response focuses on waiting and guessing rather than a proactive search for information. Bad: The response lacks a constructive plan for moving forward. Depth check: Good: The candidate describes specific resources they would use, such as documentation and peer feedback. Mid: The candidate provides only general ideas about looking at old work. Bad: The candidate provides no detail on how they would resolve the lack of information. Clarity check: Good: The candidate's logic and communication are professional and clear. Mid: The explanation is simple but coherent. Bad: The response is vague and fails to address the problem effectively. Relevance to role: Good: The candidate shows the resourcefulness and independence required for a junior professional to be productive in a busy environment. Mid: The candidate may require significant hand-holding to complete tasks. Bad: The candidate's tendency to stall when faced with ambiguity would be a major disadvantage to the project's timeline.|10|Describe how you would respond if a project lead gave you a task with very vague instructions and then became unavailable for questions?|PASS|78|[\"Full compliance with schema, ID completeness, and required performance labels.\", \"Rubrics include the specific role title, violating a negative constraint.\", \"Generic boilerplate utilized across several grading rubric sections.\", \"Thematic overlap between several question pairs, such as IDs 4 and 22.\"]|8fc063bcae1044b7a1a5abf09f8d54343ec24901|7f0b3e4db528d9a2a57b6c746d2602c5902b5726|Lawyer|249|18a2eb6ff5e99132ec364e8a0127900dfb44e41a|gemini-3-flash-preview|1.0|2026-02-20T16:42:10.608696Z
